<SLUG> BC-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HORSE IS A HORSE, OF COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Confessions of an ESPN ``SportsCentury'' voter:
</P>
<P>
   I did not vote for the horse. Not for a fleeting millisecond did
it occur to me that a vote in the ESPN ``SportsCentury'' poll to
determine the top North American athletes (hence, no Pele or Emil
Zatopek) should go to anything but a human being. I did vote for
Eddie Arcaro (my No. 36), who rode horses with distinction. But I
would no sooner have voted for Secretariat or Citation or Man O'
War than I would have voted for Richard Petty's car, as opposed to
Richard Petty, whom I did not vote for because, with all due
respect, I don't get this vroom-vroom business and never will.
</P>
<P>
   Now my friend Tony Kornheiser of the Washington Post _ let's
just say that if ``Seinfeld'' had a resident sportswriter it would
have been Tony Kornheiser _ did vote for Secretariat at No. 8.
Eight! Tony, Tony, Tony!
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten a tremendous amount of abuse from my friends,''
Kornheiser concedes. ``I understand if they see me coming, they
will probably walk on the other side of the street, or throw oats
in my path. And I do regret causing them pain from any association
with them. But if you're asking me, on a serious note, if there is
one spot left in the Top 50 for either Bonnie Blair or the horse,
I'm still taking the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   That's my Tony, now and forever a man of conviction.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, it gets worse. Roone Arledge, who should need no
introduction, put the horse at No. 4. More and more I believe, like
Mickey Rourke's Boogie in ``Diner,'' that there is a parallel
universe out there with things going on about which I know nothing.
</P>
<P>
   I can tell you one person who is very happy about the horse.
That would be Mark Shapiro, the 29-year-old ESPN producer who has
basically given up all semblance of a life for more than 2 1/2
years in order to produce the magnificent pieces on the Top 50,
which will culminate at 5 p.m. Sunday (Channel 5) with the
revelation of Nos. 2 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing that could have happened to us was Secretariat
coming in at No. 35,'' Shapiro reports. ``That got everyone's
attention. What that did was launch the controversy that is the
lifeblood of a series like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll itself was conducted in the fall of 1997. The results
had to be in by the end of that year so Shapiro and his staff could
start work producing the necessary 48 half-hour pieces for Nos. 50
through 3, and the pair of one-hour pieces for Nos. 2 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever anyone's feelings about the list itself, no one could
reasonably complain about ESPN's sincerity. The pieces have been
uniformly outstanding. They have been far from puff jobs, never
shying away from controversy. Many people were upset, for example,
that so much time in the Larry Bird piece was spent on the sadly
troubled relationship with his daughter from his brief teenage
marriage. When's the last time you heard a criticism like that on
the subject of an athlete's screen bio?
</P>
<P>
   In order to come up with 70 hours of programming, Shapiro and
his ``SportsCentury'' staff interviewed more than 1,600 people,
many of them more than once. They obtained footage from more than
300 sources and secured innumerable private personal items.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal from Day 1 was to enhance the understanding of the
impact sport has had on our society and culture, whether it's Jesse
Owens at Berlin, Jackie Robinson breaking the Major League Baseball
color barrier, gambling, Magic Johnson and AIDS, or whatever. And I
think we've done that.''
</P>
<P>
   You think voting for this list was easy? I beat myself up for
six weeks and still couldn't arrive at firm conclusions. You had to
evaluate true ``all-around'' athletes with documented prowess in
more than one sports discipline with extraordinary one-sport
achievers. You had to evaluate people who competed before radio
with people who have Web sites. You had to evaluate men vs. women.
</P>
<P>
   We were specifically instructed to ignore social impact and
concentrate exclusively on the actual achievement in the realm of
sport competition. That was, in the end, impossible. Each of my
first three choices happened to have been men whose auras far
transcended sport itself.
</P>
<P>
   The results we've seen thus far are revealing, if only to
demonstrate why a broad-based panel is essential. What seems like
the very definition of logical thought to one person who deeply
loves sport is quite often beyond the grasp of another. Forgetting
the horse for a minute, the single-most incomprehensible rating for
me was Bill Russell coming in at No. 18. My mind cannot grasp the
conceivable thought process of anyone who would leave him out of
any such Top 10. Then again, I wouldn't have voted for Bo Jackson
in my top 200, but Dick Schaap, who, I can assure you, is a
brilliant man, had him at No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   I knew from the start that hockey players would be unfairly
treated, just because. Bobby Orr at 31? All I can say is, ``Lord,
forgive them; they know not what they do.'' I suspect I had Orr
higher than any other voter (No. 8), and I likewise suspect no
other voter had as many hockey players (five) among their 50. And
they say I'm a basketball guy only . . .
</P>
<P>
   My own biggest goofs? (1) Jackie Robinson at 26. Dumb! Here I am
always going around pointing out to people that baseball was this
man's fourth-best sport (behind football, track and field, and
basketball), and then I stick him in the 20s? Mea culpa, mea culpa,
mea maxima culpa. (2) I should have had Babe Didrikson,
unquestionably the greatest female athlete of them all, somewhere
between 10 and 15, instead of at No. 20.
</P>
<P>
   My smugly proudest pick? Al Oerter at 49. This amazing man won
consecutive discus gold medals in Melbourne, Rome, Tokyo, and
Mexico City. In none was he the favorite. In each he set a personal
best. He deserves to be commemorated in such a list.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, my final four happen to be the Final Four.
On Friday night we discovered that Jim Brown was No. 4 and Muhammad
Ali was No. 3. Sunday we will learn who is No. 2 and who is No. 1,
between Babe Ruth and Michael Jordan. At this moment, the only two
people in the world who know which is which are Shapiro and ESPN
Magazine editor John Walsh. That's kinda cool.
</P>
<P>
   For me, it was The Babe, and it was an easy call. Baseball was
America's sport of choice for more years this century than anything
else, and Babe Ruth was unquestionably the greatest player (Hall of
Fame pitcher turned nonpareil slugger). Plus, he was an outsized
personality whose fame really was worldwide, a much harder
achievement in an era of limited communication than it was for Ali
or Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro might have made a serious career error. ``The fact is I
will never have the opportunity to cover this much ground, in this
much depth, in any project I will ever again be associated with,''
he sighs.
</P>
<P>
   Life is tough when you peak at 29. But at least he can go to his
grave knowing that, unlike Kornheiser, he didn't vote for a horse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
