<SLUG> BC-FBC-BEAMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAM SEASON FOR BEAMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How long ago was it now? Seven seasons? Seems like another
lifetime to Frank Beamer.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, no one was talking about Coach of the Year. No one
was mentioning multimillion-dollar contracts with annuities that
could set up his family for life.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Virginia Tech was a little school that couldn't and
most people didn't care. Hot coach? Well, if you consider a 20-40-2
record over six seasons ``hot'' then you probably think the weather
in Fargo in January is mild.
</P>
<P>
   If you look at the 2-8-1 mark posted by the Hokies in 1992 after
a 2-1 start, you can see why lots of people wanted to pay for
Beamer's bus ticket out of Blacksburg, Va., rather than do anything
to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   Beamer laughs about those days now. Just like Bobby Bowden
laughs about the times he was hanged in effigy when he was a young,
relatively unknown coach at West Virginia 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now Beamer wears the smile of a man who does have a
million-dollar annuity he can collect if he is still the coach at
Tech in 2005, with the security of a coach who will earn a
compensation package worth more than $500,000 this season and
probably more next when Beamer and Tech athletic director Jim
Weaver work out an even more lucrative package.
</P>
<P>
   Beamer can laugh with the confidence of a man whose team is
going to play for the national championship Jan. 4, when the
undefeated and second-ranked Hokies of Virginia Tech clash with
undefeated and No. 1 Florida State in the Sugar Bowl for the Bowl
Championship Series title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an unbelievable year,'' said Beamer last week as he
started preparations for the final phase of Tech's dream season.
``But we have to stay focused. We still have a job to do. We can't
lose sight of that. But it has kind of fallen into place. There
were days when I'm sure a lot of people wondered if this were
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Beamer as much as anyone knows about that. He has been coaching
at his alma mater for 13 seasons. He saw the bad times when he came
home after a stint at Murray State. He knows that it took seven
hard years just to get respectable. He has had to do some tough
things, such as firing half of his coaching staff after the 1992
crash, while wondering if the vote of confidence the administration
and former Tech athletic director Dave Braine gave him was really
backed by conviction.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1992 debacle, Tech started climbing, up the ladder of
the Big East, up the ladder of the national polls. Since 1993, Tech
has gone 64-19. The Sugar Bowl will mark Tech's seventh consecutive
bowl appearance, something only six other schools have achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Beamer had chances to leave. Nine years ago, Boston College made
a hard run at him. Former Eagles athletic director Chet Gladchuk,
looking for a replacement for Jack Bicknell, wanted Beamer.
</P>
<P>
   Gladchuk wined and dined Beamer and his wife, Cheryl.
</P>
<P>
   This was heady stuff for Beamer, who had a modest 12-9-1 record
at Tech at the time. The money was better, the package better, and
BC was in the Big East, which Tech was not at the time. It was the
big time. But Beamer had roots at Tech. In Virginia. He was a
little bit of country, and BC, despite its oasislike setting in
Chestnut Hill, was a lot of city.
</P>
<P>
   That's what you have to understand about Beamer. There's
ambition, but not blinding ambition. He grew up in a place called
Fancy Gap, an hour south of Blacksburg.
</P>
<P>
   Frank was the oldest of Herma and Raymond Beamer's four
children. Even now, after all these years, Frank is still ``Frank''
to the folks back in Fancy Gap. Herma's 82 now, and proud as could
be of her son. ``I just think he has a wonderful group of boys now
and some wonderful coaches,'' Herma told the Richmond
Times-Dispatch. ``He's done well for the state of Virginia and for
Virginia Tech and for Carroll County. I can't go anywhere without
someone talking about Frank and how proud they are of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more so considering that a childhood accident that nearly
killed him has left scars that are noticeable to this day.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1954, when Beamer was 7, he was burning some trash on
the family farm when a push broom he had been using got too close
to a can of gasoline. The smoldering handle ignited the gasoline
and the explosion engulfed Beamer.
</P>
<P>
   His younger brother pulled Beamer from the flames and rolled him
in the dirt. Beamer had major burns on his upper body and face,
which required 30 operations over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Beamer said he felt sorry for himself at first, but Herma and
Raymond wouldn't allow that to last too long. Other people had it
worse than you, they told him. Feel sorry for them.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was only 5 foot 9 inches and 170 pounds, Beamer
turned into a pretty fair quarterback at Hillsville High. He came
to Virginia Tech and switched to defense, where he was a three-year
starter as a defensive back. When he returned in 1987 as head
coach, Tech was the school he knew as a player. Small, remote, with
not a lot of big ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   It might have stayed that way if the calls to fire Beamer had
been answered in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wanted to fire Frank,'' said Braine, who is
now the athletic director at Georgia Tech. ``But I didn't think
Frank was the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite some financial problems facing the school, the
administration backed Beamer with more funding.
</P>
<P>
   Beamer also was told to make staff changes, a move that's most
often the final step before a head coach is dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Beamer always has been driven by a sense of loyalty, but his
instinct for survival was greater. To this day, Beamer says those
changes ``were the toughest thing I've done as a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially since Beamer felt the 2-8-1 season could have been
7-3-1, with the Hokies losing the lead and the game in the fourth
quarter of five of those losses.
</P>
<P>
   Changes, karma, coaches, whatever, Tech suddenly jumped to 8-3
in 1993 and went to the Independence Bowl, where it rolled over
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   From that point, it has been bowling season. And not just the
minor bowls. The Hokies already have been to the Sugar and Orange
bowls, again a hard-to-fathom occurrence for longtime Tech fans.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the rise was the formation of the Big East football
conference in 1991. As a member, Tech gained credibility and an
eventual spot in a BCS game.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, both Clemson and South Carolina made runs at Beamer.
Last month, there was talk that LSU might be interested.
</P>
<P>
   But Beamer is where he wants to be. He feels that Tech, like
Florida State, can compete with anyone. Scheduling has been a
problem because the Hokies have not played the best of the best,
with this year's nonconference games against Alabama-Birmingham and
Division 1-AA James Madison as prime examples.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hokies are slowly changing their image. Beamer says this
is what he envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day I was named coach here, I talked about winning a
national championship,'' said Beamer, conceding at the time it was
much more of a dream than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is one game, one victory away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
