<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-ROCKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKER SPITS IN FACE OF GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was only a few weeks ago that I found myself sitting
as a visiting journalist in the office of Atlanta Mayor Bill
Campbell. The subject was ``affirmative action.'' Not once did
anyone mention the name John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   But now we hear it every day, and that is sad. One can pity a
fool who makes a mistake and vows to never do it again. One can
only be angry at a man who spits out offensive comments that come
down on so many that he could apologize until he's blue in the face
and still not come across as someone who understands what the fuss
is all about. Well, maybe he should listen to a few things.
</P>
<P>
   These thoughts come not just from a black person associated with
Major League Baseball for more than 40 years. His remarks fly in
the face of a new era of world participation in the Grand Old Game.
A fine would be too little. And players rarely are suspended or
reprimanded by their clubs for making inappropriate comments.
</P>
<P>
   An immediate trade would also be a mistake. In these times,
players who are tarnished yet talented grow in value with every
offense. Like Lawrence Phillips in football, Rocker is worth a lot
of money. I wouldn't give you 2 cents for him. But somebody will.
Rocker had 33 saves last year and was a key for the Braves reaching
the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday, I hadn't even read the article in Sports
Illustrated in which Rocker becomes the most famous racist from the
state of Georgia since Ty Cobb. There are a lot of John Rockers out
there. Cobb was a beauty, too, and perhaps the comparison fits.
Flying spikes and a razor tongue that didn't hesitate to spit out
the ``N'' word were his specialty. Away from baseball, he was just
another miserable human being who had no idea what it meant for a
man of limited education and no people skills to be part of the
great game of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, he's in the baseball Hall of Fame. The world was
different when Cobb played and there was no Jackie Robinson or
Henry Aaron to refute his racist comments. There was no Al Campanis
to publicly remind us of the low esteem in which blacks were held
by the Ol' Guard who ran the game in the 1950s-70s. There weren't
enough men like Wendell Smith or Sam Lacy, both sports editors of
black newspapers of the time. Blacks back then never took Cobb
personally. Rocker might not be so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   If you run into John Rocker, you are allowed to tell him that
you disagree with his remarks in SI. His hatred for New York fans
and the thought of playing there are not grounds for damnation. Any
Red Sox fan can understand that part of it. But you have to draw
the line when he says he wouldn't play for a New York team because
he didn't want to ride the train to Yankee Stadium and sit next to
some ``queer with AIDS.'' It is a vicious thing to say about people
who, through no fault of their own, have had their lives affected,
no shortened, by a devastating medical problem. Sorry, you're out
of bounds, John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   I can say that with some conviction. I made the same mistake in
my comments about AIDS after Magic Johnson made his announcement. I
wrote that I knew the man personally and was not surprised because
of his lifestyle. That was wrong to say. I had, by inference,
placed AIDS and sexual behavior on the same plane. I should have
written about the courage of a man who, in a simple statement, had
turned his life around and become a leader in a field that
desperately needed one. The people who called me aren't ever going
to forgive me for my insensitivity. They certainly won't think well
of John Shocker. I understand.
</P>
<P>
   And I feel the same way about his remarks bashing immigrants.
``I'm not a fan of foreigners,'' Rocker said after naming a half
dozen of them. ``How the hell did they get into this country?'' He
called a black teammate a ``fat monkey.'' I wonder what boat his
ancestors took across the Atlantic? But I digress.
</P>
<P>
   Knocking blacks, Hispanics, Russians, and Japanese is just
reaffirmation that Rocker has no clue as to the struggles that took
place in baseball and in this country. It is the dollars that they
spend that allow him to have a comfortable lifestyle. I have paid
all my life. I expect the best out of every professional athlete.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1940s, I went to Comiskey Park and watched the White
Sox from a bleacher section called ``Watermelon Hill.'' In 1970, I
returned to the park after a 20-year absence and sat in the press
box for the first time. John Rocker should know about ``fat
monkeys'' like me. Just before he came to the majors, I saw Hall of
Famer Satchel Paige in the Negro League All-Star Game from the same
seat at Comiskey. I was watching the best pitcher who ever lived.
Nobody is going to ever say that about John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose nobody bothered to tell you about baseball's push for
diversity which, since 1975, has swelled minority participation to
21 percent, according to the commissioner's office. I'm not just
talking about blacks. Yes, they were the ones who saved the game
from extinction after World War II. But there were only 16 teams
then and owners had the reserve clause on their side to control the
ebb and flow of all minorities. Blacks and Hispanics were still not
seen as part of the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   But they are now in a ``sport'' where the net worth is counted
in billions of dollars. The number of baseball millionaires goes up
each year. The demand for foreign players has skyrocketed steadily,
first from Latin America and now from Japan and Korea. How in the
hell did they get into this country? We begged them to come, that's
how. They're helping us rebuild stadiums and entire communities.
Two years of Pedro Martinez in Boston have done more for relations
between the city and the Dominican Republic than you could buy for
a million dollars. Are you listening, John Rocker?
</P>
<P>
   All of this is to say that baseball has become an international
environment stressing cooperation and team work. It should not
surprise anyone that Rocker is getting no support from the Braves.
There is a war against intolerance going on in Atlanta and those on
the front line can get along very well without the likes of Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   I respect the word of Braves pitching coach Leo Mazzone. We were
in Japan in 1998 with some touring major league All-Stars. He saw
the wave of international approval from their fans and the effect
it can have on players. If he is not careful, Rocker will lose even
a chance to go there and find out for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of his teammates might punch him out,'' Mazzone said.
``Something's going to go wrong now with his career. And you watch
it, it'll end up going straight down the tubes.''
</P>
<P>
   No chance, Leo. This is America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
