</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-ANDERSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON MAKING THOSE AROUND HIM BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ With the first consecutive double doubles
recorded on his 1999-2000 resume last week, Kenny Anderson hopes to
maintain that consistency as the Celtics go west for three games,
starting Sunday afternoon at the Staples Center, home of the Los
Angeles Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran point guard clicked for 21 points and 10 assists in
the Celtics' 99-90 loss last Monday against the Lakers and followed
that with 13 points and 10 more assists in Boston's 98-81 blowout
of the Hawks on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are making the shots, so they're helping me out, too,''
said Anderson after practice Friday at HealthPoint. ``Guys are
spacing the court out and doing well in transition and we've been
finishing our plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is basically simple. At times, we all as players,
including myself, can make it difficult. If the man is open, hit
him with the pass. If not, take your shot. Part of the definition
of a point guard is to make your teammates around you better.''
</P>
<P>
   Two players who should be involved in the mix as the road trip
progresses are Danny Fortson and Paul Pierce. It will be part of
Anderson's task to help ease them back into the offense. Fortson
(stress fracture) will likely see action Sunday. Pierce (ankle) is
taking it day to day; there's a possibility he'll be activated
before the West Coast swing comes to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny has a nice jumper in the lane and he's a big bruiser,
but I don't think he's worried about points,'' said Anderson. ``His
main goal is to play tough defense and rebound and the other parts
of his game will come around.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who has shot at a .515 clip (35 for 68) in his last
five games, said his role as catalyst and playmaker takes
precedence over trying to get 20 or 30 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antoine (Walker) and Paul (Pierce) are the two guys who put up
the shots,'' Anderson said, ``and if their point guard is putting
up a lot of shots, that just creates too much confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main thing is to get everybody involved and if my shot is
there, take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting out to a big lead against Atlanta _ and keeping it _ was
a step in the right direction for the Celtics, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was definitely an important game, especially before
hitting the road. We need to learn how to maintain second-half
leads, especially on the road,'' he said. ``We need to get tough if
we want to be a playoff team, and to be a playoff team, you need to
win on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson hopes the good karma from giving the Lakers a battle to
the end and then dominating the Hawks at home _ plus having Fortson
and Pierce back _ will change the team's fortunes away from the
FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a win and got off the (losing streak) slide,'' he said.
``But lately, our problem has been that we cannot close the door in
the fourth quarter. These games coming up are definitely winnable.
We just need to show up for all four quarters. The Clippers
(Sunday), Sacramento (Tuesday), and Denver (Thursday) are all
playing well. We are going to need to be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Celtics coach Rick Pitino, who will play Pierce sparingly after
he is activated, said Pierce and Fortson should be back in the flow
by Jan. 3. ``They'll get filtered in and get some minutes, but I
expect they'll be into the offense and defense by that date,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said he's not counting any W's in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we play like we did against Atlanta, we can beat anybody,
the way we passed and distributed the ball and played defense,'' he
said. ``The Clippers have a lot of offensive firepower, and
transition defense will be a key for us. When we pass, we can be an
excellent team. We took one bad shot the entire game against
Atlanta and that's almost unheard of. Antoine's passing out of the
post and Kenny's distributing on the perimeter were big factors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
