<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO REST FOR CELTICS OUT WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Celtics are in Los Angeles Sunday. That means, on the
surface, they have a 50-50 chance of leaving the City of Angels
with a much-needed road win.
</P>
<P>
   They lucked out. They got the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional Day-After-Christmas Clipper mashing was a Celtic
staple in the 1980s. They'd get on a plane on Christmas and take
out their fury the next night on the hapless Clips. Clippers owner
Donald Sterling would be watching at courtside with a lovely
companion, remarking how much he admires the Celtics and Red
Auerbach and hopes one day to be like them.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed a bit. The Clippers are still the Clippers,
sort of, but the Celtics are sporting a nine-game road losing
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game will be the first of three straight Western
Conference roadies for Rick Pitino's boys. They'll also play at
Sacramento Tuesday (on TNT) and then finish in Denver Thursday. If
they haven't gotten a road win by then, well, it won't happen in
Denver. Their best chance will come with Sunday afternoon's game at
the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino could well have his full roster for the first time. Danny
Fortson has been activated, a little ahead of schedule. Paul Pierce
is sure to follow. All three opponents have been battling injuries.
All in all, it should not be an overly grueling, demanding ordeal.
The Celtics could even win all three. Then again . . .
</P>
<P>
   LA CLIPPERS (Sunday): This game will be worth watching if for no
other reason than to see Lamar Odom, who is the consensus leader in
the Rookie of the Year race. He is making a few teams look dumb in
passing him over _ the Bulls come to mind _ and has done what
hardly anyone has been able to do in quite some time: make the
Clippers viewable. And, the Clippers have won eight games,
including the last two with former Salem State head man Jimmy Todd
at the reins. (Chris Ford is out with back spasms.) On the surface,
it looks like the Celtics should get this one. But they also should
have won in Chicago, Philadelphia, and Houston. And the Clippers
are fresh off a home killing of the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Boston has won five of the last seven meetings between these
titans. But the Clippers of 1999-2000 have a decent front line
(when healthy), and Derek Anderson leads them in scoring. They
won't be pushovers; they've got only three fewer victories than the
Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO (Tuesday): The Kings are now the darlings of the
networks with Jason Williams and Chris Webber.Too bad they're not
the darlings of the division. They also have slowed down a mite
after a fabulous start, which featured a lot of games in ARCO
Arena. They are tough at home (9-2), and this one will be a
nationally televised affair. The Celtics dropped a close one here
last season and are 0-2 in the California capital in Pitino's
reign. The Celtics have a chance in this one for one simple reason:
The Kings don't defend very well. (Neither do the Celtics, for that
matter.) But Sacramento is one of a handful of teams (eight,
actually) allowing more than 100 points a game, while its shooting
has been awful (43 percent) most of the season. The Kings also have
been in a bit of a rut lately, including Thursday's loss to the
Clippers at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   DENVER (Thursday): Think the Nuggets will be after a little
payback? Denver easily is the surprise team of the West and already
has won more games than the horrible team of two years ago. They
have victories over the Lakers, Knicks, and, most recently, the
Spurs and Trail Blazers, back to back. (They also lost to Vancouver
on Thursday.) Antonio McDyess is finally getting his health back
(he was bothered by an ankle sprain) and Denver has been tough at
its new home, the Pepsi Center (10-3). They won't have much trouble
remembering the flogging they got in Boston Dec. 8. The final was
115-90 and Ron Mercer, in particular, will be looking for a better
showing. He can't do much worse. He was 1 of 6 and Pierce blocked
his first two shots. This one also will mark Fortson's first game
against his ex-mates. Chauncey Billups, meanwhile, won't play again
this season. He will have surgery Monday to fix his dislocated left
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, the president of the Philadelphia 76ers, Pat
Croce, began what was to have been an ocean-to-ocean motorcycle
trip. He never made it out of Philly. While waiting out a
rainstorm, one of the motorcycles in Croce's group skidded into
Croce's left leg and, well, he'll tell the rest. ``I'm in the
middle of the street and I see my boot is off. So I pick it up and
what's inside? My foot. It was hanging there, with only my
Achilles' tendon holding it together.'' He was taken to the
hospital _ ``Thank God it happened where it did,'' he said _ where
he had to sign a release approving the amputation of the foot. It
never came to that. Since that day, Croce has had four operations _
a fifth was postponed at the last moment _ and only recently has he
started taking what he calls ``baby steps'' around his house. He's
still on crutches and there's no timetable on when, or if, he'll
regain the full use of the limb. ``It's in the hands of the Great
Man Upstairs,'' he said. ``But I think he's smiling. I just want to
be able to walk on the beach this summer.'' The word irrepressible
doesn't even begin to describe Croce. ``You realize that life is so
fragile,'' he said. ``In one three-week time frame, I went from
being Jimmy Cagney, on top of the world after we beat Orlando, to
lying down there in that street.'' He's also come to realize how
his indomitable spirit has touched others. When word of his
accident hit the public, the hospital switchboard had to be closed
due to the number of phone calls. Fans and friends dressed up like
doctors to get in to see him. Now, he gets mail from people he
doesn't know who heard about his plight and have a sad tale of
their own. He calls them up out of the blue. ``I even got a call
from a guy in Boston.'' He adds, ``I'm doing great. These last two
weeks are the best I've felt since the accident.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Are you wondering, like a lot of us are, why Shaquille O'Neal is
suddenly playing the way he should have been playing all those
years ago? Namely, that he's rebounding. And blocking shots. Well,
Brian Shaw, his former teammate in Orlando and his current teammate
with the Lakers, thinks he has the answer: coaching. ``He has
matured a lot and he has accepted coaching much better,'' Shaw said
of O'Neal. ``Before, he was just so dominant, it didn't matter what
anyone told him. He just went out and did it his way. The respect
factor with Phil (Jackson) has made a big difference. It's easy to
buy into his system when you see all the success he had with it.''
. . . John Calipari is drawing interest from Memphis University
(formerly Memphis State). There is an interim coach there and
apparently contact has been made between Cal and the school. It's
an interesting situation for Calipari. Memphis plays in a
competitive conference (USA) with the likes of Cincinnati and
Louisville. It's literally the only game in town, and the team
plays in a modern, 21,000-seat arena. If he won there, Cal would
own the place. The one drawback could be money. Whatever, Cal plans
to stay alongside Larry Brown in Philly for the year . . . Alert
reader Jim Carvin of North Easton picked up an astonishingly
egregious omission in the Globe's top 100 athlete series: Bill
Sharman. Especially when you consider that Dennis Johnson, Tom
Heinsohn, Reggie Lewis, and KC Jones made it. Sharman not only is a
Hall of Famer, but, unlike DJ, Heinsohn, Jones, he was a member of
both the NBA's 25th and 50th anniversary teams. That's right. He
was named one of the 50 greatest players of all time in the NBA,
yet he didn't crack the Globe's top 100. For some unexplained
reason, Sharman tends to slip through the cracks when the topic
turns to great Celtics. Maybe it's a subconscious thing because he
spent all those years with the Lakers. But there's no way Sharman
shouldn't be in there as no worse than the ninth-best Celtic after
Bill Russell, Larry Bird, Bob Cousy, John Havlicek, Sam Jones,
Kevin McHale, Dave Cowens, and Robert Parish . . . And while we're
on the topic, where was Richie Hebner?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We've now got six high schoolers who could likely crack the
first round of the 2000 NBA draft if they came out en masse.
(That's a real encouraging thought.) We've already noted three of
them: Eddie Griffin of Philadelphia Roman Catholic (committed to
Seton Hall), Gerald Wallace of Childersburg, Ala. (committed to
Alabama); and Darius Miles of East St. Louis, Ill. (committed to
St. John's). We can now add DeShawn Stevenson of Fresno, Calif.,
Washington Union (committed to Kansas); Jerome ``Buddy'' Harper,
who has bounced around from high school to high school, but who has
signed with Cincinnati; and Alton Ford, a banger from Houston Milby
who has committed to Clyde Drexler's University of Houston Cougars.
No NBA official can comment on the record about these lads, but the
word is that Griffin, Wallace, and Miles all could go in the top 15
if they came out . . . Billups, meanwhile, couldn't have picked a
worse time to have surgery. He has gone downhill in most everyone's
view since being taken No. 3 in the 1997 draft. But he also has
shown there's a place for him in the league. Still, to have
season-ending surgery in your free agent year is not good timing.
``I just wanted to be healthy,'' he said. ``It was a tough
decision. I wanted to tough it out. But at the same time, it gets
looser every time.'' What this means for Billups is no long-term
extension. He'll probably re-up for a couple years until he shows
he can play again . . . Speaking of short-term re-upping, that's
the likely path Tim Duncan will follow if he decides to stay in San
Antonio. He would be foolish to sign a seven-year extension with
the Spurs, because 90 percent of the team will be in rest homes
when that deal expires. Look for him to sign for two or three years
unless he bolts for Orlando. That would enable him to ride into the
South Texas sunset with David Robinson, Avery Johnson, and the
other San Antonio graybeards . . . Allen Iverson and Brown had yet
another dust-up this past week. Here's one of Iverson's comments on
the brouhaha. ``It'll never happen again, man. I owe myself an
apology for putting myself in this situation.'' . . . Miami won a
big game Wednesday night at home over the Jazz, despite not having
either Tim Hardaway or Jamal Mashburn. Hardaway missed his 14th
straight game due to a jammed knee, while Mashburn was out with a
bum ankle . . . Tuesday night's game against Minnesota will be the
Heat's final game in Miami Arena . . . Speaking of the
Timberwolves, they got their first victory ever in Chicago
Wednesday night. They won by 20. ``For all the years that they
freakin' destroyed people, it's payback time,'' said Sam Mitchell.
``If you can't beat 'em by 50, by God, beat 'em by 60. They're
gonna get drilled.'' Everybody is piling on Chicago, which is on a
seven-win pace for the season, or two games behind the all-time
worst NBA team, the 9-73 Philadelphia 76ers from 1972-73.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 0031EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
