<SLUG> BC-HKO-MINOR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIRATES RECLAIM HIDDEN TREASURES 
</HEADLINE>
 LEAGUE NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY VAN HANDLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Whether it was winning a championship in their initial
season, developing future NHL players, or attracting a dedicated
fan base, the Portland Pirates knew little but success in their
first half-decade in the American Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Until last season. The Pirates skidded to last place in the
Atlantic Division with the AHL's second-worst record and no
postseason berth for the first time since entering the league.
</P>
<P>
   But a year later, order has been restored in Maine's largest
city. With more than a third of the AHL season in the books, the
Portland Pirates and their three AHL All-Star selections are the
first-place team in the New England Division.
</P>
<P>
   With players like Byron Dafoe, Olaf Kolzig, Jason Allison,
Sergei Gonchar, Brendan Witt, Anson Carter, and Andrew Brunette at
one time wearing Pirate black and red, it's not surprising that,
along with its Calder Cup victory, Portland went to the finals
another season while leading the AHL in sellouts two years running.
After five straight postseason appearances, a playoff berth had
become a foregone conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   But last season's 23-48-2-7 disaster and drop in attendance
jolted the Pirates and parent club Washington into revitalizing the
team. But unlike some who turn around their fortunes by adding
fresh talent and a new coach, the Pirates expanded on that formula
by reacquiring former key players they had let slip away.
</P>
<P>
   Step 1 was hiring Glen Hanlon to his first head coaching job
after five seasons as an assistant with the Vancouver Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   Then the International Hockey League yielded three key players
from years past. Center Jeff Nelson, a member of the Pirates'
Calder Cup team, and Brown's Ryan Mulhern, who had been a steady
contributor for two seasons, were plucked out of the International
Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brochu, who was loaned to the ``I'' last season and wound
up being sidelined by injury, also became a full-time Pirate again.
His presence helped stabilize a shaky goaltending situation, which
allowed the fourth-most goals in the league last year, and he's
also aided in the development of prospect Sebastian Charpentier.
Brochu (14-7-5, 2.18 goals-against average) was named to start for
the Canadian team in next month's AHL All-Star Game in Rochester,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters like left wings Alexandre Volchkov, Washington's No.
1 draft choice in 1996 and an All-Star starter, and Miika Elomo
(another All-Star selection) have blended with veterans such as
high-scoring Glen Metropolit, former Bruins defenseman Jamie
Huscroft, defensemen Steve Poapst and center Kent Hulst, the latter
two joining Nelson as original Pirates. The mix has enabled the
Pirates to go 16-11-7; last season, Portland didn't earn its 16th
win until Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Albeit on a smaller scale, the Pirates are mirroring the
Providence Bruins' record-setting revival of last season. Like
Portland, the Bruins were a last-place team before an infusion of
new talent and a new coach helped them rise to the top of the AHL,
though the Pirates (nor anyone else) will come close to
Providence's record of a year ago (56-16-4-4).
</P>
<P>
   But that won't stop the rest of the New England Division from
trying. Only 13 points separate first from worst _ and only 3
points between first and third _ in by far the league's toughest
and most well-balanced division.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Hartford is closest to Portland. The WolfPack's many
minor league veterans, among them goalie Jean-Francois Labbe,
30-year-old left wing Ken Gernander, and right wing Derek
Armstrong, All-Star picks, along with former Bruins draft pick
Daniel Goneau and New Hampshire's Todd Hall, both left wings,
should keep the Pack right in the pack.
</P>
<P>
   It would be unrealistic to expect Providence to equal its
supernova of a 1998-99 season, but the days of the Baby B's taking
up the rear of their division are long over.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Providence can thank right wings Chris and Peter
Ferraro and left wing Andre Savage, its All-Star representatives,
in large measure for that. As well, center Tim Lovell, the former
UMass-Amherst center, still is among the team's leading scorers
despite being slowed by a late November shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   Springfield and Worcester are likely to be fighting for the last
playoff spot. The Falcons have relied on center Eric Healy of Hull
and Brad Tiley (the AHL's leading scorer from the blue line), their
All-Stars. David Cullen, who played on Maine's NCAA championship
team last season, and Harvard's Sean McCann also have held up their
end defensively. Steven King, a Brown grad who was a key component
of Providence's playoff run last season, has been battling injuries
most of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Among Worcester's top guns are a pair of wings with
Massachusetts ties. Marty Reasoner, Boston College's Hobey Baker
finalist from two years ago, is tied for fourth in the AHL in
scoring (13-20-33) and is an All-Star selection. Worcester native
Jim Campbell remains on loan from St. Louis, while center Ladislav
Nagy, St. Louis's sixth draft choice in 1997 (177th overall), is
the IceCats' other Star. Jamie Thompson, who played collegiately at
Maine, is in his second year with Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not only a geographical curiosity that Lowell is the only
non-Canada-based member of the Atlantic Division, but given that
more Lock Monsters have ties to this area than any New England
Division team, it also is more than a little ironic. More than a
quarter of the Lock Monsters' lineup played college hockey in these
parts, including New Hampshire's Jason Krog, last year's Hobey
Baker winner who was named AHL Rookie of the Month for November on
the strength of 10 points in 11 games and is 4-14-18, fourth on the
team in scoring. The little center also got an NHL call and played
four games with the Islanders, one of Lowell's two parent clubs.
Yale's Ray Giroux, a two-time All-Star selection who also got a
taste of Long Island recently and was named an All-Star for the
second straight season, and Rich Brennan (Boston University) are
two of the team's top defensemen. Up front, left wing Dave Hymovitz
(Boston College) is Lowell's third-leading scorer (9-10-19), and
earlier this month, center Greg Bullock, Hockey East's leading
scorer in 1995, signed with the Lock Monsters after spending a
little over two seasons in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former New England collegians will be sprinkled all over the ice
at the AHL's All-Star Game next month; actually, they're all over
the minors as well. Center Eric Boguniecki, who was Krog's
predecessor as New Hampshire's go-to offensive threat, spent two
seasons predominantly in the IHL and last summer signed with
Florida as a free agent. Originally a sixth-round choice by St.
Louis in 1993 out of Westminster Prep, Boguniecki has developed as
a Top 15 scorer in the AHL (15-14-29) and was selected to start in
the All-Star Game . . . Syracuse's Chris O'Sullivan, ex of BU, was
chosen to start for the second straight year on defense, though
he's currently on recall to Vancouver. Vermont's Martin St. Louis,
who has seen considerable time on left wing in Calgary this season,
nonetheless was chosen to start as a Saint John rep . . . Two more
from BU's seemingly never-empty well, left wing Doug Friedman and
defenseman Jon Coleman, have helped Kentucky to the AHL's best
record (44 points) . . . Rochester (41) isn't far behind, thanks to
leading scorer Jason Cipolla of Yale (10-18-28) . . . Former BC
goalie Scott Lagrand leads the East Coast Hockey League with five
shootout wins for Pensacola . . . Brian Regan, who played four
seasons for UMass-Amherst, leads the United Hockey League in
goals-against average; his 1.89 with the Missouri River Otters is
more than half a goal better than his closest competition . . . It
was a great night for a Gretzky as Brent Gretzky, the Great One's
27-year-old brother, had an 8-point night with Asheville in the UHL
earlier this month. Gretzky has had only two brief stints in the
NHL, none since 1995 . . . Center Mike Omicioli burned up the ECHL
with 21 points in his first dozen games with Hampton Roads,
including a 6-point game, to earn a mid-November recall to
Portland. The rookie out of Providence College is currently on the
injured list . . . The IHL will hold its All-Star Game next month;
the rosters have yet to be announced but the coaches will be Utah's
Bob Bourne and Milwaukee's Al Sims.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The concept of road trip was taken to its literal extreme
earlier this month by Providence, which traveled 1,200 miles _ all
via highways and byways _ to play three games in less than 48
hours. The first leg of the long weekend was easy: a trip to
Springfield for a Friday night game. The Baby B's left immediately
afterward on a 234-mile jaunt to Wilkes-Barre/Scranton, Pa., for a
Saturday night game. Then it was off to Hamilton, Ontario, and
another 362 miles on the bus's odometer for a 4 p.m. faceoff the
following day. The longest part of the trip back home, a distance
of 516 miles, was the easiest part to take . . . At least the
Bruins' trip was limited to one weekend. How about Louisville,
which spent a month away from home due to scheduling conflicts at
Freedom Hall? The Panthers played 15 straight games away from home,
and at one point lived in hotels for 20 consecutive days while
logging more than 5,000 travel miles. Remarkably, Louisville went
9-6-0-1 to stay well within range of first place in the
Mid-Atlantic Division . . . Logo of the Week: Despite the Devils'
success, hockey hasn't usually been synonymous with the state of
New Jersey. But if early signs are any indication, the ECHL's
Trenton Titans are helping to change that perception. The Titans
have sold more than 5,000 season tickets and average more than
7,000 fans a game in their new 8,000-seat downtown arena. The
youngsters in the crowd have taken to the team's mascot Clash,
which resembles the figure in the team's logo pictured stepping
over the city's railroad bridge. Given that Trenton was once known
as a center of the steel industry, is it safe to assume that the
opposition will have trouble testing the Titans' mettle?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 0034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
