<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT IS ON BURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The alarm sounded here early when the Bruins went into
their recent tailspin _ resulting in a grim 2-6-3 after Tuesday's
3-1 loss to the Nashville neophytes _ because that's what we do
here in the shoot-the-messenger business.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not out front, sounding the bell for the disaster in
the making, the boss turns around and asks why you're writing about
Benny Lachanoix's infected bunion when suddenly one day the sky
falls (with a receipt fluttering down from a non-union contractor).
</P>
<P>
   If you are out front, and the thought that, say, the coach could
be fired never comes to fruition, then everyone first enjoys a good
ol' belly laugh at your expense and then accuses you of stirring
the pot just to sell papers (which, if true, would make the
National Enquirer the only paper in the Lower 48).
</P>
<P>
   But believe this: As good a coach as he is, Pat Burns could walk
the plank here in the next few days, no doubt to be replaced by
Providence (AHL) coach Peter Laviolette. That's not to say Burns
will get canned as the Bruins coach. But that's just the way the
business of the Bruins is run. In fact, it's the way virtually
every pro sports franchise is run, with coaches, even proven and
knowledgeable coaches, just part of the hired help _ and often,
just the built-in excuse for myriad bad decisions, be they
financial, personnel, or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot to like about Burns as coach, and frankly that's
why he hasn't already been fired. But we remind you: His club
opened with an 0-5-4 record, the Black and Gold's worst start in 35
years. Meld that in with a 2-6-3 stretch, and you have a total of
20 games, a quarter of the season, with a promising club stumbling
along with a .100 winning percentage. A coach without Burns's
proven track record, resume, and guaranteed future earnings (no
small part of the equation) already would be gone.
</P>
<P>
   What's gone wrong here? To a degree, and perhaps most
significantly, it's a coach getting tuned out by his players. If it
can happen to the likes of Al Arbour _ and it did, even after he
won four straight Cups on the Island _ it can happen to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The players here may be faithful to Burns's words, and repeat
the mantra about ``sticking to the system,'' but there's a huge
difference between reciting the game plan like a bunch of Stepford
Wives and executing the game plan. For much of the last month,
Burns's charges merely have been exercising a walk-through, as if
reading the lines in the school play with opening night three
months down the road. Every coach can expect, even accept, a
handful of nights like those during an 82-game schedule. But the
toll is now up to 20-plus, with not even half the season gone. The
curtain's up, boys, and the audience expects results.
</P>
<P>
   But for a precious few _ the reliable likes of Ray Bourque, Rob
DiMaio, and Don Sweeney _ the Bruins right now are emotionlessly
going through the motions. They don't forecheck. They don't hit.
They manage to move the puck out of their own end _ and that's
become harder than ever _ and chop it through the neutral zone and
usually just fizz out once over the offensive blue line. The team
logo is a 180-foot U-turn. They melt shapelessly into the ice. At
the most rudimentary level, they just don't skate.
</P>
<P>
   OK, let's consider the missing pieces from last season when,
admittedly, there were signs of this unfolding when the Bruins were
rubbed out in Round 2 of the playoffs by Buffalo. They dropped
Carolina in Round 1, despite the fact that one of their bona fide
forwards, Dmitri Khristich, pulled the chute well before the finish
of the regular season. It was easily forgotten _ but very telling _
that they won the opener in Round 2 and then barely could get out
of their own way for the remainder of the series, which left club
president/general manager Harry Sinden teeing off on Khristich and
Jason Allison after another failed Cup run.
</P>
<P>
   Khristich is now in Toronto. Tim Taylor is in New York. Grant
Ledyard plays for Ottawa, Dave Ellett for St. Louis, and Ken
Baumgartner is one of Burns's aides de camp. Landon (of the Lost)
Wilson is back in Providence (deservedly so). Ken Belanger can't
stop the buzz in his head (post-concussion syndrome).
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I wouldn't have Khristich, no matter how effective,
on my team. He quit last season. Who needs that? Bring me the heads
of Jay Miller or Bob Sweeney before another Khristich. Heck, give
Anders Brostrom another twirl.
</P>
<P>
   The big losses above are Taylor, Wilson (who floored me with his
postseason performance), and Belanger _ a bona fide tough guy, with
a good shot, decent wheels, and some, shall we say, gumption. Of
the bunch, Taylor was the single biggest loss. He didn't put up
points, but he played with nerve, took two or three shots to numb
various pains before each Buffalo game, and was a reliable faceoff
guy. The front office's indifference toward signing him _ remember,
he got no offer _ sent a disturbing message to the dressing room.
To wit: virtually all of you are interchangeable widgets. But
Taylor was more, much more, and nothing bums out a room full of
widgets than realizing that they are a room full of widgets.
Widgets thrive when they're made to feel important. Taylor's outing
delivered half the room to the doorstep of Lilliput and their games
have shrunk.
</P>
<P>
   On top of all this is the greatest ongoing rub of all, the fact
that Providence won the Calder Cup, giving Mssrs. Sinden and Mike
O'Connell the confidence to can Taylor, Ellett, Ledyard et al, but
precious few of the proud Baby B's have surfaced in the Hub.
According to the front-office game plan, two or three or four of
those kids should be here now and contributing. But the promise of
youth has turned into the ugly reality of rent-a-wrecks Marty
McSorley and Joe Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Burns's game plan isn't working, and that's truly the players'
fault.
</P>
<P>
   The front-office game plan isn't working, and ultimately that
will be Burns's fault. Count on it.
</P>
<P>
   Burns could be right, and maybe none of these kids can play. But
he might as well be wrong, because Sinden and O'Connell aren't
going to say their game plan failed. If so, they'd be the first two
front-office employees in pro sports ever to say it.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, kids come and go from Providence, but no one sticks,
beyond the bit roles played by Joe Hulbig and Joel Prpic. Cameron
Mann looked like he was turning into something last season; today,
he's agate type in the Hockey News. Burns doesn't believe many of
them can play here and be true contributors. Some he's found to be
OK _ Brandon Smith, Jeff Zehr, to a certain extent Jay Henderson _
only to be miffed when management shovels them back to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   If the product stays flat, Sinden and O'Connell will can Burns
and say that they expected better play and better results from the
coach and his team, that they believe the kids in the pipeline can
play big-league hockey, and out with the old and in with the new.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the chance that these kids can cut it here, but
that would be left to Laviolette to prove.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just to provide his players with a refresher course in reality,
Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff ordered the team bus to detour through
Harlem during the Sabres' visit to the Manhattan last week. The
next night, they showed some spark in a 3-1 victory over the
Blueshirts. Keep in mind: The average per annum on any given NHL
bus is about $1.4 million per man . . . Dallas owner Tom Hicks
spent about $1 million for the 175 Stanley Cup rings that were
delivered earlier this month. Not everyone received the the most
expensive copies (est. value: $20,000), which have four Australian
green diamonds, in the shape of a star, as the centerpiece . . .
Ex-Bruins winger Andy Brickley, last seen as Channel 38's colorman
alongside Dave Shea, has partnered twice this season with Fred
Cusick for telecasts of Lowell Lock Monsters (AHL) games. ``I've
enjoyed doing it again,'' said Brickley, who stopped by the Vault
Tuesday morning to take in the Bruins' day-of-game skate. ``In all
modesty, it reminded me that's what I should be doing again, in
some capacity.'' . . . The deal that brought ex-Panther Kirk Muller
back to the game (Dallas) was for a pro-rated $300,000 _ about
$190,000, or less than 10 cents on the dollar compared to the $2
million he made last year. The fact that so many old guys have come
in for relatively short money no doubt will influence what owners
will pay restricted (Group 2) free agents in July. Muller also gets
about $3,500 for any game in which he plays more than 10 minutes .
. . Edmonton recently hired former slick forward Anders Hedberg as
its European pro scout. Hedberg was jockeying for position to
become the Leafs' GM last year, alongside Mike Smith, but
ultimately it was head coach Pat Quinn who added the GM duties.
Smith is now running the Blackhawk makeover . . . The NHL contends
that, league-wide, it is spending 133 percent of its gate receipts
to cover player payroll. That means the cash taken in for every
seat in every building for every game goes directly to the players'
pockets, and then the owners have to cull one-third more from other
revenue streams just to pay the help. If true, this is a league
that needs: (1) a field trip to the Money Store; (2) 29 copies of
``Mathematics for Dummies,'' or (3) some of that creative Bruce
McNall bookkeeping . . . Ex-Bruin Jozef Stumpel, sidelined since
undergoing Nov. 8 hernia surgery, returned to the LA lineup
Wednesday night . . . Bostonian Larry Holden will handle the Uwe
Krupp-Detroit Red Wings arbitration case (no date set yet). Krupp,
signed to a four-year, $16.4 million free agent deal in the summer
of '98, has played only 22 games for the Wings, claiming his back
is too bad to get back on the ice. The Wings turned indignant _ and
then refused to pay _ when Krupp was spotted mushing his huskies,
his long-time passion. Word around the Winged Wheels is that Krupp
finally has provided the Wings with his medical records, what had
been a lingering and contentious issue. The bet here: the Wings, at
best, buy Krupp out at two-thirds the remaining value of the
contract (around $8 million-plus) or Krupp settles for slightly
less rather than risk having Holden void the pact.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Word around the rink has it that Ray Bourque could be getting
into the rink-ownership business, just north of the Hub, possibly
in a partnership with the MDC. Steve Freyer, Bourque's longtime
agent and friend, said last week, ``I don't think it's prudent for
me or Ray to be commenting about what his business plans could be.
A key to his success has always been his focus, and right now _
just as he has been for 21 years _ he's focused on making the
Bruins a better team this season.'' . . . Mark Messier will slap
his name on a hockey invention, to be marketed as ``Joe Player.''
The device, which will anchor on the ice or driveway, will collect
a puck or a tennis ball and then pass it back from the direction it
came. Sure beats the days of banging it off the garage door . . .
As many predicted, Dominik Hasek last week began to hint that,
well, you know, he might not retire following this season, after
all. Recovering from a severe groin tear (he is at least two months
from playing), Hasek said a season lost to injury might not be the
footnote on which he wants to end his career. Of course, he did
sign a three-year deal with Louisville before this season began,
and his standing deal in Buffalo would bring him at least $7.5
million for next season and maybe $9 million for 2001-02 . . . The
surprise last week wasn't that the Canucks landed Felix Potvin as
their No. 1 goalie, but rather that they gave up Kevin Weekes as
part of the package to get him. Weekes, once considered the goalie
of Florida's future, came to Vancouver in the Pavel Bure exchange
last season and was touted as Vancouver's goalie of the future. Now
he's Roberto Luongo's understudy/partner on Long Island. The
Canucks also parted with two young forwards, Dave Scratchard and
Bill Muckalt, but they're banking on bringing in Swedish twins
Henrik and Daniel Sedin next season to fill those spots . . . Just
when you'd think the Panthers should be packing the place _ if not
with Bure, then when? _ Wayne Huizenga's sons of Sunrise have seen
attendance drop some 15 percent this season, a dropoff of about
42,000 tickets . . . Last week we told you about the great promise
of Bruins goalie prospect Don Choukalos, the 179th pick in last
June's draft. Wait, there's another promising puckstopper in the
pipeline. Andrew Raycroft, Boston's fourth pick (135th overall) is
having a sensational year for Kingston in the Ontario Hockey
League. He was the league's goalie of the month in November and
posted a 3-0-0 mark for recent player of the week honors. As of the
middle of last week, he led the OHL in save percentage (.930) and
was second in wins (19) . . . Ex-Bruin Willie O'Ree, the first
black to play in the NHL, visited the Vault last week, here for a
taping session with Boston forward Anson Carter. Carter is one of
the black athletes who is the focal point of an upcoming ABC
special featuring black athletes performing in non-traditional
sports _ such as Tiger Woods (golf) and sisters Venus and Serena
Williams (tennis) . . . Boston's second pick in last June's draft,
6-foot-4-inch pivot Matt Zultek, recently underwent knee surgery,
repairing troubles dating back to before his game-winning goal in
last season's Memorial Cup. Bruins scout Bob Tindall reports Zultek
should resume skating soon and will play the remainder of the
season as an over-age (21 years old in March) junior with the
Ottawa 67s . . . Speedskating legend Eric Heiden _ five gold medals
in at the '80 Games _ is now Dr. Heiden and will be the Team USA
physician at the upcoming World Junior championships in Sweden . .
. With a huge assist to good freind Jack Falla, formerly with
Sports Illustrated and now teaching at Boston University, your
faithful correspondent constructed his first backyard rink,
complete with sideboards (no advertising, yet). I don't expect my
son to grow up to be the next Gretzky, and he is only 2 1/2 years
old. But before he disappeared into the neighbor's house for the
duration of the entire construction process, I thought, you know,
he'd look around, take a deep breath, and dwell on what was a
postcard New England moment. Next year, he buys into it or I cut
his ice time. Hey, what else has a coach got? Happy holidays and
skate your lane.
</P>
</TEXT>
