<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWHER'S JOB HAS BECOME THE PITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ If Pete Carroll feels like a man under
siege, who could blame him?
</P>
<P>
   If he feels ill-treated by some and misunderstood by others,
that is an understandable response to the predicament he finds
himself in this morning, with two games remaining and nothing to
play for but pride and perhaps his job. But before he wastes much
time feeling blue, Carroll should pick up his phone and call Bill
Cowher down in Pittsburgh. There's a man under siege.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Cowher has been the subject of public ridicule for
the nonperformance of his team, which comes with the territory and
the $2 million-a-year salary he receives. But he's also faced
things Carroll is not, including a rumor campaign against him and
not-so-private whispers about the real reason for his allegedly
impending departure from the Steelers' sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Cowher's work habits have been questioned. Fine, part of the
deal. His response to the new contract he landed a couple of
seasons ago has been questioned. Fine, comes with the money,
especially if losing follows it. He has been alleged to be taking
over the North Carolina State program, where he and his wife met
and were varsity athletes. OK, those kind of rumors are part of the
deal if you coach for a living and things turn sour where you are.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Carroll, Cowher also has been dealt a hand from the
bottom of the deck. A dirty little hand whether any of it is true
or not. It's the kind of hand no coach _ good or bad _ and no
coach's family _ sundered or secure _ deserves.
</P>
<P>
   Things became so bad in Pittsburgh recently that some
extraordinary measures have been taken by Cowher and his family to
try to quell a flame of unsubstantiated rumor that seemed about to
consume him, despite his having led the Steelers to the playoffs
six times in the past eight years, including two trips to the AFC
championship game and one to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the streets of Pittsburgh, which is still a small
town in many ways, rumors have run rampant that Cowher was leaving
at the behest of his wife after committing an act of infidelity.
The charges have appeared on the Internet and been well discussed
on the corners, in the steel mills, and at the bars that are
staples of life in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   With three daughters (age 13, 12, and 8) and a wife of 16 years
who once was a professional basketball player but now works with
fourth-graders as a volunteer basketball coach, it was the kind of
charge that spreads like wildfire and hurts like tacks in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough the whispers were in print and on the lips of
Steeler fans, some in less than flattering ways. As the Steelers
continued to lose, the whispers only grew louder until Kaye Cowher
finally took the extraordinary step of denying them last Sunday in
the pages of the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband being attacked for calling the wrong plays goes
with the territory, but it has crossed the line,'' she said, while
saying there was ``absolutely no truth'' to the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Kaye Cowher is Tammy Wynette standing by her man or
whether the father of her three daughters has been falsely accused
is irrelevant. What is relevant is that this should not be
happening to Cowher or anybody else and that it should give all of
us in the sports journalism business reason to pause.
</P>
<P>
   Cowher went well beyond what seems necessary to stall these
rumors when he reportedly told a member of the Pittsburgh media
that he could not have fathered a child out of wedlock, as some
were whispering, because he underwent a vasectomy. What on Earth
does that have to do with the problems of the Steelers' offense?
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, if Cowher were an adulterer whose team was going to the
Super Bowl, it wouldn't even be an issue.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is Cowher's Steelers are not going to the playoffs for
the second straight year. They have a major problem at quarterback,
where millions are tied up in Kordell Stewart at a time when he's
doing more for the team by catching the ball than throwing it. They
have won only five games and for the first time in 50 years have
not placed a single player on the Pro Bowl team _ unless you
include the five ex-Steelers who are there.
</P>
<P>
   So there might be ample reason to speculate about the future of
Cowher and no shortage of things to criticize him about in
Pittsburgh, but one of them is not what he may or may not be doing
in his free time unless the cops or the courts are involved.
</P>
<P>
   Neither are and yet last week both he and his wife found
themselves denying rumors about the most private part of their
lives on the most public of stages. That Cowher's future in
Pittsburgh has been questioned by some is understandable because
his team is near the end of its second straight losing season and
has lost six in a row after a 5-3 start.
</P>
<P>
   On that score it is no different than Carroll's situation,
although his team is 7-7 and a juggernaut by comparison after
making the playoffs the first two years he was in charge before
stumbling this season. Yet Carroll has faced nothing but doubts
about his ability to be a head coach, which is a legitimate area of
debate when things don't go as planned.
</P>
<P>
   What is not is the debate Bill and Kaye Cowher have found
themselves the subject of the past few weeks. Monday, Cowher again
tried to defuse the matter by announcing at a press conference that
he was not going to North Carolina State and never was, a statement
he made only after his wife and the team's communications director
told him he had not clarified the growing rumors of his departure
when asked about them at an earlier press conference.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to call an impromptu press briefing 30 minutes after
his first one ended and apologized for being vague in the past and
reiterating that he was staying in the town of his birth to coach
the team he once rooted for. He promised to stay through the end of
his contract, which runs out in 2002, and said he hoped to bring
the Steelers back to playoff prominence.
</P>
<P>
   After what he and his wife have been through, it would be great
if he did. And frankly, after what Carroll's been through in New
England, he should thank his lucky stars the only ghost chasing him
has been Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Willie McGinest read teammates the riot act after last Sunday's
loss in Philadelphia. In an expletive-laced tirade, McGinest
accused many of his younger teammates of being ``party animals''
who didn't understand what it takes to win in the NFL. Clearly
distraught after the 24-9 debacle against the lowly Eagles,
McGinest lingered a long time alone on the visitors' bench before
he finally walked back to the locker room at Veterans Stadium.
After he got in there, McGinest went wild, aiming a goodly portion
of his high-decibel criticism at the receiving corps, many of whom
who were out at a local nightclub the night before the trip to
Philadelphia. No one rose to dispute him. By the time the press was
admitted, all was quiet and McGinest would only say, ``I'm tired of
(expletive) losing,'' when asked about his emotions . . . Things
went from bad to worse with the Saints this week after All-Draft
pick Ricky Williams was late for Sunday's game in Baltimore after
missing both team buses and then failed to show for practice
Tuesday. Williams rode to last Sunday's game in a police squad car
sent to the team hotel to fetch him by the Saints. After not
playing for the fourth straight week because of a turf toe problem,
he spent more than 20 minutes curled on the floor of his locker in
street clothes after the 31-8 loss. Tuesday Williams missed
practice, but showed up later at the team's facility and met with
Mike Ditka, who was less than understanding privately. Williams's
response to this latest pickle was to announce Wednesday that he
would no longer talk to the media the rest of the year, forgetting
that not a one of them has tackled him this season. On his weekly
radio show Tuesday, Ditka chastised Williams's mental and physical
conditioning and even criticized the rookie's odd habit of
conducting all press interviews while wearing his helmet . . . One
thing Williams might be mad about is the incentive-laden contract
he signed. While he's failed to hit any of his incentives, Edgerrin
James has made millions in Indianapolis with his startling rookie
season. James was the surprise pick ahead of Williams as the first
back taken in April. After reaching the 1,400-yard rushing plateau
last Sunday, he reached each of his three-tiered bonus. That
brought James's earnings to $14.8 million this season (including
his signing bonus), the most by a rookie. Williams, meanwhile, got
an $8.1 million signing bonus, but he ended up playing for the
minimum salary because he had to rush for 1,600 yards for his
incentives to kick in . . . Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman gave his
11 linemen gas grills, a box of steaks, and a champagne basket for
Christmas. Wonder what Drew Bledsoe gave his? Voodoo dolls? . . .
Perhaps trying to fire a pre-empetive salvo, 49ers general manager
Bill Walsh publicly said this week he intended to be back running
the beleaguered franchise next year. Walsh's public remarks came on
the heels of growing speculation about a power struggle between
Walsh and head coach Steve Mariucci that Walsh was losing. Walsh
denied that but acknowledged he has a meeting scheduled Monday with
club vice president John York to discuss the future. Two weeks ago
there was public speculation that Mariucci was urging the hiring of
Fox Sports analyst Matt Millen, who is a friend, as the club's
general manager. Last year, Lions owner Bill Ford nearly brought
him in to serve as Detroit's general manager, but head coach Bobby
Ross threatened to quit if the move was made. Walsh's wife, Geri,
has had health problems this year, and that could become an excuse
for Walsh's early departure if things do not work out as he hopes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati owner Mike Brown doesn't often make sense these days
when it comes to how pro football should run, except when the
question is about profit margin, but he made some sense this week.
Brown is a member of the league's competition committee and he had
a perfect solution to avoid a repeat of the eye injury from a
thrown official's flag that led Cleveland tackle Orlando Brown to
charge referee Jeff Triplette and push him to the ground last
Sunday: Don't throw the flag at the players. ``That's obvious,
isn't it?'' Brown said. Well, yeah. What will be more interesting
though is what the league has to say to the Bengals' owner about
his further remarks: ``In our league, the officials may be blind,
but they're also sacrosanct and you can't just stand by and allow
what amounted to an assault.'' What do you think the league would
have done if a player had said that? . . . Speaking of Orlando
Brown, it's all well and good to find and suspend him well into
next season. Certainly no player can be allowed to charge an
official and knock him flat, as the 350-pound tackle did. But
please, let's keep his actions in perspective. There's no
comparison between Brown's fit of pique and some of the true
criminal acts committed by NFL players lately. This was not an
assault, it was a guy getting pretty angry at someone throwing a
bag of BBs into his eye . . . How's this for a conflict of
interest: Agent Tom Condon represents both Brown, who hinted about
suing someone after he was suspended, and the referees association,
who had insisted on the suspension? . . . Dolphins kicker Orlindo
Mare needs one more field goal to break the single-season record of
37. Last weekend, when he booted four field goals in a 12-9 victory
over San Diego, he tied the record set by John Kasay of the
Carolina Panthers in 1996 . . . The sale last week of 49 percent of
the Baltimore Ravens to Stephen Bisciotti is expected to easily win
the approval of the league's finance committee chaired by Bob Kraft
and by the full membership. Under the terms, owner Art Modell
receives $275 million now for minority interest and another $325
million in four years for the remaining 51 percent. With the way
Modell goes through money, he'll need that extra $325 million by
the time he gets it. No league owner had yet met Bisciotti when
Modell announced the deal, but Kraft, and other members of the
finance committee, are already on record supporting the sale in
part because they've all grown weary of Modell's seemingly endless
financial crisis . . . The $600 million price tag is third in NFL
history, behind the $800 million Daniel Snyder paid for the
Redskins and their stadium and the $700 million Houston businessman
Bob McNair forked over to get an expansion franchise. But it's a
big enough number to help bolster the sale price of the New York
Jets. That deal was originally expected to close before the New
Year, but now has been delayed . . . To put into perspective what
the value of an NFL franchise can mean, Modell paid $3.93 million
for the Cleveland Browns in 1961 and Bob Tisch paid $75 million for
50 percent of the New York Giants as recently as 1991. You think
Kraft made a good investment in the Patriots despite their present
on-field problems?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The story of ex-Bengals running back James Brooks is a sad one
for himself and his university. Brooks spent six years at Auburn,
yet left in 1983 still illiterate. After a successful career in the
NFL, Brooks found himself all but unemployable and ultimately was
jailed recently for nonpayment of child support. He says it's
because his inability to read made it impossible to keep a decent
paying job. Brooks has been put on probation and ordered into a
reading program in Ohio that Auburn says it will pay for. Kind of
late, isn't it? . . . Now that he's a Pro Bowl quarterback, Kurt
Warner says he has no intention of going back to the St. Louis
bench next season when Trent Green returns. Green was signed as a
free agent last offseason for $16.5 million, while Warner was left
unprotected on the expansion list. But after Green went down with a
season-ending knee injury in training camp, Warner got his chance.
Now he's the quarterback without question, but he acknowledged this
week, ``I think it would be an injustice to make one of us go back
and sit on the bench.'' So what does he have in mind, both of them
playing? Word out of St. Louis is the job is now Warner's but the
Rams will retain Green for at least one more season for cap
reasons, if nothing else, before trying to move him if Warner
continues to star . . . Az-Zahir Hakim is a tiny wide receiver Rams
college personnel director Charley Armey coveted in the NFL draft
two years ago. This season he has shown why. Despite playing
sparingly, The Wizard of Az is among the league's touchdown
leaders, averaging a score every four receptions. He has nine on
the season and they tend to come in bunches _ four vs. Cincinnati,
two against Carolina, and two more against the New York Giants. You
may remember Hakim because he scored his only touchdown of the
season a year ago against the Patriots. By way of comparison with a
local contemporary, Armey took Hakim with the 96th pick in the 1998
draft out of San Diego State while Bobby Grier took Tony Simmons
with the 52d pick. Hakim was drafted nearly twice as late as
Simmons, but has scored twice as many career touchdowns (10-5).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dick Vermeil, the Rams' emotional coach, blames himself for the
poor performances of wide receiver Isaac Bruce in Vermeil's first
two years in St. Louis. Bruce, who chafed under Vermeil's hard-line
approach, is back to his old Pro Bowl form after missing 15 games
the previous two years in part because Vermeil has cooled his jets.
After missing 15 games the previous two years, Bruce has 73 catches
this season for 1,120 yards, 11 touchdowns, and now an apology of
sorts from his boss . . . If the Rams score 6 points Sunday, they
will set a franchise scoring record. The old mark is 466 points set
in 1950. The Rams are not just about offense, however. They have
made 29 sacks on the road, which is as many as the 49ers have in
all their games and exceeds the totals of the Packers (27), Browns
(25), and Jets (25) . . . In case you missed it, ex-Patriots Sam
Gash and Tom Tupa made the Pro Bowl. Gash has been the AFC's Pro
Bowl fullback the past two seasons, or ever since he was run out of
New England labeled as damaged goods. The only thing damaged about
Gash has been the guys he's drilled with his blocks. His loss
remains a big one for the Patriots . . . The Colts need one more
regular-season victory to complete the greatest single-season
turnaround in NFL history. Their 10-win improvement ties them with
the 1963 Raiders (who were coached by Al Davis) and the 1929 New
York Giants . . . Peyton Manning became the fourth-youngest
quarterback to be named to the Pro Bowl. The only ones with more
peach fuzz were Dan Marino, Drew Bledsoe, and Brett Favre . . .
Before the season began, if someone told you Warner, Steve
Beuerlein, and Brad Johnson would be the NFC Pro Bowl quarterbacks,
what would your reaction have been? . . . Old friend Curtis
Martin's 6,320 career rushing yards are the eighth-highest total
for a fifth-year back in NFL history. He could pass Jim Brown
(6,463) into seventh place with reasonable performances in his last
two games. Martin plans to call Brown, whom he knows well, and rub
it in if he makes it . . . Chargers linebacker Junior Seau was
irate when he learned Wednesday that he had not been voted to the
AFC Pro Bowl team for the first time in nine years. ``This started
a war,'' Seau said after he learned five linebackers had been
picked ahead of him. ``It's a battle now. I look forward to the
next millennium because there are going to be fireworks. I don't
take things like this lightly.'' Chargers coach Mike Riley called
Seau's exclusion ``a travesty'' and insisted he was the best
linebacker in football. The Chargers did not have a single player
named to the team. That had not happened in San Diego since 1973 .
. . Here's an assessment of Tennessee's phenomenal rookie pass
rusher Jevon Kearse by someone who knows him well. ``This guy is
going to be the first player to get a $100 million contract in the
NFL,'' said Mike Frederick, who like most players measures value in
dollars and cents. Frederick is Kearse's backup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
