<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO SAYS YOU GET WHAT YOU PAY FOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ If the Patriots feel like laying down and
not playing out, starting with Sunday's game against the Buffalo
Bills, many more players other than Drew Bledsoe should apologize
to owner Robert Kraft for the mediocre season they handed the
owner, who paid some serious money expecting a much better product.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures obtained through the National Football
League Players' Association, Kraft spent $75.2 million in salaries
and bonuses in 1999, third in the league behind Green Bay ($76.0
million) and Cleveland ($76.6 million) and more than $10 million
above the league average. The Patriots had the second-highest
difference between the league-wide cap ($57.29 million) and the
actual amount of money the team paid out ($19.3 million).
</P>
<P>
   The payout also was $10.8 million more than last year's $64.4
million in salaries. Since 1994, the Patriots have had the highest
difference between salary cap and actual payout ($53.1 million).
Second are the Detroit Lions ($48.2 million).
</P>
<P>
   According to the September issue of Forbes, the Patriots'
estimated value was $460 million. Only Dallas ($663 million),
Washington ($607 million), and Tampa Bay ($502 million) had higher
values, but the Patriots are about two seasons away from a new
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots tied the Atlanta Falcons, Carolina Panthers, and
Minnesota Vikings with the most millionaire players (21).
</P>
<P>
   The following numbers are what players were _ and still are _
paid in actual dollars for 1999, including salary and bonuses. (Not
all players are included.)
</P>
<P>
   COST OF DOING BUSINESS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   --Ty Law, CB ($14.6 million) _ Law was left off the Pro Bowl
team after making it in 1998, which earned him a seven-year, $50
million deal. He had a solid year, but not of the caliber of '98
and will likely miss the rest of the season with a broken right
hand.
</P>
<P>
   --Ted Johnson, MLB ($5.48 million) _ Tore his left biceps tendon
in an Aug. 7 intrasquad game and was out of action until Dec. 5. A
top run-stopper, he was missed for his guts and determination
through most of this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   --Drew Bledsoe, QB ($5.27 million) _ Considering his experience
and status in the league, Bledsoe had the worst year of his career,
throwing 20 interceptions, 16 of them in his last six games when
the Patriots went 1-5 and fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   --Damien Woody, C ($4.08 million) _ A very good rookie season.
Woody had to fill the shoes of savvy veteran Dave Wohlabaugh.
Though still not as polished as Wohlabaugh, his upside is higher
with tremendously quick feet for a man his size. He had problems on
snaps to the quarterback and picking up the many zone blitzes teams
threw his way.
</P>
<P>
   --Henry Thomas, DT ($3.7 million) _ A decent year, but a decline
from last season. Thomas was plagued with nagging injuries
throughout the season and at times had to be moved off his ``3''
technique spot to the nose where he was, at times, more effective.
</P>
<P>
   --Bruce Armstrong, LT ($3.5 million) _ Got himself into great
shape and was having a very good season until knee problems slowed
him down. Armstrong still has a lot left when he's healthy.
</P>
<P>
   --Willie McGinest, DE ($3.06 million) _ McGinest will tell you
he could have gotten to the quarterback more, but he has eight
sacks and has been among the top two or three in quarterback
knockdowns.
</P>
<P>
   --Terry Glenn, WR ($2.66 million) _ He has caught 69 balls for
1,147 yards, stayed healthy all season, and has taken part in every
team practice (late for one team meeting). Other than some
off-field things, Glenn earned the money.
</P>
<P>
   --Andy Katzenmoyer, LB ($2.56 million) _ Gets great grades for
effort in replacing Johnson in the middle for most of the year.
Should be an excellent player on the outside in the future, but had
a lot of rookie issues on the field.
</P>
<P>
   --Ben Coates, TE ($2.1 million) _ Phased out of the offense in
what was his least productive year since Bledsoe joined the team in
'93 with 28 catches, two TDs, and a boatload of frustration. In a
different offensive system, Coates could still be effective. The
Patriots will be tempted to cut corners here, but that would be a
difficult move considering the difficulty of replacing him.
</P>
<P>
   --Chris Slade, LB ($1.95 million) _ Not the most visible player
on defense, but that's because he was in so many coverage
situations. He had 3.5 sacks, which is a down number for Slade.
</P>
<P>
   --Shawn Jefferson, WR ($1.3 million) _ Thirty-nine receptions
and six TDs, maximum effort and a great character guy in the locker
room. An unrestricted free agent, Jefferson will be in demand in
the open market.
</P>
<P>
   --Max Lane, OL ($1.3 million) _ One of the offensive linemen who
came under fire, but Lane was the most versatile and played well
when he had a chance to play one position for a while.
</P>
<P>
   --Adam Vinatieri, K ($1.28 million) _ Hit on 22 of 26 field-goal
attempts, but the miss in Kansas City will haunt him.
</P>
<P>
   --Kevin Faulk, RB ($1.28 million) _ Proved to be an effective
returner and third-down back who can catch the ball, but was not
able to replace Robert Edwards as the No. 1 back.
</P>
<P>
   --Todd Rucci, RG ($1.2 million) _ He was left unprotected in the
expansion draft; started all year and was average.
</P>
<P>
   --Vincent Brisby, WR ($1.16 million) _ Still a lot of money for
a receiver who caught 12 passes, but that's not all Brisby's fault.
He was the fifth receiver and the ``emergency'' guy in case one of
the others went down. He will likely have a similar role next
season.
</P>
<P>
   --Zefross Moss, RT ($1.15 million) _ With one year remaining on
his contract, it would appear Moss will be a top candidate to be
cut in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   --Lee Johnson, P ($1.1 million) _ Adequately replaced Tom Tupa
at less money.
</P>
<P>
   --Larry Whigham, SS ($1.06 million) _ Can make mistakes, but he
still makes plays.
</P>
<P>
   --John Friesz, QB ($1 million) _ Bledsoe's backup. Has thrown no
passes.
</P>
<P>
   --Terry Allen, RB ($500,000) _ He'll be the 22d millionaire
before it's over as he reaches incentives.
</P>
<P>
   TRUE VALUE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   --Lawyer Milloy, SS ($492,000) _ Two-time Pro Bowler, he may be
the best value in the league.
</P>
<P>
   --Troy Brown, WR, PR ($446,000) _ What can you say? Maybe the
best player on the team and one of the lowest paid. He'll make his
money in free agency.
</P>
<P>
   --Tedy Bruschi, LB ($934,000) _ Proved to be an every-down
player. Will make a good score in free agency.
</P>
<P>
   --Heath Irwin, LG ($435,000) _ Maybe the best of the
run-blockers. Also an unrestricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   --Steve Israel, CB ($902,000) _ A solid year and an unrestricted
free agent.
</P>
<P>
   --Ferric Collons, DE ($400,000) _ Good play for a
minimum-salaried veteran.
</P>
<P>
   --Chad Eaton, DT ($881,000) _ A down year compared to last, but
plays better with Ted Johnson in the game.
</P>
<P>
   VALUE IN EYES OF BEHOLDER &QC;
</P>
<P>
   --Marty Moore, LB ($450,000) _ Always room for Marty.
</P>
<P>
   --Lamont Warren, RB ($704,000) _ Decent role player.
</P>
<P>
   --Brandon Mitchell, DE ($331,000) _ Flashes, but no consistency.
</P>
<P>
   --Tebucky Jones, CB ($465,000) _ Good special teams player.
</P>
<P>
   --Tony George, SS ($515,000) _ Saw too little time for a
third-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   --Rod Rutledge, TE ($295,000) _ Good blocker.
</P>
<P>
   --Tony Carter, FB ($656,000) _ Decent player, but no Sam Gash.
</P>
<P>
   --Chris Floyd, FB ($276,000) _ Potential, but always hurt.
</P>
<P>
   --Tony Simmons, WR ($311,000) _ The Patriots expected more than
19 catches.
</P>
<P>
   --Chris Sullivan, DT ($934,000) _ Played better late in the
season.
</P>
<P>
   --Chris Carter, FS ($331,000) _ Tough year as a first-year
starter.
</P>
<P>
   NO VALUE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   --Willie Clay, FS ($401,900) _ Amount that counted against the
cap when he was cut.
</P>
<P>
   --Brian Stablein, WR ($333,300) _ Amount counted against cap
after he was cut two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   --Chris Canty, CB ($300,000) _ Amount against the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   --J'Juan Cherry, CB ($410,000) _ Supplemental draft pick who
went on IR and never played for Pats. He'll return next season.
</P>
<P>
   --Derrick Cullors, KR, RB (366,100) _ The kick returner went on
IR in exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   --Bob Kuberski, DT ($375,000) _ Spent most of the year inactive.
</P>
<P>
   --Derrick Fletcher, OT ($269,000) _ Fifth-round pick inactive
all year.
</P>
<P>
   --Michael Bishop, QB ($201,000) _ Seventh-round pick never
played.
</P>
<P>
   --Sean Morey, WR ($200,000) _ Seventh-round pick activated this
week for the first time.
</P>
</TEXT>
