<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT WORLD READY TO RING IN NEW YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ 'Tis the season to be jolly, which is never easy in
boxing unless you're Don King.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in an effort to spread some Christmas cheer and avoid
being a humbug (that's the rating organizations' job), we have
drawn up a wish list for some of boxing's big names, small names,
and a few names in between.
</P>
<P>
   For John Ruiz: A shot at Michael Grant's chin. Failing that, a
shot at Evander Holyfield's legs. Failing that, a shot at Lennox
Lewis's heavyweight title belt.
</P>
<P>
   For Dana Rosenblatt: Another shot at Vinny Pazienza so he can at
least beat him once.
</P>
<P>
   For Vinny Pazienza: Another shot at Rosenblatt so he can at
least get paid once more.
</P>
<P>
   For Mickey Ward: Someone around him who knows what a title shot
is worth.
</P>
<P>
   For Al Valenti and Goodwin A.C.: A knockout of Bob Arum.
</P>
<P>
   For Norman Stone: A knockout for Ruiz when the money is on the
line.
</P>
<P>
   For Lennox Lewis: A fight with Holyfield he actually wins.
</P>
<P>
   For Evander Holyfield: A fight with Lewis he actually wins.
</P>
<P>
   For Oscar De La Hoya: Track shoes.
</P>
<P>
   For Felix Trinidad: A rematch with De La Hoya that doesn't
require track shoes.
</P>
<P>
   For Bob Lee: A legal defense fund.
</P>
<P>
   For Cedric Kushner: A good alibi and a better heavyweight.
</P>
<P>
   For the IBF: A farewell party.
</P>
<P>
   For the WBC: A death notice.
</P>
<P>
   For the WBA: Likewise.
</P>
<P>
   For the IBA, IBC, WBA, WBO, WBF and any other IB-anythings or
WB-whatevers: The cold shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   For Teddy Atlas: A fighter who really wants to learn how to win,
has the skill, and will do it inside the ring and out. Failing
that, a bigger TV microphone.
</P>
<P>
   For Eddie Futch: A comeback, because boxing needs him.
</P>
<P>
   For Riddick Bowe: No comeback, because he doesn't need boxing.
</P>
<P>
   For Floyd Mayweather Jr.: An abacus, because he forgot how to
count.
</P>
<P>
   For Bob Arum: Patience and aspirin _ he'll need 'em with
Mayweather around.
</P>
<P>
   For Mike Tyson: A year's supply of Zoloft.
</P>
<P>
   For Shelly Finkel: The same.
</P>
<P>
   For Orlin Norris: A walking cast.
</P>
<P>
   For Emanuel Steward: The Lennox Lewis he wishes he sees instead
of the one in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   For the Duva clan: A reconciliation in the family.
</P>
<P>
   For Lou Duva: One more guy who can fight like hell to keep him
going.
</P>
<P>
   For Michael Grant: Boxing lessons.
</P>
<P>
   For Don Turner: The time to give Grant those lessons.
</P>
<P>
   For Prince Naseem Hamed: A new act.
</P>
<P>
   For Andrew Golota: A heart.
</P>
<P>
   For David Tua: A chance.
</P>
<P>
   For Ike Ibeabuchi: A padded cell.
</P>
<P>
   For Vitali Klitschko: A lesson in how to bend his knees.
</P>
<P>
   For Henry Akinwande: A disappearing act.
</P>
<P>
   For Roy Jones Jr.: An opponent who can test his mettle.
</P>
<P>
   For Darius Michalczewski: A shot to be the one to try.
</P>
<P>
   For Bernard Hopkins: Some respect.
</P>
<P>
   For Fernando Vargas: Either a good therapist or a good lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   For Jose Luis Lopez: A very good therapist.
</P>
<P>
   For David Reid: A chance to fight Trinidad or Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   For James Page: A big welterweight title fight.
</P>
<P>
   For Vernon Forrest: Any welterweight title fight.
</P>
<P>
   For Shane Mosley: Any title fight at all.
</P>
<P>
   For Derrell Coley: Forget him, he got his Christmas wish from De
La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   For Kostya Tszyu: Some recognition that he's back.
</P>
<P>
   For Zab Judah: A chance to make Tszyu disappear.
</P>
<P>
   For Stevie Johnson: Someone a little guy can make money with.
</P>
<P>
   For Paul Ingle: A rematch with Hamed.
</P>
<P>
   For Erik Morales: A stiff chin, because he'll soon need it.
</P>
<P>
   For Marco Antonio Barrera: A stiffer chin to stand up to
Morales.
</P>
<P>
   For Johnny Tapia: A rematch with Paulie Ayala.
</P>
<P>
   For Paulie Ayala: The good sense to stay away from Tapia.
</P>
<P>
   For Tim Austin: A chance to beat them both.
</P>
<P>
   For Gerry Penalosa: A chance to fight Mark Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   For Mark Johnson: A chance to fight someone who can fight like
Penalosa.
</P>
<P>
   For Dan Goossen and Mat Tinley: Continued good health to Bill
Daniels, the money behind their promotional efforts.
</P>
<P>
   For Laila Ali: A new profession.
</P>
<P>
   For Muhammad Ali: Allah's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   For the US boxing team: A bag full of gold in Sydney next
September.
</P>
<P>
   For Lou DiBella and Seth Abraham at HBO: They don't need
anything.
</P>
<P>
   For Jay Larkin at Showtime: HBO's budget.
</P>
<P>
   For fight fans: A break, the same gift you didn't get last year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Junior Jones will finally get a chance to square off with Hamed
March 11, probably in London. On the same card, Ingle is lined up
to fight Kevin Kelley if Kelley survives a fight next month in
England. The Kelley-Ingle winner, in theory, gets the Hamed-Jones
winner later in the year. Jones can still punch and if he lands,
Hamed will go down because he's as balanced as a three-legged
chair. The fight is still being shopped in the United States, but
Hamed's wife is due to have a baby 10 days after the bout and the
WBO-WBC featherweight champion is reluctant to leave. Good for him
. . . Pity poor Bernard Hopkins (36-2-1). The best middleweight in
the world just earned a paltry $100,000 beating Antwun Echols with
his 11th defense of the IBF title while Coley will earn $1.1
million to be cold-cocked by De La Hoya Feb. 26 at Madison Square
Garden. Nothing against Coley, but when does the 35-year-old
Hopkins get paid? ``I don't think you can find one person, even
among my enemies, who would say I'm not worthy of a million-dollar
payday,'' Hopkins said, and he's quite right. He may have to go
down to 154 pounds and fight Vargas or Reid to finally get paid . .
. Here's De La Hoya's take on Trinidad's insistence on flipping
their contracts from the first fight to make a rematch. ``They made
a wrong move by thinking they had all the power because they won
the title,'' De La Hoya said. ``They think I need Trinidad. I don't
need Trinidad.'' Not as long as he doesn't care what boxing fans
think of him he doesn't . . . After taking a short break from
training, Tyson will return to Las Vegas this week to continue his
preparations for a Jan. 29 bout with British and Commonwealth
champion Julius Francis (21-7) at MET Arena in Manchester, England.
Tyson will travel to London to train for the bout in early January.
He will stay in London until early in fight week and then take a
train up to Manchester . . . The world's fascination with Tyson
persists. He sold out the MET Arena's 21,000 seats in two days,
said British promoter Frank Warren. ``We had in excess of 40,000
requests for tickets,'' he said. ``Within two days, all the tickets
had been sold and Tyson's opponent hadn't even been confirmed
yet.'' Francis is an ex-kickboxer and a former soccer hooligan who
did time 10 years ago for causing what the British press called
``grievous bodily harm'' to someone. Sounds like the perfect rival
for Tyson . . . Lewis's manager, Frank Maloney, also manages
Francis and didn't exactly flood him with praise when he said,
``Tyson could fight Mickey Mouse in Manchester and the people would
show up.'' . . . Do you think it's an accident unranked Francis
suddenly showed up at No. 12 this month on the WBC list? . . .
Shannon Briggs is claiming he's already signed to fight Tyson at
the end of March in New York. Maybe he has, but it doesn't mean a
thing until Tyson's name is on a contract. Which it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How's this for replacement work? Isidro Garcia won the WBO
flyweight title last Saturday night on two hour's notice,
outpointing champion Jose Lopez. Promoters of the fight in Indio,
Calif., were ready to cancel the bout after Alejandro Montiel
pulled out four hours before the fight. But Garcia walked into the
Fantasy Springs Casino and was asked to fight. He did _ with a
borrowed mouthpiece, a borrowed protector, borrowed trunks, and now
a borrowed title belt from Lopez. On the same card, the California
Athletic Commission canceled a fight between former world champion
Barrera and Cesar Najera when it was learned Najera was Barrera's
sparring partner and had only five known pro fights. The match was
ultimately put on as an exhibition . . . Here's three-time world
champion Tapia's explanation for why he's coming back Jan. 8 at the
Pit in Albuquerque to face WBO bantamweight champion Jorge Julio:
``The main thing is to show that I have what it takes to be a world
champion again,'' Tapia said. ``Mostly, I have to prove to myself
that it's not against who, or not against what, but what I do. I
don't like being called the challenger after so many years of being
a champion. I want to be in this game as a champion. I want to go
out as a champion. I want to get that feeling back that I had when
I was a champion. That's what I plan to do.'' . . . Pity France's
Bruno Girard. He recently fought more than well enough to win the
WBA super middleweight title from hard-punching Byron Mitchell only
to lose a controversial split decision draw in Tunica, Miss. ``It's
a scandal,'' Girard said. ``I'm a French fighter. I came to the
United States without fear.'' What was he thinking?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's how boxing's inner workings go: When Ruiz's manager and
lawyer, Stone and Anthony Cardinale, showed up in Mexico last week
to plead for a boxoff with No. 2 contender Grant, they had to
listen to a letter read into the record by WBC president Jose
Sulaiman from King calling for Holyfield to be named the No. 1
contender over Ruiz. King just happens to be Ruiz's promoter. He's
also Holyfield's, but he's supposed to be looking out for all his
fighters. Later, after the WBC ordered a Ruiz-Grant boxoff be
negotiated by Dec. 28 or it would order a Jan. 4 purse bid, King
called Stone to tell him he was only fooling about Holyfield. Sure
he was . . . If Grant signs to fight Lewis, by the way, Ruiz would
get the same deal against Holyfield, who is now rated No. 3 by the
WBC. But don't count on seeing Grant-Lewis. Lewis's people are
asking for too many options on Grant's future fights to make the
deal, insiders say, while offering barely half the money Grant's
people are demanding . . . Former world champion Arturo Gatti will
meet former world champion Joey Gamache, the pride of Maine,
underneath De La Hoya Feb. 26. That fight will be a war and don't
bet against Gamache because Gatti is ready to go and doesn't know
it . . . Here's how Gamache got the fight: He showed up in
DiBella's office at HBO Sports and tried to convince the senior
vice president for programming. Then he sent him tapes of some
recent fights. Then he called back. ``Joey did a great job of
selling himself. And when we made the deal, he promised me we were
getting more than we expected,'' DiBella said. ``I don't doubt
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 0049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
