<HEADLINE>
STEWART'S COACH FACES HOLIDAY WITHOUT FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He greeted the holidays that have become so much a part
of our culture, though you will excuse Chuck Cook if he did so
without the traditional spirit. The void in his life is still
fresh, the pain he feels very real.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all miss him,'' said Cook from his home in San Antonio.
``We all do. He left a big hole in our lives that we won't fill.''
</P>
<P>
   He was talking, of course, about Payne Stewart, his longtime
friend who was one of six people killed in that eerie Learjet
accident just two months ago. For years, Cook stood on practice
ranges and watched Stewart hit shot after shot, bucket after
bucket, until he was probably too tired to watch and Stewart was
too tired to swing. Like all teacher-student relationships, there
were good times and bad times. As Cook tries to go about his
routine back home in Texas, he draws strength from the fact that
Stewart achieved so much in 1999 _ a second US Open championship
and a coveted spot on the Ryder Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was as happy as he ever was,'' said Cook. ``If I go, I sure
hope I go as happy as he was.''
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, but Cook keeps in touch with Tracey Stewart and the
children, Chelsea and Aaron, though he knows Christmas was even
rougher for them. ``The community really responded and she got help
from a lot of friends. The response has been overwhelming, but I
think they sort of ignored Christmas (this year).''
</P>
<P>
   Cook delivered a eulogy at Stewart's memorial service and began
that day by asking: ``How do you celebrate the life of the greatest
celebrator of life that you know?'' It's a question he's still
asking himself.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ways he had intended to celebrate in 2000 was to
accompany Stewart to Pebble Beach for the US Open in June, where
his student would be defending a championship he had earned with
arguably the most dramatic putt in major golf history. Cook will
probably still make the trip, only it will be to symbolically
return the championship trophy to the USGA. Just another step in a
life that must go on.
</P>
<P>
   As the new year approaches, Cook takes some pleasure out of a
pairing that seems appropriate. Another of his splendid students,
Bob Estes, has asked Stewart's longtime caddie, Mike Hicks, to
carry for him in 2000. Hicks was by Stewart's side in tournaments
for 12 years and they were close friends (Stewart celebrated his US
Open triumph at Pinehurst last June by riding in Hicks's truck to
the caddie's home in North Carolina), but again, life goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hicks will be real good for (Estes),'' said Cook. ``The things
Bob lacks Hicks can give him.''
</P>
<P>
   It has the makings of another great team, for Estes is a golfer
just waiting to break out. In 1999, Estes missed the cut just one
time in 28 starts, chalking up nine Top 10s and 15 Top 25 finishes.
``A money-making machine,'' said Cook of the 33-year-old Estes, who
was just a few shots away from making the US Ryder Cup team when he
closed with a 69 at the PGA Championship in August.
</P>
<P>
   Estes has won just once on tour, the 1994 Texas Open, but after
losing his playing privileges with a dismal 1996 season, Estes has
come back strong _ 69th on the money list to 28th to 25th this past
season with $1,359,724 in prize money.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't surprise many people, most of all Cook, if Estes
broke through with a big season in 2000. Cook is certainly looking
forward to the new year, if only to put the old one behind him.
``I'm glad to see it come to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, he was in constant pain and unable to even think
about playing golf. Today, Jack Nicklaus is preparing for a 2000
season in which he plans to play in perhaps 20 tournaments _
including all four majors. ``I don't know how successful I'm going
to be, but you never know unless you try,'' Nicklaus told
reporters. ``I think I may fool some people. I think I may even
fool myself.'' Hard to imagine being fooled again by a man who at
age 46 won the 1986 Masters, or at 58 closed with a 68 and finished
in a tie for sixth at Augusta, particularly with so many variables
fueling his enthusiasm. There is the hip replacement surgery
performed by Dr. Benjamin Bierbaum in Boston last January which has
him pain-free; the arrival of his youngest son, Gary, as a
card-carrying member of the PGA Tour; venues for the majors are
courses on which he has won (Augusta National, Pebble Beach, St.
Andrews) or designed (Valhalla); and a nice stretch of success,
albeit team-oriented, during golf's ``Silly Season'' (Nicklaus was
on the winning team in the Three-Tour Challenge, the Father-Son
Challenge with Gary, and the Diner's Club Matches). Nicklaus, who
will turn 60 Jan. 21, will be paired with Gary at the AT&AMP;T Pebble
Beach National Pro-Am (Feb. 3-6). The son just this week accepted a
sponsor's exemption into the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic (Jan. 19-23)
. . . J.L. Lewis, a four-year veteran of the PGA Tour who won this
past summer's John Deere Classic, is helping to raise money for the
First Tee through a raffle available at www.wwathlete.com/jl. The
winner will receive a golf outing for four with Lewis at any TPC
course of their choice, with green fees, one night's lodging, and
meals included. Raffle tickets are $295; check the Web site for
information . . . As Casey Martin's debut as a member of the PGA
Tour approaches (Jan. 19 at the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic), take
note that a similar controversy is brewing in Australia. Nigel
Lane, who suffers from an arthritic condition that makes walking
painful, is going ahead with a lawsuit against the Australian Golf
Union, which has denied him access to a cart during competition.
Lane, 31, said he has been taking the same medication that
reportedly helped Jose Maria Olazabal recover from his foot woes .
. . Last spring at the Bay Hill Invitational, Ian Woosnam was asked
about his chances of making the 1999 European Ryder Cup team. He
said it wasn't in his plans, that he was ``sick of the Ryder Cup''
and all the hoopla. But with his friend, Sam Torrance, named
captain for the 2001 contest at The Belfry, Woosnam has a different
view. ``The way I am playing now, I fancy my chances of making the
team in 2001,'' he told Alister Nicol of golf.com. That assumes
that the spirited Welshman conquers putting woes that have kept him
winless for two years. ``Every day I go out and I think about
quitting the game altogether. Every single day,'' said Woosnam, the
1991 Masters champ who has authored 43 worldwide victories. He had
No. 44 in his grasp a few weeks ago at the Argentine Open, but with
that choppy, uncertain putting stroke letting him down, it slipped
away . . . Renee Powell has been awarded the 1999 Budget Service
Award for her tireless work in bringing the game of golf to juniors
who would otherwise be unable to enjoy its benefits. Recently,
Powell was named head of development and programming for the First
Tee Program by the PGA Tour. One of three African-Americans who has
played on the LPGA Tour, Powell is head professional at Clearview
GC in East Canton, Ohio . . . With its first tournament of the new
year scheduled for Jan. 13, the LPGA will kick off its yearlong
50th anniversary celebration with a gala event a few nights earlier
at the Breakers Hotel in Palm Beach, Fla. Vince Gill will host and
the evening will pay tribute to the LPGA's founding members and
those women who helped build the tour through the 1950s and '60s .
. . No argument that Karrie Webb and Juli Inkster were the premier
players on the LPGA Tour in 1999, but here is further
head-scratching material for those who can't believe Lorie Kane is
still winless: 71 times in 1999 she shot a sub-par round,
establishing a tour record.
</P>
</TEXT>
