<HEADLINE>
(RESCUED CRASH VICTIM IN STABLE CONDITION
</HEADLINE>
 
(Adds first name and title in sixth graf and fixes graf nine.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Orith Goldberg  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- For two days, Jolene Rae Donohue lay on the
driver's seat of her car with its roof smashed against her body,
until her rescue that many called a Christmas Eve miracle.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Donohue was listed in serious but stable condition
at Holy Cross Medical Center in suburban Los Angeles, where instead
of focusing on her injuries, she wished others a happy holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fine,'' Donohue told a friend. ``Have a Merry Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, her car had rolled down a 70-foot embankment
south of the eastbound 210 Freeway, near the Golden State Freeway
northwest of downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The injured 52-year old Santa Clarita woman went undetected as
thousands of people drove by.
</P>
<P>
   ``(She was) on the outskirts of this giant city and no one saw
her,'' said Los Angeles County Fire Captain Dave Leary. ``That, to
me, is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on Friday, a passing motorist stopped near the
embankment and discovered the trapped woman when he briefly walked
away from the road, said Leary.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers had to work about 20 minutes to free Donohue, who
complained of neck pain and being cold, Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was doing really well,'' Leary said. ``All of her vital
signs were really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue was last seen a party Wednesday night in La Crescenta.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, her son David, of Sun Valley, filed a missing
person report with the Santa Clarita Sheriff's station.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (missing party) was supposed to return home, but has not
shown up, ``The (reporting party) has contacted any relatives she
may have gone to, but nobody has seen or heard from her.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue was headed to her Santa Clarita home on the westbound
210 freeway, when the green 1998 Mazda 626 she was driving at an
estimated speed of 65 mph crossed the dirt divider for unknown
reasons and traveled the wrong way across the eastbound lanes of
the 210 Freeway, California Highway Patrol officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The car continued into a dirt embankment south of the eastbound
lanes, east of the Golden State Freeway, flipping over and landing
upright about 70 feet below.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until passing motorist John Teslich of Stockton
stopped on the freeway about 12:10 p.m. Friday that Donohue was
discovered. Teslich apparently flagged down a UPS driver for help.
</P>
<P>
   Leary was already in the area because there had been some
traffic collisions and stopped when he saw a motorist wave him
down.
</P>
<P>
   Leary said the man he spoke with at the location said he made
contact with Donohue and called her son, who had said his mother
had been missing for two days.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue seemed quite coherent, Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had told me she had been there for two days,'' Leary said.
``I looked at the blood on her face and it was dried and I noticed
the car's engine was cold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing she didn't know was where she was and what day
it was, ``She just woke up and there she was.''
</P>
<P>
   Leary and other firefighters quickly went into action,
requesting aid from both Los Angeles County and Los Angeles city
fire departments. About 25 firefighters from both agencies came to
help.
</P>
<P>
   They cut the roof off the car and gently removed Donohue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all worked out...'' Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
