<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Texas </SLUG>
 A&AMP;M-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Slocum sees Paterno as ideal college coach
<TEXT>
<P>
   By NEIL HOHLFELD
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Before being promoted to head coach, he spent 16
years as an assistant, growing to learn and love the football
traditions of the university in the rural setting.
</P>
<P>
   When he took over as the top man, he stressed defense and
discipline. Nothing fancy here, just an honest approach to
team-oriented football that has remained constant through the
years.
</P>
<P>
   In his first 11 seasons, he won 102 games, went to eight bowls
and 10 times had a team in the Top 25.
</P>
<P>
   That description could be of Joe Paterno, the coaching icon at
Penn State, but it is of Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum, who would
like nothing more than to have the Aggies program mentioned in the
same breath as Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Paterno is in his 50th season at Penn State _ 34 as head coach
after serving 16 years as an assistant. After learning his craft as
an assistant from 1950-65, he took over as head coach in 1966. In
his first 11 seasons as head coach, Paterno was 101-23-1 and 5-3-1
in bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum was an assistant at Texas A&AMP;M from 1972-80 and again from
1982-88 after spending a season as defensive coordinator at
Southern Cal in 1981. Slocum took over as head coach in 1989,
meaning he's spent 26 of the last 27 seasons in College Station, a
record for stability that's also worth noting.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum will face Paterno as a head coach for the first time
Tuesday night at the Alamo Bowl in San Antonio. The similarities in
the programs are a source of pride for Slocum, who considers
Paterno a model for all coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an outsider looked at us and compared our program to Penn
State's, that would be a heck of a compliment,'' Slocum said.
``Other than the fact that I wouldn't want people to think that
both teams have old coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum, 55, was kidding, of course. During a news conference
before the bowl, Slocum found it amusing to be called a ``kid'' by
Paterno, who celebrated his 73rd birthday last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking and he made some reference to me as `kid,'''
Slocum said. ``That feels pretty good. To be able to go to a bowl
game and spend a week with a guy you respect and admire as much as
Joe Paterno is a thrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go back over the last 30 years and ask which are the
top three, four, five programs, Penn State is one of them. In the
last 30 years, if you ask who are the top two or three coaches, Joe
is one of them. He's a guy who has gone through a generation or two
of coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Paterno's stability is remarkable. He has 317 wins, third among
Division I-A coaches and should pass Bear Bryant's 323 wins next
season. Since he turned 66 _ one year past the retirement age for
most people _ Paterno is 69-16.
</P>
<P>
   Success on the field aside, Slocum probably admires more the way
Paterno has handled himself and built the Penn State program.
Slocum would like nothing more than to build something approaching
Paterno's longevity and his accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you'd ask me which team I could pattern my team after,
which would one fit Texas A&AMP;M best, I'd say that the image people
have of Penn State is the image that would be most fitting for
Texas A&AMP;M,'' Slocum said. ``There are some other programs around,
you'd look at them and say, that's not A&AMP;M. If you were to have a
program like that, it would be the total opposite of what Texas A&AMP;M
is all about. It wouldn't fit. But Penn State's program does fit
what we're about. The way they've done it, you don't hear a lot of
negatives coming out of that program. When you see their players,
they usually handle themselves well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe is a straightforward guy, very principled person. I've
always admired the way they run their program. A lot of other
programs have come with some flash, and then they're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Nittany Lions were in the running for the
national championship after winning their first nine games. In
early November, they were upset by Minnesota, starting a
three-game, season-ending slide that kept them out of a New Year's
Day bowl for the first time in nine seasons.
</P>
<P>
   There was early speculation Penn State might decide to skip the
postseason, so deep was the disappointment in Happy Valley.
Instead, the Nittany Lions will try to lick their wounds against
the Aggies, who enter the game with a two-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the initial reaction was disappointing,'' Paterno said
of his team's Alamo Bowl bid. ``They (the Lions) seemed to think
they could still get into a New Year's Day bowl. That feeling has
passed. They feel good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum says he believes Paterno will have his team ready to play
Tuesday. Paterno's record of 19-9-1 in bowls is an indication he
knows what to do this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at Joe's record in bowl games, it's one of the
best records of anybody,'' Slocum said.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one area in which the Aggies have not succeeded
under Slocum it has been in the bowls. Slocum's record is 2-6 in
bowls _ losing to the likes of Ohio State, Florida State, Notre
Dame and UCLA. Playing Penn State is another test against a
nationally renown program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played traditional bowl teams, for the most part,''
Slocum said. ``The next step is for us to get better in the bowls.
We're close, but it goes down as a `W' or an `L.' I think we'll
play well. Our guys are in a good frame of mind. We're here with
every intent to win the game, and we'll give it our best shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the result, Slocum will get a look at the man who runs
the program he would most like to emulate. With that in mind, this
week should be a kick for Slocum and the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big part of me that's still a little kid,'' Slocum
said. ``I can remember seeing Joe Paterno on TV when I was in
college and just starting out as an assistant. It's always a thrill
when you get a chance to coach against someone like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never, ever dreamed I'd grow up to know a guy like Joe
Paterno when I was a kid. I still am into that hero stuff. I love
the guy. To be around the guy and be friends with him, it's
something special to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
