<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9244 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     12-26 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Fading stars give rise to a new one
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY MICKEY HERSKOWITZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   While Jake Delhomme waited for his phone to ring, he stayed busy
shoveling manure in the barn of his father, a horse trainer in
Lafayette, La.
</P>
<P>
   You are reminded it isn't easy giving up show business, but when
the Saints called, Jake returned to pro football. Friday, they hung
a star on his door, one that had belonged to the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Delhomme, the latest graduate of Quarterbacks Anonymous,
outgunned Troy Aikman, a three-time Super Bowl winner, to guide the
Saints to one of the season's wildest upsets. The Saints led by 10,
then had to rally twice to gain their third win 31-24.
</P>
<P>
   A former Ragin' Cajun, who set records at Southwestern
Louisiana, in his hometown, Jake did more than end the suffering of
the Saints, for at least a week. He brought back the fans. Some
47,000 attended Christmas Eve services at the Superdome, and a
majority of them were cheering heartily for the Cowboys at the
start of the game. By the end of the first quarter, they were
celebrating a Saints revival. In the second half, the Cowboys were
having trouble hearing Aikman's snap count.
</P>
<P>
   All through the day, Delhomme moved into uncharted territory:
his first NFL game, his first start, first interception, first
completion, first touchdown pass, first touchdown run. He tied the
game at 24 with a picture-perfect quarterback draw from the
four-yard line, breaking the huddle quickly because the coaches
were thinking about changing the play _ and he liked that one.
</P>
<P>
   This footnote tells you a lot about the kid, who did everything
but carry babies out of a burning building. But his performance
also creates a minor problem for the New Orleans coaching staff. If
he doesn't turn out to be a one-game fluke, you have to ask, what
took them so long to give him the ball? And did they really think
they had three quarterbacks who were better?
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make me look very smart,'' Mike Ditka said, getting
into an area where most coaches won't go, ``but I thought Jake was
pretty special. His mind is in the game. It was wonderful to see
that. I never played quarterback, but I know I was a lot more
excited than Jake was in my first professional game. He seemed
pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   He appeared in two preseason games, and had three days of
practice with the starters. In short, he rolled out of bed and
completed 16 passes for 278 yards and two touchdowns. He threw a
pair of 50-yarders to Eddie Kennison and Keith Poole that were
right on the money.
</P>
<P>
   Delhomme took the scenic route from Lafayette to New Orleans,
stopping off in Amsterdam in 1998 to battle Kurt Warner for the
starting job with the Admirals. He says Warner, now the hot new
discovery in St. Louis, got the nod three hours before the season
opener. Jake moved on to Frankfurt, in the spring of '99, and took
it to a championship.
</P>
<P>
   If these miracle workers keep popping out of NFL Europe, the
owners might have to rethink the way they invest their millions.
They might soon be scouting elves in Santa's workshop. Hey, Buffalo
is plenty happy with Doug Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   The win really won't salvage the season for the Saints _ ``it's
still dreary,'' Ditka said. But they have a chance to go into the
new year with renewed hope, as opposed to the Cowboys, whose sights
were set so much higher.
</P>
<P>
   A not very subtle passage is taking place at Valley Ranch. The
Cowboys have lost seven in a row on the road, since opening the
season with a win at Washington. They have lost their last two
games to teams they were heavily favored to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   There is a tortured scenario in which the Cowboys can still make
the playoffs, if they beat the Giants and just about everybody else
loses their remaining games. But coach Chan Gailey says he doesn't
know why his team, now 7-8, can't find a way to win, why it blows
leads in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Losing teams rarely know why they lose. The Cowboys are
overrated and uninspired, an awful combination, and they face the
task of rebuilding. The question is how major an overhaul is needed
and whether it starts with Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman was picked off twice, Fred Weary's theft setting up the
first Saints touchdown and the second, by Mark Fields in the end
zone after a tip, foiling the Cowboys after they had reached the
six-yard line and seemed certain to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith rushed for over 100 yards, but his fumble after a
pass reception was returned 58 yards by Weary for the winning
score.
</P>
<P>
   The standout for Dallas was Jason Tucker, the TCU ex who had a
monster game, catching seven passes for 128 yards and returning six
kickoffs for 203 yards. He had a 97-yarder rubbed out by a penalty.
And, yes, he prepped in the European league, with the Rhein Fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
