<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9248 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     12-26 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GIANT STEP FORWARD FOR SHAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Christmas Day found Shaquille O'Neal standing with
his nose pressed against a store window, admiring the only thing he
really, really wants.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't under his tree Saturday because it's something not
even $120 million can buy. The only way to acquire it is through a
layaway plan.
</P>
<P>
   For seven years, O'Neal has been chipping away at his balance.
He's not one to admit it but the truth is he's starting to feel the
pinch. After all, that shiny NBA championship ring won't be there
for his taking forever.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal has only so long to square his account, cinch his legacy.
That's why the Los Angeles Lakers' game against San Antonio _ a
present from the NBA schedule makers _ was the next-best thing to
unwrapping a ring for the 7-foot-1 center.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio embarrassed the Lakers last May on its way to the
NBA title. When the Spurs swept O'Neal and Company out of the
playoffs in the Western Conference semifinals, there was cause to
wonder whether O'Neal would ever win an NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't seem at all serious about earning it, collecting just
two assists in the series, converting only 47.5 percent of his free
throws and playing defense like a blind man.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal led the Lakers in scoring but wasn't close to the best
7-footer on the floor. Tim Duncan conducted a clinic, turning
O'Neal into the world's tallest pylon.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last O'Neal saw of Duncan and David Robinson _
except in his nightmares _ until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   This season had started off like a dream. In the Lakers' first
27 games, O'Neal lived up to his Superman tattoo, averaging 26.9
points, 14.4 rebounds and three blocked shots a game.
</P>
<P>
   But those numbers, while gaudy as any department store Christmas
display in New York City, would look like so much window dressing
if O'Neal didn't show more maturity against the Spurs than he had
the last time these teams had met.
</P>
<P>
   It was time for O'Neal to show the Lakers are for real.
</P>
<P>
   That he did. Playing like a man on borrowed time, O'Neal
mustered 32 points, 11 rebounds and five blocked shots to star in
the Lakers' 99-93 win.
</P>
<P>
   The dexterity he showed in the paint, spinning away from
Robinson for easy points and pirouetting around Duncan for rebounds
and kicking the ball out when prudent, was impressive. So was his
nimbleness in deflecting questions about the significance of his
performance in light of what happened in May.
</P>
<P>
   In acting like it was just another game, O'Neal showed why he
shouldn't quit his day job for the silver screen.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't convince anybody, least of all Lakers point guard
Derek Fisher, who said, ``Shaq wants an NBA championship ring more
than he wants his next paycheck. He'd give you all his paychecks
for one, I assure you.''
</P>
<P>
   What can it mean, a piece of jewelry, to a man who has hundreds
of millions of dollars, mansions, a music career and a spot on the
list of the all-time 50 greatest NBA players?
</P>
<P>
   Everything, Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be financially secure and have all these wonderful
things going on and still seek validation,'' Fisher said. ``You
know how male egos flare. You want people to understand you want to
be the best.''
</P>
<P>
   In case the Spurs didn't get the message, O'Neal drove the point
home, rejecting a couple of Duncan's shots and forcing him to the
bench with six fouls and slowing the foul-plagued Robinson before
he could work up much momentum.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, the most dominant big man in the game was the
most dominant big man on the floor. That ring O'Neal covets must
have looked close enough to touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaquille was great out there tonight,'' Duncan acknowledged.
``He made a lot of big plays for them.''
</P>
<P>
   It's about time. O'Neal knows that. Lakers coach Phil Jackson
was merely stating the obvious when he said, ``Obviously the
window's starting to look smaller and smaller as far as (O'Neal's)
opportunity to be a champion. And the fact he could end up being a
30-year-old guy in this league and not have a championship ring is
something I'm sure is a concern to him. Because he knows in his
heart that he's the most dominant big guy in this game and his
effectiveness is going to be measured by how many championships he
wins.''
</P>
<P>
   It's much too early to measure O'Neal for that championship ring
he covets. Let's just say the balance he has remaining on it looks
significantly smaller today than it did in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
