<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDINALS-MASS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL EXHORTS CATHOLICS TO BE FREE FROM FEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Harrison Sheppard  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Delivering his last Christmas Mass of the
century, Los Angeles Cardinal Roger Mahony told Roman Catholic
worshippers to be free from fear in their daily lives because God
and Jesus are guiding and watching over us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can face death in our own lives without being afraid
because Jesus is on the other side of death,'' Mahony said.
</P>
<P>
   Mahony presided over Christmas Mass at Incarnation Church in
Glendale, nine miles north of downtown Los Angeles, before more
than 600 worshippers. Earlier Saturday he celebrated Mass for
inmates at the Los Angeles County Men's Jail.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the Archdiocese of Los Angeles said he is
optimistic about the state of the world as it enters the next
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could it always be better? Obviously yes,'' Mahony said in an
interview following the mass. ``Still, great progress has been made
and there's great faith in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was hopeful that mankind would continue to make
strides in fighting disease and illness and avoiding major
conflicts in the coming century.
</P>
<P>
   Incarnation Church's Father Paul Hruby said he was delighted
that Mahony chose to honor the church with his presence for the
last mass of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Hruby said he too was optimistic about the state of the world
nearly 2,000 years after Christ's birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's like it was when he came,'' Hruby said. ``There's
a lot of darkness still out there, but still people who can find
faith spread his message to others. I see a lot of good.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
