<HEADER>
A9255 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-ADS27-COX     12-26 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-ADS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Interest groups hammer McCain's reform bill
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A conservative group has spent $100,000 to attack
Republican presidential candidate John McCain in New Hampshire over
the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Americans for Tax Reform, renewing a long-running fight with the
Arizona senator, has a new television ad that claims McCain's
campaign finance reform legislation would be a boon to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The ad levels a blunt attack on McCain that appears to be aimed
at traditional Republican voters. ``He's the only candidate
approved by the liberal New York Times. Bill Clinton, Al Gore and
Big Labor all endorse his top legislative priority,'' the ad says.
</P>
<P>
   While it strikes a similar theme to criticism made by Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, the commercial is an ``issue advocacy'' ad that is
not tied to any campaign and does not urge a vote for or against
any candidate. Instead, it ends by urging viewers to ``call John
McCain and tell him to leave the Republican Party alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Grover Norquist, the group's chairman, denied that the ad is
intended to affect votes in the Feb. 1 primary in New Hampshire. He
said its purpose is ``to get his attention and get him to withdraw
support for the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   That is hardly likely since McCain has ridden the call for
reform to a slim lead over Bush in New Hampshire. He is especially
popular among independent voters, who like the message of reform.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign issued a blistering response to the ad,
which it said was inspired by a desire to keep soft money flowing
to Americans for Tax Reform. The group received $4.5 million from
the Republican National Committee to help counter Democratic
attacks on Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is, who is paying for these ads?'' said
Peter Spaulding, chairman of McCain's campaign in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Norquist said his organization has 90,000 members whose
contributions helped pay for the ad.
</P>
<P>
   Some McCain supporters welcome Norquist's involvement because
they think his tactics are ham-handed and will backfire in
reform-minded New Hampshire. ``You can judge a man not only by his
friends, but also by his enemies,'' Spaulding said.
</P>
<P>
   Norquist has been working against McCain's presidential campaign
since September, when, joined by leaders of other conservative
groups, he traveled to New Hampshire and South Carolina to denounce
the Arizonan. Both states hold crucial early primaries.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has been campaigning to end the unregulated, unlimited
donations to political parties known as ``soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   Those contributions have no direct effect on groups like
Norquist's, although as a lobbyist, he represents several
organizations that make soft money contributions.
</P>
<P>
   And many Republicans fear that ending soft money would benefit
Democrats because labor unions could still use a portion of member
dues to make political contributions. But unions also would be
barred from giving soft money.
</P>
<P>
   Americans for Tax Reform, the National Rifle Association, the
Christian Coalition and other groups also object to another idea
pushed by McCain and his co-sponsor, Democratic Sen. Russell
Feingold of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Feingold want to ban issue advocacy ads in the last
60 days of a campaign because, they argue, the ads are little more
than thinly veiled attacks on a candidate that serve no purpose
other than to influence voters when they are aired so close to an
election.
</P>
<P>
   McCain dropped that provision from his latest Senate bill but
still likes the idea.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
