<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9256 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN27-COX     12-26 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. should be ready to strike back in case of New Year's
attacks
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Happy New Year. Toot. Cheer. Hug. Boom.
</P>
<P>
   If Americans are harmed celebrating the millennial holidays that
mark the birth of the Christian savior, the United States should
treat the crime as an act of war.
</P>
<P>
   Americans should not live in fear that they will be bombed,
poisoned, gassed or kidnapped by anti-American terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   That's what terrorists want.
</P>
<P>
   They want to bring down the mighty. They want to see Americans
cower in fear. They should never get the chance.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has warned Americans to watch out for
terrorism over the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The holidays are a time for giving and love for all. It is a
time for celebrating new beginnings in the shared happiness of
friends and friendly crowds.
</P>
<P>
   The holidays are not supposed to be a time to stay on the alert
for slimeballs who want to kill you and destroy your way of life.
</P>
<P>
   According to the latest government warning, ``The U.S.
government believes that terrorists may be planning to conduct
attacks, including against official and non-official Americans, in
and around the New Year period, from now through mid-January
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably, the warnings by Clinton and other high-ranking
government officials in charge of national security are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials don't want to panic Americans. But they
would be ducking their responsibilities if they failed to give
adequate warnings of actual threats.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago in Jordan, an anti-American terrorist cell of
Islamic extremists was arrested in time to prevent a plan to kill
Americans and Israelis during celebrations on the eve of the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The group supposedly was under the control of exiled Saudi
billionaire Osama bin Laden, the committed anti-American terrorist
indicted for the 1998 bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Intelligence Agency speculates that bin Laden and
his associates could be planning 15 other similar attacks
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   United States border crossings now are on high alert after U.S.
Customs officers in Port Angeles, Wash., arrested Ahmed Ressam, a
32-year-old Algerian-born man with ties to bin Laden and the
Algerian extremist organization, Armed Islamic Group.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam was smuggling sophisticated and powerful bomb-making
material into the United States from Canada in his rented car.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam is not talking, but it is apparent that he was just
dropping off the nitroglycerin, timing devices and other materials
to terrorists already in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden is making himself comfortable in Afghanistan, a county
now run by the Islamic fundamentalist Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
   Many of bin Laden's ``associates'' were armed and assisted by
the CIA during the war that eventually drove the Soviet Union out
of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden and his associates now have declared a holy war on the
United States and Americans anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Two can play that game.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's bin Laden or any other terrorist group, domestic or
foreign, the United States should never allow terrorists to force
Americans to live in fear. When that happens, the terrorists have
won.
</P>
<P>
   It must be remembered that the greatest act of terrorism on
American soil was the homegrown terrorist bombing of the federal
building in Oklahoma City in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   America has its own share of terrorist hate groups and dangerous
loners.
</P>
<P>
   Americans should continue with the holiday plans aware, but
unafraid, of the threat.
</P>
<P>
   However, if terrorists harm Americans during the holidays, the
United States should take off the gloves and treat the outrage as
an act of war.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
