<SLUG> BC-NEWYEAR27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hotel accommodates New Year's staff and eases holiday worries
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Rosalyn McCrary had a touch of the millennium jitters.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of ringing in the New Year with her 9-year-old son,
Brandon, she was to be on the job as a banquet server at the J.W.
Marriott Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Atlanta employees who have to work that night,
McCrary was worried about how her family would fare without her.
Would the lights go out? Would her son be left without telephone
service?
</P>
<P>
   So, McCrary went to her boss. Now, she doesn't have to worry
about her son. He will be at work with her.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel officials are making sure that employees' minds will stay
on their jobs and not on the welfare of their families.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the hotel stopped taking reservations from the
public. Instead, about 50 rooms will be reserved for employees and
their families.
</P>
<P>
   Meals and lodging will be provided free to those who have to
work New Year's Eve _ from executives to bellhops. There will also
be a party for the families and baby-sitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little more reassured,'' said McCrary. ``At least now I
will be with my child in the same vicinity.''
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Peter Kacheris, who plans to bring his family to
the 371-room hotel, said the rooms usually fetch more than $200 a
night.
</P>
<P>
   That's a small price for the hotel to pay for employees' peace
of mind, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many employees said they don't mind working, but they really
wanted their families close to them,'' he said. ``This is the
appropriate thing to do. We're trying to make the best of a strange
situation. I guess during the next millennium, we'll do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
