<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN logo charms tourists
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It may not offer the grandeur of Stone Mountain, the
pizzazz of Underground Atlanta or the myth of Tara. It may seem
like just another gaudy corporate logo. It may serve no civic
purpose other than to give pigeons a place to squat.
</P>
<P>
   But tourists, especially those from overseas, love the
16-by-24-foot CNN logo erected in mid-September at the Techwood
Drive entrance to CNN Center. Many tourists take pictures of what
is quickly becoming the latest Atlanta landmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same thing as going to the Tour Eiffel in Paris or
the Twin Towers in New York City or the Statue of Liberty,'' says
Redgie Blanco, a young Venezuelan. ``It is one of the main things
here in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   The tourists hail from locales as far away as Munich, Germany;
Berlin, Manila, Philippines; Seoul, South Korea; Islamabad,
Pakistan; Taipei, Taiwan; and Alpharetta, Ga. They caress the
aluminum letters, climb inside the C, pose proudly for pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely happy and pleased with the response,'' says
Phillip Evans, senior publicist for Turner Broadcasting Co. The
logo's installation was part of the center's massive renovation.
</P>
<P>
   It's significance goes far beyond a photo op for many visitors.
In many countries with government-controlled media, CNN offers a
largely unvarnished spin on the news. Oliver Lee, a Filipino by way
of Philadelphia, says he'll send a photo to CNN-loving relatives in
the Philippines who remember fondly the journalistic role the cable
network played during the 1986 ``people's power'' revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Hsieh, a precocious 12-year-old from Sunnyvale, Calif.,
says about the logo: ``It's like the symbol of freedom of speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Schulz from Munich is less effusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This image is recognized worldwide, so I guess it's cool,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps her brother-in-law provided the most accurate global
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a typically touristy thing to do,'' Oliver Schulz said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
