<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-RETURNS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Returns from Web purchases not always welcome at stores
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Amazon.com may have one-click ordering, but finding
out how to return the gifts is a little more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   More shoppers than ever took to the Web to do their holiday
shopping this season. Expansive ad campaigns promised consumers the
experience would be quick, easy and a huge time-saver.
</P>
<P>
   But online merchants weren't ready for the crush of
cybershoppers, which resulted in out of stock items only days after
Thanksgiving, orders that couldn't be fulfilled or delivered by
Christmastime and a litany of other problems. Many shoppers, unsure
if they would ever see their online purchases, wound up doing the
one thing they dearly hoped to avoid _ heading to the mall just
days before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the buying frenzy is over, the second phase of the
online shopping experience _ returning unwanted items _ is
underway.
</P>
<P>
   David Schatsky, principal analyst with Jupiter Communications,
saw the e-commerce sky falling in November, and unfortunately for
everyone involved, his predictions of unfulfilled orders and return
hassles have turned out to be correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet selling chain is not a smoothly integrated
chain,'' he said. ``Many sites report they don't have integration
between their Web site and their inventory management. Even if the
Web site is running smoothly, there could be problems down the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Few online shoppers bothered to familiarize themselves with the
return process and few Web sites make their return policies readily
visible.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, returning online purchases isn't quick, easy or time
saving.
</P>
<P>
   For example, even the savviest online shopper will have trouble
finding Amazon's return policy, which is hidden under the ``help''
section.
</P>
<P>
   If you thought you were going to save yourself some hassles by
shopping online at Barnesandnoble.com, figuring you could just
bring returns back to your local superstore, think again. The
Barnes and Noble online return policy (also under the ``help''
section) states that the ``bricks and mortar'' retail stores will
not accept online returns.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to return an online purchase, you'll probably have
to send it back the way it came _ via UPS or regular mail, at your
own expense. If you didn't save the packing materials, you'll have
to check the Web site's help section to find the address and
directions for returns. Amazon, for example, requires returns in 30
days in the original packing. Software, music and videos must be in
original, unopened and pristine condition. Other Web sites have
different rules for returns, but for the most part, few will pay
postage. If you don't like it, you'll have to pay to send it back.
</P>
<P>
   The same retailers who excitedly trumped their online stores
this holiday season are now busy refitting their sites with easy to
find buttons to help users track their orders and send e-mail to
customer service departments.
</P>
<P>
   The beautifully designed Williams-Sonoma Web site has
anticipated or perhaps already experienced the wrath of angry
shoppers and has a link called ``Where is my order?'' on its start
page. The link takes users to a page where they can track missing
packages along with phone and fax numbers, and a form for customer
inquiries. However, the company's return policy is in small print
under the ``frequently asked questions'' icon and doesn't say if
the retail stores will accept online returns or not.
</P>
<P>
   Toysrus.com has a Web site that appears to be the cyberspace
version of a lump of coal. Ironically, it's actually easier to
return toys than to order them.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 23, Toysrus.com said it could no longer guarantee
Christmas delivery. Even though the company worked hard to get its
site ready for Christmas, it underestimated the holiday demand. If
you did get the toys on time but the recipient didn't like them,
you can take them back to the nearest Toys 'R Us store for a
refund. The Gap stores also will accept online purchases.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone will be so accommodating, says Forrester
Research analyst Seema Williams. ``Internet holiday newbies like
Crate &AMP; Barrel and Nieman Marcus will face a rude awakening when
disgruntled online buyers turn to brick-and-mortar store managers
to solve Internet problems. Offline merchants must prepare store
managers to provide customer service for online shoppers and inform
all sales staff about Web prices, products, and return policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Before you head off to the mall with your online purchases, call
the store first or check the Web site to make sure you will get a
warm and courteous welcome. Not every store or sales associate will
know what to do with your dot-com returns or exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
