<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9261 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-SOFT-MONEY27-COX     12-26 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFT-MONEY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush, McCain at odds over soft money
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a downtown civic center on a chilly Des
Moines night, Arizona Sen. John McCain worked to heat up the chase
for the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   With a quiet fervor, McCain talked about his plan to overhaul
the way America finances politics by killing off the unlimited
``soft money'' that makes a mockery of contribution limits. For
McCain, it is the be-all issue, the necessary first step in dealing
with just about every major topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without reining in soft money and reducing the role of money
in politics, we will never have a government that works as hard for
the average American as it does for the special interests,'' McCain
says.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's plan for soft money is simple: End it. Under his
vision, all political contributions would be subject to the limits
and scrutiny required under federal law for donations to individual
candidates. Currently, that includes a $1,000 cap on individual
donations and a $5,000 limit on donations from political action
committees. McCain favors increasing those limits.
</P>
<P>
   Though Texas Gov. George W. Bush and McCain generally agree on
the issue, it's become a flashpoint between them. Bush, in what the
McCain campaign insists is an effort to mislead voters, charges
that McCain's plan would be tough on soft money from business
interests that generally back Republicans but light on soft money
from labor groups that lean heavily Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, whose fund-raising prowess forces him to defend
against charges of being the big-monied candidate of special
interests, campaign-finance reform is a potentially tricky issue.
It's hard to challenge something that sounds so wholesome, though
the GOP majority in the Senate manages to kill it off every year.
At the same time, however, Bush campaign strategists don't believe
campaign finance reform is a burning issue with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ranks somewhere lower on the scale than education and
defense and taxes and welfare,'' said Karl Rove, Bush's top
strategist, after the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bush believes he has found a hole in McCain's top
issue, as well as an enemy _ big labor _ to drag into the fray.
``Unilateral disarmament,'' Bush says, over and over again of any
plan that would not address the labor union issue.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law that says union members' dues money cannot be given
to candidates. Labor's direct support of candidates must come from
separate funds stocked with money voluntarily given for that
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the Federal Election Commission notes in its guidelines,
``there are many ways in which a corporation or union may legally
participate in federal election activities.''
</P>
<P>
   The most common route is soft money. Union members' dues can
wind up as soft money, spent at will by labor leaders. Critics,
like Bush, say that means union members' dues wind up supporting
candidates and causes the members might not like.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of laboring people who are Republicans and
conservatives,'' Bush told McCain during the recent debate. ``And
yet, under the vision you've got ... it's OK that (labor leaders)
take their money and spend it the way they want to spend it. I
don't think it's fair.''
</P>
<P>
   He wants to cut labor's political spending by pushing so-called
``paycheck protection,'' a concept that says union members' dues
should not be spent on politics without the members' OK. It's a
change that would restrict union officials' use of soft money funds
stocked with members' dues. McCain supports the concept, but it was
not included in the version of his campaign finance reform that bit
the dust in the Senate this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is for it, why did he not include it in the plan he put
before the Senate?'' asked Bush spokesman Scott McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, says McCain spokeswoman Nancy Ives, is tactics. The
bill was stripped to a bare-minimum version to get it to the Senate
floor, according to Ives. McCain's plan was to then add amendments,
including one to make sure labor money would be subject to the same
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate killed the bill before the amending began.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush and McCain seem to agree on what to do about soft
money from business and labor, they may not agree on what to do
about soft money from individuals. McCain wants to ban such
contributions. Bush has not weighed in on that issue, allowing
McCain to attack him for supporting ``a loophole large enough to
drive a Chinese tank through,'' a not-so-subtle reference to
political donations from foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush stands as guardian of special interest control of
political process,'' the McCain campaign said in a release this
month.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's dream, rejected annually by his GOP colleagues in the
Senate, is a political system unfettered by soft money. He feels so
strongly about it that he teamed up with Democratic presidential
contender Bill Bradley in a pledge to reject soft money if each
becomes his party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to indirect support of candidates, soft money does
things like help pay for national political conventions.
Restricting it could force a major re-tooling of how politics is
financed. Though McCain favors raising the caps on donations,
there's little chance they would be raised to anywhere near the
levels of soft money now given.
</P>
<P>
   Still to be answered is how the system would function on less
cash. For example, the major parties count heavily on soft money to
pay for their national conventions. Organizers of next summer's GOP
convention in Philadelphia are now trying to line up $100,000
donations toward the $35 million cost of the event. Organizers of
the Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles also are luring
high-dollar support.
</P>
<P>
   Bush believes full, prompt disclosure is the best campaign
finance reform. To that end, his campaign uses its Web site to list
contributions shortly after they are received. McCain has posted
his donor lists, but only after they are filed with the Federal
Election Commission to meet its quarterly reporting deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis by the nonprofit, independent Center for Responsive
Politics shows union money becomes Democratic money in overwhelming
proportions. In the 1998 election cycle, labor spent $60.8 million
on politics. Ninety-two percent of it went to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the numbers, Texas AFL-CIO spokesman Ed Sills says Bush
is distorting the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal for paycheck protection assumes that there would
be an imbalance if you take away (corporate) soft money,'' Sills
said. ``Historically, that's never been the case.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 election cycle, business interests kicked $667
million into the system, about 10 times more than labor ponied up,
with about 60 percent of the business money going to Republicans,
according to the Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Sills also questions Bush's allegations about how labor's
political money is spent. Unions are democracies, Sills said, and
members are free to vote their leaders out of office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are democratic with a small `d','' said Sills. ``I know
people sometimes accuse us of being Democratic with a large `D.' If
that's the case, it's because a majority of our membership points
in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any other organization that is being asked to
disregard its majority viewpoint for the sake of its minority,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
