<HEADER>
A9263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      12-26 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(js) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, Dec. 27:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Russian forces pushed deep into
Grozny on the second day of an operation aimed at gaining control
of the Chechen capital. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FALUN-GONG (Beijing) _ In the most significant
prosecutions yet in the government's campaign against the Falun
Gong spiritual movement, three men and one woman accused of being
top leaders were handed prison sentences Sunday ranging up to 18
years. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-STORM (Paris) _ A fierce winter storm swept through
Europe, killing at least 20 people in France, uprooting some 4,000
trees and leaving 2 million homes without power. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   IVORYCOAST-COUP (Paris) _ The ousted president of Ivory Coast
left for exile, under French protection, leaving the country under
the control of its military leaders. By Donald G. McNeil Jr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BURUNDI-RELOCATION (Bujumbura, Burundi) _ It would be hard to
name a place in the world where the forced relocation of a third of
a million people would not spark major international protest. But
this has not been so for Burundi, where in the last three months
the government has herded 350,000 people from their homes into
grubby camps. The government calls the camps a last resort to end a
series of guerrilla attacks. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-TV-SHEEPDOG (London) _ If the BBC has its way, millions
of Britons will spend Monday evening watching a special edition of
``One Man And His Dog,'' a program in which a sheep running in the
wrong direction qualifies as high drama. Monday's episode is a
crucial test for ``One Man and His Dog,'' which was threatened with
cancellation last winter. But the threat caused such an uproar that
the BBC finally agreed to broadcast a special over Christmas. By
Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PSYCHIATRIC-HOSPITALS (Pembroke Pines, Fla.) _ South Florida
State Psychiatric Hospital is at the heart of a cutting-edge
experiment, the first state mental hospital in the nation to be
completely turned over to a private company that hopes to operate
it at a profit. In 1997, legislators in Florida, which faced a
court order to improve conditions here, voted to contract out the
operation. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLIC-UNIVERSITIES (Washington) _ When the nation's Roman
Catholic bishops voted in November to tie Catholic universities
more closely to the church, they left institutions like Georgetown
University with a lingering question. What will it mean for
Catholic theologians, teaching in Catholic universities, to have to
apply to their local bishop for a certification that they are
teaching ``authentic'' doctrine, a requirement laid out in the
document the bishops approved? By Gustav Niebuhr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-SURPLUS (Washington) _ Thanks to projections of a large
and growing federal budget surplus, the current presidential
candidates are the first in decades who can credibly propose
expensive tax and spending programs, and they are doing so in ways
that reveal clear differences within and between the parties. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ Just 15 months ago, former
Senator Bill Bradley was not a candidate and Vice President Al Gore
was the party's presumptive nominee. Today, he has matched Gore in
fund-raising, built a national organization and given himself a
shot, though perhaps a long one perhaps, at upsetting the vice
president. But the coming weeks will provide a critical test of
Bradley's staying power.By James Dao. (This is the first of 5
articles on the state of the individual presidential campaigns as
the primary season begins.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-ORGANIZER-PROFILE (Washington) _ George Stevens is
co-producing his biggest outdoor extravaganza ever, the New Year's
Eve celebration, ``America's Millennium,'' on the Mall in
Washington. By John M. Broder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Undated) _ ``Essay'' by William Safire.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ ``On America'' by Bob Herbert.
