<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-MUSIC-PICKS (New York) _ Having built his career on
his passion for an unusually wide range of musical styles and an
uncanny sense of how to combine them in entertaining and
illuminating ways, Peter Schickele, host and creator of the PDQ
Bach program, was invited to discuss some of the recordings that he
considered the best of the century _ or, why not?, the millennium.
By Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   SPALDING-GRAY-DOMESTICITY (Sag Harbor, N.Y.) _ At home with
Spalding Gray, a question is asked of this monologist who has long
used his life experiences as dramatic material: Now that he has
preserved all his peak paternal experiences to date and presented
them to the public, will this chapter continue to hold his
interest? Will whatever consumes him next diminish his newly
discovered commitment to home? By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   BAROQUE-BRAZIL (Paris) _ A beautifully designed exhibition is
now giving Parisians a chance to discover not only some two dozen
works by the sculptor Aleijadinho, but also other treasures from
the Baroque movement that shaped Brazilian art and architecture
from the early 17th century to the early 19th. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   RIGOLETTO-OPERA-REVIEW (New York) _ Real opera fans relish
nothing more than a nice, contentious debate about a singer, and
Paolo Gavanelli is going to provoke one for sure. The Italian
baritone sang the title role in Verdi's ``Rigoletto'' at the
Metropolitan Opera on Friday night, the first performance this
season of the 1989 Otto Schenk production. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   SITWELL-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ There have been individual
biographies of Edith and Sacheverell and at least two major studies
of the Sitwells as a group and cultural phenomenon. Up to now there
had been no biography of Sir Osbert Sitwell, and Philip Ziegler,
best known for his life of Lord Mountbatten, has written one:
``Osbert Sitwell'' (Knopf). By Richard Eder.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   DICTAPHONE-TURNAROUND (Undated) _ After a sometimes stumbling
overhaul that involved several years of depressed sales, declining
profits and near brushes with bankruptcy, Dictaphone is now nearly
in the black. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-NEWS (Undated) _ As they move from a cyberchildhood of
experimentation and starry-eyed possibilities into a sometimes
awkward adolescence on the Web, the nation's largest news
organizations are getting more sure-footed. And as the news site
with largest audience, MSNBC.com is emerging as an exemplar of the
new medium's new self-assurance. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Madison Avenue has embraced
millennial marketing with the fervor of a zealot _ albeit one who
has banished apocalyptic intimations in favor of the world view
articulated by Mad magazine's Alfred E. Neuman: ``What, me worry?''
By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY-STOCKS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Why has Merrill
largely missed out on technology bankers' big bull market? To hear
Merrill Lynch explain it, the firm has not missed out at all; it
simply got a late start. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   ACCURATE-TIME (Undated) _ Uptight New Year's Eve celebrators
intent on uncorking the Champagne at precisely the right
millisecond of midnight may find themselves in a quandary. Which
clock on Earth offers the most accurate accounting of time? In
fact, there is no single answer. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   WARRANTIES-ONLINE (Undated) _ Until recently, online buyers were
spared the experience of a hard sell for extended service
warranties, as most World Wide Web merchants had neglected to offer
extended service plans. Now, however, retailers are looking more
closely at warranty options, for several reasons. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-EAST-TIMOR (Singapore) _ While aid workers help East
Timor's people build an economy and government from ruins, the U.N.
Development Program this month dispatched an official to bring the
World Wide Web to the capital, Dili, and to begin drafting
blueprints for the kind of national data network that is fast
becoming vital to participation in the new information economy. By
Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CONSULTANTS (Undated) _ They have devoted months and
sometimes years to raising consciousness about potential year 2000
computer disruptions. Now, many of the most prominent worriers are
folding their tents. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Teresa
Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TV-MEDIA (Undated) _ The Internet continues to change
the face of the conventional media. Take the Toronto television
market, where for the last 18 months viewers have been able to
catch up on the news by turning to a 24-hour cable television
station that looks more like a World Wide Web page than a
traditional video screen. By Dylan Loeb McClain.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ The Media Talk column, with items on
