<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-NEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LED BY MSNBC.COM, A NEW JOURNALISTIC FORM DEVELOPS ON THE
INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)  (mk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minutes after The Seattle Times disclosed on Dec. 17 that a man
with the makings of a fertilizer bomb in his car trunk had been
arrested in Port Angeles, Wash., news sites across the World Wide
Web were sprinting to deliver details. But no other site gave the
Port Angeles arrest a showcase to match MSNBC.com, the news Web
site that for the last year has consistently commanded the largest
audience.
</P>
<P>
   A picture of the Seattle space needle dominated the home page,
overlaid with the headline ``Y2K Plot?'' In slightly smaller type
were the words ``NBC News: Officials fear suspect was part of plan
to bomb Seattle.'' A report by NBC correspondents popped up with
links to the Web site of NBC's Seattle affiliate, KING-TV. Another
link took the reader to a video report by an NBC correspondent.
Another led to a map showing where, according to law-enforcement
authorities, the suspected terrorist Osama Bin Laden had been
active.
</P>
<P>
   The MSNBC.com report was an archetype of a new journalistic form
and of the emerging values of general news sites as run by major
news organizations. These include speedy, professional crafting of
original material, multimedia options, clean packaging and lots of
self-promotion.
</P>
<P>
   As they move from a cyberchildhood of experimentation and
starry-eyed possibilities into a sometimes awkward adolescence on
the Web, the nation's largest news organizations are getting more
sure-footed. And as the news site with the largest audience,
MSNBC.com, a partnership of General Electric's NBC and Microsoft,
is emerging as an exemplar of the new medium's new self-assurance.
</P>
<P>
   The site is also in sync with those who believe that the verb
``to brand'' is not a neologism but an imperative; MSNBC.com puts
the logo of one of its parents, NBC, on everything in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile its other parent, Microsoft, puts links on its Web
sites to let some of the biggest audiences anywhere on the Web know
that MSNBC.com is the place to go for news.
</P>
<P>
   ``MSNBC is heavily branded,'' said Tim McGuire, who, as the
senior vice president for new media at The Minneapolis
Star-Tribune, is a professional connoisseur of online news
packaging and a student of what does and does not work in news
delivery on the Web. ``When we come out the other side of this tube
we're in, the big brands will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   But the site does not ride just on NBC's name or Microsoft's
muscle. ``One of the keys to this whole thing,'' McGuire said, is
``using the information that plays to the medium's strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done some interesting things and are creating a new
medium,'' he said. Of course, as he and other newspaper journalists
say, broadcasters are more used to supplying continuous news
updates.
</P>
<P>
   Among MSNBC.com's innovations, according to its editor, Merrill
Brown, are things like short news clips on breaking developments,
taped in the site's offices in Secaucus, N.J., and a navigation
scheme that creates direct paths among scores of pages on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Like CNN Interactive's sites, which MSNBC.com dethroned as the
Web's most-visited news organization earlier this year, it is also
quick to provide supplemental interactive graphic material. A
recent example was an elegant montage that showed how genetic
researchers deconstructed the DNA on chromosome 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal from the beginning has been to package the
experience, instead of giving people endless lists of things _
which for many other news sites is the norm,'' said Brown, who has
been editor in chief of the site since its start in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But MSNBC.com does not live by content alone. The site's ties to
the behemoth sites of Microsoft, which funnel news-hungry audiences
its way, are the envy of its rivals. According to MSNBC.com's
statistics, about one-third of the site's traffic comes from the
pages of MSN.com, the Web site of Microsoft Network.
</P>
<P>
   In October, according to Media Metrix, the Web-audience
measurement firm, MSNBC.com had more than 7 million ``unique''
visitors _ a measure of how many different computer users visited
the site, regardless of how many times each may have returned. The
October figure topped a previous high for news sites that MSNBC.com
reached in July, the month that John F. Kennedy Jr.'s sudden death
drew a record news audience on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The October figure outstripped its rival CNN.com by about 1
million unique visitors _ although Scott Woelfel, the general
manager of CNN Interactive, says that CNN.com's visitors typically
look at more pages a visit than MSNBC.com's audience does.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC.com, with a staff of about 185, has achieved its No. 1
rank chiefly by making deals with an array of partners. The list
includes The Washington Post and Newsweek, the crime reporting site
APBnews.com, the technology news provider ZDNet and a site
specializing in cancer news called oncology.com.
</P>
<P>
   For partners like The Washington Post, MSNBC.com has an enviable
heft. Chris Ma, the senior vice president of
Washingtonpost.Newsweek Interactive, said, ``We felt that we very
much needed a partner who lived in this world to help shepherd our
brand and our product into a multimedia realm.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers with national reach, like The New York Times and
Gannett's USA Today _ which has the biggest audience of any
newspaper, both in its print and online forms _ find their sites
evolving with ambitions similar to those of the successful
broadcast organizations' sites, like MSNBC.com, cnn.com and
abcnews.com. They want to provide quality information and video
across subjects that include financial news and science and sports,
and they are trying to decide how best to do it.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two months, both The New York Times and The
Washington Post have moved into the 24-hour news cycle,
establishing links with newsroom editors who channel dispatches to
the sites during the day. The Times on the Web also has updated
financial reports filed by a small financial news staff, operated
by Thestreet.com, a Web operation in which New York Times Co. has a
6.3 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Coll, the managing editor of The Washington Post, said in
a recent interview, ``We see the Web as another edition of the
newspaper.'' But, he added, ``it is incumbent on us to make sure
that as we add editions, we maintain a commitment to the same
quality of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard J. Meislin, the editor in chief of the Times' unit Times
Co. Digital, said: ``Our gut instinct is going to be that people
come to The New York Times for news that is the quality of The New
York Times newspaper and they would like to have that throughout
the day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
