<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-TRADEMARKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLERS OF BRAS, BEER AND BEEF AMONG THOSE EXPLOITING Y2K 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MILLENNIUM-AD-COLUMN, PATENTS, Y2K-CONSULTANTS) 
(mk) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a rush to capitalize on millenniummania, year 2000 trademark
applications have been tumbling into the Patent and Trademark
Office at a terrific rate.
</P>
<P>
   According to Alan Davidson, executive vice president for
trademarks at MicroPatent, a patent and trademark research company
based in East Haven, Conn., more than 4,400 trademarks now have the
number 2000 in them.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is that handy shorthand ``Y2K.'' ``Before 1995,
there was not a single registration that used `Y2K,''' Davidson
said. ``Now, in one form or another there are currently 400 of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the ``Y2K''varieties: Y2K Bras; Y2K Beer; PraY2k; OKinY2K;
Y2K Happens; IMY2KRU?; Y2KOK, and Y2Kool.
</P>
<P>
   And Davidson's personal favorite: Y2K Complacent.
</P>
<P>
   As for the word ``millennium,'' it appears in more than 2,200
marks (including all the trademarks that misspell ``millennium'').
More than 200 of them are for the ``official'' this or that of the
millennium. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   The Official Multiple Vitamin of the Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The Official Mattress of the Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The Official Donut of the Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The Official Canned Beef of the Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The Official Flea Market of the Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The Official Work Boot of the Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The Official Condom of the New Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   So which city had enough hubris to dub itself the ``Official
City of the Millennium''? Paris? Tokyo? New York?
</P>
<P>
   No, said Davidson. San Jose, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 1633EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
