u f BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT &LR;      12-26 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAY TUNED FOR MORE IN `THIS WEEK' REVAMP 
STAR THRILLER WRITER OPTS FOR A NEW TACK 
BENETTON ADS OFFER TOUR OF DEATH ROW
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Inside ABC News, staff members viewed last week's dismissal of
William Kristol, the conservative commentator, as perhaps only an
initial move in what most conclude is a long overdue reshaping of
the network's faltering Sunday morning discussion program, ``This
Week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If David Westin thinks this is the answer to the show's
problems, he has no idea what's wrong with that show,'' said one
longtime ABC News producer.
</P>
<P>
   But Westin, president of ABC News, gave no indication that he
believed removing Kristol would turn around what has become almost
a ratings freefall for ``This Week.'' And Eileen Murphy, an ABC
News spokeswoman, said that the ouster was only a ``step along the
way'' to addressing the program's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Once the dominant network Sunday talk show, ``This Week'' is now
at best a distant second behind NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' and
lately has often finished an embarrassing third behind CBS's ``Face
the Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Westin began making moves when he removed the show's longtime
executive producer, Dorrance Smith, in September.
</P>
<P>
   One specific complaint Westin had about the show under Smith was
in its coverage of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, which he called
``tedious'' because the voices on the show were all saying mainly
the same critical things about President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The show has declined even further since Smith's departure. He
was replaced by Virginia Mosely, who had been senior producer. No
senior producer has yet been named to replace her.
</P>
<P>
   In its days of glory, ``This Week'' had a single anchor, David
Brinkley. Since he retired, the program has used Sam Donaldson and
Cokie Roberts as dual anchors. Several staff members at ABC News, a
unit of the Walt Disney Co., said the program could not hope to
recover until it focuses on a single anchor.
</P>
<P>
   But Westin ``is not planning any other imminent changes of
personnel,'' Ms. Murphy said. ``Cokie and Sam will remain the
co-anchors.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Star Thriller Writer Opts for a New Tack
</P>
<P>
   For readers of airport literature and fans of popular cinema,
the name John Grisham elicits three words: blockbuster legal
thriller. But Grisham is revealing a new side of himself, while
indulging in what some might call vanity publishing.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, he will publish a semi-autobiographical
literary novel. Thed book, ``A Painted House,'' will be published
over the next year in serial form in The Oxford American, a
bimonthly review of Southern literature of which Grisham has been
co-owner and publisher since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The first 32-page installment appears in the magazine's
January-February 2000 issue, which is on newsstands a month before
Grisham's next legal thriller, ``The Brethren,'' is to be published
by Doubleday.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Smirnoff, the editor of The Oxford American, said that
Grisham was eager to explore new formats. ``This allows him to try
something new and not interfere with his annual thrillers,''
Smirnoff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Painted House'' takes place in the Arkansas delta in the
early 1950s, centers on a family of Arkansas cotton farmers, David
Gernert, Grisham's editor and agent, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a portrait of life in a certain part of the South in a
certain time,'' Gernert said. ``It was so unlike his major books
that we thought we should do something different with it.'' Gernert
said that Doubleday, which has published most of Grisham's legal
novels, would most likely publish this book when it was completed
at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Like all things Grisham related, word of the serialization has
caused a frenzy in some quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We usually print about 50,000 copies,'' Smirnoff said. ``And
the distributors wanted 400,000 this time.'' The magazine managed
to print 260,000 copies. And Smirnoff said that the magazine had
sent out 1 million direct-mail pieces, exhorting readers to
subscribe for the Grisham-serialization year.
</P>
<P>
   Readers received the solicitation in December, when consumers
tend to be at their most distracted, and were asked to prepay. Both
tactics are considered no-no's in the psychologically delicate
chess game of direct-mail marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to take a lot of his fans by surprise,''
Smirnoff said. ``And if it succeeds, it will be something pretty
new for the industry. If it flops, I am going to have to drag
myself out to a pasture somewhere and do something drastic.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYSNKI
</P>
<P>
   Benetton Ads Offer Tour of Death Row
</P>
<P>
   During the 1990s, the Benetton Group S.p.A. became notorious for
politically provocative advertising. The tactic even gained a name,
shockvertising, to describe the Italian company's use of
contentious images to sell its United Colors of Benetton apparel
around the world: an AIDS patient on his deathbed, two horses
procreating, an actor and an actress dressed as a priest and a nun
kissing, victims of genocide and Mafia vendettas.
</P>
<P>
   For the new decade, Benetton is at it again. Oliviero Toscani,
Benetton's creative director and editorial director of Colors, the
Benetton magazine, is producing a 96-page brochure of photographs
of inmates on death row in prisons in seven states. The images are
accompanied by interviews conducted by Ken Shulman, a journalist
based in Cambridge, Mass.; the inmates are identified by name and
the dates they have been sentenced to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe, we hate the death penalty,'' Toscani said. ``I'm
pretty sure that one day it won't exist any more.''
</P>
<P>
   The brochure is to be distributed in 13 languages in 60
countries, making its first appearance in the United States in the
form of consecutive advertising pages in the February issue of Talk
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an intensely controversial subject, a thought-provoking
campaign that's perfect for us,'' said Ronald A. Galotti, president
and publisher of Talk magazine in New York. The magazine is a joint
venture of the Hearst Corp. and the Miramax Film Corp., part of the
Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that Talk is running the ads, because
Toscani, in addition to his duties at Benetton and Colors, has been
hired by Talk as creative director to retool the magazine's look.
</P>
<P>
   There was no quid pro quo, Galotti said, adding that ``his
people back in Italy made the decision'' to spend the amount in
``seven figures'' to buy the advertising space.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were only that easy'' to sell ad pages, Galotti said,
laughing. ``Anybody who could come with 100 ad pages, we'd hire.''
</P>
<P>
   _ STUART ELLIOTT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
