<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DICTAPHONE-TURNAROUND     12-26 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICTAPHONE-TURNAROUND-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
 
(ATTN: Conn., Texas)  
 TAKE A MEMO: DICTAPHONE IS STILL IN BUSINESS  (ART ADV: A photo is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John H. Duerden well remembers his surprise four years ago when
Stonington Partners, the buyout firm that had just bought the
Dictaphone Corp., asked him to be Dictaphone's new chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, my God, Dictaphone, are they still in business?''
Duerden recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was yes _ but not so that anyone would notice.
Dictaphone, which was founded in 1888 by Alexander Graham Bell and
was once synonymous with business dictating equipment, had pretty
much faded from public view.
</P>
<P>
   The company was profitable, but not astoundingly so. It was
growing, but only at 3 percent a year. Though it had developed new
products in the 16 years that it had been part of Pitney Bowes
before Stonington bought Dictaphone, even the newest of them was
getting gray. And though the days of executives dictating letters
were on the wane, Dictaphone _ despite its competence in recording
voices _ had never capitalized on the boom in voice mail, cellular
telephones and the like.
</P>
<P>
   When the Stonington call came, Duerden, a former Xerox
executive, had just resigned from the top sales job at Reebok
International. Although he was en route to an executive slot at
Nike, he was tempted by the ``fantastic offer in money and stock''
that Dictaphone's owner dangled. But what hooked him, he said, was
reading the prospectus and recognizing a vast potential in using
voice as a tool for communicating over computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   Duerden, 59, had lived through Xerox's first encounters with
digital document processing technologies. So he was attuned to the
transitional possibilities at Dictaphone. ``For too long,
Dictaphone thought of its core competency as word processing,'' he
said. ``It's not. It's recording, storing and retrieving data that
happens to enter the system as voice.''
</P>
<P>
   That became his strategy for the company. And after a sometimes
stumbling overhaul that involved several years of depressed sales,
declining profits and near brushes with bankruptcy, Dictaphone is
now nearly in the black.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Duerden knew worldwide sales and marketing from Reebok,
he had a grasp of technology and office equipment from Xerox, and
we figured he could take Dictaphone to a higher level,'' said Trey
Fitzgibbons, a partner at Stonington, which plans a public offering
of Dictaphone stock sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   Dictaphone does have a few products that use IBM technology to
convert dictated files into text, but voice recognition is not a
major component in Dictaphone's product lines as yet. The company
does plan to introduce products for medical applications next year
that will utilize speech recognition software. While such products
might wreak havoc on the job market for human transcribers, they
could be a major boon to Dictaphone's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Dictaphone, based in Stratford, Conn., still derives
most of its sales from office dictating equipment _ albeit newer
digital models that allow executives to download the dictation onto
a computer network that can be retrieved by human transcribers. But
the company's future, as Duerden sees it, lies with medical
records-keeping, as well as systems to log, monitor and trace
telephone calls to customer help desks, financial trading floors
and 911 emergency lines.
</P>
<P>
   Dictaphone's older products had long been used in those markets.
But most of them required scrolling through lengthy tapes to find a
particular call, and they needed to be manually transcribed to be
entered into a computer system as text files.
</P>
<P>
   Duerden figured Dictaphone had to offer a medical product that
would enable doctors to get accurate transcriptions of patient
information with minimum delay, and enable hospitals to
automatically use that information to update patient records as
well as send bills out more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   For help desks and other call-center customers, he decided the
company had to provide systems that not only retrieved archived
calls more easily, but that tracked those calls if the customer had
been handed off to several agents.
</P>
<P>
   The company needed products, in other words, that would help
Dictaphone clients provide better service to their own customers.
Dictaphone now contends that it has such products. In June, the
company introduced Da Vinci, a Windows-based system for recording
and monitoring calls at large call centers. A product that can cost
as much as $400,000 to buy and install, Da Vinci already counts
America Online, First Union National Bank and Wal-Mart Stores among
its customers. In October, Dictaphone followed with Freedom, a
smaller version that sells for as little as $6,000 for a setup that
can handle four workers. Capital Blue Cross and several small
police departments have already ordered Freedom systems.
</P>
<P>
   On the medical front, Dictaphone is developing an Internet-based
system in which Dictaphone will accept dictated files from doctors
and return partly-edited transcripts. Another offering, Enterprise
Express, which can convert a doctor's dictation to an e-mail voice
attachment, already is selling well to hospitals, despite price
tags that range from $200,000 to $3 million. The product,
introduced in 1997, has already captured 55 percent of the health
care market and ``is turning into one of Dictaphone's most
important product lines,'' said John J. Helms, a high-yield bond
analyst at the APS Financial Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Initial users seem pleased. Doctors affiliated with the Covenant
Health System, a network of four hospitals in Lubbock, Texas, can
examine patients in their offices, send a patient to the hospital,
then phone in relevant information that is recorded as a digitized
voice file. A central computer logs in the file and automatically
assigns it to the next available human transcriber. Often, the
voice file is already logged in and partly transcribed by the time
the patient reaches the hospital, according to Lyn Moore,
Covenant's director of health information management.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Radiologists, cardiologists and pathologists who are conducting
medical tests on the hospital premises use some 20 Enterprise
Express phone stations scattered around the hospital to dictate
test results that will be added to patient records.
</P>
<P>
   The system can handle simultaneous dictation by 112 physicians,
more than 10 percent of the hospital's physician team. And Ms.
Moore called the voice quality superb. ``The transcriptionists tell
me it's as though the dictator was in the room,'' she said.
``That's cut errors and transcriber turnover.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Dictaphone, as it lays plans for a stock offering, is getting an
ever-warmer reception on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they'd talked about going IPO nine months ago, everyone
would have laughed,'' said George Edwards, a portfolio manager at
Prudential Investments whose holdings include Dictaphone's
high-yield bonds. ``But the numbers are stronger, and there are
visible new products.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is still laboring under a heavy debt load from
Stonington's $462 million buyout in 1995. And its revenue was up
only 4 percent in the first nine months of 1999, to $264 million.
But Duerden said that sales were up 12 percent in the third
quarter, compared with a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   And the company cut its losses to $4.6 million during the last
nine months, compared with a loss of $26.9 million for the first
nine months of 1998. Moreover, Dictaphone's nine-month operating
profit _ a number that does not include interest payments _ was
$27.5 million, compared with just $2.2 million for the first nine
months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Dictaphone's path has been strewn with boulder-size
obstacles. When Duerden took over the company, it had 550 sales
people and 700 service people, few of whom had the expertise to
sell digital products to doctors or police chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Dictaphone let many of these employees go, figuring that
independent dealers could sell their low-end products. But dealers
have been lukewarm to the products, particularly overseas, and
Dictaphone's office-equipment revenue has declined. And the
sales-force reduction did little to trim Dictaphone's costs, since
the cuts were largely offset by the cadre of programmers and
digitally savvy sales people who were needed for its new products.
</P>
<P>
   Duerden also has made some expensive mistakes. He made a
last-ditch attempt to introduce a voice mail product, but found
that Lucent Technologies and other well-heeled competitors had the
market locked up. And he licensed a product from an Australian
company that was meant to replace court stenographers with
recording and transcription devices. But the system was expensive
and complicated to use, and judges were skeptical. Unable to
finance a marketing blitz to win them over, Dictaphone pulled the
plug last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spread our net too widely,'' Duerden said, ``and we brought
Da Vinci and Freedom to market a year later than we would have
liked.''
</P>
<P>
   The delay has hurt the company, which is playing technological
catch-up with competitors like Lanier Worldwide in the medical
market, and Nice Systems Ltd. of Israel in the call-center world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dictaphone has a shot at a reasonable market share, but they
are too late to ever be leaders,'' said Victor Halpert, an analyst
at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the contrast to Nice is sobering. Nice's sales
skyrocketed to $120 million this year from just $5 million in 1994,
when it first branched out from military intelligence systems to
systems for recording and tracking call-center communications.
Benny Levin, Nice's chairman, predicts sales will hit $500 million
in five years, as he uses the company's publicly traded stock and
$110 million in cash on hand to acquire other companies. ``We won't
let what happened to Dictaphone happen to us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Duerden readily acknowledges the implied criticism. ``Benny
jumped our technology by three years, forcing us to reconfigure Da
Vinci before we could even introduce it,'' he said. ``You can't
discount these kinds of competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, after a miserable 1998 _ a year in which Dictaphone
consistently lost money _ Dictaphone is finally back on its fiscal
feet. The digital products are easier and cheaper to make than
their tape-based predecessors, which bodes well for Dictaphone's
profit margins. It is using some of its excess manufacturing
capacity to make facsimile machines for Pitney Bowes and to
assemble circuit boards for Monarch Electronics, another former
Pitney Bowes subsidiary. The manufacturing business is bringing in
about $50 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Dictaphone has also revved up overseas sales to call-center
customers, and now counts the London offices of Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter and the Bank of Nova Scotia among its users in Britain and
Canada, and is signing up distributors in the Far East. And it is
talking to Siemens and other computer companies about including
Dictaphone recording and tracking systems in some of their
products.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Stonington, which specializes in leveraged buyouts, financed the
Dictaphone purchase with high-yield bonds, and from the first
Dictaphone was saddled with $40 million annual interest on a $350
million debt. For a company whose sales barely hit that level, it
was an onerous load.
</P>
<P>
   ``We generated $64 million from operations, and immediately had
to funnel $40 million toward interest,'' recalled Joseph
Skrzypczak, a former Pitney Bowes executive who is now Dictaphone's
chief financial officer. ``Take another $12 million or so out for
maintaining computers and other capital investments, and you don't
have a lot left for anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   By last year, Dictaphone's income from operations was down to
$31 million, not enough to service debt, let alone develop products
and upgrade computer systems. Stonington made up the shortfall,
though. And, analysts estimate that Dictaphone's operating income
is back near $60 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're approaching the time when we're ready for the public
markets, and we're happy we own Dictaphone now,'' Fitzgibbons said.
``But there were certainly times we wondered if we hadn't overpaid
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dictaphone still labors under $345 million in debt, and
Skrzypczak concedes that its interest payments and modernization
expenses leave it little breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference, though, is that in 1995 all we had was debt
and old products,'' he said. ``This time we've replenished our
product line.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
