u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      12-26 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Dec. 27, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a cold front that crossed the Northeast, readings
will average 10 degrees colder on Monday afternoon than they were
Sunday. Very strong, gusty winds from the northwest will add to the
numbing chill. On the southern and eastern shores of the Great
Lakes, snow showers and squalls will produce measurable snowfalls
in the traditional lake effect snow regions. Meanwhile, east of the
Appalachians, clouds will break and mix with sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, high and middle clouds will streak across the
Gulf Coast into the panhandle of Florida. To the north, skies will
be partly cloudy with an isolated flurry in southern Missouri as a
jet stream disturbance crosses the region. Meanwhile, clouds and
drizzle will continue to plague the Rio Grande Valley and spread
into much of south Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It will remain chilly in the northern Great Lakes, where
readings will stay in the teens throughout the day. However, warmer
weather will approach from the west as mild Pacific air moves
inland. Some locations in the western Dakotas and eastern Montana
will see readings more typical of early November as winds from the
west descend the Rockies and warm.
</P>
<P>
   Patches of dense fog will persist in the interior of Washington
as burly high pressure overhead prevents moisture near the surface
from mixing into the drier upper levels of the atmosphere. Farther
south, much of California will remain mild and sunny, although a
few patches of high clouds will drift across the central sections.
It will be sunny and seasonable in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Melting the Icebox
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas Day, International Falls, Minn., recorded their
highest temperature for the date with a reading of 45 degrees.
Meanwhile, Atlanta only had a high of 41 degrees on Christmas. This
unusual occurrence was the result of a large dip in the jet stream
bringing chilly air far into the Southeast. At the same time,
strong surface winds from the southwest in International Falls
pushed the mercury upward. Despite cooling off Sunday behind a cold
front, milder Pacific air will again move into the northern Plains
later this week, bringing unseasonably high readings to the
region. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
