<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Monday, Dec. 27, Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service
Supervisor is Josephine Schmidt (888) 346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FALUN-GONG (Beijing) _ In the most significant
prosecutions yet in the government's campaign against the Falun
Gong spiritual movement, three men and one woman accused of being
top leaders were handed prison sentences Sunday ranging up to 18
years. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   BURUNDI-RELOCATION (Bujumbura, Burundi) _ It would be hard to
name a place in the world where the forced relocation of a third of
a million people would not spark major international protest. But
this has not been so for Burundi, where in the last three months
the government has herded 350,000 people from their homes into
grubby camps. The government calls the camps a last resort to end a
series of guerrilla attacks. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Photo reefer to:
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-STORM (Paris) _ A fierce storm with hurricane force winds
barreled across northern France and parts of Switzerland and
Germany Sunday, injuring hundreds and killing as many as 62 people,
including one victim who was crushed in a falling ski gondola in
the Swiss Alps. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SPEEDING-DRIVERS (Hartford, Conn.) _ Early last week, Mathew
Hennessy, mild-mannered computer programmer, was driving toward
Manhattan at 100 mph. He is one of a growing number of American
drivers who, according to traffic experts, are pushing highway
speeds to new heights. Steering bigger and more powerful cars and
exploiting increasingly lax police enforcement, more drivers than
ever are treating speed limits as suggestions, experts say. By Paul
Zielbauer.
</P>
<P>
   NEWEST-IMMIGRANTS (Bridgewater, N.J.) _ By leapfrogging to the
most desirable suburbs, many Asian immigrants are upending
stereotypes about new immigrants being poor and invisible, tethered
to ethnic neighborhoods, desperate to wriggle out of the city.
Instead, these newcomers are younger and more economically diverse,
equipped with graduate degrees and work visas, gifted in science
and technology. By David W. Chen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-SURPLUS (Washington) _ Thanks to projections of a large
and growing federal budget surplus, the current presidential
candidates are the first in decades who can credibly propose
expensive tax and spending programs, and they are doing so in ways
that reveal clear differences within and between the parties. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ Just 15 months ago, former
Senator Bill Bradley was not a candidate and Vice President Al Gore
was the party's presumptive nominee. Today, he has matched Gore in
fund-raising, built a national organization and given himself a
shot, though perhaps a long one perhaps, at upsetting the vice
president. But the coming weeks will provide a critical test of
Bradley's staying power. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   (This is the first of 5 articles on the state of the individual
presidential campaigns as the primary season begins.)
</P>
