A9288 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CALENDAR27-COX     12-26 1539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALENDAR27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attempts to change calendar strong, but largely unsuccessful
 &HT;    By George Bennett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Alan Dechert was once a fringe
presidential candidate whose anti-nuke message faded before the
1988 Iowa caucuses. But he didn't really learn about longshot
campaigns until he tried to change the way the world reckons time.
</P>
<P>
   With 1999 in its waning days and sales of his ``Year Zero
Calendar'' languishing at a few hundred, Dechert concedes there's
no global groundswell to scrap centuries of religious, cultural and
business tradition and recognize 2000 as the year 0 instead.
</P>
<P>
   But the California computer programmer isn't giving up his
lonely pursuit of calendar reform. Nor is Randy Bruner, a
Cincinnati psychic who believes 2000 will bring a ``mind shift''
and widespread acceptance of his New Age adaptation of the ancient
Mayan calendar. And International World Calendar Association leader
Norman Lindhjem of Bend, Ore., keeps plodding on even though he's
the reform group's only member.
</P>
<P>
   They are part of a long and futile tradition. French
Revolutionists, Kodak founder George Eastman, United Nations
functionaries and other pamphleteers and proselytizers have all
tried and failed to dislodge the inelegant Gregorian calendar and
its politically incorrect cousin, the Anno Domini scheme of
numbering years.
</P>
<P>
   Some have wanted to redefine history. Others have simply been
bugged by the calendar's uneven months and the fact that dates
never fall on the same day of the week from one year to the next.
</P>
<P>
   The scattered tribes of modern reformism would seem to have to
have a wider audience as 2000 approaches. Calendrical curiosity is
soaring. There's been revived interest, for example, in Dionysius
Exiguus, the sixth-century monk who came up with the current system
of numbering years from the birth of Jesus Christ. A computer
search for published references to the B.C. and A.D. impresario
shows more than 200 mentions this year, compared to only 74 in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   But such interest hasn't spilled over to calendar reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millennium fatigue,'' suggests a disappointed Rick McCarty, a
philosophy professor at East Carolina University in Greenville,
N.C., who maintains a calendar reform Web site and pitches a reform
idea of his own called the ``Long-Sabbath Perennial Calendar.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting about 10,000 visits to his site in 1998, McCarty
thought the run-up to 2000 would bring more Internet traffic this
year. It hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   So the reform-minded continue in relative obscurity. Dechert and
a few others harbor real hopes of change. Most are mere hobbyists
who post their ideas on the Internet. There's a metric calendar
with 10-day weeks. There's a 13-month ``Tranquility Calendar'' that
counts years from the 1969 moon landing and includes an ``Aldrin
Day'' on leap years. There are several perennial calendars, in
which days and dates are the same from one year to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Strictly speaking, calendar reformers are those like McCarty who
would alter the 12 uneven months of the calendar Pope Gregory XIII
instituted in 1582. Dechert and those who focus on the numbering of
years are ``chronologists.''
</P>
<P>
   The twain seldom meet.
</P>
<P>
   Chronologists are usually trying to make a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a different world, and a change of year-numbering
acknowledges that,'' says Dechert, who mentions the threat of
nuclear war and overpopulation as evidence that ``things have
drastically changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Calendar reformers, on the other hand, tend to fixate on the
tricky mathematics of organizing 365.242199 days (the time it takes
the earth to revolve around the sun) into a harmonious set of weeks
and months. It's that portion of a day to the right of the decimal
point that has vexed calendar makers for thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman calendar reform under Julius Caesar in approximately
45 B.C. was based on a 365.25-day year, so years were 365 days with
an extra day every fourth year. Sounds close enough, but that extra
0.007801 of a day per year adds up over the centuries. By 1582, the
calendar was 10 days out of whack with the true solar year, causing
problems for the scheduling of farming and religious rites.
</P>
<P>
   Pope Gregory XIII hacked 10 days from October 1582 to realign
the calendar with the sun. And, importantly, the length of a year
was figured to be 365.2422 days. The slight modification meant
there would still be a leap year with an extra day every four
years, except in years that end with 00 and are not divisible by
400. So 1700, 1800 and 1900 were not leap years, but 2000 will be.
</P>
<P>
   (That's the source of one potential Y2K problem. If computers
think 2000 is 1900, they won't be able to deal with Feb. 29.)
</P>
<P>
   The Gregorian solution was so close to accuracy that the
calendar will not be an entire day out of sync with the true solar
year until 4909.
</P>
<P>
   Today's calendar reformers aren't satisfied, though. Using a
traditional 7-day week, a nonleap year divides into 52 weeks plus
one day. That means dates never fall on the same weekday from one
year to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Most people are untroubled by this.
</P>
<P>
   But many reformers say it's inefficient for businesses,
governments, schools and other institutions to have to use a new
calendar each year.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak's Eastman was particularly animated on the subject. In the
1920s, he railed against the months of unequal lengths, some with
four paydays and some with five, because they made it impossible to
produce uniform financial reports and comparisons from one month to
the next. He disliked the fact that holidays occurred on different
days of the week from one year to the next. ``Wandering Easter''
was especially vexing, Eastman said, because years with an early
Easter hurt retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   His solution: dividing the year into 13 months of 28-days
apiece, with each month beginning on a Sunday. That accounts for
364 days, so the 365th day of the year would be called ``Year Day''
and inserted between Saturday, Dec. 28 and Sunday, Jan. 1. For leap
years, an extra ``Year Day'' would be inserted midyear.
</P>
<P>
   Bruner, the Cincinnati psychic, also advocates a 13-month
calendar with a ``day out of time'' at year's end. He's less
concerned with business efficiency than with putting people in
touch with a Mayan-inspired biorhythmic ``natural cycle'' of 28-day
months.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Gregorian calendar, Bruner says, ``you're completely
out of touch with yourself and your body and nature. That's where
separation begins. Separation is the beginning of the fear
paradigm.''
</P>
<P>
   He said advocates of his ``Dreamspell'' calendar have lobbied
the United Nations and the Vatican and heard ``nothing particularly
positive.'' No matter. The ``mind shift'' he expects in 2000 will
create ``a grass-roots movement where people will wake up and say
something isn't right'' with the Gregorian calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Bruner isn't the first to look to the U.N. for calendar reform.
In the 1950s, a U.N. committee entertained the idea of a ``World
Calendar'' that always begins on a Sunday and has a blank day at
year's end.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. squelched the idea. Henry Cabot Lodge Jr., the U.S.
representative to the U.N. at the time, said the blank day would
``conflict with the principles of important religious faiths'' by
throwing off the cycle of six days and a sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   The main proponent of the World Calendar, a rubber heiress and
prolific calendrical author named Elisabeth Achelis, pressed on.
Her idea received the ``guarded support'' of House Minority Leader
Gerald Ford, according to a 1966 New York Times article, but
eventually got lost in the political and historical shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   Achelis' calendar is still advocated today by Lindhjem's
International World Calendar Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only one,'' says Lindhjem when asked about the group's
membership. Lindhjem doesn't care too much about the approach of
2000. He's a calendarist, not a chronologist. He's focused on 2006
_ the next time New Year's Day falls on a Sunday and the ideal
time, he says, to switch to the World Calendar. If not 2006, then
2012 or 2017.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of time,'' Lindhjem says.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Gregorian calendar was the product of about 300
years of reform efforts. And Dionysius Exiguus' year-numbering plan
took centuries to win widespread acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Dechert, too, says it might take years for his Year Zero
proposal to catch on, in which case 2000 would be recognized as 0
after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   He began promoting the Year Zero idea in 1996, sending letters
and e-mails to the White House and other world leaders as well as
to local governments in hopes that a city council somewhere would
endorse his proposal and gin up some publicity.
</P>
<P>
   He's offered his self-published calendar for sale at a few
bookstores and through Amazon.com on the Internet, but hasn't had
much response. Another setback came this year when the U.S. Patent
and Trademark Office turned down Dechert's request to register
``Year Zero Calendar'' as a trademark.
</P>
<P>
   He's undeterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any movement that changes things starts with a few people,''
Dechert says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
