 &HT;    1ST UPDATE
 &HT;    EDs: Adds: MAYFIELD-OBIT
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CoxNet Cox News Service budget
 &HT;    FOR MONDAY, December 27, 1999
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For questions, please call 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WEEKEND DUTY EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   IN ATLANTA: Chante LaGon, 404-526-5456
</P>
<P>
   IN WASHINGTON: Art Dalglish at 301-460-6176 (home) or
301-996-3036 (cell phone).
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL
</P>
<P>
   SOFT-MONEY _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Though Texas Gov. George W. Bush
and Arizona Sen. John McCain generally agree on the issue of soft
money, it's become a flashpoint between them. Bush, in what the
McCain campaign insists is an effort to mislead voters, charges
that McCain's plan would be tough on soft money from business
interests that generally back Republicans but light on soft money
from labor groups that lean heavily Democratic. For Bush, whose
fund-raising prowess forces him to defend against charges of being
the big-monied candidate of special interests, campaign-finance
reform is a potentially tricky issue. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-ADS _ WASHINGTON _ A conservative group has spent
$100,000 to attack Republican presidential candidate John McCain in
New Hampshire over the holidays. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MAYFIELD-OBIT _ ATLANTA _ Composer, songwriter Curtis Mayfield
dead at 57. (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CNN-LOGO _ ATLANTA _ It may not offer the grandeur of Stone
Mountain, the pizzazz of Underground Atlanta or the myth of Tara.
It may seem just another gaudy corporate logo. But tourists,
especially those from overseas, love the 16-by-24-foot logo erected
in mid-September at the Techwood Drive entrance to CNN Center.
Seems all of the tourists take a picture of what is quickly
becoming the latest Atlanta landmark. (Chapman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WEB-RETURNS _ ATLANTA _ Amazon.com may have one-click ordering,
but finding out how to return the gifts is a little more difficult.
More shoppers than ever took to the Web to do their holiday
shopping this season. Now that the buying frenzy is over, the
second phase of the online shopping experience _ returning unwanted
items _ is underway. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   NEWYEAR _ ATLANTA _ Rosalyn McCrary had a touch of the
millennium jitters. Instead of ringing in the New Year with her
9-year-old son, Brandon, she was to be on the job as a banquet
server at the J.W. Marriott Hotel. So, McCrary went to her boss.
Now, she doesn't have to worry about her son. He will be at work
with her. (Poole, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
