<HEADER>
A9292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SITWELL-BOOK-REVIEW-N     12-26 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SITWELL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OSBERT SITWELL': HE WROTE NOT WISELY NOR WELL, BUT WHAT DINNERS! 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(lb) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The glittery Sitwell siblings were Edith, the most original and
frail; Sir Osbert, alternately lodged on Parnassus and in
Derbyshire (where he oversaw the family property); and Sacheverell,
who might have preferred a quiet life but was not allowed one. They
dispensed entertainment, excellent dinners (Osbert, mainly, as
titled heir and money man) and a reassuring artistic buffoonery to
England's interwar literary generation, shattered and needing
reassurance.
</P>
<P>
   We can dress up and play at art, was the Sitwell message, though
as members of what the Spanish would call the rancid aristocracy
they were lordly serious about it. It was a message in which the
real artists in their fizzy crowd _ Evelyn Waugh and Anthony Powell
_ and such vastly talented writers as Cyril Connolly found a kind
of nursery solace.
</P>
<P>
   Other eminences were skeptical. T.S. Eliot, always polite to the
hierarchy of the literary-social set he had entered as an
anglicized immigrant, was privately condescending.
</P>
<P>
   ``All foliage and no filberts,'' Virginia Woolf observed of
Osbert's elaborately posturing and quite vacuous poems. ``The
rhododendrons grow to such a height,'' she remarked of his prose.
She confessed to liking him, though, in part because there was
charm beneath his comic arrogance and even a kind of innocence. One
thinks of Alice's pugnaciously rattly White Knight who keeps
toppling from his horse.
</P>
<P>
   It amused Woolf to be amusing about the Sitwells. This may be
the key to their 40-year-reign as London literary celebrities. Art
is dangerous when it gets to bedrock; doubly dangerous when the
rock shifts _ as it did from the 1920s through the '50s _ and
triply dangerous when a collar is forced around the shifting.
</P>
<P>
   The class illusions and constrictions of England were just such
a collar; and it was the genuine artists who were simultaneously
held rigid and torn. What a relief to frolic with the Sitwells'
mock feuds and posturing, sturmlets and dranglets _ all conducted
with utmost seriousness _ and neo-Swinburnian artistic effulgence.
Ruins are comforting; the English used to be good at them; and
Edith, Osbert and Sacheverell were toy Tintern Abbeys.
</P>
<P>
   There have been individual biographies of Edith and Sacheverell
and at least two major studies of the Sitwells as a group and
cultural phenomenon. Up to now there had been no biography of
Osbert, and Philip Ziegler, best known for his life of Lord
Mountbatten, has written one.
</P>
<P>
   He makes no great claims about meeting a need or filling a hole,
or about giving us the person who wielded a notable pen. He asserts
only the smallest virtues for Osbert's poetry and fiction _ the
forthcoming edition of the ``Oxford Book of English Poetry'' has
nothing by any Sitwell _ a bit more for his travel writing, and
about his journalism the main point is that it was copious and
fluent.
</P>
<P>
   The most enduring work, he tells us, is the five-volume
autobiography that Osbert turned out in the 1940s. Perhaps it is
the best work _ Ziegler valiantly bears out the modesty of his
claims for Osbert's other writing by quoting some fairly horrible
stuff _ but ``enduring'' is questionable. A fine five-volume
autobiography? It is like praising the fine curve of a 5-foot nose.
</P>
<P>
   Of the author's two reasons for writing and for being read, one
of them seems doubtful. The history of English letters would have
been different without the Sitwells, Ziegler tells us. Technically
this may be true, but the history they play a significant role in
is not of literature but of literary life.
</P>
<P>
   There are many amusing details about the London social and
literary scene as the author portrays the character and
year-by-year history of his subject. What is lacking is a framework
that would place the details in a larger context. Late chapters
titled ``Parkinson's'' and ``A Good Deal of Time in Bed'' set out
the minutiae of the illness of a figure whose health has never been
made very significant. Can you have ``Taps'' without ``Reveille''?
</P>
<P>
   Ziegler's more winning reason is that he enjoyed bringing to
life the man and the crowd Osbert moved among. Enjoyment is an
excellent thing, assuming that it is communicated.
</P>
<P>
   The author communicates quite a lot. There is a poignant and
sometimes funny account of the lifelong quarrel between Osbert and
his father: partly over money, which the old baronet both begrudged
and lavished on his high-living son, but mostly as the blind
shovings of two eccentric solipsists bent upon establishing each
other's nonexistence.
</P>
<P>
   There is Osbert languidly (though briefly) enjoying the easy
life of a peacetime Guards officer. At one point, while marching
his men through London on a hot day, he commandeered a city bus at
sword's point so they could all ride.
</P>
<P>
   There are his literary efforts, the catered scandals, and the
enjoyably showy feuds with Noel Coward, Cecil Beaton, Wyndham Lewis
and a dozen others. Many of these were conducted in mutually
promoting partnership with Edith. (Sacheverell tagged along.) The
critic F.R. Leavis made the famously sour remark that the Sitwells
belonged to the history of publicity, not literature.
</P>
<P>
   There are clever things said, though they tend to come from
Osbert's friends and enemies. Many of his own sallies sag before
they have sallied far enough to make it. Perhaps like Falstaff he
was not so much witty in himself as a cause of wit in others. The
bons mots that Ziegler collects have something of a
you-had-to-be-there quality.
</P>
<P>
   One of the loveliest is the most devastating and, considering
its source, the most unexpected. On good terms with the royal
family, Osbert would send his books to the duchess of York, future
queen and now the queen mother. Once, very kindly, she wrote back:
</P>
<P>
   ``What a lot of words you know, pleasant-sounding words strung
pleasantly together and entrancing to read or listen to. I wish
that I knew more.'' Put not your trust in kings. They may tell you
the truth.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `OSBERT SITWELL'
</P>
<P>
   By Philip Ziegler
</P>
<P>
   444 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
