<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SPALDING-GRAY-DOMESTI     12-26 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPALDING-GRAY-DOMESTICITY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MELLOWER MONOLOGIST, TRYING HOME LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAG HARBOR, N.Y. _ In the green clapboard Victorian house,
everything is much as Spalding Gray describes it in his latest
monologue: the pine plank floors and angled doorways, the view of
the old Whalers' church from the window, the books with ``death''
in the title lining the library walls.
</P>
<P>
   But the scene is not quite the idyllic vision of firelit family
togetherness that Gray depicts in his latest work about one day in
his household, ``Morning, Noon and Night,'' which he is performing
on Sunday and Monday evenings at the Vivian Beaumont Theater at
Lincoln Center through Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   It is an average winter weekday, after all. The light is less
golden than gray. The children are scattered in different
directions _ his stepdaughter, Marissa, 13, is still at school;
Forrest, 7, at a drum lesson; Theo, almost 3, in front of an
``Austin Powers'' video. There are beds to be made upstairs, piles
of laundry in the basement, dentist appointments to keep and dinner
parties to attend.
</P>
<P>
   And that, of course, raises a question for this accomplished
monologist, who has long used his life experiences as dramatic
material: Now that Gray, 58, has written his opus on fatherhood,
now that he has preserved all his peak paternal experiences to date
and presented them to the public, now that the day-to-day details
of getting his children out the door, picking them up from school
and putting them to sleep are no longer essential to his work, will
this chapter continue to hold his interest? Will whatever consumes
him next diminish his newly discovered commitment to home?
</P>
<P>
   Sitting back in one of the Colonial wing chairs that flank the
fireplace, comfortable in blue corduroys, blue turtleneck sweater
and black shoes, Gray readily concedes that is exactly what he
cannot know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real life has always let me down,'' he said. ``That's why I do
the monologues. I have always said I'd rather tell a life than live
a life. But I have to live a life in order to tell one.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray also said there might not even be another monologue.
(Though he also said he says that after every monologue.) ``It's
been 20 years, and this is a full circle,'' he said. ```Morning,
Noon and Night' feels like I've landed. I've played it all. There's
nothing I'm conscious of that I've not spoken.''
</P>
<P>
   Domesticity and life outside the city have clearly had something
of a calming effect on Gray, who left a SoHo loft and a racier life
three and a half years ago for this home on the east end of Long
Island. In his latest performance he talks about appreciating the
open space that surrounds him now, the sight of the water, the
slower rhythm of rural existence. In an interview he said that he
was glad to be away from the ``erotic energy'' of the city and that
having children had muted his ``promiscuous drive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel somewhat reformed,'' Gray said. ``Like an A.A.
person, I'm taking it one day at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had been weighing other ways of earning money and
spending his time: voice-overs, a soap opera (his agent advised
against it), volunteering at a hospice. Gray said he planned to
teach autobiographical storytelling one day a week next fall at
Southampton College. He has been active in protesting a nuclear
reactor in the area.
</P>
<P>
   But it is hard to imagine Gray without a new piece to write and
perform. His theatrical work seems to organize his life, to ground
him and connect him to a cultural, urban world he is far from ready
to abandon. He said he liked taking the bus into New York City
every Sunday evening to perform, buying a green health drink on his
way to theater, soaking up the vitality of streets.
</P>
<P>
   And what else would Gray do with his journals, composition books
he fills with his scrawled script every morning at the dining room
table with some words capitalized, like VULNERABLE and THUNDER?
</P>
<P>
   That is why he recently returned to therapy for the first time
in three years. ``I was going into a new turbulent, chaotic place
because I wasn't focused on something, another monologue,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the monologue, Gray describes his first son as open and
inquisitive, but Forrest was 5 at the time he wrote it. Now Forrest
is 7 and pulling away. Instead of their easy conversations
exploring Forrest's countless questions _ What is behind the stars?
Why don't we feel the world spinning? _ he now often walks paces in
front of his father to assert his independence and withholds
certain things to claim some privacy. Gray said this stung in
unexpected ways, that he was experiencing a kind of mourning.
</P>
<P>
   It was the birth of Forrest, Gray said, that lifted him from a
self-destructive spiral that left him fearing he would go the way
of his mother, who committed suicide when he was 26.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, perhaps, Gray had tried to persuade his
companion, Kathie Russo, 39, not to have the baby. He had been
having an affair with Ms. Russo during his marriage to Renee
Shafransky, who figured prominently in his previous monologues. Ms.
Russo, a talent agent, represents other solo performers like Eric
Bogosian and Danny Hoch, and works from home.
</P>
<P>
   In the monologue, Gray describes how he told Ms. Russo that he
didn't want their next baby, who turned out to be Theo. But he also
describes how he changed his mind and now cherishes the little boy
as ``my outdoor bliss kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Russo wants to adopt a child, Gray said he was
finished having children. ``I'm glad the house is the size it is
because that limits it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the monologue what is not said but comes across clearly is
that Ms. Russo is carrying most of the load. ``Where is Theo?'' you
find yourself wondering as Gray describes stretching out on the
living room rug for his yoga exercises or whizzing past the duck
pond on his daily bike ride or toying with the possibility of a
quick sail in his beetle boat.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Russo said, ``He really pitches in,'' but added that while
she put off having her breakfast and reading the newspaper until
the children were off to school, Gray was able to settle down to
eat and read while the chaos still swirled around him. ``How can
you do that?'' she said she sometimes asked him. One also suspects
Gray is a better talker than a listener. Ms. Russo's view: ``He's a
better talker.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gray described his latest monologue as ``a watershed piece for
me.'' Every other monologue has been about trying to conquer
something. ``Terrors of Pleasure'' in 1986 was about renting his
first summer house in the Catskills; ``Swimming to Cambodia'' in
1990 was about making his first film; ``Monster in the Box'' in
1992 was about trying to finish his first novel. ``Morning, Noon
and Night'' is just about family, Gray said, ``this nest, this
choice of this town, this stopping.''
</P>
<P>
   In his review of the play in The New York Times, Peter Marks
wrote that Gray's current subject matter seemed to have pulled him
outside himself for the first time. ``Mr. Gray may have gained
renown for his obsessive contemplation of his own navel,'' Marks
said. ``But during 95 lovestruck minutes at the Vivian Beaumont
Theater he begins to shed his myriad neuroses as if they were the
strands of a suffocating chrysalis.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, at this point in his life Gray seems as close to
normal as he has ever come. He has a back yard, eats leftovers for
lunch, rents a house on Martha's Vineyard every summer, drives a
Volvo. ``He's more content,'' Ms. Russo said. ``He used to be the
party guy: `Let's go! Where's the next big event?'''
</P>
<P>
   He said that his creative consultant, Paul Spencer, had
suggested that he needed more conflict in ``Morning, Noon and
Night.'' But Gray disagreed. ``I'm not there anymore,'' Gray said.
``What is the shadow? It's the dealing with the ruminations on
death.''
</P>
<P>
   In his monologue Gray talks about lying in the dark, thinking
about all the things that could go wrong, realizing in a reverie
about Forrest how painful it would be to die and never be able to
``kiss, touch or hug this sweet child again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why the existentialists have always been my heroes,''
Gray said in the interview. ``In the face of the absurd, one makes
a choice, a positive choice, to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless Gray seems less transformed by fatherhood than
tempered by it. He guards his independence, noting that he likes
walking outside to his work studio adjacent to the house, and
wishes it were even farther away.
</P>
<P>
   He still clearly harbors a stormy, complicated soul and seems
stirred by it. One senses that he needs some angst in his life,
that it gives him something to wrestle with and mull over and makes
him feel alive. ``If anything starts good, it's bound to get
worse,'' Gray said. ``It can't get better. That's transcendence.
That's entropy.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, after performing ``It's a Slippery Slope,'' his
monologue about learning how to ski, Gray said he suspected he
would lose interest in the sport. But he has surprised himself by
staying with it. ``I hope the same will hold true for family,'' he
said. ``After the monologue ends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
