<DOCNO> NYT19991226.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9295 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RIGOLETTO-OPERA-REVIE     12-26 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIGOLETTO-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RIGOLETTO': FANS HAVE A SINGER TO ARGUE ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
 (jw) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Real opera fans relish nothing more than a nice
contentious debate about a singer, and Paolo Gavanelli is going to
provoke one for sure. This Italian baritone sang the title role in
Verdi's ``Rigoletto'' at the Metropolitan Opera on Friday night,
the first performance this season of the 1989 Otto Schenk
production. By the first intermission audience members in the lobby
were heatedly exchanging assessments of Gavanelli's singing.
</P>
<P>
   Since his Met debut in 1990 as Count di Luna in Verdi's
``Trovatore,'' Gavanelli has sung periodically with the company,
including some performances earlier this season as Alfio in
``Cavalleria Rusticana.'' But Alfio is a relatively short role. No
one can perform Rigoletto, a touchstone of the baritone repertory,
without revealing the full range of his vocal and dramatic
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Gavanelli's singing is not conventionally beautiful. His tone is
somewhat thin, and he uses vibrato sparingly. His voice is not
especially large: He can summon robust sound in his chesty low
range, but his top notes lack power. His middle-range lyrical
singing is, depending on one's view, either the hallmark of his
artistry or his major shortcoming.
</P>
<P>
   He shapes Verdi's long-spun melodic lines with suppleness and
poignancy, singing with focused tone, confident breath control and
restrained emotionalism. Some opera buffs will consider this
approach as true to the Italian operatic style that values melodic
continuity and vocal evenness. Other vocal devotees will simply
find his singing thin-toned, insufficiently supported and croony.
</P>
<P>
   Those who can overlook his vocal idiosyncrasies and listen for
style and interpretive richness will find things to admire in
Gavanelli's work. He is also a vivid actor. As played here, this
hunchbacked jester at the court of the rapacious Duke of Mantua
commands the stage, entertaining the courtiers with his barbed
jokes and mocking imitations of the Duke's wronged accusers.
</P>
<P>
   Conveying Rigoletto's bodily deformity, Gavanelli shuffles from
side to side as he walks. At the palace he is light on his feet and
full of swagger. But later on, alone, sunk by the reality that he
must make a fool of himself to amuse men he despises, that same
unsteady step turns heavy, halting and pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   The Duke was sung by the tenor Marcelo Alvarez, who made his Met
debut last season in the new production of Verdi's ``Traviata,''
and Alvarez is also likely to divide opinion. He emerged from
Argentina atop a wave of publicity promoting him as the dashing
young tenor hope for the future. Though he is looking a little
huskier these days, he certainly has a burnished, sizable voice.
</P>
<P>
   But on this occasion he seemed to cover over some vocal rough
spots with tenorial bluster and emotive huffing. Perhaps because
``La Donna e mobile'' is such an iconic aria, he was wary of
fussing around with it: this was his most straightforward and
impressive singing of the night. But in general his blatant
approach was in stark contrast to Gavanelli's subtlety.
</P>
<P>
   The soprano Sumi Jo was excellent as Gilda, Rigoletto's
tragically overprotected daughter. When she made her Met debut 10
years ago (in this role) Ms. Jo was already a technically exquisite
and stylistically informed singer. Her artistry has only deepened
over the years, and her voice today is more richly colored than
ever. Ms. Jo's soft, sustained upper-range-lying singing was
especially beautiful. Though not a highly skilled actress, she was
always a winning stage presence.
</P>
<P>
   The fine German bass Franz Hawlata was chillingly good as the
hired assassin Sparafucile, and the mezzo-soprano Victoria
Livengood was a naturally seductive and vocally alluring Maddalena,
Sparafucile's sister and accomplice in crime.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to tell after just one performance, but Vladimir
Jurowski, a 27-year-old Russian-born conductor who made his Met
debut, could become valuable to the company. He has already
conducted a wide range of repertory in opera houses around the
world, and he brought a precise technique, abundant energy and
excellent musical instincts to his work.
</P>
<P>
   The playing of the orchestra was crisp and resonant. He was
admirably sensitive to the singers, allowing them plenty of
breathing room without losing the thread of musical continuity.
Gavanelli, who sings with great expressive freedom, was lucky to
have Jurowski in the pit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 1810EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
