<DOCNO> NYT19991226.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9296 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-EMAIL-EAST-TIMOR-2TAK     12-26 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMAIL-EAST-TIMOR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. AGENCY IS BRINGING TIMOR ONLINE (HORSEMEN IN MONGOLIA, AS
WELL)
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also sent in category ``f'') 
(nk) 
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ With a legacy of violence and a quarter-century of
repressive Indonesian rule, East Timor lacks almost all the
essentials: adequate drinking water, health care, a working
educational system.
</P>
<P>
   To that litany of need, add a contemporary essential: Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   So while aid workers help East Timor's people build an economy
and government from the ruins of the province, the United Nations
Development Program this month dispatched an official from Malaysia
to bring the World Wide Web to the capital, Dili, and to begin
drafting blueprints for the kind of national data network that is
fast becoming vital to participation in the new information
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The network is the key,'' said Gabriel Accascina, manager of
the United Nations Development Program's Asia-Pacific Development
Information Program, who visited East Timor this month. ``It's the
one enabling factor today that is basically changing the way people
think, changing the way governments operate and giving
opportunities that weren't there before.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Timorese, the information superhighway so often cited in
technologically advanced places was a distant bit of geography
early in September, when pro-Indonesian militias responded to an
Aug. 30 vote for independence by laying waste to the territory.
Now, everything _ the buildings, the port, the civil administration
and the schools _ must be rebuilt, a task being overseen by the
U.N. transitional administration in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The process could take take two or three years. While it is
going on, a nation is to be created using the Internet as one of
its building blocks _ something of a first.
</P>
<P>
   Accascina said the initial step was to establish an Internet
connection from Dili via satellite to Singapore, giving the U.N.
staff reliable access to e-mail service. The next task, he said,
would be to import the computer equipment needed to develop the
first Web site operating from East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations created the Asia-Pacific Development
Information Program in 1997 to foster the use of information
technology for social and economic development. From its
headquarters in Kuala Lumpur, the program tries to help Asian
governments and community groups develop their own information
structures and adopt the policies and legislation for entering the
electronic marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of work to do. Though Tokyo, Singapore and Hong
Kong compete with each other as centers of Internet innovation,
most of Asia still lacks either the telephone lines or the
computers needed to get online. Only eight of every 1,000 Asians
outside Japan use the Internet, according to estimates by the
International Data Corp., compared with 320 of every 1,000
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``In countries like India and China, people can't afford to go
online, and the geography makes laying down the infrastructure a
pain,'' said Pete Hitchen, an International Data analyst in
Singapore. Other obstacles abound. ``There's regulation, there's
infrastructure, there's language, there's a cultural thing as
well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giving destitute countries the ability to tap into the
Internet's largely American-style ferment may seem of dubious
benefit. But Accascina says that Net access is an urgent priority
in a continent that is home to nearly three quarters of the world's
poor. Not only does the Internet create the potential for
long-distance education and medicinal help, it enables producers in
remote areas to offer goods and services on the global market,
providing them a louder voice.
</P>
<P>
   Accascina, a 46-year-old Sicilian, followed a zigzag path to his
role as the U.N. Development Program's high-technology missionary.
The son of an engineer and a lawyer, and a certified pilot,
Accascina worked for the World Health Organization in India in the
late 1970s. In the mid-1980s, he went to California. He worked
briefly for Microsoft, set up his own computer consulting firm and
developed an interest in digital video. A software project for
Unicef turned into a full-time job shooting a documentary in
Albania, and in 1994 a stint in Fiji. In 1996, he joined the U.N.
Development Program.
</P>
<P>
   The world organization, he said, hopes to eventually hand over
to an East Timor government a fiber optic digital network that
merges voice telephone calls with data transmissions. ``This will
be a great opportunity to leapfrog technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And although East Timor's homes and buildings were largely
destroyed, Accascina said the militias left a surprising degree of
infrastructure intact. Dili's power plant was torched, but
electricity has been restored, he said. The cellular phone network
seems to be operating. Attempts to burn down Dili's technical
institute also failed, Accascina said, leaving behind laboratories
and classrooms that he hopes will soon house an academy to train
networking engineers _ part of a program that the Asia-Pacific
Development Information Program began in August with Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The East Timor project is one of several by the agency that have
started to bring the computer age to remote populations. In
October, it helped set up the first Internet connection on Tuvalu,
a self-governing atoll in the South Pacific. In June, workers from
the U.N. Development Program helped establish the first Internet
service in Bhutan, just as the Himalayan nation got its first
television station.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a landlocked country, information is a good commodity,''
said Henrik Holde at the development program's office in the
capital, Thimphu, where efforts are under way to set up an Internet
cafe.
</P>
<P>
   With per-capita incomes in the $400 range, few Bhutanese can
afford Internet access, much less a personal computer. But by using
microwave signals to carry the Internet to community centers in
villages separated by mountains, Holde says health workers can take
advantage of information on disease, and rice farmers can get
better information on prices in India and Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Mongolia's people are spread over a largely flat
area almost as big as Alaska, and most Mongolians live as nomadic
herders. But thanks to heavy subsidies from the old Soviet Union,
more than four of five Mongolians can read; periodically horsemen
ride into a town to sell their meat and read newspapers flown in
from the capital, says Atsushi Yamanaka, information and
communications technology officer at the U.N. Development Program
in Ulan Bator. The flights ended with the fall of Communism, so the
United Nations has helped establish community e-mail centers for
the newspapers to be downloaded and printed out.
</P>
<P>
   Borderless communications is already paying off in India, with
an increasing number of Western companies moving some back-office
and data-processing functions there to cut costs or offer
round-the-clock services, said Mark Leigh, president of business
communications systems at Lucent Technologies in Singapore. GE
Capital International Services, for example, performs some
transaction processing outside New Delhi and Swissair, British
Airways and Lufthansa have moved some data processing to Bombay.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are those who doubt whether access to the global
network will really benefit people who have yet to own a telephone
and whose craftsmanship, however considerable, has not prepared
them for the vexations of troubleshooting the personal computer.
Realities like these have stymied past efforts in Africa and Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   Internet advocates reply that failure to set up networks for the
poorest countries only keeps them poor. ``You can't exclude these
countries just because they're backwaters,'' Hitchen of the
International Data Corp. said. ``The Internet is becoming so
important on a basic economic level you have to start looking at
Internet adoption as a measure of development like you would
televisions and telephones.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 1812EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
