<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9300 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-TV-MEDIA-ART     12-26 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TV-MEDIA-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORONTO TV STATION ADOPTS WEB-PAGE FORMAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Canada)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DYLAN LOEB McCLAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet continues to change the face of the conventional
media.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Toronto television market, where for the last 18 months
viewers have been able to catch up on the news by turning to a
24-hour cable television station that looks more like a World Wide
Web page than a traditional video screen.
</P>
<P>
   The cable station is Cable Pulse 24, or CP24, a subsidiary of
Chum Limited, a Canadian broadcasting company. Its news screen has
seven different fields of information, including stock prices,
weather updates, headline news and a rotating selection of shots of
area roads so that people can check local traffic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by Rocky Mountain Media Watch, a media watchdog
group that is often critical of local news coverage, praised CP24
for offering ``without doubt, the most information-packed newscast
in North America.''
</P>
<P>
   The screen's resemblance to a Web page is not coincidental,
Stephen Hurlbut, the station's vice president and general manager,
said. ``We want to blur the line between the news channel and the
Web site,'' he said. The station plans to start a Web site in
January.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to give people information quickly. ``It's designed
for people who have busy lives,'' Hurlbut said. ``They turn it on
and get their 15-minute hit and they go off to work. This is
utility TV for people in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the format seems to be successful in attracting viewers.
A year and a half ago, CP24 started with about 800,000 people a
week watching it. It now has a weekly audience of 2.2 million,
making it the leading news channel in its market, Hurlbut said.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings have not yet translated to profits, though. The
significant capital investment needed to start the station and the
additional personnel needed to run it have kept CP24 in the red.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Rubinstein, a senior vice president at Chum Television
Channels, said that the new format offered the best possibilities
for future business growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hoping we can turn this into a model of how television
and the Web can be packaged and sold,'' Rubinstein said. ``Our
expectation is that new media and business opportunities will
outstrip the traditional revenue channel.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike McKean, associate professor of broadcast journalism at the
University of Missouri, sees CP24 as a trailblazer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you start to see media converge and stations begin
broadcasting digitally, you'll see more stations with that sort of
information on the screen,'' he said. ``People will have the option
of turning those types of things off, especially as it becomes more
interactive.''
</P>
<P>
   And while he conjectures that older viewers may be more
resistant to such approaches, he says that the television medium
must adapt to the times. ``There are many ways for the general
audience to get information now, often more tailored to their
needs,'' McKean said. ``Television has got to figure out a way to
present information in an appealing way.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees that television will be able to match the
Web. Edward Tufte, author of three books on information design and
professor emeritus at Yale University, says that dividing the
screen is helpful, but multiple fields of information on a TV
screen cannot compete with the interactive features of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The really good channels on the Web just far outperform nearly
any kind of television way of conveying information _ except moving
information,'' Tufte said. ``For data, the Web has been so much
more effective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 1813EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991226.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9301 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BAROQUE-BRAZIL-ART-95     12-26 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAROQUE-BRAZIL-ART-955&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRAZILIAN MASTER WHO FLOURISHED IN CITIES OF GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Until he was in his late 30s, Antonio Francisco Lisboa
was a successful architect and sculptor who enjoyed the good times
accompanying the 18th-century gold boom in Minas Gerais, a state in
east central Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Then around 1777 he contracted a mysterious disease that forced
the amputation of his lower legs and fingers. His infirmity earned
him the nickname of Aleijadinho, or Little Crippled, but he carried
on working, using instruments tied to his wrist, until a few years
before his death in 1814.
</P>
<P>
   Today it is as Aleijadinho (pronounced a-ley-zha-DJEE-nyo) that
Lisboa is celebrated as one of the most important sculptors to come
out of the New World, his wooden and stone statues of religious
figures representing the high point of baroque art in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   But if he is not widely recognized outside Brazil, it is partly
because most of his work is to be found in the churches of Ouro
Preto, Congonhas do Campo, Sao Joao del Rei and other colonial
cities of Minas Gerais. Even the art movement to which he belonged
is little known outside Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baroque Brazil: Between Heaven and Earth,'' a beautifully
designed exhibition at the Petit Palais through Feb. 6, is now
giving Parisians a chance to discover not only some two dozen works
by Aleijadinho, but also other treasures from the baroque movement
that shaped Brazilian art and architecture from the early 17th
century to the early 19th.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by the Union Latine, a Paris-based association of
countries speaking Romance languages, along with the Petit Palais
and Brazil's Culture Ministry, the show offers an overview that
even Brazilians have never seen.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion is the coincidence of millennium celebrations and
next year's 500th anniversary of the discovery of Brazil. But there
is a special reason for the show to be held in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   In 1945 Germain Bazin, a curator of paintings at the Louvre,
traveled to Rio de Janeiro, where he discovered Brazilian baroque.
He was so inspired that he became an expert in the genre,
publishing several works on baroque art and architecture that
became reference books for Brazilians. So the exhibition is also a
homage to Bazin, who died in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is not surprising that European and American art
historians should be unfamiliar with the baroque movement that
swept not only Brazil but also Mexico, Peru, Ecuador and Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   Spain and Portugal, themselves weighed down by religious art,
showed little interest in the art of their Latin American colonies;
the Protestants of northern Europe and the United States were not
drawn by Catholic iconography. Thus, at best the movement was
considered an imitation of what already existed in southern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Latin American baroque was different. It appeared first in
Mexico, Peru, Ecuador and Bolivia, not only because Spain found
gold and silver to finance construction of churches, but also
because the pre-Columbian peoples of these countries were already
experienced masons and sculptors. (Witness the great Aztec, Maya,
Inca and other temples that survive.)
</P>
<P>
   While providing the manpower, Indian craftsmen brought their own
vision to their work, giving a syncretic quality to the new
baroque.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, in contrast, the Indians were largely nomadic. As a
result, unlike the Spanish, the Portuguese did not immediately
found major cities. It was not until the beginning of the 17th
century that sugar plantations worked by African slaves spawned the
wealth that brought the first baroque churches to Salvador, Recife,
Olinda and other northeastern cities.
</P>
<P>
   But in time the African slaves and their descendants _
Aleijadinho himself had a Portuguese father and a slave mother _
proved to be skilled sculptors and, as such, also created their
version of baroque.
</P>
<P>
   The show in the Petit Palais sets the stage with 16th-century
maps and Indian feathered headdresses as well as landscape
paintings by the 17th-century Dutch artist Frans Post and a rare
cartoonlike series of watercolors illustrating a meeting between
Portuguese soldiers and Indians.
</P>
<P>
   It then introduces the first religious polychrome and
terra-cotta statues dating back to 17th-century Salvador. In most
cases, the artists are anonymous, but works by two friars,
Agostinho da Piedade and Agostinho de Jesus, stand out.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the great cathedrals and churches of Spanish
America, the early Brazilian churches had relatively simple
exteriors, with simple whitewashed plaster walls decorated only
with elaborate stone door and window frames.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, until gold was found in Minas Gerais in 1698, the
ornateness of their interiors was provided by carved wooden altars
and statues. The discovery of gold, however, turned Minas Gerais
into the Florence of Brazilian baroque.
</P>
<P>
   This exhibition uses huge photographs to show some of the dozens
of churches that sprang up in new towns across the state.
Aleijadinho's greatest work, unable to travel, is also seen only in
photographs: the 12 stone statues of Old Testament prophets that
stand outside the church at Congonhas do Campo along with the 64
life-size polychrome wood statues portraying the passion of Jesus
that stand in six chapels beside the church. All these were done
between 1796 and 1806, when the artist was already disabled.
</P>
<P>
   In uniting more than 300 religious works from across Brazil, the
show has been able to pull together the most comprehensive display
of Brazilian baroque to date. Along with wooden, terra-cotta and
stone statues, delicately carved wooden retables and oratories and
silver crosses and candelabra, it even presents small statues made
of ivory brought to Brazil from Portugal's colony of Goa on the
Indian subcontinent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But it is Aleijadinho who has pride of place. The show includes
some of his architectural drawings of church facades, but his
talent is most evident in his sculptures, not only in the way he
carved the folds of garments and captured the movement of figures,
but also in the powerful and always different emotions conveyed by
the faces of his statues.
</P>
<P>
   Aleijadinho, it seems, did not see himself as creating merely
symbols, but rather living people caught up in a transcendental
drama.
</P>
<P>
   With Aleijadinho's death in the early 19th century, less than a
decade before Brazil's independence from Portugal, the baroque
movement lost its dynamism. Brazil's intellectuals now turned to
Europe, above all to France, for modern ideas that in turn brought
new tastes in art and architecture to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Today the baroque is again recognized as part of Brazil's
heritage, but in a country obsessed by the future, it is perhaps
most appreciated by the droves of foreign tourists who trek to the
great colonial cities of Minas Gerais. It is appropriate, then,
that ``Baroque Brazil'' should be held, and warmly applauded, in
Paris: many of its rococo works of art look more at home in the
ornate Petit Palais than they might in modern Sao Paulo or Rio de
Janeiro.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
