<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WARRANTIES-ONLINE-100     12-26 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARRANTIES-ONLINE-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE: WEB MERCHANTS WAKE UP TO EXTENDED WARRANTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many consumers, there is nothing to love about buying
extended service warranties. First comes the hard sell at the cash
register, typically punctuated with a horror story about someone
who was ``saved by the warranty.'' If customers reject the
warranty, the horror story lingers. If they accept, they contend
with the aftertaste of a $200 high-pressure purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, online buyers were spared that experience, as
most World Wide Web merchants had neglected to offer extended
service plans. Now, however, retailers are looking more closely at
warranty options, for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Not only can extended warranties generate more profit than the
products they cover, but they give online merchants the chance to
bolster what has generally been an anemic record of post-sale
support. And if one believes the rhetoric of e-commerce sites
offering extended service plans, the Internet may even make the
buying process palatable for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no salesman in a plaid suit saying, `Hey, buy this
warranty,''' said Rich Pournelle, vice president for marketing at
WarrantyNow, which offers extended warranties in partnership with
e-commerce sites. ``The customer is much more in control.''
</P>
<P>
   WarrantyNow and RevBox are among the first companies to offer
warranties online, and though their businesses differ in
significant ways, the basic approach is the same. Both companies
provide Web retailers with the technology to sell extended
warranties and to offer consumers a secure site where they can keep
track of the warranties and get help with service.
</P>
<P>
   Through WarrantyNow, for instance, Wristwatch.com customers can
buy a two-year, $70 extended warranty on a $1,500 Breitling 867
watch, covering theft or breakage due to ``normal use.'' When
buyers choose the coverage, they can record their warranty on
WarrantyNow's Web site, where they can also process a repair claim
or find local repair shops.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ron Goedendorp, WarrantyNow's chief executive, the
company offers broader support for more complex products, like
computers or consumer electronics. In those categories, customers
can call a toll-free number or send an e-mail message to get
technical support.
</P>
<P>
   Goedendorp said that the company, which began operations in
July, had signed up 13 merchants _ including Onvia.com,
Wristwatch.com and Miadora _ and 60,000 repair companies in the
United States. That network, he said, covers 97 percent of the ZIP
codes in the country, and spans an array of product categories,
including lawn equipment, fitness equipment and personal
electronics.
</P>
<P>
   RevBox, WarrantyNow's chief competitor, began operations last
month, and so far has signed up two merchants, according to James
Wu, the company's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   It, too, covers a wide range of product categories, and it has
33,000 repair shops within its network. Wu said that RevBox also
offered warranties on products not sold at merchant partners, as
long as those products were still covered by the manufacturer's
warranty when the extended service plan was purchased.
</P>
<P>
   Wu said that the company would stress two features as it vied
for consumers and merchant partners. First, he said, the site and
its merchant partners would compete aggressively on price. Second,
it would offer extensive additional information about product
warranties and user manuals.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and executives said that retailers typically earn
profit margins of 30 percent to 75 percent on extended warranties.
Wu declined to say what margin RevBox would seek, but he said that
the company's merchant partners would charge significantly less
than other retailers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the company recently offered a two-year extended
warranty on a Compaq Presario 1685 notebook computer for $80, while
CompUSA and WarrantyNow charged $199 for a similar plan. ``We're an
Internet company,'' Wu said. ``We're funded to be aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   RevBox will also try to differentiate itself by offering more
information on its Web site. Customers are automatically registered
on the RevBox site when they purchase an extended warranty from a
merchant partner, but they can also register other purchases at the
site, regardless of where or when they bought the product or
whether they bought a warranty.
</P>
<P>
   Once they have registered the model numbers of various products
on a personalized Web page, customers can then avail themselves of
warranty information on 55,000 products, as well as 10,000 user
manuals from more than 5,000 manufacturers. ``It's taken a lot of
work to develop that,'' Wu said. ``I suspect it'll take a long time
for any competitor to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   Notably, RevBox also plans to chronicle the breakdown history of
those products, and offer that data to customers as a way to
research future purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Both RevBox and WarrantyNow are selling what amount to wholesale
insurance and service plans. When WarrantyNow users make a claim on
a damaged product, for instance, they are actually relying on one
of several ``third-party administrators,'' which for years have
offered post-purchase support services to offline retailers. The
warranties of those third-party administrators are themselves
underwritten, typically by large insurers.
</P>
<P>
   RevBox, on the other hand, resells the warranty and service
offering of one company, Federal Warranty, a unit of Fortis Group.
The extended warranties offered offline by retailers like Macy's,
Tandy and CompUSA often originate with Federal Warranty, Wu said.
Since RevBox plans to sell warranties at prices below Federal's
other partners, he said, ``it's a bit of a delicate situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the prices and the approach of online warranty sites could
change the way consumers approach extended service plans, said
Robert Brown, the chief marketing officer for Techsumer, a company
selling consumer electronics and computers online at
www.techsumer.com, and selling extended warranties through RevBox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be real honest,'' Brown said. ``Everybody knows that not
all warranties will be redeemed, so we recognize there's the
opportunity for profit here.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the lower prices from RevBox will not necessarily translate
to lower revenue for retailers who sell the warranties, he said,
because lower prices should translate to higher sales volume. Brown
cited other factors that he said boded well for higher online
sales. Not only would consumers be more informed about warranties
when they buy, for example, but the online services of sites like
RevBox mean that consumers would be less likely to lose track of
warranty slips, and more likely to stay informed of the warranty's
benefits, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might get more people opting in to these warranties, so
even if there's a higher redemption rate, our net revenue could be
higher as a result,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Brown said, is the fact that extended warranties
allow Web sites to offer ``better customer service, by educating
them about what the products do, and giving them options for
additional support if they have an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Chris Martins, an analyst with Aberdeen Group, this
realization in itself is a big step forward for Internet retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the original focus in e-commerce was up to the sale.
After that, the attitude was, `It'll get handled,''' Martins said.
``This allows retailers to provide a more complete sales
experience, as well as give themselves a revenue opportunity _
which they could use.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
