<SLUG> BC-ACCURATE-TIME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES ANYBODY REALLY KNOW WHAT TIME IT IS? 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Uptight New Year's Eve celebrators intent on uncorking the
Champagne at precisely the right millisecond of midnight may find
themselves in a quandary. Which clock on Earth offers the most
accurate accounting of time?
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the answer is no mere matter of academics or party
etiquette, given the increasing significance that time plays in the
high-technology age.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is no single answer. The Coordinated Universal
Time, which is kept by the Paris-based International Bureau of
Weights and Measures, derives the official time from taking the
average reading at any given moment from 210 organizations
worldwide that keep time using sophisticated atomic clocks.
</P>
<P>
   And even among those 210 organizations, some have clocks that
are more accurate than others. Almost 80 percent of those
organizations use cesium clocks made by Agilent Technologies of
Palo Alto, Calif., a subsidiary of Hewlett-Packard. On their face _
so to speak _ these clocks seem pretty accurate. They lose or gain
a mere second every 162,000 years. That is not bad for a VCR-sized
timepiece that sells for $65,000, but it is downright unreliable,
compared with a handful of clocks like the NIST 7.
</P>
<P>
   Housed at the National Institute of Standards and Technology in
Boulder, Colo., the $2.5 million NIST 7 measures the vibrations of
cesium atoms, which jiggle 9.2 billion times a second. But this
cesium clock, the experts promise, will neither gain nor lose a
second in 6 million years.
</P>
<P>
   Punctual New Year's Eve celebrants can check www.time.gov for
the precise countdown from the institute.
</P>
<P>
   Party-going aside, time is truly of the essence in the digital
age. Consider the growing number of technical tasks that require
exceedingly accurate time, like the satellite-aided global
positioning systems used in the military and space industries and,
increasingly, by consumers.
</P>
<P>
   With global positioning, ``a foot equals a billionth of a
second,'' said Jack Kusters, manager of precise time and frequency
for Agilent. ``So if you're off by a second, you're off by a
billion feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Much too far away, in other words, to see the ball drop in Times
Square.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 1818EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991226.0065 </DOCNO>
