</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOXOFFICE-HOLIDAY-WEEKEND-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A BAFFLING BOX OFFICE WEEKEND, TWO WINNERS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Calif., N.Y.)   (jw) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ One movie opened on Tuesday, several on Wednesday,
several more on Saturday and none at all on the normal opening day,
Friday, which also happened to be Christmas Eve, traditionally one
of the worst moviegoing days of the year. And, as usual for the
holiday season, some of the movies opened last week in thousands of
theaters, others in just a handful, so they could beat the Dec. 31
deadline for Oscar consideration.
</P>
<P>
   It is always tricky figuring out from the skewed perspective of
the Christmas weekend which movies will be the enduring hits of the
season, always a matter of comparing apples and oranges. But this
year some bananas and kumquats were thrown in as well, and the
result was a particularly strange fruit salad. There were two clear
winners, though, and perhaps a few more will emerge as the picture
clarifies after the New Year's weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Stone had the biggest opening of his career with ``Any
Given Sunday,'' a loud, rambunctious, star-studded football movie
that earned an estimated $22.3 million since opening on Wednesday
and $14.2 million in the three-day span that began on Friday. This
director's most successful opening before this was $11 million for
``Natural Born Killers'' in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Talented Ripley,'' a stylish but decidedly dark drama
about a young impostor (Matt Damon) who bludgeons his way to the
life he desires, earned $13.8 million since its opening on
Saturday. The film is the director Anthony Minghella's eagerly
awaited follow-up to the Oscar-winning ``English Patient'' from
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Robert G. Friedman, vice chairman of the Paramount Motion
Picture Group, said the studio was encouraged that audiences turned
out in such numbers for such a film. ``It's the Academy season, and
I think people do expect to see movies that make you think,''
Friedman said. ``And I think we were successful in the way we
alerted the public as to the movie's content. We have not hidden
the fact that it is not your average holiday fare.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Paramount and Warner Bros., which released Stone's film,
were able to claim a share of victory for the weekend. For the
Friday-to-Sunday period that constitutes a normal box office
weekend, ``Any Given Sunday'' was in first place, but ``Ripley''
was not playing on all three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If `Ripley' was a three-day run, it would have been in first
place,'' said Paul Dergarabedian, chairman of Exhibitor Relations,
a company that monitors box office performance. Dan Fellman,
Warner's president for distribution, preferred the hard figures to
speculation. ``We always go by the three-day numbers,'' he said.
``Everybody I talked to is focusing on the three-day weekend, and
they all have us as No. 1. So there you are.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of weekend. Which figures should people focus
on? The five-day figure, since many of the films opened on
Wednesday? Only the two days (Saturday and Sunday) that all of the
movies have been open? Or the traditional three-day weekend, even
though not a single film opened on Friday? Better yet, why focus on
any of them?
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood executives, not to mention directors and actors,
routinely bemoan the industry's _ and the entertainment media's _
fascination with opening weekend performance. But a weekend like
this makes the whole exercise seem even more absurd than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really is a time of the year when to freeze at any one
moment in time to look at the box office is sort of misleading,
because some days favor the kids, some days favor the young adults,
some days favor the women,'' said Jeff Blake, president for
distribution at Columbia Pictures. ``I mean, you had 17 movies
opening in the last couple of weeks. The real answer is, Who's got
what on Jan. 3? And I think the winners will be pretty clear at
that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Focusing solely on the three-day weekend, ``Any Given Sunday''
and ``The Talented Ripley'' were followed at the box office by a
pair of films aimed primarily at young audiences, ``Toy Story 2,''
which opened the day before Thanksgiving, and ``Stuart Little,''
both of which claimed $12.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Blake said that Columbia was particularly buoyed with the
performance of ``Stuart Little'' in its second week. The film, he
said, is expected to earn $5 million a day during the coming week _
the prime holiday period for family moviegoing, when the gifts have
all been opened but the children are still out of school _ and
should top $70 million in earnings by the end of next weekend,
putting it on track to pass the $100 million mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're clearly one of the winners of the period,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Mile,'' a supernatural prison drama starring Tom
Hanks that has been open since Dec. 10, was in fifth place with
$9.04 million, just in front of the $9 million claimed by Universal
Pictures for ``Man on the Moon,'' which opened Wednesday and
features Jim Carrey as the comedian Andy Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Carrey is a big draw, but the subject matter skewed a
little bit older,'' said Dergarabedian, trying to explain why a
movie with such a big star opened so low.
</P>
<P>
   The only other major wide release of the weekend, Tim Allen and
Sigourney Weaver in ``Galaxy Quest,'' a comedy about actors in a
sci-fi television show mistaken by aliens for real space rangers,
landed in a disappointing eighth place with $8.1 million in two
days of distribution, just behind the second week of Robin Williams
in ``Bicentennial Man'' ($8.3 million) and just ahead of the third
week of ``Deuce Bigalow: Male Gigolo'' ($6.2 million).
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Top 10 figures, of course, do not include films that opened
in limited release this week: ``Girl, Interrupted'' on Tuesday;
``Snow Falling on Cedars'' on Wednesday; ``Titus,'' ``Angela's
Ashes'' and ``Play It to the Bone'' on Saturday. By opening before
the end of the year, even in just a few theaters, these films
become eligible for the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Each of them _ except perhaps ``Play It to the Bone,'' a boxing
comedy with Woody Harrelson and Antonio Banderas that made only
$3,660 on one screen in Los Angeles _ can claim strong per-screen
numbers. But again, what that means is unclear. An Oscar-yearning
film might fill up three or four theaters in New York and Los
Angeles, but the real test will come in January when these movies
go into wider release.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the holiday weekend figures were down from recent
years, though Hollywood is still clearly on its way to breaking
last year's record annual total of $6.95 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Partly, this is because Christmas Eve fell on a Friday,''
Dergarabedian said. ``And while the films out there appealed to
diverse audiences, a lot of them were more adult oriented than in
previous years.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's holiday weekend, for instance, saw such mass-appeal
hits as ``Patch Adams,'' ``Stepmom'' and ``You've Got Mail.'' This
year, Dergarabedian said, the most mainstream-oriented of the
movies was Stone's, and many of the others were decidedly more
sophisticated or aimed at smaller audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to make an apt comparison here,'' Dergarabedian
said. ``However, if you look, these are more niche-oriented films,
so it's not surprising that some of the grosses are down a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I think, if anything, it shows a continuing strength
at the box office that, with this kind of week, with movies opening
on Saturday and with this mix of movies, you still have pretty good
box office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
