<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-TV-SHEEPDOG-A     12-26 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-TV-SHEEPDOG-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONDON JOURNAL: BBC ROUNDS UP AN AUDIENCE (WITH SHEEP DOGS)
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Admittedly, it is not likely to make anyone's blood
surge wildly with excitement. But the BBC is waiting to see whether
millions of Britons will spend Monday evening watching a special
edition of ``One Man And His Dog,'' a sports show in which a bunch
of sheep running in the wrong direction qualifies as high drama.
</P>
<P>
   And why, exactly, would anybody want to watch this program?
</P>
<P>
   ``Strangely, it's not boring,'' said Paul Latham, spokesman for
the Countryside Alliance, speaking fondly of a show in which
spectacularly taciturn shepherds compete to see whose dog can most
neatly herd some sheep into a pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually quite an interesting contest to watch, the man
working with an animal to persuade other animals that they want to
go in a certain direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's episode is a crucial test for ``One Man and His Dog,''
which was threatened with cancellation last winter when the BBC
decided that the 23-year-old show's quaint old pace does not mesh
with the racier new image it wants to project. But the threat
caused such an uproar, with celebrities, politicians and The Daily
Telegraph joining a ``One Man'' campaign, that the BBC finally
agreed to broadcast a special over Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other protests when British stations tried to
drop much-loved programs, including ``Shipping Forecast,'' a radio
program in which the announcer read a long list of marine-related
place names, followed by bits of weather.
</P>
<P>
   If the ratings for the special ``One Man and His Dog'' are good,
then the BBC has promised to bring it back, at least from time to
time. In its glory days in the 1980s, the program could draw an
audience of 8 million people, in a country of about 55 million. It
was down to 1.6 million when the BBC decided to cut it, but fans
said it was because it was being shown in a bad time slot.
Meanwhile, the BBC has high hopes for the Christmas program, which
has been scheduled to air in the time of year when Britons most
love to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   Stuffed witless with turkey redux, rendered nearly catatonic by
too much confinement with too many relatives, and not anxious to go
outside because it is raining and the stores are closed, millions
of Britons traditionally spend the better part of the Christmas
season in their living rooms, their eyes fixed like lasers on the
television. Television is such a big deal that in 1994, ``Auntie's
New Bloomers 2,'' a compendium of television gaffes,'' drew 17.9
million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without TV this Christmas, we may have to talk to each
other,'' said The London Observer in its special Christmas
television section last week. In the Christmas-day episode of ``The
Royle Family,'' the working-class family featured in the program
gathers in front of the television after Christmas dinner and
proceeds to criticize the programs.
</P>
<P>
   Watching a preview of Monday's special, it is not impossible to
understand why some people in the BBC thought it was time to say
good-bye to ``One Man And His Dog.'' Even with the show's latest
innovation _ wiring the sheep with microphones so you can hear the
faintest ``Baa'' _ it is often hard to follow the action, or even
the inaction.
</P>
<P>
   The show opens with a shot of some sheep scurrying across a
field, a dog close behind. Then the contestants are introduced.
They are people of such retiring natures that when one admits to
being ``quietly confident'' about the competition, he comes across
as the Donald Trump of the sheep-dog world. They stand around,
whistling and shouting virtually incomprehensible commands to their
dogs, who then herd groups of random sheep around the field and
through various obstacles before depositing them in a pen.
</P>
<P>
   There are standards to meet. The sheep are supposed to run
smoothly and in a straight line, for instance, with no zigzagging,
and the shepherds are not allowed to touch the sheep themselves.
And there are pitfalls to overcome. The sheep can be too fast, too
willful, too nervous and too thick to do as they're directed.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the program, a sheep makes a bid for freedom by
leaping over a dog. One contestant stands by helplessly while his
sheep repeatedly refuse to go into the pen, scattering as
mindlessly as confetti in the wind. Inexplicably spooked, one of
the dogs lies down at his master's feet and refuses to budge.
</P>
<P>
   But the X-factor in the contest, it seems, is the sheep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with the best dog in the world, if you've got bad sheep _
if you have sheep who challenge the dog or who run off in a mad
panic _ you're going to be struggling,'' said Gus Dermody, one of
the show's hosts. ``You have to alter your tactics according to the
sheep you have.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is its very lack of conventional charms that can make
``One Man And His Dog'' so exciting, its admirers say. ``It doesn't
kowtow to the idea that people can only concentrate for 30 seconds,
and I love the idea that it sometimes takes place in the rain,''
actor Stephen Fry said last year.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Hall, who along with his wife is co-editor of Working
Sheepdog News, a six-times-a-year magazine based in York, said that
in a time when the rural way of life is fast being forgotten by a
Britain that is increasingly city-dominated, ``One Man And His
Dog'' helps Britons reach back to their country roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The television is so full of glitz and glamour that it's nice
to see something that's a bit different,'' Hall said. ``It's like
soothing music with Pan pipes. There's a real beauty in a really
good dog moving sheep very gently. There's a beauty all its own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
