<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORY DAYS: COWBOYS HAVE GONE DOGMEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Somebody do something, quick. End this
playoff-formula silliness, here and now. Put the Cowboys out of
their misery by allowing their season to do what it's already done.
Die.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing except NFL mathematical mumbo-jumbo separates the
Cowboys from an off-season of hell-and-heads-rolling. If Chan
Gailey survives with his job intact, then yes, there is a Santa
Claus, and his name is Jerry.
</P>
<P>
   But unfortunately for Gailey, he was at the mercy yesterday,
like he has been all year, of high-dollar has-beens who no longer
play the game as they once did.
</P>
<P>
   Yet until this visit to a half-empty Superdome, being bad hadn't
been properly defined. Losing to the gawd-awful Saints, 31-24,
meant the absolute worst had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   This is the NFL equivalent of December without Christmas. And on
the eve of Christmas, the dawn of franchise disaster arrived,
putting to rest the Jerry Jones ownership formula of reviving the
glory days.
</P>
<P>
   These, friends, are the gory days. And don't expect that to
change anytime soon. Even after yesterday, the NFL math declares
the 7-8 Cowboys as a playoff possibility, depending on what happens
around the NFC on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But it's over. It's been over. And let it get over. The big
question is where it goes from here, meaning the off-season and
beyond. Even a larger question? Can Jones handle such a
responsibility as the self-appointed general manager at Valley
Ranch?
</P>
<P>
   What Jerry should do first is cancel some of those
million-dollar paychecks due Troy Aikman, Emmitt Smith and
Nine-Toed Deion at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, it was an angry Jones who admitted in a postgame
steam, ``I feel a little foolish and stupid for doing and making
some of the commitments I did, and ending up 7-and-9.''
</P>
<P>
   He should.
</P>
<P>
   The downfall against the Saints, who had only lost 12 of 14
coming in, was a direct result of those three future Hall of Famers
becoming crunch-time patsies.
</P>
<P>
   In the final 90 seconds, with the Cowboys needing a touchdown to
tie, Aikman attempted to force an end-zone pass to tight end David
LaFleur. A deflection, then an interception, and that was that. The
upset had been sealed for the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   But how did it come to that? The Cowboys at the New Orleans
6-yard line, needing seven points to get to overtime against
probably the worst team in the league?
</P>
<P>
   An Emmitt fumble was returned 58 yards for a touchdown with 10
minutes remaining, giving the Saints the 31-24 lead. The amazing
part was New Orleans being in a position to take the lead after the
Cowboys had seemingly taken over the game offensively in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   It was Dallas-gone-dogmeat while falling behind, 10-0, in the
first half, but then there were leads of 17-10 and 24-17 after
intermission. Both times, however, the Saints roared back behind
the Christmas spirit of Jake ``The Cajun Snake'' Delhomme, who was
not only making his first NFL start, but also taking his first
snap.
</P>
<P>
   Delhomme was more than terrific, and more than ``pretty cool''
as Saints coach Mike Ditka said afterward. He was an inspiration to
his team with Mr. Clutch accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys rookie cornerback Duane Hawthorne was beaten on a
51-yard TD throw for the 17-17 tie.
</P>
<P>
   And then Mr. Wonderful, Deion himself, got smoked on a 50-yard
pass play to set up the TD for the 24-24 deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive week, the Cowboys' defense fell into
a state of collapse. It unraveled while facing a Ray Lucas of the
Jets and yesterday while facing a Jake Delhomme.
Un-bleeping-believable.
</P>
<P>
   But for those comments all season about defensive coordinator
Dave Campo doing it with smoke and mirrors ... the last two weeks
Campo &AMP; Co. have been reduced to a cloud of dust.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive game plan was to curtail Ricky Williams. Done.
Ricky managed 61 yards on 23 carries. But ``The Cajun Snake,'' with
receivers running wide open all day, and with very little pressure
from the Cowboys' front seven, did a 278-yard passing number
against the secondary. He threw for two TDs and ran for another on
a sharp third-down quarterback draw.
</P>
<P>
   So what the Cowboys had yesterday was superstars choking _
Deion, Aikman and Emmitt _ plus a clueless defense, plus ...
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you guessed it. The rain of senseless yellow flags was on
display, meaning nothing changed the entire season. Eleven
penalties for 86 yards padded the Cowboys' league-leading total.
</P>
<P>
   One of those flags erased a 98-yard kickoff return for a
touchdown by Jason Tucker, who had a standout game as a receiver
and return man.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys proved weeks ago they aren't a serious playoff team.
Even a semi-serious one. But in losing to the Saints, they defined
both the season and the future. And that definition is not for
print in this family publication.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
