<SLUG> BC-FBN-SAINTS-DELHOMME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAINTS' DELHOMME MADE MOST OF CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Quarterback Jake Delhomme, a veteran of NFL Europe
and the Saints' fourth-team signal-caller, spent most of this
season cleaning stalls for his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shoveling manure and having fun doing it,'' Delhomme
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers would consider that an apt description of
yesterday's events at the Louisiana Superdome.
</P>
<P>
   Delhomme buried the Cowboys (7-8) and perhaps their playoff
hopes in the first start of his NFL career. The wide-eyed,
24-year-old completed 16 of 27 passes for 278 yards and two
touchdowns and rushed for another in the Saints' 31-24 upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make me look very smart, but I thought Jake was
pretty special,'' said coach Mike Ditka, who appointed Delhomme as
the starter for the final two regular-season games with Billy Joe
Tolliver injured. ``He's a special kid, and hopefully he never
changes one bit because he is so down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mind was on the football game, and it was wonderful to see
that today. I thought he did a marvelous job in every aspect of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saints released Delhomme late in training camp, but numerous
injuries forced the organization to re-sign the former
Louisiana-Lafayette player Nov. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the way it was in college,'' Delhomme said. ``This
was the way it was when I was in \RNFL Europe\S and was `The Man.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Delhomme's first touchdown pass materialized on a bootleg after
a fake to tailback Ricky Williams. Delhomme passed to wide receiver
Keith Poole in the back corner of the end zone for an 8-yard
touchdown that gave the Saints a 10-0 lead with 1:38 remaining in
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The second touchdown pass went to wide receiver Eddie Kennison,
who beat cornerback Duane Hawthorne, and covered 51 yards for a
third-quarter score that tied the game 17-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sure made some plays,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said.
``He threw it up and gave his receivers a chance to make a play for
him. He got out of some tight spots. You've got to give the guy
credit for the way he played.''
</P>
<P>
   Delhomme also scored a game-tying, fourth-quarter touchdown on a
draw play that covered 4 yards against the blitzing Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've quit being amazed by guys' performances who get
an opportunity in this world,'' Gailey said. ``That's what this
nation is made up of _ people who just want an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Delhomme received his, and his performance did not surprise
Saints tackle Kyle Turley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake Delhomme is a great quarterback,'' Turley said. ``Someone
just needed to give him a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Delhomme did not set out to be the conquering hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't plan on coming out here and doing anything special,''
he said. ``I think maybe the biggest thing that I might have done
was stay calm and relaxed all week. I think the players felt that.
We were 2-12. We had nothing to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   It crystallized as the lowly Saints' feel-good Christmas story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say I hope it's the start of a nice dream,''
Delhomme said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
