<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SAINTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS HO-HO-HORRIBLE AGAINST SAINTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The Cowboys not only lost a game they couldn't
afford to lose yesterday, but they left their owner feeling ``a
little foolish and stupid'' for putting his effort and money into a
team that seems to have become a 7-8 embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys _ 31-24 losers to the 3-12 New Orleans Saints before
a more than half-empty Superdome on Christmas Eve] yesterday _ are
still alive (but apparently not well) in their bid for a playoff
berth after losing their second game in a span of six days to an
underdog already eliminated from playoff picture.
</P>
<P>
   Jones wouldn't reveal what he has in mind concerning the future
of the Cowboys, only that he does have something in mind.
</P>
<P>
   He said his intent won't be meant to be ``punitive,'' but that
he will change the direction of this Cowboys team after a season
of:
</P>
<P>
   Losing seven consecutive road games after opening Sept. 12 with
an overtime victory at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to win back-to-back games since beginning the season
3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to beat a nondivisional opponent on the road (0-11)
since the 1997 season opener at Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who has been outspoken in his support of Gailey as
recently as this past week, would only say yesterday that he
``continues'' that way of thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even thinking about fixing this thing without Chan as
the head coach,'' Jones said. ``With the exception of Jimmy
\RJohnson\S, I never have been a proponent of changing the man out
as much as changing the man \Rinto\S changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey was hired 22 months ago to bring an offense to the
Cowboys and restore their prominence in the NFC. Neither one has
happened. The Cowboys brought the NFL's 25th-ranked passing game
into the Superdome ... and left with one of seven sub-.500 records
in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I have ever spent any more time and worked
harder at giving us an edge as I have this past year,'' Jones said.
``I feel a little foolish and stupid for doing and making some of
the commitments I did and ending up 7-8.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones also admitted that he was ``very angry'' after the
Cowboys' 22-21 home loss to the New York Jets last week and that
yesterday's defeat has ushered reality into the equation.
</P>
<P>
   His latest mood is, as he put it, ``OK, let's get with it. Let's
fix this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey was most upset by first-half penalties (eight for 61
yards) and that the Cowboys again failed to find a way to win close
games. They are 0-6 in games this season decided by seven points or
fewer, including four times in the past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game today,'' Jones said, ``would mirror what our season
has been. When given an opportunity, we come up short.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the feeling among the Cowboys, who cornerback
Deion Sanders said can be considered underachievers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only this year, but last year and the year before and the
year before,'' Sanders said. ``You tried to place everything on
Barry \RSwitzer\S. Now you want to blame Chan. Sooner or later you
have to point the arrow where it should fall, with the players.
Start with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saints rallied from second-half deficits of 17-10 and 24-17
behind a former NFL Europe quarterback, Jake ``The Cajun Snake''
Delhomme, who was playing in his first NFL game.
</P>
<P>
   The record will show that the Cowboys lost this game on a
58-yard return of an Emmitt Smith fumble for a touchdown with just
under 10 minutes remaining in the game, breaking a 24-24 tie.
</P>
<P>
   But Gailey knows better. This game was lost by the Cowboys over
a period of 3 hours, 8 minutes, mostly above the shoulder pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our guys played hard,'' Gailey said. ``But I don't
think we played very smart. Our record right now says we're below
.500 \Rand\S that's not a good football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jones: ``I've seen very smart people do dumb things. I
think we have players who can play smart enough to go to the Super
Bowl. We need to not only look at how our players are approaching
it, but we need to look at what we're asking them to do. We will
look at all of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can get any clearer message than winning one
game on the road all season and ending up here \Rin New Orleans\S
at 7-8.''
</P>
<P>
   As team owner, he called it a ``clear mandate'' that changes
need to be made, and that it is up to him to make them. When asked
about what changes, he wouldn't be specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see where \Rwe've\S got to do different,'' Jones said. ``In
my life, I have a lot of hard decisions that are difficult \Rto
make\S ... but this isn't even hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' defense allowed its first first-quarter touchdown
of the season. Worse, it allowed a first-time NFL starter who never
before yesterday had thrown an NFL pass to throw for two touchdowns
and score a game-tying touchdown on a quarterback draw early in the
fourth quarter. It was only the fifth rushing touchdown the Cowboys
have allowed this season.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the Cowboys, as they have done so well and so often
this season, took aim at their foot ... and squeezed the trigger.
Some of the mishaps inlcuded:
</P>
<P>
   Jason Tucker had what would have been a 97-yard kickoff return
for a first-quarter touchdown nullified by a holding penalty on
Lemanski Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith had a third-and-one carry for 1 yard and apparently
a first down at the Saints' 32 snuffed out by a holding penalty on
Flozell Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had a third-quarter run of 20 yards to inside the Saints'
5 called back by a holding penalty on All-Pro Larry Allen, who was
playing in his first game in six weeks. Four plays later, the
Cowboys had to settle for a 33-yard Eddie Murray field goal. Two
plays after that, the Saints tied the score, 17-17.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   It should.
</P>
<P>
   But this time it was enough to make the owner realize that it's
broken, and it needs to be fixed.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
