<HEADER>
A9313 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-PENALTIES     12-26 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-PENALTIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENALTIES, MISCUES PUT COWBOYS DOWN IN THE BAYOU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ There will be no need to review the game film on
this one.
</P>
<P>
   No need to break down where and why execution failed. To review
the numerous penalties and blunders coming from a veteran team in a
now-or-never game would overstate what the players already know.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to concentration,'' said linebacker Dexter
Coakley of the Cowboys' 31-24 defeat to the New Orleans Saints
yesterday. ``Obviously we're not focused enough. Penalties are
caused by not being focused. It's not so much what they did. We're
beating ourselves. That's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   No one, not even coach Chan Gailey, can answer how or why the
Cowboys could commit 11 penalties and three turnovers in the 15th
game of the season with the playoffs on the line and playing
against one of the worst teams in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even answer that,'' offensive tackle Erik Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very surprising, especially when so much is on the line,
so much is at stake,'' linebacker Randall Godfrey said. ``Everybody
has to step up and play and be committed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were penalized eight times in the first half. They
lost more yards in the first half to penalties (61) than they
gained rushing (45). It resulted in a 10-7 halftime deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played hard, but we didn't play smart, and that costs
you,'' Gailey said. ``It's frustrating. Look around that locker
room. We're accountable to each other on the field. You have to
play smart to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Examples of dumbfounding play was evident throughout, especially
in the first half when:
</P>
<P>
   Jason Tucker's 97-yard kickoff return for a touchdown was
brought back on a holding penalty against Lemanski Hall.
</P>
<P>
   An offside penalty on Leon Lett provided the Saints with
first-and-five in Cowboys territory.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman threw behind Chris Brazzell, and Fred Weary made the
interception and returned it to the Cowboys 23, leading to a
touchdown and a 10-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tackle Flozell Adams was called for holding on
third-and-one to create a third-and-11 pass play. The pass fell
incomplete and led to a punt.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive guard Larry Allen jumped offside on second-and-seven
at the Cowboys' 27 to push the offense back into second-and-12 from
the 22, again forcing a punt.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Alonzo Spellman jumped offside on
third-and-five to give the Saints a first down at their own 42.
</P>
<P>
   All that proceeded unusual fourth-quarter follies by Cowboys
veterans. In the waning moments, Aikman tried to thread a pass to
David LaFleur in the end zone through triple coverage, resulting in
an interception to seal the Saints' victory. Emmitt Smith fumbled,
and Weary returned it 58 yards for the game-winning touchdown.
Deion Sanders was beaten for a 50-yard gain that set up the Saints'
game-tying touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen, sometimes even to the best of them,'' Smith
said. ``The thing you try to do is keep them to a minimum and not
let them occur at a critical moment. Mine occurred at a critical
moment.'' \Ntagtop:Jeff Caplan, (817) 390-7971
\Ntagbottom:jcaplan\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
