<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ITEMS FROM THE HOLLYWOOD HIGH TIME CAPSULE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jerry Anker  &LR; is second cousin of the late  &UR; Jack Benny &LR; , but
this isn't THAT kind of item. Anker, 75, is curator of the
Hollywood High School Museum, which is described in a Detours
magazine story forwarded to Personals by  &UR; Tom Costner &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Among the treasures in this historic showplace, which occupies
the library and several rest rooms of Hollywood High:
</P>
<P>
   - A gavel and robe belonging to Judge  &UR; Joseph Wapner &LR;  (class of
'37).
</P>
<P>
   - A Tony award won by &UR; Nanette Fabray  &LR; (class of '39).
</P>
<P>
   - A washerwoman's hat worn by  &UR; Carole Burnett &LR;  (class of '51).
</P>
<P>
   - A TV script autographed by  &UR; Mike Farrell &LR;  (class of '57).
</P>
<P>
   - A Ken doll modeled after &UR; Ken Handler &LR;  (class of '61).
</P>
<P>
   - Articles on the mother of  &UR; Michael Jackson &LR; 's kids,  &UR; Deborah &LR; 
 &UR; Rowe &LR;  (class of '77).
</P>
<P>
   Detour describes the rest of the exhibits as ``less glitzy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Lead paragraph of the month, mined from the Berkeley Voice by
 &UR; Gene Marine &LR; : `` &UR; Joshua Redman &LR;  has the continence of a devout
man, one who knows his calling and pursues it with cool and quiet
ardor.''
</P>
<P>
   - The men's magazine Maxim describes several Web sites
(www.game-worn.com, www.dropthegloves.com, for example) that sell
athletic equipment worn by star athletes. Among the treasures is an
$875 hockey jersey worn by  &UR; Tony Twist  &LR; of the bygone Quebec
Nordiques, which is described as displaying ``excellent general
filth'': stick and puck marks, bloodstains, sliced sleeves, torn
collar and sweat stains.
</P>
<P>
   - At the end of a series of tests in Glamour magazine _ Were you
made to be monogamous? Why is one man romantic, the next repulsive?
What did your partner take on to be with you? _ comes a playful
question for online searchers for love: ``Is He an Ax Murderer?''
</P>
<P>
   - At a press conference promoting ``Bicentennial Man'' in
Australia,  &UR; Robin Williams  &LR; suggested that children leave the
room, &LR;  and then discussed, among other things, chat rooms on the
Net. ``You realize the typing is so bad,'' he said, in comments
quoted in the Sydney Morning Herald, ``because people are only
using one hand.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Angela Weber &LR;  forwards a clipping from England from the
magazine BBC Homes and Gardens, wherein readers were polled as to
``what they believed the '90s would be remembered for'' (in
America, where the president's English is spoken and prepositions
do not end sentences, we would say polled as to ``their most
pungent memories of the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The  &UR; Clintons &LR; ,'' said the magazine. ``A president trying to
live down the  &UR; Monica Lewinsky  &LR; trial and a First Lady who wants to
be mayor of New York.'' As  &UR; Glenda Jackson  &LR; wants to be the
Archbishop of Canterbury.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VANISHING BOOTHS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ian Frazier &LR;  waxes nostalgic, in Mother Jones, about the
vanishing pay phone, which the cell phone is rendering obsolete.
``The pay phone is to the cell phone as the troubled and difficult
older sibling is to the cherished newborn. People even treat their
cell phones likes babies, cradling them in their palms and beaming
down upon them lovingly as they dial. You sometimes hear people
yelling on their cell phones, but almost never yelling at them.
...''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier recalls the sound of people cursing at pay phones, and
the noise of the fan in the phone booth, ``the essence of romantic
lonely-guy melancholy for me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally,'' writes Frazier, ``the world would be covered with
plaques and markers listing the notable events that occurred at
each particular spot. A sign on every pay phone would describe how
a woman broke up with her fiance here, how a young ballplayer
learned that he had made the team. ... Meanwhile, our passions
proliferate into illegibility, and the places they occur can't hold
them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I got so curious about what it would be like to French kiss a
chimp that I convinced one of the handlers to take me and a couple
of the other actors into the pen after hours and let us smooch with
them. When we got into the monkey compound the trainer started
running after one of them. ... So I said, `There are a dozen chimps
and only four of us, what is your big rush?' He replied, `What! And
get stuck with an ugly one?' ''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Alan Cumming &LR; , a man known for his imagination, at the
premiere party in New York for ``Titus.'' Cumming was talking to
Personals spy &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  about chimpanzees, his fellow actors in
the forthcoming movie, ``Buddy.''
</P>
