<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many Year 2000 Worriers Starting to Close Up Shop
</P>
<P>
   After devoting months and sometimes years to raising
consciousness about potential year 2000 disruptions, many prominent
worriers are folding up their tents. For example, Peter de Jager,
the Canadian programmer who became a year 2000 Paul Revere in 1993,
has put Year2000.com, the popular Internet site he created, up for
sale at eBay.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crusade part of this is just about over,'' said Edward
Yardeni, a Wall Street economist who still thinks there is a 70
percent chance that year 2000 breakdowns will usher in a worldwide
recession. ``Now it's just a matter of what happens. There's no
point in being alarmist anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   More Moves Seen for `This Week'
</P>
<P>
   Inside ABC News, staff members viewed last week's dismissal of
William Kristol, the conservative commentator, as perhaps only an
initial move in what most conclude is a long overdue reshaping of
the network's faltering Sunday morning discussion program, ``This
Week.'' David Westin, the president of ABC News, removed the show's
longtime executive producer in September. But ratings have
continued to decline, and many producers and correspondents at the
network think the main problem is the absence of a single anchor.
</P>
<P>
   Web Retailers Discover Warranties
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, online buyers were spared the hard sell for
extended service warranties. Now, retailers are looking more
closely at warranty options. Not only can extended warranties
generate more profit than the products they cover, but they give
online merchants the chance to bolster what has generally been an
anemic record of post-sale support.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Helps to Wire East Timor
</P>
<P>
   While aid workers help East Timor's people build an economy and
government from the ruins of the province, the U.N. Development
Program sent an official to bring the World Wide Web to the capital
and to begin designing the kind of national data network that is
fast becoming vital to participation in the new information
economy.
</P>
<P>
   TV Station Adopts Web Format
</P>
<P>
   A cable television channel in Canada is trying to blur the lines
between TV and the Internet. Its news screen has seven different
fields of information, including stock prices, weather updates,
headline news and a rotating selection of shots of area roads so
that people can check traffic conditions. The idea is to provide
information quickly, and so far the format seems to be successful
in attracting viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Publisher in Israel Is Indicted
</P>
<P>
   In the latest development in a circulation war gone wild, a
newspaper publisher in Israel, Ofer Nimrodi, was indicted on
charges of trying to arrange the murder of a witness against him in
a wiretapping scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Dream of Convergence Dies Hard
</P>
<P>
   Americans have traditionally shunned devices that combined too
many functions or inappropriately matched them into one unit. That
has been especially notable this holiday season as consumers
snapped up record numbers of specialized electronic devices, from
digital cameras to electronic organizers. But that has not stymied
the idea of converging personal computers, television and the Web.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Financial Markets Reopen
</P>
<P>
   U.S. financial markets, which were closed on Friday in
observance of Christmas, will reopen Monday. Some foreign markets
are closed Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
