<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9341 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u v BC-LADN-BUDGET-ADD &LR;      12-26 0330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADN-BUDGET-ADD </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Dec. 27 and thereafter. For questions about stories, contact the
Daily News, (818) 713-3705.
</P>
<P>
   LASCHOOL-BREAKUP (Sacramento) -- The state of California
</P>
<P>
   is set for a legislative showdown next year over dismantling the
Los Angeles Unified School District with the governor and
speaker-in-waiting setting a high standard for support: prove
breakup will improve classroom education. Sen. Richard Polanco, the
powerful East Side Democrat who joined the LAUSD breakup movement
over Superintendent Ruben Zacarias' ouster, rebuffed leaders from
United Teachers Los Angeles and other unions who recently pressured
him to give the reform-minded school board more time. Polanco
intends to present a bill in the first weeks of the new Legislative
session that would call for a blueprint of how to split the entire
district into many small ones. By Terri Hardy. (Will move on the
``n'' California news wire.)
</P>
<P>
   WASP-EUCALUPTIS (Los Angeles) -- Several communities in Los
Angeles city will be among the first Southern California areas for
release of a wasp that scientists hope will kill pests that are
threating eucalyptus trees.
</P>
<P>
   Officials plan to release the non-stinging wasps this spring at
trial sites in sections hardest hit by the infestation of redgum
lerp psyllids. ``The idea is for the wasps to get ahold, multiply
and feed on the redgum lerp psyllids,'' said Robert Donley, deputy
director of the environmental protection bureau in the county
Department of Agricultural Commissioner and Weights and Measures.
</P>
<P>
   The psyllids so far have faced few enemies in their spread
across Southern California and the Bay Area since being discovered
in June last year _ the worst infestation since the ash whitefly a
decade ago. By Troy Anderson. (Will move on the ``n'' California
news wire.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 1923EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991226.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9344 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUDGET-SURPLUS-2TAKES     12-26 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SURPLUS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES DIFFER ON PLANS FOR BUDGET SURPLUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thanks to projections of a large and growing
federal budget surplus, the presidential candidates are proposing
ambitious initiatives that reveal clear differences within and
between the parties over taxes, spending programs and Social
Security's long-term problems.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in decades, the candidates this time around
are not constrained by the need to deal with big budget deficits.
Indeed, it is likely that the current forecast of a $3 trillion
surplus over the next decade _ of which $2 trillion would come from
excess Social Security revenues _ will be revised upward in the
next several months, putting even more money on the table.
</P>
<P>
   The leading candidates in both parties have already set out
plans to use all or most of the surplus, and are vigorously
debating the relative merits of tax cuts, plans to reduce the
national debt and ambitious efforts to address issues like health
care and education.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are edging into a debate over how they would use the
bounty of the nation's current prosperity to address the
politically explosive problems facing the two most sacrosanct of
government programs, Social Security and Medicare. Without any
changes, both programs could run short of money in the next few
decades as the vast baby boom generation ages.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore would divide the surplus among a variety
of purposes, including reducing the national debt, a strategy he
said would be a first step towards fixing Social Security. Gore
would also provide money to shore up Medicare and increase spending
on education, health care and the military.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, the former senator from New Jersey, would use most
of the non-Social Security surplus on his proposal to expand access
to health care, while reserving the Social Security surplus to deal
with the retirement system's problems in ways that he has yet to
describe.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Republicans, Sen. John McCain of Arizona is drawing a
distinction between his emphasis on using most of the surplus to
deal with Social Security and the big tax cut proposed by Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas. Both Bush and McCain support increased
spending for the military and reining in spending on many domestic
programs.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, the fiscal plans set up a traditional choice
between Republican tax-cutting and Democratic spending. But they
also provide the framework for an emerging debate over how to
prepare for the aging of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither has yet laid out a detailed plan, their aides
said Bush and McCain both favored using the Social Security surplus
to finance the creation of a new system of private investment
accounts within the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   In allocating money to set up the accounts, McCain would go
further than Bush, dedicating not just the Social Security surplus
but a majority of the non-Social Security surplus as well.
</P>
<P>
   Private accounts have been vigorously debated in Congress for
the last two years, with proponents saying that they would allow
the country to tap into the power of the financial markets to
ensure the retirement security of the baby boomers and their
children.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidates, by contrast, oppose creating private
accounts within Social Security, saying such a step would introduce
too much risk into a program intended to be a safety net for
retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has so far had little to say on the subject. But Gore
strongly backs a plan developed by the Clinton administration to
dedicate the Social Security surplus to debt reduction, and his
advisers say they are eager to begin a debate with the Republicans
on the issue, which they predict will take center stage in the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would use the Social Security surplus to pay down the $3.5
trillion portion of the national debt held by the public in the
form of Treasury bonds. The vice president says debt reduction
would yield lower interest rates and higher rates of economic
growth, leaving the government with a stronger balance sheet and
the ability to direct the interest savings into paying Social
Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dedicating the nearly $2 trillion in Social
Security surpluses to debt reduction over the next decade, he has
earmarked $374 billion of the $1 billion non-Social Security
surplus for Medicare. He would also provide $146 billion for his
health care program, $115 billion for education, $127 billion for
the military and $190 billion for other domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   His advisers say the vice president's strategy is to seek the
middle of the road, resisting both the big spending programs
advocated by Bradley and the sweeping tax cuts proposed by Bush and
other Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he looks around, he sees on the one side this reckless tax
cut mentality, and on the other side he sees this reckless spending
mentality,'' said Elaine Kamarck, a policy adviser to Gore. ``Both
of those are things that the last seven years of Democratic
leadership have taught us to stay away from.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gore has regularly suggested that Bradley is open to
further raising the retirement age _ an assertion Bradley says is
wrong _ no candidates in either party has emphasized the likelihood
that using the surplus will not be enough to solve Social
Security's problems, which by current estimates could leave the
retirement program short of money starting in 2033. And they have
repeatedly dodged questions about which of several painful options,
including reducing guaranteed benefits and raising taxes, they
might support to put the system on sound footing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a leader who's going to be able to convene a
bipartisan approach to this problem to consider all the
possibilities,'' Bradley said in his Dec. 19 debate with Gore, on
NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's fiscal plan is built around his proposal to improve
access to health care, which he estimates would cost as much as $65
billion a year, to be paid for out of the surplus. He would spend
another $10 billion a year on child poverty reduction, $2.6 billion
on programs to help working families and $1.3 billion on farm aid.
If fully enacted immediately, his plans would cost as much as $80
billion a year by his own reckoning, or $800 billion over 10 years
out of a non-Social Security surplus of $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a moment now when we have an opportunity to solve
some big problems we haven't been able to address before,'' said
Eric Hauser, Bradley's spokesman. ``We should fix the roof while
the sun is shining.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite polls suggesting that tax cuts do not rank high as a
priority for most voters, Bush, the Republican front-runner, has
made his tax cut, which he values at $483 billion over five years,
the centerpiece of his domestic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says his tax plan, which would likely use up nearly all of
the non-Social Security surplus over 10 years, or perhaps even
more, would provide benefits to workers across the income spectrum.
Moreover, he said, by putting money back in the hands of taxpayers
it would keep Washington from spending it on ever-larger government
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to get rid of the so-called surpluses in the
short term is to put Al Gore or Bill Bradley as president of the
United States, and they'll spend it all,'' Bush said at the most
recent Republican debate, earlier this month in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers said they had not decided whether to put out a
detailed plan for Social Security. But they said that Bush
generally favored creating individual Social Security investment
accounts, financed by perhaps 2 or 3 percentage points of the 12.4
percent payroll tax that supports the retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   To create private accounts on that scale while still having
enough revenue to pay current Social Security beneficiaries would
probably require using the entire $2 trillion in Social Security
surpluses over the next decade, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Such an approach would leave Bush vulnerable to attack from
Democrats that he is forgoing an opportunity to reduce or even pay
off the national debt held by the public. But Bush's advisers said
that creating private accounts would help reduce the national debt
by another definition _ the government's deferred obligations to
pay Social Security benefits down the road for which no money has
been put aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a practical matter, fixing Social Security is as effective
at improving the balance sheet of the United States as a direct
debt paydown,'' said Lawrence B. Lindsey, Bush's chief economic
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The other Republican candidates have Social Security plans of
their own. And now McCain is starting to question whether Bush is
too focused on tax cuts at the expense of ensuring Social
Security's survival.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush would reserve the $2 trillion Social Security surplus
for the retirement system, McCain proposes using the $2 trillion
plus 62 percent of the non-Social Security surplus _ roughly
another $620 billion over 10 years _ to pay for a revamped system
including personal accounts.
</P>
<P>
   That approach leaves McCain with relatively little money out of
the surplus for tax cuts. But his emerging fiscal strategy is that
shoring up Social Security will trump Bush's tax plan even among
the Republican faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until his campaign offers a fuller explanation of his plan,
it's difficult to see how Governor Bush's tax proposal leaves
enough money for Social Security,'' said Dan Schnur, a spokesman
for McCain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
