<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9351 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SLOTMACHINES-CARTOONS     12-26 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLOTMACHINES-CARTOONS-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
 
(Attn: Nev., N.J., Ariz.)  
 CARTOON-THEMED SLOT MACHINES OUTRAGE GAMBLING CRITICS  (jw) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Instead of lemons, cherries and black bars, a new
slot machine sports characters from the popular television show
``South Park.'' Another shows clips of ``The Three Stooges'' and
lures gamblers with the sound of Curly's trademark ``Nyuk, nyuk,
nyuk.'' Other machines feature Betty Boop, the Addams Family, the
Pink Panther and the Munsters.
</P>
<P>
   Slot machine makers are turning to popular themes to make
betting more entertaining and appealing for those who are not
dedicated gamblers. The trend worries regulators and critics, who
say that these new machines could appeal to children, worsening the
national problem of underage gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The Nevada Gaming Control Board is drafting rules that would ban
cartoon, comic book other themes based on material ``primarily''
intended for children. What happens in Nevada is expected to
influence other states, like New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a myriad of themes that these games can be based on
other than Saturday morning cartoon characters,'' said Steve
DuCharme, chairman of the Nevada Gaming Control Board.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., chairman of the Senate Committee on
Commerce, Science and Technology, said this month that the panel
would investigate the issue. He wrote a letter to the Federal Trade
Commission asking for its assistance in the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling industry executives say the new machines are intended
to appeal not to children but to nostalgic adults. And in any case,
they add, children are not allowed to use slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   But in Nevada, slot machines are allowed at airports,
supermarkets, convenience stores and restaurants, and critics say
that children can be exposed to them there, as well as when they
walk through casinos with adults. In addition, a Supreme Court
decision this year lifted a ban on gambling advertisements on
television.
</P>
<P>
   Using its existing power, the Nevada agency has already
informally rejected the South Park slot machine and a proposed one
based on Spider-Man, DuCharme said. The commission also blocked a
game called Easy Street that features a display that looks like the
board game ``Candyland.'' The manufacturer, Casino Data Systems,
says any similarity was unintentional.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents draw parallels between the ``slots for tots''
controversy and the battle over ``Joe Camel,'' the cartoon
character dropped by the R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. in 1997 after
criticism that it was luring children to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of gambling opponents sent a letter last month to
the House and Senate commerce committees, warning, ``These
child-enticing slot machines are the latest innovation in a broader
advertising and marketing campaign by casinos and the gambling
industry to promote a `family friendly' image and, apparently, to
bring children to the casinos and thereby shape the next generation
of gambling addicts.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay James, chairwoman of the National Gambling Impact Study
Commission, and three other members were among the signers.
Chartered by Congress to study the social and economic effects of
gambling, the commission concluded in June that as many as 1.1
million adolescents ages 12 to 18 are pathological gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the business say that these concerns are overblown and
that there is no evidence the new machines are attracting children.
``The presence of a slot machine that has a cartoon character on it
is not the reason someone under 21 is trying to get into a
casino,'' said Philip Satre, chairman of Harrah's Entertainment, a
major casino chain. Peer pressure is the main factor, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Machine manufacturers say that unlike cigarettes, slot machines
are rarely advertised outside casinos. Moreover, since children are
not allowed to gamble, there is no point developing machines for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would we invest a million dollars in a game that has no
return?'' said Ed Rogich, vice president for marketing at
International Game Technology, which developed the South Park
machine and several others at issue. ``We're not looking at a
five-year plan,'' he added. ``The game lives or dies in the first
two weeks it's on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Slot machine manufacturers say that children can be exposed to
gambling in many other ways. Toys R Us advertises a toy slot
machine on its Web site for children 6 and older. And the
commission report indicates that much of underage gambling consists
of card games, lotteries and sports betting, not casino play.
</P>
<P>
   Still, casino executives are worried that the controversy
provides an easy target for opponents of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need a Joe Camel,'' said Mike Sloan, a vice president
of the Mandalay Resort Group. Station Casinos Inc. last month
removed Shuffle Master Inc.'s Three Stooges and Alliance Gaming
Corp.'s Betty Boop machines from its properties because of the
controversy and because they were not attracting enough business.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is sensitive for casinos because many of them _
especially in Las Vegas _ are trying to change from betting parlors
into full-fledged resorts. That has meant providing restaurants,
shopping and entertainment for the entire family.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, regulators say, the casinos here do prevent those
younger than 21 from gambling, although there have been lapses. The
Las Vegas Hilton was fined $350,000 last year because children
waiting in line for its ``Star Trek'' ride were found in the casino
and some were seen gambling. In Atlantic City, N.J., 36,441 minors
were escorted out of casinos last year, though fewer than 400 were
actually caught gambling, according to the New Jersey Casino
Control Commission.
</P>
<P>
   There are now an estimated 190,000 slot machines in Nevada and
nearly 450,000 in the United States, according to Bear, Stearns &AMP;
Co. The machines now account for about three-quarters of casino
gambling revenue, having largely displaced table games.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Efforts of casinos to attract a broader audience have put
pressure on slot machine makers to produce machines that are more
entertaining, with familiar characters and high-quality sound and
images. ``These products are more and more becoming
amusement-like'' said Kevin Verner, chief operating officer of WMS
Industries, a manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The wave of themed slot machines began with the Wheel of Fortune
machine introduced in 1993 by International Game Technology and
Anchor Gaming. WMS has done very well with a machine based on the
game Monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Computer technology has transformed slot machines into video
games with images of spinning reels rather than mechanical ones.
This allows a cherry to turn into a smiling face or the reels to
fade out altogether and as a new image is shown.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of paying out when the proper symbols appear on a single
line, the latest video machines reward players when the proper
combination appears on any of nine lines, some of them zigzag.
Players ``win'' on as many as half their spins, though in many
cases the winnings are less than the number of coins bet. The
casino ultimately holds on to the same percentage of the money bet
as with older machines, but people tend to play longer in the
belief that they are winning, Verner said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason slot machine manufacturers strive for hits is that it
gives them more leverage to demand a share of the winnings, rather
than just selling the machine outright. This raises profits for the
machine manufacturers at the expense of the casinos, which tried
unsuccessfully this year to get the Nevada legislature to outlaw
such arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   When they share in the winnings, slot machine manufacturers have
an incentive to advertise their machines to the public.
International Game Technology, for instance, has advertised its
Wheel of Fortune game on Nevada television.
</P>
<P>
   Gaming Control Board members say they want a regulation in part
so that companies will not spend hundreds of thousands of dollars
developing a game only to see it rejected. And the industry, while
at first reluctant, is warming up to state regulation in part to
stave off any federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But this is uncharted territory for the regulators. ``What we've
always looked at historically are the guts of the device and how it
functions,'' said Dennis Neilander, a member of the three-person
board. ``We've never really been faced with a question of a theme
and whether it's appropriate or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing distinctions between Monopoly and the Three Stooges,
between the Pink Panther and a generic pink elephant may be
difficult. The rules also must not infringe on rights of free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Under the latest draft of the regulations, decisions would be
based on the rating of the television show, movie or game upon
which a machine is based. The South Park slot machine might be
acceptable because the television show is rated for mature
audiences. The latest draft would also allow themes from shows that
are more than 21 years old, like the Pink Panther and the Addams
Family. However, regulators could still ban any of these machines
if they decided the machine was based on a product that ``currently
and primarily intended, marketed and used'' by people under 21. The
board hopes to complete the regulation in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 1941EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991226.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9355 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-BURUNDI-RELOCATION-AR     12-26 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURUNDI-RELOCATION-ART-1195(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELOCATION CAMPS ARE LATEST TRAGEDY IN BURUNDI 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUJUMBURA, Burundi _ In the last three months, Burundi's
government has herded 350,000 people, mostly poor farmers, from
their homes into grubby new villages atop the hills that encircle
this city, the country's capital. The camps are supposed to be
temporary, but a permanence is settling in. On a recent day, two
parishioners pounded nails into eucalyptus poles, attempting to
build a house of worship, the Church of the Holy Spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were brought here by force,'' a choir member, Sampson
Bizimana, 32, complained. ``We are cold. There is disease. We don't
have food.''
</P>
<P>
   The camps, which number nearly 60, are the latest turn in the
ethnic struggle between the elite Tutsi, who rule Burundi, and the
majority Hutu, who do not.
</P>
<P>
   The government calls them a last resort to end a series of
guerrilla attacks on Bujumbura since this summer. By forcing people
into the camps, officials say, they can deprive the Hutu rebels of
their main source of food and shelter.
</P>
<P>
   That may be, even if diplomats worry that the camps may
eventually worsen the situation in Burundi, which is afflicted with
a similar ethnic dynamic as its northern neighbor, Rwanda, where at
least half a million people were killed in massacres in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But the camps are an unquestionable human disaster. Crowded into
huts made of mud, metal sheeting and palm leaves, several dozen
people have died of cholera and dysentery. There are reports of a
fire in one camp that spread to 50 huts. A drunken soldier
reportedly opened fire on a crowd last month, killing five
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's odious because it's a policy that is presented as if it
were for the security of the people,'' said Sylvestre
Ntibantunganya, a Hutu and the president of Burundi from 1994 to
1996. ``In fact, the reality is that the people die in these
camps.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to name any other place in the world where the
forced relocation of a third of a million people would not touch
off major international protest. Yet the opposition has been
relatively muted. Foreign governments say they are horrified but
worry that too much protest might hurt peace negotiations between
the government and the rebels, which won a needed injection of hope
this month when Nelson Mandela was appointed as mediator.
</P>
<P>
   The need to close the camps, one diplomat said on the condition
of anonymity, is one reason for the peace process to continue.
``And that's why Mandela has to keep the momentum going,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis has also created a major dilemma for aid
organizations, which are on the defensive these days for
unintentionally doing harm in places like Somalia or Congo. In
Burundi, aid officials are engaged in a heated debate about whether
they are actually encouraging the camps by providing food, blankets
and medical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea of limiting a large population to one area and
not allowing them free access to their homes and land is a human
rights violation which we could never support,'' said Michele
Quintaglie, a spokeswoman for the U.N. World Food Program, which
has supplied most of the food to the camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, what you can't do either, as an aid agency,
is stand by and watch these people who are suffering from the
decision of the government waste away.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month the medical group Doctors Without Borders said it was
leaving the camps, because it felt it was helping the government
sustain the camps more than it was helping sick people. Other aid
groups criticized that decision as an abandonment of the camps'
victims and have stayed on, though without an entirely clear
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   The World Food Program has also pulled out of the camps but for
safety's sake: On Oct. 12, two U.N. workers, one with the World
Food Program and the other with UNICEF, were executed in
southeastern Burundi. The government named several rebels as the
killers, although many aid officials suspect the army itself.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the United Nations has put Burundi on its
second-highest security alert, meaning that its staff cannot leave
the capital. Now other aid groups are distributing the U.N. food in
the camps.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of widespread violence is common these days in Burundi,
where there have been periodic explosions: In 1972 Tutsi extremists
exterminated virtually a generation of educated Hutu. In 1993 Hutu
slaughtered Tutsi in retaliation for the assassination of the
nation's first democratically elected president, Melchior Ndadaye,
a Hutu. That killing started a civil war in which an estimated
200,000 people have died.
</P>
<P>
   Hutu make up nearly 85 percent of the population, though Tutsi
control the army, the government and business. The current
government, headed by Maj. Pierre Buyoya, a Tutsi soldier, has been
engaged in talks with the opposition and rebels for over a year,
with little concrete progress toward elections and democracy.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Hutu rebels stepped up their attacks on Bujumbura _
where most Hutu have been killed or driven out _ and in September
hit a rich Tutsi neighborhood. Cows began disappearing, possibly
being killed by rebels for food. The attacks unsettled Buyoya's
supporters, who demanded action.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 19, soldiers began ousting Hutu from their homes in the
area around Bujumbura and put them into camps on the top of hills,
so the army could more easily patrol the roads and valleys for
rebels who might attack the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was much, much fear in the capital and in those
neighborhoods that are particularly targeted,'' said Albert
Nitunga, a driver who is Tutsi and who lives in a mixed
neighborhood that the rebels have attacked several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since the regroupment camps have been created, we sleep
soundly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Longin Minani, a spokesman for the army, noted that the
government created camps in rural areas in 1996 and 1997, cutting
down rebel attacks. Like the earlier camps _ which were in place a
year and a half _ these camps will be broken up, he said, when the
area becomes safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Security-wise, I think it has proved to be efficient,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting criticism from the United States and others, Minani
recalled the camps set up by the United States to intern
Japanese-Americans in World War II and Vietnamese civilians during
the Vietnam war. Others have noted a similar policy, though with
much more planning and better services, in Rwanda, an ally of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want us to do what you did,'' Minani said. He added,
``The people are happy with it.''
</P>
<P>
   That did not appear to be case among Hutu interviewed last week
in three camps outside Bujumbura. The camps themselves, unfenced
but heavily guarded by armed soldiers, had been slapped together
hastily from whatever materials were available.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are allowed to leave the camps a few times a week to
farm their land, but even then government soldiers stand over them
in the fields, purportedly to protect against rebel attacks.
Nonetheless, people complained about shortages of food, water and
medicine, and said that both the rebels and the army were stealing
their crops and pieces of the homes they left behind.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing to be pleased about,'' said Michel
Baranyibikiye, a 57-year-old farmer who had just received a blanket
from Catholic Relief Services, which has provided aid to some
200,000 people. ``The soldiers and rebels rob whatever they can
find.''
</P>
<P>
   It is rainy season and, in another camp, Ruziba, on Lake
Tanganyika, a 53-year-old woman named Regine Raranyedetse took a
visitor inside the tiny hut where she, her husband and seven
children live. In all, 18,000 people live at the camp. Thirty have
died of cholera. Mrs. Raranyedetse's hut is made of sticks
interwoven with straw and dried banana leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we get wet,'' she said. ``The rain comes down.''
</P>
<P>
   Many critics of the policy say that any reduction in violence is
temporary. The U.S. statement expressed concern that the camps
would become ``breeding grounds not only for disease and death but
also for forces of resistance and opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis-Marie Nindorera, executive secretary of the Burundian
human rights group Iteka, echoed the comments of many critics when
he said he believed that the army controlled only the roads and the
camps, not the rest of the countryside where the people once lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you have a very big area which is quite empty,'' he said.
``Now the rebels are living and moving into this area.''
</P>
<P>
   Another fear is that if there are attacks on Bujumbura, and
Tutsi militias, among the most extreme forces in Burundi, look for
revenge, they will find a huge number of Hutu grouped close
together in camps. One massacre may lead to another, some fear,
setting off another spiral of mass killings.
</P>
<P>
   Some people see signs of hope: Two political movements have
formed recently that mix Hutu and Tutsi, even if the alliances
agree mostly on their support or dislike for Buyoya. Some people
say Burundians are growing so weary of war that reprisal killings
were kept to a minimum after the rebel attacks this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Many feel that Mandela, the retired South African president, is
the person best able to bring about a peace accord, if Burundi is
really ready for peace. Many people here say they are not so sure
it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe God will heal,'' said one Burundian aid worker who said
he was afraid to give his name, ``but not Mandela.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
