<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9357 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IVORYCOAST-COUP-ART-7     12-26 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVORYCOAST-COUP-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPOSED PRESIDENT OF IVORY COAST LEAVES COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The ousted president of Ivory Coast left the country in
a French aircraft Sunday, landed in nearby Togo and may seek asylum
in France, the government here said.
</P>
<P>
   Three days of rioting seemed to be coming to an end Sunday as
the army established control over the West African country, which
until last week was considered one of the most stable, prosperous
and democratic on the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Abidjan, the main city, who were unable to finish
their Christmas shopping when looting and car hijackings began on
Thursday, as soldiers held a protest, were back in stores, guarded
by soldiers. There were military checkpoints on the thoroughfares,
but buses, the main means of transportation for the city's 3
million people, began running again at dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, a nightly curfew and patrols by soldiers and police
officers empowered to shoot anyone on the street after 6 p.m. will
continue for the moment, security officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The country is being run by a nine-man military junta calling
itself the National Public Salvation Committee, and the commanders
of police, marines, paratroops, and armored and infantry units took
oaths to it on television Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the real power seems to be Gen. Robert Guei, 58, a former
armed forces chief. He said Sunday that he would create a
government that would include civilians, but did not say when.
Saturday, he invited political parties to discuss a unified
government.
</P>
<P>
   France and the United States condemned the overthrow of
President Henri Konan Bedie, 65, as did Nigeria and South Africa,
the two most powerful countries in sub-Saharan Africa. A panel of
foreign ministers from the Economic Community of West African
States said it would meet soon to discuss the crisis. Ivory Coast
is a member of the group, which has intervened militarily in civil
wars in Sierra Leone and Liberia.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first coup in Ivory Coast, which is the world's
largest producer of cocoa, exports palm oil, bananas and other
tropical products. The country had a history of stable government.
It was ruled by Felix Houphouet-Boigny from its independence in
1960 until his death in 1993. Bedie, of Houphouet-Boigny's
Democratic Party, succeeded him.
</P>
<P>
   Guei said Sunday that mutineers had overthrown the government
because it was taking political prisoners and showing ethnic
intolerance uncharacteristic of Ivorian traditions. But several
forces seemed to be at work.
</P>
<P>
   Guei, a French-trained career officer with a relatively low
profile, was himself dismissed as armed forces chief by Bedie in
1995 after rumors of a potential coup were circulated. The general
has said he was not involved in plotting a coup and was working on
his farm when the mutineers asked him to be their spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The young soldiers who participated with hooligans in the
looting that began on Thursday complained about their low pay and
working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The government has recently been showing virulent nationalism
and a xenophobic attitude toward migrant workers; a third of the 19
million population is from neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the governing Democratic Party, dominated by
members of Bedie's Baoule tribe, had tried to prevent Alassane
Ouattara, an International Monetary Fund official who was
Houphouet-Boigny's prime minister, from becoming a candidate in
next October's presidential elections. Bedie contends that Ouattara
is really a citizen of Burkina Faso and is thus ineligible to run.
</P>
<P>
   The government also jailed leaders of his Rally for the
Republicans party, who were freed by the mutineers.
</P>
<P>
   The coup junta has some apparent links to Ouattara's party. Gen.
Lassana Palenfo, another prominent member of the junta, was once
Ouattara's security minister. The soldiers made their initial
statements from Radio Nostalgie, whose owner is reported to be
close to Ouattara.
</P>
<P>
   The junta expressed satisfaction with the departure of Bedie
under what the French Foreign Ministry described as ``safe and
dignified circumstances.'' Bedie had spent two days hiding inside a
French military base near the Abidjan airport under the protection
of 550 French marines.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Guei had suggested that Bedie leave the country quickly because
his life was in danger from mutinous young officers. Bedie had
sought to take his prime minister, Daniel Kablan Duncan, and
defense minister, Vincent Bandama N'Gatta, but the new government
compelled the French, who have them in custody, to keep them in
Ivory Coast, Reuters news service reported. Some other cabinet
ministers were being held by the junta, which said it was for their
own protection. At least two appeared on television endorsing the
coup, one of them surrounded by soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Bedie's wife and children were among the entourage of about 12
people who were allowed to leave with him. He was greeted at the
airport in Lome, Togo's capital, by the Togolese president.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Agence France-Presse whether Bedie could end up in
France, a foreign ministry spokeswoman replied that she did not
know whether he wanted to come here but, ``if he wishes to, he has
the option of doing so.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, France reinforced its garrison with 40 troops from
Gabon and positioned 300 more in Senegal to aid in any possible
evacuation of the 20,000 or more French citizens in Ivory Coast.
</P>
<P>
   But Guei refused permission for any more French troops to enter
and personally guaranteed the safety of French citizens and
property. He said an increase in troop strength could lead to a
bloodbath but also seemed to fear that France might try to restore
Bedie to power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
