<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9358 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-ART-     12-26 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING WEEKS PRESENT BIGGEST CHALLENGE FOR BRADLEY CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 9 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Eds: This is the first in a series of status reports on the
campaigns of the top contenders for the Democratic and Republican
presidential nominations as they enter the primary season. The next
article will spotlight Vice President Al Gore's campaign. (mk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his professorial style, former Sen. Bill Bradley
reminds some people of Adlai Stevenson. Others hear the liberal
idealism of Robert Kennedy in his speeches, or find his distaste
for hardball politics reminiscent of Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   But the candidate that Bradley invokes most often in his
insurgent campaign for president is not a liberal or even a
Democrat. It is former President Reagan, in whose political
playbook he and his advisers have found much to admire, and perhaps
emulate, as they battle Vice President Al Gore for the Democratic
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Like Reagan, Bradley has sought to project a sunny optimism,
calling for a ``world of new possibilities'' that echoes Reagan's
``morning in America.'' Like Reagan, he has focused on a few
issues, hoping that expanding health care and reducing poverty will
grab voters' imagination the way shrinking government and fighting
communism did for Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   And like Reagan, a former actor, Bradley, a former basketball
star, is running as a celebrity outsider, trying to build an
anti-Washington rebellion against a White House scarred by scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admired the focus that he had when he ran,'' Bradley said of
Reagan in an interview. ``He told people what he wanted to do. And
when people voted for him in sizable majorities, it gave him a
mandate.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a game plan that has helped Bradley mount a surprisingly
potent challenge to Gore. Just 15 months ago, he was not a
candidate and Gore was a shoo-in for the party's nomination. Today,
he has matched Gore in fund raising, pulled even with him in polls
in New Hampshire, built a national organization and given himself a
shot, though still a long one, at upsetting the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   But the coming weeks will provide a critical test of Bradley's
staying power. First up are the Iowa caucuses on Jan. 24 and the
New Hampshire primary a week later. Then come five weeks of
coast-to-coast campaigning for what Bradley calls the national
primary of March 7: New York, California, Ohio and several other
major states. If either candidate stumbles badly, the race could be
over by mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   And with that daunting schedule, many analysts have begun
questioning whether Bradley's campaign is up to the task. Did he
fail to take advantage of a wave of positive news coverage in the
early fall? Is he winning attention mainly because of his
basketball celebrity? Is he in a seemingly strong position now
simply because he is the only challenger to an opponent who seems
to be constantly trying to reinvent himself so that he can somehow
connect with voters?
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts have also begun sensing vulnerabilities in his
Reaganesque strategy. They say that Bradley seems to be trying too
hard to stay above the fray. And some assert that in focusing on
just a few issues _ health care, poverty, campaign finance and race
relations _ he has failed to address problems people care about as
much or more, like education and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But most important, a large number of analysts argue, Bradley
has yet to demonstrate that he has built the kind of national
movement needed to upset a vice president who dominates the party's
organization and has spent seven years recruiting endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must throw Gore into disarray to have a shot in
California,'' said Fred Siegel, a history professor at the Cooper
Union for Arts and Sciences in New York. ``He needs to win
decisively in New Hampshire and New York, and I don't know if all
those things can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel and other experts point to Reagan's first presidential
campaign _ his failed primary challenge of President Ford in 1976 _
as evidence of just how difficult Bradley's task is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reagan ran an extraordinary campaign in 1976, but it still
wasn't enough to overcome Mr. Ford's institutional advantage,''
said Siegel. ``Sure, Gore has made plenty of miscues. But I'm not
sure it's enough to knock him out.''
</P>
<P>
   That year, Reagan had an important advantage that Bradley does
not: He was viewed as the leader of the Republican's conservative
wing, a group disaffected with Ford. Bradley cannot claim any such
base and, in fact, is widely viewed within the party as centrist,
on the same ideological plane as Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has tried to outflank the vice president among the
party's liberal base, which includes blacks, women, labor unions
and environmentalists. In every stump speech, he talks about
improving race relations, protecting the environment and reducing
poverty. And he has proposed increasing the minimum wage
automatically when inflation rises.
</P>
<P>
   But while Bradley has made inroads on the left, the Gore
campaign still holds more cards. The AFL-CIO has endorsed the vice
president and polls show that black voters and women remain very
supportive of the administration and, by extension, Gore.
</P>
<P>
   With those obstacles in mind, Bradley has also mapped out a
strategy to ``expand the electorate'' by energizing first-time
voters and people who have become apathetic or disgusted with
politics. His pledges to reduce the influence of money in politics
and to speak from his heart are aimed directly at disaffected
independents and Democrats angry with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem an impossible task to build a national movement in
just a few months. But Bradley has actually been laying the
groundwork for a national campaign for more than a decade. And by
the time he announced in late 1998, he had a group of devoted
longtime advisers and a network of fund-raisers in place _ much
like Reagan in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By October this year, he had raised nearly $20 million, and his
frugal spending had left him more cash on hand than Gore. Bradley
also won much national attention by unveiling a plan to subsidize
health insurance for 95 percent of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   As he campaigns these days, Bradley often tells audiences that
he decided to release a detailed health plan partly because he
thought the strategy had worked for Reagan in 1980. By being
specific, Bradley argues, Reagan could claim a mandate for his
budget-and-tax-cutting policies when he won, helping to soften
opposition in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But the specificity that Bradley considers a strength is a
tempting target for Gore. For two months now, the Gore camp has
picked apart the Bradley health plan. Since then, Gore and his
supporters have broadened their criticisms to include Bradley's
record on education, campaign finance and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides say they think their combative approach has tied
the Bradley campaign in knots. ``It's a conundrum for them,'' said
one aide. ``If they engage us, it's a mistake, because his strength
is being a philosopher-king. If you stay out there and don't do
anything, you get defined negatively.'' Either way, the aide said,
the Gore campaign has managed to muddle Bradley's message and knock
him off stride.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Bradley has become somewhat more forceful in
his responses. During a testy debate with Gore on ``Meet the
Press,'' Bradley repeatedly shouted ``That's not true!'' when Gore
criticized his health plan. And when Gore offered a handshake deal
to eschew television commercials, Bradley sarcastically rejected
it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some analysts said that Bradley should have delivered a
more forceful blow directly at what they consider Gore's Achilles'
heel: the much-criticized fund-raising practices of the
Clinton-Gore campaign in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley hit at some of those problems when he staged an event
recently with Sen. John McCain of Arizona, a Republican
presidential candidate, where both pledged to forsake so-called
soft money if they are nominated. Then McCain took some potshots at
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say that Bradley himself may need to take those
shots. ``Sooner or later he's going to have to engage Gore in
hand-to-hand combat,'' said Mitchell Moss, director of New York
University's urban research center.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bradley says his greatest challenge will be to
amplify his message above the noise of Gore's attacks. So far, he
has had some success with that in Iowa and New Hampshire, where
small-group campaigning dominates and his folksy style seems most
effective. The fight for March 7, however, will be played out
mostly on television, which has not always been kind to Bradley,
who can come across on camera as sleepy-eyed or stiff.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has worked hard, with some success, at appearing
comfortable on television. And his campaign is preparing
commercials that will try to evoke his plain-spoken, earnest style,
probably by relying on shots of him speaking into the camera or to
groups of voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional answer is you hire political consulting firms
and they turn you into a cookie-cutter production,'' Bradley said.
``And what I decided was, no, I wanted to convey who I am and what
I believe and where I want to take the country to the widest
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he added, ``we are going to test whether I am able to
do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 1957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
