u s BC-FBN-JETS-MARINO-NYT     12-26 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-MARINO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINO DAUNTING TO JETS, ONE MORE TIME
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Fla., N.Y., Texas)   (jw) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Jason Ferguson almost whispered it, lest Dan Marino
hear. ``I got a sack against him,'' Ferguson, the Jets' nose
tackle, said. ``But I don't want that to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino is 38, this could be the final home game of his Hall of
Fame career, and there are historic overtones in the Jets' Monday
night meeting with Marino's Dolphins. For it is also the final
Monday night game of the century, a fitting denouement since the
Jets were in the debut game in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Jets have only a .500 record to shoot for as they bring
in a 6-8 mark against the Dolphins (9-5), a team in the middle of
the playoff race. But the Jets play their division rival and the
man who has thrown 69 touchdown passes against them, more than any
other quarterback in history has thrown against another team. John
Elway threw 44 in his career against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder these Jets still speak of Marino as if contemplating a
legend. Indeed, some of them seem miffed that this hoary warrior,
whose career began in 1983, has lost respect in some circles.
</P>
<P>
   But not with the Jets, who have a three-game winning streak
against him. Not even considering that the Jets have sent him to
three of his poorer efforts in those games _ including his worst
sack performance against them when he was dumped five times last
December.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, many of these same players who were not even there
remember the famous faked spike against the Jets in 1994. Perhaps
they know of his 521-yard game against them as well, or his 60
passes in one contest, or his six-touchdown game.
</P>
<P>
   His 17-12 record against the Jets helps put him one game away
from tying Elway for the most winning performances ever. This could
be the first of Marino's two final shots at breaking it. Elway has
148 career victories and Marino has 147. Fran Tarkenton is third
with 125.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in his season shortened by five games because of a pinched
nerve in his neck, Marino will try to undo the second-game jinx
that has bothered all the other top quarterbacks from the American
Football Conference East when they faced the Jets this season. They
played badly. The Jets halted Doug Flutie and Drew Bledsoe, and
narrowly lost to the Colts and Peyton Manning, holding him to his
least productive game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year is different,'' Jets Coach Bill Parcells said in
reflecting on Marino's season.
</P>
<P>
   Marino is far down in the passer rating, thanks to 13
interceptions and only nine touchdowns. Two weeks ago, the Jets
picked him off twice, kept him from throwing a touchdown and made
him miss more than half his passing attempts. His gifted receiver
O.J. McDuffie has been battling a hamstring injury. His running
backs have been battered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when Dan was playing with Duper and Clayton,''
Parcells said of the dangerous receivers known as the Marks
Brothers. ``The whole deal is different now. Dan always had a
third-down receiving back when Don Shula was there. Also, the
offense is different now with a different coordinator. They have
kept some of the play-action he's been doing for years and years.
But on third downs, they used to have four receivers, two on each
side. Now they go to three. He could blister you. Now there's
blitzing zones, and they have to protect him more.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite this lessened danger in the clutch, Parcells said: ``I
still feel threatened by the guy. I like him. I think winning means
something to him. I would have loved to have coached him. I think
we would have butted heads once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Glenn and Marino butted heads figuratively. The faked
spike that symbolized Marino's superiority and the Jets'
inferiority came in 1994 when Glenn was a rookie. He bit when
Marino pretended to spike the ball, thinking the quarterback would
down the ball to stop the clock. Instead, Marino tossed a touchdown
that kept the Jets from tying the Dolphins for first place in the
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``My best memory?'' Glenn said. ``My interception.''
</P>
<P>
   That happened two years after the spike. He stepped in front of
a Marino fourth-down pass at the goal line and returned it 100
yards for a club-record return.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to Glenn, Marino remains dangerous, especially on third
down. ``You know what he's going to do,'' Glenn said, ``but he does
it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Mickens was transfixed when he saw what Marino did to Glenn,
who is Mickens' former Texas A&AMP;M teammate. Mickens was still in
college at the time, and saw the game on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time that ever happened,'' Mickens, a
defensive back, said. ``I said to myself, `I guess I better watch
for it.' Now, every time there's a clock play, I think he might be
faking it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickens also has to look at the ball differently when Marino is
winging it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some quarterbacks, like Mark Brunell and Drew Bledsoe, throw
an accurate ball with air under it,'' Mickens said. ``It sails into
the receiver's hands. But Marino, it's a frozen rope. If you don't
get your head around, the pass is complete. I'm not used to being
15, 20 yards downfield and seeing a ball come in at eye level. The
first time I faced him, I had to adjust to that. He's got the
quickest release I ever saw. You're wasting your time even trying
to blitz him.''
</P>
<P>
   The arm is still there, and the quick release, say Jets
defenders. And so is the personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always grumping at the officials,'' Mickens said. ``I
guess when you've done as much as he has, you figure you might get
a break by always complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does Parcells think about this possibly being Marino's
final home game?
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had the hearses out for this guy before,'' the coach
said. ``But he's sent a lot of defensive backs to the bus
station.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
