<HEADER>
A9363 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-WIZARDS-H     12-26 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-WIZARDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
WASHINGTON, D.C. _ The Rockets saw the familiar, smiling faces
lining the court. There were banners and cheers for the visiting
team, loads of spirit of the season and good, warm feelings.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rockets, polite guests of honor, were not about to put their
feet on the furniture. They were not the sorts to hog the eggnog or
double-dip the chips. They were perfect gentlemen.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets did not quite gift-wrap a 103-92 win for the Wizards
on Sunday at the MCI Center. But they did little to interfere with
the hosts' party plans, allowing the Wizards' offense, usually
among the NBA's worst, to run easily and score inside consistently.
The Rockets accepted only a courteous share of free throws, making
barely half of their attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very loose, Merry Christmas environment,'' Rockets
forward Carlos Rogers said. ``I know we didn't come out like `Let's
play basketball.' We came out like Christmas was yesterday. And we
just went through the motions.''
</P>
<P>
   With guard Steve Francis, forward Walt Williams and injured
forward Tony Massenburg back in their hometown, and a holiday
hangover throughout the quiet arena, the Rockets never could
maintain the intensity or execution of their 16-point win over the
Wizards on Thursday at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   There were moments. Francis had the most breathtaking one with a
spectacular leap over the reach of Wizards center Jahidi White to a
powerful dunk the crowd celebrated nearly as much as Reebok
marketers will when they put together Francis' inevitable shoe
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with 21 points, seven assists and a season-best six
steals. But he never could control the game as he did Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a Steve Francis welcome-home party,'' said Wizards
guard Laron Profit, Francis' Maryland teammate. ``We got what we
wanted. He got to play in front of his family and friends, which is
what he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who had played just one minute in the previous two
games, had a season-high 20 points in 23 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But the game rarely generated any sense of urgency to maintain
momentum from Francis' playmaking or Williams' shooting. And when
the Rockets did make a run, the Wizards had little trouble beating
them down the floor to fast-break points, or driving the lane to
layups.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards scored 54 points in the paint, the most any team has
scored inside against the Rockets since the Kings had 56 on Nov.
21. The Wizards scored 25 fast-break points, the most by a Rockets
opponent since the Kings' 27.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wizards are not normally the high-scoring, high-speed
Kings. The Kings lead the NBA with an average of 102.3 points per
game. The Wizards' average of 92.3 points ranks 25th in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were horrible on the fast break,'' Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich said. ``That's just horrible when you give up that many
fast-break points.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were just as charitable on the other end. They made
just 35 of 89 shots (39.3 percent), their worst shooting
performance since the Dec. 8 loss in Philadelphia when Charles
Barkley's career ended with a ruptured quadriceps tendon.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Matt Bullard's 1-for-7, the bulk of
Sunday's misses were on drives through the lane. There were more
missed opportunities on passes mishandled in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Steve created a lot of situations,'' Tomjanovich
said. ``We just didn't catch the ball. We had a lot of those. And
then if we did, we didn't finish the layup.''
</P>
<P>
   To those problems, the Rockets added a 16-of-28 (57.1 percent)
shooting performance from the foul line, including nine missed free
throws in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't shoot the ball well at all from the field or the
free-throw line,'' Tomjanovich said. ``It's frustrating when you
get a team to foul you and you don't cash in. It changes the whole
tension for the other team if we kept it closer. They were
free-stroking at the end with a nice cushion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards did shoot well, particularly guard Mitch Richmond,
who had 27 points to go with seven assists and six rebounds, but
the Rockets blamed their own generosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we lost the game ourselves with missed layups and
free throws and the little intangible stuff,'' Francis said. ``We
came out flat. Probably the holiday season, everybody was just
happy they went home for Christmas, I guess. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The noon start also might have contributed to an atmosphere more
suited for a Sunday pickup game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to make excuses,'' Rogers said. ``But this early
start _ I was trying to do everything today to get ready. I even
drank a cup of coffee. I never, ever drink coffee. I was just
trying to get going. I'm not used to such an early game.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the slow start and the quiet atmosphere, the Rockets
had a lead and an opportunity to build momentum with Francis' dunk.
He had given the Rockets a 41-39 lead 4:20 before halftime and left
the crowd buzzing and calling for a scoreboard replay that never
game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets did little to build on that play. They missed
their next five shots and three of four free throws and committed
four turnovers in four minutes, as the Wizards finished the half
with a 10-1 run.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets began the second half just as poorly, missing their
first four shots while the Wizards pushed the lead to 16. After
scoring two points in the first half, White had 13 points in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the jam over me,'' White said of Francis' dunk. ``He
really jumped high. He got me. I just had to come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for us to come out after the half ready to
play. We needed to start the third quarter with some power and
intensity. I knew if we did that, we'd win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   If they did that, they would be the only team with power and
intensity. But at least no one could accuse the Rockets of being
impolite party guests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
