<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-PRESIDENT-ART-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PRESIDENT'S LIGHT TOUCH WORRIES SOME IN INDONESIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Two months after taking office, Indonesia's
new president, Abdurrahman Wahid, seems to be having a
disconcertingly good time.
</P>
<P>
   Relaxed, joking, spinning off ideas as if he were a quirky
commentator rather than the president, proposing solutions and then
changing his mind, he has brought a new, light touch to the often
grim job of leading the world's fourth-most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   After three decades of harsh control under President Suharto,
Wahid's wide-open, come-one-come-all style has begun to make his
countrymen nervous. Is he really in charge? Does he grasp the
urgency of his nation's crisis? Does he have a plan?
</P>
<P>
   As Indonesia ends a tumultuous year of tension, violence and
democratic transition and launches into a heady but chaotic period
of self-redefinition, Wahid seems to be playing a risky game of
free-rein leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say he is offering his fragmented and fractious
nation more freedom than it can handle _ something his defense
minister, Juwono Sudarsono, calls ``overdemocracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very confusing,'' said Pramoedya Ananta Toer, Indonesia's
most prominent novelist, who is a friend of the president. ``He
doesn't seem to have a sense of priorities. There is unrest
throughout the country, yet he travels abroad. It's very odd. When
I try to follow what he is doing, I can't keep it straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of Wahid, who was elected Oct. 20, say he is a true
democrat, committed to _ and reveling in _ the messy clamor of
public debate. They say his open, inclusive, experimental approach
to leadership, guided by his keen political instincts, could just
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not only a liberal democrat but a man of intrinsic
tolerance,'' said a foreign official who visited him recently. ``My
worry is that even with the best intentions, he could be presiding
over a highly unstable government in which his own ideas are
difficult to implement.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble right now is that many of Indonesia's more than 200
million people seem confused over just what those ideas are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this is part of his strategy, to be unpredictable,''
said Sri Purwati, a local journalist. ``But it is hard to put
yourself in the hands of someone without knowing what is going to
happen next. People know that he likes to joke around, and
sometimes we are not sure if he is joking.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of his more surprising actions, Wahid spent 17 of his
first 50 days in office abroad on a series of off-the-cuff trips at
a time when some people fear that his nation is in danger of
breaking apart.
</P>
<P>
   At home, he has taken few decisive steps apart from shutting
down two marginal ministries and opening another ministry, on
maritime affairs. One of his first acts was to raise the
possibility of establishing diplomatic relations with Israel _
something of a personal hobbyhorse, but tricky for the world's most
populous Muslim nation.
</P>
<P>
   None of this, his critics say, does much to address Indonesia's
crises of separatist insurgencies, military restiveness, economic
collapse and a desperate need for wide-ranging political reforms
and government restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is unpredictable, always very quick off the mark, not
terribly structured, not much of a manager, always full of ideas,''
said Dewi Fortuna Anwar, who was a close aide to the previous
president, B.J. Habibie. ``There still seems to be a lot of trial
and error in the things he does.''
</P>
<P>
   These are things that some people have always known about Wahid,
who for decades headed Indonesia's largest Muslim organization and
has been known as a brilliant eccentric.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Wahid as president, Ms. Anwar said, ``my concern is
that he tends to take things too lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Her concern was echoed in an interview by Juwono, who, as the
first civilian defense minister in 40 years, faces the crucial task
of beginning to de-politicize the military.
</P>
<P>
   When he talks to the president, Juwono said, ``I feel a strong
sense of responsibility to try and instill a sense of crisis and
urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems, he said, are compounded by Wahid's near-blindness,
which limits his sources of information. At Cabinet meetings, for
instance, he is unable to take notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all his intelligence, I don't think he can really absorb
the extent and importance of the points of, say, seven ministers
reporting,'' Juwono said. ``The most he can remember is probably
three or four points. So I try to limit my presentations to three
minutes or so.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's defenders reply that Wahid's light touch is his
special genius. His country's problems defy quick or forceful
solutions, they say, and his tactic is to restore a sense of
humanity and calm to public discourse.
</P>
<P>
   His strength is as a conciliator and consensus builder; he is a
hard man not to like. He is committed to the country's clumsier new
structure of checks and balances, with its newly empowered
Parliament and aggressive public institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has his own way,'' said Nurcholis Madjid, a Muslim scholar
who is an unofficial adviser to the president. ``People accuse him
of nonaction, but it seems to me he is relying on the psychology
that time will soften things.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, some experts say, the new president's more relaxed
style is the right one for the moment, allowing the newly emerging
social and political forces to begin to reshape the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gus Dur is not only decent but a liberal with a genuine
commitment to free speech, to disagreement,'' said Donald K.
Emmerson, an expert on Indonesia at Stanford University, using the
president's nickname. ``He's a teacher at heart. He's full of
ideas.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So, with its president as a sort of creative scholar in chief,
Indonesia has plunged into a ferment of change. The roster of
urgent problems seems overwhelming: a new role for the politicized
and often brutal military; a better balance between the central
government and its restive provinces and between the executive and
the legislature; a rebuilt economy free from the distortions of
corruption and monopolies; effective political parties; a fair and
professional judiciary; an efficient and honest bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Work has already begun in some areas, most dangerously in
beginning to hold the military to account for past and current
abuses of human rights. In particular, Indonesian investigators
have begun summoning generals to answer for the bloodshed and
destruction that followed East Timor's vote for independence at the
end of August.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, other separatist movements in Aceh province
and elsewhere are putting military and civilian leaders _ Wahid in
particular _ to their toughest test.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia took on much of its momentum for change during the
17-month presidency of Habibie, who began dismantling the legacy of
his predecessor and mentor, Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   The reform movement that has set the national agenda comes from
pent-up social forces that burst free when Suharto was forced to
step down in May 1998, after 32 years in power. Wahid, who has
spoken of wanting to unleash his nation's creative forces, may see
his role as conductor of a grand national orchestra of reform.
</P>
<P>
   But as Juwono suggested, there may be a risk here of too much
unstructured freedom, too quickly, in a country where limits have
for decades been set only by force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weight of enforcement dissipated after the fall of
Suharto,'' Juwono said. ``For the first time in modern history the
gravitas of an order of the president is being challenged by these
new elements of openness, transparency, accountability and
litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   With a government still in disarray and without a firm leader,
there is a danger of the kind of mob rule that helped bring down
Suharto and has kept Indonesia on edge since.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper editors who once bowed to the grip of the censor now
say they fear the angry mobs that sometimes invade their newsrooms.
Local government offices have often been taken over by
demonstrators demanding the removal of officials they see as
corrupt or incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   In early December, a mob of several hundred men with sticks took
over the Jakarta city hall demanding that all nightclubs be closed
during the Muslim holy month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   The government had already ruled that they could stay open.
Closing them would run counter to the tolerant approach that is at
the heart of the new president's philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   If this example is a sign of things to come as the liberal
president confronts the angry mob, it is not an encouraging one:
The nightclubs were ordered closed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
