<HEADLINE>
LIGHTS, CAMERA, ACTION, YEAR, CENTURY, MILLENNIUM ... 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Resending to add art note.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a child, George Stevens Jr. loved to hang around
the movie sets where his father, the celebrated director, was
working.
</P>
<P>
   George Sr., director of such classics as ``Woman of the Year,''
``A Place in the Sun'' and ``Shane,'' was often asked if young
George would follow him into the business.
</P>
<P>
   George Sr. would laugh and say, ``Oh, I think he may go
straight.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course he did not. George Jr. worked with his father on
``The Diary of Anne Frank'' and ``Giant'' and, by the time he was
28, had directed episodes of the television series ``Alfred
Hitchcock Presents'' and ``Peter Gunn.''
</P>
<P>
   He has gone on to a career producing and directing hundreds of
films for the federal government, numerous documentaries and dozens
of television specials, including the annual ``Kennedy Center
Honors.'' He was executive producer of the 1998 film ``The Thin Red
Line.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, George Stevens is co-producing his biggest outdoor
extravaganza, the New Year's Eve celebration of ``America's
Millennium,'' on the Mall in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens is 67 but looks a decade younger. He wears a perpetual
smile and has a glimmer in his eye as if a key light were following
him, as he conducts a tour of the giant stage he has built on the
steps of the Lincoln Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   It is from here that President Clinton and Hillary Rodham
Clinton will welcome the new century, but they are bit players in
the $10 million production that Stevens and Quincy Jones are
concocting.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is scheduled to speak a few minutes before
midnight on New Year's Eve, after a 19-minute Steven Spielberg
paean to America called ``The Unfinished Journey'' accompanied by
an original score by John Williams. In keeping with the patriotic
theme, the host will be Will Smith, the actor who saved America
from aliens bent on annihilation in ``Independence Day,'' backed up
by 30 dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Jessye Norman and Kathleen Battle, the opera divas, will be
there to raise the brow of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who commutes between Washington and Los Angeles and who
has long been active in Democratic politics, said that he was
recruited by Mrs. Clinton three years ago to help design the
celebration. He said the Clintons had also sounded out Jones and
Spielberg about what might be an ``appropriate manifestation'' of
the turn of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who is busy on several other film projects, said he had
decided to take on the millennium celebration ``because it is
there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity _ you might even say an honor _ to be
able to conceive this with Quincy,'' Stevens said. The result was a
gigantic undertaking encompassing hundreds of workers, tons of
sound, lighting and video equipment trucked in from California and
New York, and complex security considerations involving the local
police, the Park Police and the Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens has mixed government service with filmmaking for much of
his career. He served in the Kennedy administration as director of
movie and television services for the U.S. Information Agency,
working under Edward R. Murrow. Among his projects were
documentaries on the Little Rock school desegregation battle and
the death of President Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   President Johnson named Stevens founding director of the
American Film Institute, which is dedicated to preserving archival
films and supporting aspiring filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens and his wife, Liz, are active in the Washington social
scene, frequently entertaining the city's media and political elite
at their Georgetown home. They are die-hard Democrats, but
latecomers to the Clinton bandwagon, preferring the more
old-fashioned Democratic politics of Robert F. Kennedy and his
ideological heirs.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton saw valuable allies in the Stevenses and
cultivated them for their ties to the Washington establishment.
</P>
<P>
   That, in part, accounts for Stevens' selection as co-producer of
the millennium show, which is being staged in close consultation
with the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities expect a crowd of 100,000 to gather on Friday
evening at the base of the Lincoln Memorial, with tens of thousands
more on the grounds of the Washington Monument and along the Mall.
</P>
<P>
   While the producers have devoted thousands of hours to planning
the entertainment and the speeches, the event may be remembered
most for the fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   A half-minute before midnight, a burning fuse will travel the
length of the reflecting pool, ending at the base of the Washington
Monument. As the final seconds of the century tick away, the
monument will be transformed into a giant Roman candle, sheathed in
cascading pyrotechnic light. At the stroke of midnight, the sky
behind the obelisk will turn golden with fireworks, symbolizing,
Stevens said, ``something about aspiration and the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of the whole program, Stevens said, is to celebrate the
American experiment in popular government _ and to have a little
fun along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the persiflage and hype and expense,'' he said,
``our hope is to somehow capture a little of the wonder of
democracy on the swamp that George Washington chose as our capital
and designed into a city, between the monuments to Lincoln and
Washington with the Capitol in the background.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In this cynical age,'' he concluded, ``it makes your heart
beat a little faster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
