<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN TROOPS MEETING STIFF RESISTANCE FROM CHECHEN REBELS IN
GROZNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After two days of fighting in the streets of Grozny,
the Russian military conceded on Sunday night that its troops were
meeting strong opposition as they struggled to seize control of the
Chechen capital from Islamic rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advance of the Russian troops is very difficult,'' the
Russian Defense Ministry told the Itar-Tass news agency.
``Practically at all crucial points the the rebels have established
strong positions.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior rebel leader, Isa Numunayev, told the Interfax news
agency that the fighting over the weekend was comparable in
intensity to the fiercest battles of the 1994-96 Chechen war.
Russia's NTV television network reported that the militants had
constructed a network of fortified trenches near the southwestern
part of the city, which has slowed the Russian advance.
</P>
<P>
   A light rain fell on Sunday in Chechnya, which, coupled with
fog, made it difficult for Russian planes to carry out the air
strikes that have been used to bombard Grozny for weeks. Russian
commanders pointedly refused to say when they expected to seize the
city.
</P>
<P>
   The battle for Grozny has become a critical test for Russia's
generals, who have promised a decisive victory over the rebels.
Even as they concede difficulties, military officials are anxious
to maintain popular support and have presented a picture of a
successful and disciplined campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Interior Ministry troops and Chechen paramilitary forces
loyal to Moscow began the operation to seize Grozny on Saturday
after a heavy Russian bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Russian commanders have vowed not to repeat the mistakes of the
1994-1996 war in Chechnya, when Russian troops raced to the center
of Grozny and were cut off and destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Russian forces hope to advance methodically through the
city, calling in devastating artillery and air strikes when they
encounter resistance.
</P>
<P>
   After a weekend of fighting in Grozny's streets, it was
impossible to confirm what territory the Russian forces actually
controlled or how many soldiers the Russian military had lost.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic rebels claimed to have killed hundreds of Russian
troops, but Russian authorities have only acknowledged the death of
two of their soldiers in the bitter fighting in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Little is also known about the fate of the tens of thousands of
residents who have found themselves trapped in the battle zone. As
many as 50,000 civilians are still believed to be hiding in
basement shelters in Grozny, according to Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military had hoped to evacuate Grozny's residents
before the battle but went ahead with its attack anyway after
efforts to remove the civilians failed. Talks were under way on
Sunday night between Sergei Shoigu, the minister for emergency
situations, and other officials on possible ways to evacuate the
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the current storming of Grozny, there'll be nobody to
evacuate in a few days time,'' Numunayev, the rebel leader, told
Interfax.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials again deplored Russia's heavy bombardment of
Grozny. But the complaints have become almost an empty ritual since
the Kremlin has made it clear that it is not listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia runs the risk of isolating itself from the
international community by continuing to utilize indiscriminate
force,'' a Clinton administration official said. ``We continue to
urge restraint and the commencement of dialogue.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Col. Gen. Viktor Kazantsev, the commander of the Russian forces
in the North Caucasus, provided an answer of sorts for that
criticism. He said the Russian flag would be flying over Grozny
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not hurry, but you'll soon see,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fight for Grozny has been brewing for months. Russian troops
moved from the north, west and east to blockade the city. The
strategy was to bottle up the Islamic militants in the city and
force their surrender.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the Russian military said it hoped the rebels in
Grozny could be talked into submitting. Russian commanders invoked
the example of Gudermes, Chechnya's second-largest city, where
local elders agreed to the occupation of the city by Russian troops
after the militants left.
</P>
<P>
   But Grozny has always been different. Along with the mountainous
regions in the south, it has been a center of rebel resistance. And
by encircling the city, the Russians also closed the rebels' main
escape routes, setting the stage for a climatic and potentially
very bloody battle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is not clear how many militants are still in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military says there are 1,500 Islamic fighters in
Grozny. But the whereabouts of the Chechen warlord Shamil Basayev
and Kattab, a rebel born in the Middle East, are unknown. That
raises the prospect that Russia will take the city only to find
that its main adversaries have escaped.
</P>
<P>
   While the Russian military has not publicly set a deadline for
taking the city, it seems determined to seize Grozny by early in
the new year.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to highlight their progress, Russian officials asserted
today that Russian troops had driven through Minutka Square, near
the heart of the city. They did not claim, however, that the
Russian military currently controlled the square.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen paramilitary forces allied with Moscow said that they
had captured Dom Pechati, a building in the city center that was
once the headquarters for local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The forces are under the command of Bislan Gantamirov, the
former mayor of Grozny who had been imprisoned for embezzlement,
but was released by the Russian authorities so he could serve as an
ally in the war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are conducting a cleanup of the city, checking all homes
and basements where rebels could hide,'' Gantamirov said.
</P>
<P>
   Gantamirov's forces, however, are widely viewed as a bit of
political window dressing for the Russian military, and his claims
of battlefield success could not be verified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991226.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9368 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CATHOLIC-UNIVERSITIES     12-26 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-UNIVERSITIES-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC THEOLOGIANS UNSETTLED BY BISHOPS' OVERSIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On a recent afternoon, in her class on how people
have portrayed Jesus throughout history, Theresa Sanders read aloud
a passage by a medieval nun, who had imagined Jesus in an
unconventional way, as a mothering figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christians have always used the images at hand to talk about
the significance of Jesus,'' said Ms. Sanders, a professor at
Georgetown University, provoking a question from Michael Ballard, a
senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a limit on where you can go with that symbolism?''
Ballard asked, prompting Ms. Sanders to guide the class into a
discussion of how far Christians ought to go in seeking common
ground with people of other faiths in understanding God.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sanders said afterward: ``When I present Catholic teaching,
like any responsible professor, I try to do it accurately. I
present it in as complex and nuanced and faithful a way as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   A Roman Catholic institution, Georgetown has become more
religiously diverse than it was a generation ago. In 1988, among
those undergraduates who indicated a religious background, only
about 57 percent were Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Its theology department has also grown, the offerings ranging
from courses in Scripture to feminist ethics to Islamic politics.
</P>
<P>
   These days, theology departments at all Catholic universities in
the United States, face a question of what will result from a
decision by the nation's bishops to require theologians to obtain a
mandate certifying that what they teach is ``authentic'' Catholic
doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   The stipulation was included in a document adopted by the
bishops at their meeting in November. The document, ``Ex Corde
Ecclesiae'' (``From the Heart of the Church''), is subject to
approval by the Vatican, which is expected in the next several
months.
</P>
<P>
   Then the bishops will have to decide how to grant mandates, how
to revoke them and what they think a university ought to do when a
theologian loses a mandate.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to Georgetown suggested that any bishop who decided that
he wanted a closer look at theologians within his jurisdiction
might have a lot to do.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown offers more than 100 theology classes, taught by 25
full-time professors. Undergraduates may choose among numerous
courses, on Catholic social action, religion and film, the Dead Sea
Scrolls, Protestant Christianity, Judaism, Islam, Buddhism,
Hinduism and African religions.
</P>
<P>
   Would a bishop want to sit in on a class? Would he feel obliged
to read what the theologians have written?
</P>
<P>
   While the bishop's role is to convey Catholic teaching in the
community, said Anthony Tambasco, chairman of the theology
department at Georgetown, the university has a different focus.
There is, he said, ``an important distinction between evangelism
and mission, and the academic study of theology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Theology is not catechism,'' Tambasco said, referring to basic
religious instruction. ``We do the academic study,'' he said, ``and
campus ministry takes care of the spiritual needs of students.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The distinction at Georgetown was not always clear, Tambasco
said. In the 1950s, the department was smaller, staffed by Jesuit
priests who took an interest in promoting the faith within a
student body that was overwhelmingly Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   But the department has changed. These days, although the
majority of professors are Catholic, most are lay people, a group
over whom the bishops have less direct control. And while the
number of students opting for a theology major is up, the Catholics
among them belong to a generation that has far less religious
education than their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen must take a nonsectarian theology course, ``The Problem
of God,'' a nonsectarian class intended for a student body where a
majority is Catholic. The class deals with such issues as the
relationship between reason and faith, and the way religious
thinkers have responded to atheism.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before about 30 students recently, the Rev. Stephen
Fields discussed the conversion of St. Augustine. But as he
concluded the session, he reminded students that the class was not
intended to win over nonbelievers or to shake the faith of those
who did believe.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Fields said, the class was intended to introduce them to
the historic arguments for God's existence, and the strengths and
weaknesses in those arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get this criticism here at Georgetown,'' Fields said.
```You're a Catholic university, shouldn't you be teaching
something explicitly Catholic to first-year students?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we have a whole range of courses and Catholic
subjects,'' he said, adding that the bishops' document emphasized
that the mission of a Catholic university was to educate. ``So, I
think it's perfectly appropriate that the goals of a course like
this should be broadly humane,'' Fields said. ``And I think it's
perfectly consonant with our identity as a Catholic university.''
</P>
<P>
   Tambasco estimated that about 60 students were majoring in
theology at Georgetown, a fourfold increase over the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   One is John Favier, 22, a Catholic and a senior from San
Francisco, who said studying theology ``forces you to think in new
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no longer in the comfort of blissful ignorance,'' said
Favier, a student in Ms. Sanders' class. By that, he said, he meant
that he had passed beyond ``a blind acceptance'' that lacked
``critical research and critical analysis of the faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballard, 22, a Presbyterian from Dallas, was one of Favier's
classmates. ``I really enjoy the discussions we have,'' Ballard
said, ``because there are so many people with radically different
viewpoints.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991226.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CATHOLIC-UNIVERSITIES     12-26 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-UNIVERSITIES-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGETOWN TAKES TEACHING VIEW OF NEW THEOLOGY MANDATE
</HEADLINE>
   (lb) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On a recent afternoon, in her class on how people
have portrayed Jesus throughout history, Theresa Sanders read aloud
a passage by a medieval nun, who had imagined Jesus in an
unconventional way, as a mothering figure.
</P>
