<SLUG> BC-MAYFIELD-OBIT27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    R&AMP;B artist Curtis Mayfield dies at 57
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If there's any good news to be gleaned from the death
of R&AMP;B pioneer Curtis Mayfield, it's that until he passed away
Sunday, he kept on pushing.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield, 57, died Sunday morning at North Fulton Regional
Hospital in Roswell, Ga. No other details were available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my husband, the father of our children, my best friend
and my soulmate,'' said Mayfield's widow, Altheida. ``Thank God his
music and his legacy will live far beyond today.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as March, when he was inducted into the Rock and
Roll Hall of Fame, Mayfield pushed, trying unsuccessfully to travel
from his Dunwoody, Ga., home to New York for the ceremony.
Ultimately, complications from a 1990 stage accident that paralyzed
him from the neck down kept him from going.
</P>
<P>
   For some time, the Chicago native's injuries also kept him from
adding to his 41-year-old catalog, which includes ``Keep on
Moving,'' a civil rights rallying cry in 1964; the similar-minded
1965 classic, ``People Get Ready''; and the breakthrough funk
soundtrack of 1972, ``Superfly.'' In 1996, when the
singer-songwriter had been an Atlantan for 20 years, he recruited
local producers Darryl Simmons and Organized Noize to record his
last album of original work, the Grammy-nominated ``New World
Order.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Making music keeps my soul working even when my body doesn't
want to,'' Mayfield said in 1996, one of the last times he was able
to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:20 a.m. Sunday, his body gave in.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
