A9383 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CATHOLIC-UNIVERSITIES     12-26 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-UNIVERSITIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGETOWN TAKES TEACHING VIEW OF NEW THEOLOGY MANDATE
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Changes ``1988'' to ``1998'' in 5th graf.) 
(lb) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On a recent afternoon, in her class on how people
have portrayed Jesus throughout history, Theresa Sanders read aloud
a passage by a medieval nun, who had imagined Jesus in an
unconventional way, as a mothering figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christians have always used the images at hand to talk about
the significance of Jesus,'' said Ms. Sanders, a professor at
Georgetown University, provoking a question from Michael Ballard, a
senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a limit on where you can go with that symbolism?''
Ballard asked, prompting Ms. Sanders to guide the class into a
discussion of how far Christians ought to go in seeking common
ground with people of other faiths in understanding God.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sanders said afterward: ``When I present Catholic teaching,
like any responsible professor, I try to do it accurately. I
present it in as complex and nuanced and faithful a way as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   A Roman Catholic institution, Georgetown has become more
religiously diverse than it was a generation ago. In 1998, among
those undergraduates who indicated a religious background, only
about 57 percent were Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Its theology department has also grown, the offerings ranging
from courses in Scripture to feminist ethics to Islamic politics.
</P>
<P>
   These days, theology departments at all Catholic universities in
the United States, face a question of what will result from a
decision by the nation's bishops to require theologians to obtain a
mandate certifying that what they teach is ``authentic'' Catholic
doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   The stipulation was included in a document adopted by the
bishops at their meeting in November. The document, ``Ex Corde
Ecclesiae'' (``From the Heart of the Church''), is subject to
approval by the Vatican, which is expected in the next several
months.
</P>
<P>
   Then the bishops will have to decide how to grant mandates, how
to revoke them and what they think a university ought to do when a
theologian loses a mandate.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to Georgetown suggested that any bishop who decided that
he wanted a closer look at theologians within his jurisdiction
might have a lot to do.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown offers more than 100 theology classes, taught by 25
full-time professors. Undergraduates may choose among numerous
courses, on Catholic social action, religion and film, the Dead Sea
Scrolls, Protestant Christianity, Judaism, Islam, Buddhism,
Hinduism and African religions.
</P>
<P>
   Would a bishop want to sit in on a class? Would he feel obliged
to read what the theologians have written?
</P>
<P>
   While the bishop's role is to convey Catholic teaching in the
community, said Anthony Tambasco, chairman of the theology
department at Georgetown, the university has a different focus.
There is, he said, ``an important distinction between evangelism
and mission, and the academic study of theology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Theology is not catechism,'' Tambasco said, referring to basic
religious instruction. ``We do the academic study,'' he said, ``and
campus ministry takes care of the spiritual needs of students.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The distinction at Georgetown was not always clear, Tambasco
said. In the 1950s, the department was smaller, staffed by Jesuit
priests who took an interest in promoting the faith within a
student body that was overwhelmingly Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   But the department has changed. These days, although the
majority of professors are Catholic, most are lay people, a group
over whom the bishops have less direct control. And while the
number of students opting for a theology major is up, the Catholics
among them belong to a generation that has far less religious
education than their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen must take a theology course, ``The Problem of God,'' a
nonsectarian class intended for a student body where a majority is
Catholic. The class deals with such issues as the relationship
between reason and faith, and the way religious thinkers have
responded to atheism.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before about 30 students recently, the Rev. Stephen
Fields discussed the conversion of St. Augustine. But as he
concluded the session, he reminded students that the class was not
intended to win over nonbelievers or to shake the faith of those
who did believe.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Fields said, the class was intended to introduce them to
the historic arguments for God's existence, and the strengths and
weaknesses in those arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get this criticism here at Georgetown,'' Fields said.
```You're a Catholic university, shouldn't you be teaching
something explicitly Catholic to first-year students?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we have a whole range of courses and Catholic
subjects,'' he said, adding that the bishops' document emphasized
that the mission of a Catholic university was to educate. ``So, I
think it's perfectly appropriate that the goals of a course like
this should be broadly humane,'' Fields said. ``And I think it's
perfectly consonant with our identity as a Catholic university.''
</P>
<P>
   Tambasco estimated that about 60 students were majoring in
theology at Georgetown, a fourfold increase over the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   One is John Favier, 22, a Catholic and a senior from San
Francisco, who said studying theology ``forces you to think in new
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no longer in the comfort of blissful ignorance,'' said
Favier, a student in Ms. Sanders' class. By that, he said, he meant
that he had passed beyond ``a blind acceptance'' that lacked
``critical research and critical analysis of the faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballard, 22, a Presbyterian from Dallas, was one of Favier's
classmates. ``I really enjoy the discussions we have,'' Ballard
said, ``because there are so many people with radically different
viewpoints.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
