<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BOWL WINNERS MAY BE MONEY LOSERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Wisconsin's football team journeyed to Pasadena, Calif.,
last January to play UCLA in the Rose Bowl, the travel party
totaled 832, far more than were needed to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   Besides 110 uniformed Badgers, the contingent included the
coaches, the 380-member band, the spirit squad, university
officials, athletic department staff and assorted spouses. The tab:
$2.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers won, 38-31, but lost $300,000 on the California
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Losing money on the Rose Bowl sounds like a feat of fiscal
nuttiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``People heard about the payout and that we lost money, and
wondered `How could that be?''' said Vince Sweeney, an associate
athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, whatever happens on the field, bowl teams are not
always winners on the bottom line. Whether a bowl pays out top
dollar, which can be $10 million and up _ for Wisconsin last season
it was about $12.5 million _ or it pays considerably less, some
teams consider themselves lucky if their costs do not exceed their
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, bowl games have offered colleges major
opportunities to strut before national television audiences,
whether they are Bowl Championship Series games with eight-figure
payouts like the Rose Bowl or smaller ones with payouts below $1
million like the Music City Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Red ink or not, the bowls are about pageantry and recruiting, as
well as rewarding players and administrators for a successful
season with a nice road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be in the bowl business,'' said Val Hale,
athletic director of Brigham Young, which plays Marshall in
Monday's Motor City Bowl. ``If you don't, it hurts your recruiting
and your image.''
</P>
<P>
   And if appearing in a bowl causes a short-term financial loss,
he said, ``It's a cost of doing business.''
</P>
<P>
   For playing in last season's Rose Bowl, Wisconsin and UCLA
received about $12.5 million each. But no team playing in a major
bowl game, except for an independent like Notre Dame, goes home
with the entire bounty. The revenue is shared among the other teams
in its conference, with the conference paying its bowl teams'
``expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin's cut from the Rose Bowl came to $1.4 million. The
team raised $400,000 more from sponsors and alumni. Yet $1.8
million was still not enough to break even on the jaunt to
Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   The loss on the trip generated criticism from local politicians
and state legislators, so for Wisconsin's return trip to the Rose
Bowl on Saturday to play Stanford, the team's contingent will be
pared by at least 100 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that we'll get to where we want to be,''
Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sweeney added, the bowl season produced a profit. Five
Big Ten teams _ Wisconsin, Ohio State, Michigan, Purdue and Penn
State _ played bowl games last season. The windfall from
distributing the bowl revenues produced an additional $1.5 million
for each team in the conference _ even Northwestern, which lost
nine of its 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Some state legislators are angry that Minnesota is spending $1
million to send 700 people, including the Gophers team, to Friday's
Sun Bowl in El Paso, Texas, so soon after an academic fraud scandal
in the men's basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think the university, when it has such great
needs, should spend money like that, regardless of the source,''
said Leo Foley, a state senator.
</P>
<P>
   But Rick Chryst, commissioner of the Mid-American Conference,
which sent Marshall to the Motor City Bowl in Pontiac, Mich., said
that even if a university loses money going to a bowl game, there
are many good reasons to sign on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still great and still worth it to go,'' Chryst said.
``Only our champion gets to go to a bowl, and for Marshall to play
a great opponent like BYU, it's great for the players to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Motor City Bowl pays each team $750,000, which Marshall and
BYU will use for expenses. David Steele, Marshall's associate
athletic director, said the school would lose $100,000 to $120,000
to send its party from Huntington, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regard it as a positive expense,'' Steele said. The
Thundering Herd lost similar sums to make Motor City Bowl
appearances in 1998 and in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Like BYU, Marshall's bowl finances would improve if it sold out
its allocation of 16,000 tickets, at $32 each, to the game at the
Silverdome. Every bowl team must guarantee the sale of a designated
number of tickets, but Steele said Marshall would sell only about
9,000 tickets, creating a loss of $224,000 for the tickets alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is selling out your tickets,'' said Hale of BYU. ``If
you can do that, you'll make a profit or break even.'' The
university is sending 500 people to Pontiac, including 300 band
members.
</P>
<P>
   Hale was hoping for a trip to the Las Vegas Bowl, which would
have entailed a shorter, cheaper trip from Provo, Utah, than the
one the Cougars will make to Michigan, and would almost have
guaranteed a profit. But Utah, which had the same overall (8-3) and
conference records (5-2) as BYU, was selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had gone to Las Vegas, we'd have sold all our tickets
and sent everyone on buses,'' Hale said. But the trip to Pontiac
will mean a loss of $256,000 to BYU on 8,000 unsold tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Hale remains hopeful that the trip will not require the school
to spend more than the $750,000 it will receive for playing. Yet he
knows that at the Mormon school, a greater percentage of players
have wives and children than do players at other colleges. The
families' travel costs are also covered. ``When they get off the
plane, it's like a family reunion, with all the baby strollers,''
Hale said.
</P>
<P>
   Each conference divides bowl revenues differently. The Sugar
Bowl, which will determine the national champion, is paying $11
million to $13 million each to Virginia Tech and Florida State.
(The exact sum will depend on ticket sales and other revenues.) The
Orange Bowl will pay Alabama and Michigan a similar amount.
</P>
<P>
   But Virginia Tech will keep $4 million _ more than ensuring a
profitable trip, with 600 people in tow, win or lose against the
Seminoles. Alabama will keep $2.5 million, a reflection of the
different philosophies of their conferences. Alabama hopes to avoid
losing money, as it did last year when it played for a modest
payout at the Music City Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone else pays as much, which has been our
history,'' said John Paquette, associate commissioner of the Big
East. ``Part of our philosophy is to reward success.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Southeastern Conference, the lower payment to Alabama
means more for the other 11 teams and the league office, said
Charles Bloom, a league spokesman. He added that the Big East could
be more generous because it had only eight football teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a fair way to let all 12 schools get a piece of the
pie,'' Bloom said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
