<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Monday, December 27, on the New York
Times wire. For questions, please call Greg Ambrose at 415-777-7219
or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business stories running
in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BIOSCOPE_  &LR; Suddenly, biotech is hot, so hot that investors are
bidding up shares of new offerings and private startups are queuing
up to go public while the IPO window is open. As recently as this
summer, when the Amex Biotech Stock Index languished around 200,
industry watchers fretted that Wall Street's fascination with
dot-anything would create a capital drought that would make biotech
extinct.
</P>
<P>
   But since November, that same index, which includes Immunex,
Biogen and Amgen, has climbed above 350. By TOM ABATE
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; TECH _  &LR; A century ago, even if some seer could have foreseen the
flowering of digital technology, there was little reason to predict
it would be centered here. Santa Clara County was then a lush
agricultural district known as the Valley of Heart's Delight, while
San Francisco's economy revolved around trade, finance and
shipbuilding.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, though, it's possible to trace the origins of high
tech in the Bay Area during the first half of the century. By HENRY
NORR
</P>
