<BODY>
<SLUG> BC---HISTORY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWTH OF A SILICON EMPIRE 

</HEADLINE>
  By HENRY NORR &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
A century ago, even if some seer could have foreseen the flowering
of digital technology, there was little reason to predict it would
be centered here. Santa Clara County was then a lush agricultural
district known as the Valley of Heart's Delight, while San
Francisco's economy revolved around trade, finance and
shipbuilding.
<P>
   In hindsight, though, it's possible to trace the origins of high
tech in the Bay Area during the first half of the century.
</P>
<P>
   One key contributor, undoubtedly, was Stanford University, which
opened in 1891. By all accounts, the institution's founders _
lawyer, merchant, governor, senator and railroad magnate Leland
Stanford, his influential wife, Jane Leland Stanford, and the
founding president they appointed, David Starr Jordan _
deliberately set out to build a college with a more practical bent
than the elite private universities back east.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, that meant that Stanford, from the start,
had a strong focus on the sciences and engineering. It also meant
that the university administration sought to encourage and build
ties with local industry, and it tended to recruit faculty who
shared those objectives.
</P>
<P>
   In 1909, for example, Jordan himself put up $500, and several
members of his faculty made additional investments, to help a
recent graduate named Cyril Elwell launch a wireless communications
company in Palo Alto. Under the name Federal Telegraph Co., it
quickly grew into the area's largest electronics business and
scored some significant advances in the development of radio.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's role in fostering the industry grew after 1927, when
Frederick Terman (son of Lewis Terman, the noted Stanford
psychologist and intelligence-test pioneer) began teaching radio
engineering there. He went on to become chairman of the electrical
engineering department, dean of engineering and, finally, provost
of the whole university. Throughout his almost 40-year career, one
of his chief preoccupations was encouraging and assisting local
electronics businesses _ and getting their help for the university
and his students.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, for example, when three alumni of the school _ the
brothers Sigurd and Russell Varian and junior faculty member
William Hansen _ began developing a new kind of microwave
transmitter and receiver called a klystron, the university gave
them free use of a lab plus $100 worth of materials per year, in
exchange for a 50 percent interest in their patents. (Russell
Varian had worked for a time in the San Francisco laboratory where
Philo T. Farnsworth was developing some of the key underpinnings
for an emerging technology called television.)
</P>
<P>
   The klystron became an important component in radar-detection
and guidance systems and later in electron-acceleration technology.
After World War II, the Varian brothers, together with other
Stanford researchers, set up Varian Associates, which became the
first tenant of what was then called the Stanford Industrial Park.
</P>
<P>
   Nuturing Entrepreneurs
</P>
<P>
   Though it wasn't obvious at the time, one of Terman's most
important achievements was encouraging two of his former students,
William R. Hewlett and David Packard, to build a business around
the audio oscillator they had developed. Terman even invested some
of his own money in the operation, which was launched in a Palo
Alto garage and incorporated on Jan. 1, 1939, as the
Hewlett-Packard Co.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to becoming the Bay Area's largest company, HP over
the last half century has trained thousands of engineers and
managers who went on to build other companies. And with the ``HP
Way'' _ a set of policies that include profit sharing, open doors
and ``management by wandering around'' _ it set the tone for the
future Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   By the outbreak of World War II, then, the foundations for the
eventual emergence of a major electronics industry here had been
laid. But it would be foolish to argue that the region's eventual
leadership was already cemented at that time. In the scale of its
industry and the sophistication of its research, the area still
lagged far behind main centers of the nation's electronics
industry, such as New Jersey and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Federal Telegraph had relocated most of its operations
to New Jersey in 1931, on the grounds that Palo Alto was too remote
from its key markets and sources of supplies and skilled labor _
precisely the obverse of the arguments that were to bring so many
technology companies to this area a few decades later.
</P>
<P>
   And while local electronics companies grew and prospered from
federal contracts during World War II, most of the government's
wartime funding for electronics research went elsewhere, especially
to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and its spin-offs.
Even Terman himself, to contribute to the war effort, went east,
assuming the position of director of the Radio Research Laboratory
at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to Stanford as dean of engineering in 1946, he
was very aware that he was going back to the minor leagues. As he
wrote at the time, ``Stanford emerged from World War II as an
underprivileged institution. It had not been significantly involved
in any of the exciting engineering and scientific activities
associated with the war.''
</P>
<P>
   To bring to this region the kind of dynamism that had so
impressed him about the Boston area, Terman redoubled his efforts
to foster and support local industry. The results included new
programs that allowed engineers at local companies to take graduate
courses at the campus, as well as the formation of the Stanford
Industrial (later Research) Park and the Stanford Research
Institute (later SRI International), founded in 1946 to do applied
and contract research.
</P>
<P>
   Terman's efforts produced some important results. In the 1950s
he persuaded Lockheed Aircraft to set up a lab in the industrial
park and then to move its Missiles and Space Division from Burbank
to Sunnyvale. In the era of the Cold War and the space race,
Lockheed was one of the area's largest high-tech employers. And
researchers at SRI generated a long series of breakthroughs in
computing and communications, including the invention of the mouse
and pioneering work in wireless networking.
</P>
<P>
   Another milestone was IBM's decision to set up a lab in the area
to develop new data-storage technologies. According to company
lore, it was originally planned for Palo Alto, but was finally
situated in San Jose's Almaden Valley because real estate in Palo
Alto was considered too expensive, even for a giant such as IBM!
</P>
<P>
   From the lab soon emerged the first hard drives and later the
floppy disk. Both through its own advances and through alumni such
as Al Shugart, who left the company to start Shugart Associates and
later Seagate Technologies, IBM's Almaden facility was a central
factor in establishing the Bay Area's continuing leadership in the
storage industry.
</P>
<P>
   All of these factors helped make the Bay Area an increasingly
important technology center, but it was still far from being the
center. Through the 1950s and '60s, that distinction belonged to
the Route 128 belt outside Boston, with its scores of spin-offs
from MIT and Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Fortuitous Homecoming
</P>
<P>
   If there's one event that can be said to have set the Bay Area
on course to overtake Boston, it was William Shockley's decision to
return to Palo Alto, his boyhood home, in 1956 and set up the
Shockley Semiconductor Laboratories there. In 1947, while working
at Bell Laboratories in New Jersey, Shockley and two associates had
invented the transistor, the tiny switching devices that are the
foundation of modern high tech.
</P>
<P>
   The achievement won Shockley and his colleagues the Nobel Prize
for Physics in 1956, but he didn't succeed in convincing
Massachusetts' leading electronics manufacturer, Raytheon, to
support him in commercializing the breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he won backing from Beckman Instruments, a Southern
California manufacturer of biomedical devices, to set up the Palo
Alto lab, for which he recruited a star-studded roster of young
engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Shockley's high-handed management style _ including lie-detector
tests _ alienated most of his team, however. Only a year later,
eight of them, including Shockley's favorite, Robert Noyce,
abruptly resigned. An infuriated Shockley denounced them as ``the
traitorous eight.''
</P>
<P>
   With help from Arthur Rock, then the local representative of an
East Coast investment company, the eight secured funding from the
Fairchild Camera and Instrument Co. of Connecticut and set up shop
_ first in Palo Alto, then in Mountain View _ as Fairchild
Semiconductor.
</P>
<P>
   Under Fairchild's auspices, Noyce in 1959 developed what is
generally considered the first commercially practical integrated
circuit, a single chip containing multiple transistors and other
devices. (Jack S. Kilby of Texas Instruments in Dallas had produced
a different kind of integrated circuit the year before; most
consider him and Noyce co-inventors of the technology.)
</P>
<P>
   Fairchild Semiconductor went on to become an important defense
contractor, but it never lived up to the hopes of its founders _ in
part, it is said, because its remote parent company never really
understood the business. But in several ways, the company played a
critical role in the creation of Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   First, its unofficial corporate culture was reportedly marked by
the freewheeling exchange of ideas, enthusiasm about technology's
potential and a tolerance for failure that was unheard of in most
of corporate America _ all hallmarks of the distinct culture that
eventually became identified with the valley.
</P>
<P>
   Second, restless Fairchild employees _ including the original
eight, all of whom had left by 1968, and scores of talented young
engineers they hired, trained and inspired _ went on to establish
dozens of other companies. These pioneers _ sometimes known as
``the Fairchildren'' _ carried with them not only cutting-edge
semiconductor technology, but also the company's distinct culture.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Intel Enters the Valley
</P>
<P>
   The most important of these Fairchild-spawned startups was
Intel, founded by Noyce and Gordon Moore in 1968. Even before the
fledgling company had a written business plan, Arthur Rock raised
$5 million for it in 30 minutes on the phone _ an episode that
lives on in Silicon Valley legend, even though larger deals now
occur almost hourly.
</P>
<P>
   Noyce and Moore, soon joined by the young Andrew Grove,
originally built their business around the manufacture of
semiconductor memory chips, a faster and cheaper alternative to the
cumbersome magnetic ``core memory'' technology then prevalent in
the growing mainframe computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Intel was primarily a memory-maker until the mid-1980s,
when it was forced to abandon the business and slash employment
after Japanese manufacturers entered the market with more efficient
production techniques and aggressive pricing strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Happily for Intel, by then it had another fast-growing business:
building microprocessors, the programmable central processing chips
used in personal computers. IBM had selected one Intel
microprocessor model, the 8088, to power the original IBM PC. IBM's
design, copied by scores of clone manufacturers, quickly
established itself as the standard for business computing, and
Intel was soon selling tens of millions of microprocessors every
year.
</P>
<P>
   PARC Place
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, researchers elsewhere in the area were gradually
working out other elements of the computer as we know it.
Pre-eminent among them was Douglas Engelbart, a former Ames
employee then working at the Stanford Research Institute. In a 1968
conference in San Francisco, Engelbart staged a legendary
demonstration (later called ``the mother of all demos'') of several
of his inventions: not only the first mouse, but also the first
display capable of combining text, graphics and video, and even
early implementations of what we now call hypertext and video
conferencing.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these ideas were taken up at Xerox's Palo Alto Research
Center (PARC), a technology think tank set up in 1970. Over the
next 15 years, PARC employees generated a portfolio of innovations
probably unmatched in the history of technology by any other single
research center (with the possible exception of Thomas Edison's
labs in that other Menlo Park).
</P>
<P>
   Among PARC's achievements were such mainstays of modern
computing as the point-and-click graphical user interface (later
popularized by Apple's Macintosh and then Microsoft Windows),
Ethernet local-area networking, object-oriented programming
techniques, the laser printer and the PostScript imaging language.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox's failure to capitalize on PARC's innovations earned it a
permanent place in the business hall of shame, but countless other
local companies, including Apple, Adobe Systems and 3Com continue
to profit from its work.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1970s, Silicon Valley had evolved into an
extraordinary center of high-tech innovation, but it still wasn't
the leader in the growing computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   In that era, the cutting edge of computing was the minicomputer,
a refrigerator-size unit that generally cost in the tens of
thousands of dollars, low enough so universities and businesses
that couldn't afford a mainframe could acquire them. And virtually
all of the top minicomputer-makers _ Digital Equipment, Data
General, Prime, Wang and others _ were located in the Boston
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   In those years, Route 128 and the prosperity its high-tech
companies generated (known then as ``the Massachusetts miracle'')
were almost as celebrated as Silicon Valley is today.
</P>
<P>
   By 1985, however, Massachusetts' high-tech industry was in a
severe decline, while Silicon Valley continued to flourish _ even
after the Japanese takeover of the RAM market pushed this area's
semiconductor industry into crisis.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, this reversal of fortunes can be explained by
epochal changes in the evolution of computing technology _
specifically, the rise of the workstation (powerful desktop
machines used mainly by engineers and scientists) and of the
personal computer, and the corresponding decline of the
minicomputer.
</P>
<P>
   Although some East Coast companies became players in the
workstation market, the emerging industry was dominated by Bay Area
businesses: HP, Sun Microsystems (established in 1982 to market
machines based on a design by Stanford graduate student Andreas
Bechtolsheim, which he called ``SUN'' for ``Stanford University
Network'') and Silicon Graphics (also founded in 1982, to
commercialize a graphics processing chip developed by Jim Clark,
then a Stanford professor).
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area also played a central role in the emergence of the
personal computer. The Homebrew Computer Club, a pioneering group
of personal-computing enthusiasts, began meeting in a Menlo Park
garage in 1975. Within months, its monthly sessions were drawing
overflow crowds from all over the region, and it had to relocate to
a large auditorium at the Stanford Linear Acceleration Center.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the club's meetings were marked by the selfless
sharing of ideas and innovations (and software), a countercultural
opposition to the old order of computing (where ``high priests'' in
the ``glass houses'' where mainframes and minis were located
controlled access and limited innovation) and a determination
(influenced in part by New Left ideas prevalent on campus then) to
use technology to build new forms of community and democracy.
</P>
<P>
   While many important pioneers in the personal computer market
sprang up in the Bay Area _ including IMSAI of San Leandro, North
Star of Berkeley and later Hayward's Osborne Computers _ nearly all
of them have long since been forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Only Apple, founded on April Fool's Day 1976 by Homebrew members
Steve Jobs and Steve Wozniak, survived to become a major player
when the personal computer entered the mainstream in the 1980s.
Though its history has been tumultuous, the company has retained a
loyal following and remained an important source of innovation,
especially in making technology easier to use.
</P>
<P>
   With the emergence of the IBM PC in 1981 and the ``IBM clone''
market in subsequent years, production and distribution of the
standardized machines came to be concentrated in areas where costs
were lower, such as Texas, North Carolina and even North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many Bay Area companies benefited handsomely from the PC
revolution. Intel, of course, made most of the microprocessors that
powered the new machines, while Advanced Micro Devices carved out a
smaller role as a second source of x86-compatible chips. The area's
smaller semiconductor-makers cranked out graphics processors,
peripheral controllers and the slew of other chips required to
build a fully functional PC.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-drive manufacturers such as Seagate, Conner Peripherals,
Quantum, Maxtor and even IBM battled ferociously _ often at the
expense of profits _ to increase storage capacity and market share.
While HP, with its focus on more-powerful business systems, stayed
out of the PC market itself in the early years, its introduction of
both inkjet and laser printers in 1984 gave it a commanding lead in
the lucrative printer and printer-supply market. (In the 1990s HP
made itself a leader in PC sales, too.)
</P>
<P>
   And during the past 15 years, with the emergence of local-area
networking, followed by the Internet and voice-data integration,
Cisco Systems, 3Com and other local networking companies have
joined the ranks of the giants.
</P>
<P>
   Networking for Success
</P>
<P>
   While the Bay Area's rise to undisputed pre-eminence in high
tech coincided with the rise of the PC and the workstation and the
decline of the mini, hardware evolution alone doesn't explain the
shift in power from Massachusetts to Northern California; it merely
begs the question of why the Bay Area was able to adapt so quickly
and successfully to the new technologies, while the Bay State was
not.
</P>
<P>
   That question is confronted directly in an influential book
called ``Regional Advantage: Culture and Competition in Silicon
Valley and Route 128'' by AnnaLee Saxenian, a Massachusetts native
who now teaches at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Saxenian undertook the study in the 1980s, she said in an
interview, to try to understand why events had disproved the dire
predictions she made about Silicon Valley in a late 1970s master's
thesis. Saxenian had predicted that high costs and inadequate
infrastructure would soon bring the area's growth to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   The answer she came up with, now widely accepted among other
authorities, is that the Bay Area had evolved a unique culture and
economic framework, one that gave it an unmatched ability to adapt
to and profit from fast-changing technologies.
</P>
<P>
   In that model, which she called a ``regional network-based
industrial system,'' technology leaders forgo the traditional goal
of vertical integration _ producing as many of their own components
as possible _ in favor of relying on a dense network of specialist
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Associated with that industrial model are such attributes as
open labor markets, marked by frequent job hopping; relatively
unimpeded exchange of ideas and techniques, through both formal
organizations and informal personal ties, even across company
lines; flattened corporate structures, with decision making largely
in the hands of individual product teams and engineering groups;
and a strong focus on innovation and risk taking and a concomitant
tolerance of failure.
</P>
<P>
   And all of it depends on an infrastructure of educational
institutions, technology consultants, contract manufacturers, law
firms, venture capitalists and even public-relations specialists
that consider their fortunes tied up not with any one company, but
with the economy of the valley as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   It's this dynamic, self-reinforcing model, Saxenian argues, that
really explains the Bay Area's emergence over the past quarter
century as the undisputed leader of the high-tech revolution. It
explains why ambitious entrepreneurs and engineers keep pouring
into the region, and why so many firms with roots elsewhere feel
compelled to establish branches here, in spite of the area's
astonishing costs and jammed highways.
</P>
<P>
   And it explains why the region's high-tech economy has been so
resilient in the wake of setbacks like the collapse of the memory
market in the 1980s and so quick to capitalize on new technologies
and new opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this model and the associated culture, Saxenian argues,
have enabled Silicon Valley to extend its leadership to a steady
stream of derivative markets _ multimedia, gaming and personal
digital assistants, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, it explains why Silicon Valley has led the Internet
explosion of the 1990s, an economic revolution whose significance
extends far beyond the area's traditional silicon, hardware and
software industries. Indeed, Saxenian notes, ``dot-com'' startups
are overwhelmingly concentrated here, even though they could by
definition locate themselves anywhere, and in most cases they have
no direct dependence on the valley's older high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
