<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-TITANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCNAIR AIRS IT OUT AS TITANS ROUT JAGUARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ The Tennessee Titans had won 11 games in a variety
of ways. They had won with ruthless running from Eddie George. They
had breezed to victory by unleashing the rookie Pro Bowl end Jevon
Kearse. The snappy cornerback Samari Rolle had produced
game-winning plays. They had won with sparkling special teams.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   What about Steve McNair?
</P>
<P>
   Critics called him the Titans' weak link, a runner more than a
passer. They wanted Neil O'Donnell, who replaced an injured McNair
for five starts early in the season, to become the permanent
starter. Entering Sunday's clash with the Jacksonville Jaguars,
O'Donnell in 172 passes had tossed eight touchdowns. McNair in 287
passes had tossed six.
</P>
<P>
   McNair had heard enough. So had the Titans' coaches.
</P>
<P>
   McNair took a game plan designed to feature his arm and whipped
the ball around Adelphia Coliseum with extra style and amazing
punch Sunday. He threw five touchdown passes _ of 4, 62, 2, 65 and
13 yards _ electrified the crowd of 66,641 and mystified the
Jaguars in a 41-14 victory over what had been a glowing bunch that
owned the National Football League's best record. A team that had
lost only one game.
</P>
<P>
   That one, too, was to Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Now Tennessee (12-3) can topple Jacksonville (13-2) in the chase
for the American Football Conference Central title if it finishes
the regular season next week with a victory at Pittsburgh and
Jacksonville loses at home to Cincinnati. Tennessee can win the
home-field advantage throughout the AFC playoffs if it wins and
both Jacksonville and Indianapolis lose next week.
</P>
<P>
   With Sunday's victory, Tennessee insured it would be the host of
at least one playoff game and finished unbeaten at home (8-0) for
the first time in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   McNair completed 23 of 33 passes for 291 yards, did not throw an
interception and connected with eight receivers. Each of his
scoring tosses was to a different receiver. He left the game late
in the third quarter proud and pleased.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacksonville quarterback Mark Brunell exited before
halftime, having sprained his left knee. The Jaguars expect him to
miss some practice and maybe even the finale against Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you bring the heat on me, the more I want to respond,''
McNair said. ``Of course, I felt the pressure and the talk. But
people don't realize the style of ball we play. We can win a lot of
different ways and, all year, we have. Today we decided to pass the
ball first. I decided to do something with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville had won 11 straight games, its last loss having
been to Tennessee in Jacksonville on Sept. 26, by 20-19. This one
was much uglier for the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat us to the punch; they answered the bell,'' Jaguars
offensive tackle Tony Boselli said. ``They blew us out. Any time
you get whipped like that, it's embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars safety Carnell Lake said: ``They threw us off balance.
We have lost twice to these guys, so we've got to really take a
look at this and figure out what is going on, hopefully make some
changes and compete.''
</P>
<P>
   And Tom Coughlin, the Jaguars' coach, said: ``I don't have any
great explanations for this. One team came to play and one team
didn't. Once it started to slip, it looked like it was not the type
of effort we are accustomed to getting. I take my hat off to
Tennessee. They played extremely well. They controlled the game
from the outset. They were never in doubt, never challenged, and
I'm very disappointed in that. It concerns me greatly.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee began the game with a drive from its 22. Thirteen
plays and nearly eight minutes later the Titans had scored when
McNair rolled right and passed 4 yards to tight end Michael Roan.
</P>
<P>
   The rout was on. An extraordinary McNair passing display was in
gear.
</P>
<P>
   And there was help everywhere. George rushed for 102 yards.
Tight end Frank Wycheck caught a team-high nine passes. Rolle
intercepted three passes. The Titans limited Jacksonville to 65
rushing yards and running back Fred Taylor to 44, and won in first
downs, 26-16, and in total yards, 476-237. The Titans gained four
sacks, but neither McNair nor O'Donnell, who finished the game
while McNair was rested, was sacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve has had a lot of heat on him since Day 1,'' Titans
cornerback Anthony Dorsett said. ``People need to realize that
Steve is the quarterback of this team. He doesn't have to throw
touchdown passes for us to win. We have a team that tries to win
the way the coaches ask us to play, whether it is in the running
game first or special teams or whatever. We've beaten the Rams and
we've beaten Jacksonville twice. They are supposed to be two of the
top teams. What more at this point could you want?''
</P>
<P>
   George said he recognized McNair's determination from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was quiet, focused _ he looked ticked off,'' George said.
``He just came out today and showed off. We're breaking out of that
mold of being a one-dimensional team. We've established something.
We've proved something.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair's nickname is Air McNair. Some began calling him Dare
McNair. Play the run. Make McNair pass. Watch the mistakes, the
lack of production. But Sunday McNair shredded that concept _ and
the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve does what we ask him to do,'' said Jeff Fisher, the
Titans' coach. ``He can run for 62 yards and score. He can throw
for 62 and score. Today we asked him to throw it and he did, with
style against a really good football team. We've got some things
going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
