<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9393 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC---COLUMN-SFCHRON &LR;      12-26 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC---COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   SURGE COULD SEND PROSPECTORS SEARCHING FOR MOTHER LODE &HT;    By TOM ABATE
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Suddenly, biotech is hot, so hot that investors are bidding up
shares of new offerings and private startups are queuing up to go
public while the IPO window is open.
<P>
   As recently as this summer, when the Amex Biotech Stock Index
languished around 200, industry watchers fretted that Wall Street's
fascination with dot-anything would create a capital drought that
would make biotech extinct.
</P>
<P>
   But since November, that same index, which includes Immunex,
Biogen and Amgen, has climbed above 350.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the phenomenal reception of December IPOs like Maxygen,
a Redwood City firm with a technique for making stronger vaccines
and enzymes by swapping parts between genes, and Caliper
Technologies, a Mountain View company that makes chips to automate
lab tests.
</P>
<P>
   Maxygen stock is up 300 percent since its launch, while Caliper
is up 200 percent. Three other firms are on the verge of going
public, including Diversa, a San Diego firm with a gene-shuffling
story similar to Maxygen's.
</P>
<P>
   Expect a flood of other offerings around the time the investing
community gathers in San Francisco for the Hambrecht &AMP; Quist _
oops, make that the Chase H&AMP;Q _ life sciences conference in early
January.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent edition of the San Carlos' BioCentury newsletter
listed 23 private firms with the venture backing and ambition to go
public soon. The list included Aclara Biosciences in Mountain View,
which has a lab-on-a-chip story nearly identical to Caliper's.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco biotech banker Steve Burrill said the
fastest-moving biotech issues are those that fall into the
tool-making or genomics category. Caliper, for instance, sells
chips that make for faster lab experiments. If biomedical research
is the equivalent of a Gold Rush, Caliper is among a class of
companies selling picks, pans and shovels.
</P>
<P>
   Genomics companies sell prospectors (i.e., big drug and biotech
firms) maps of the human genome that disclose the most promising
places to dig for the cures to a variety of diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Burrill said Wall Street is bidding up the stocks of genomics
companies, such as Incyte Pharmaceuticals of Palo Alto, Human
Genome Sciences of Maryland and Millennium Pharmaceuticals of
Massachusetts, on the theory that gene maps will lead to pay dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a massive increase in valuations for all the
companies that are perceived as making drug discovery more
efficient,'' Burrill said.
</P>
<P>
   While I was in the Boston area a few weeks ago, I heard
Millennium CEO Mark Levin, a veteran of several Bay Area biotech
firms starting with Genentech, give his spiel for the value of
genomics.
</P>
<P>
   Levin crossed his hands in the air to make an ``X.'' The rising
slope indicated the amounts _ starting at $20 billion in 1988 and
passing $35 billion in 1998 _ that drug and biotech firms worldwide
were spending to discover new remedies.
</P>
<P>
   The falling slope represented the fact that, in the same 10-year
period, the number of novel drug candidates being discovered had
actually fallen _ from 60 per year in 1988 to under 25 by the end
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by Millennium's stock price, Wall Street has bought
Levin's argument that companies like his, which use genome maps to
focus their discovery efforts, will eventually prove to be the
luckiest bets.
</P>
<P>
   So there seems to be no arguing that, for the near term, the
sheen is back on biotech, especially the segment of the industry
that can tell a persuasive tool-kit or genomics story.
</P>
<P>
   But having been one of the Chicken Little pundits who wrote,
accurately enough at the time, that the sky was falling on biotech
earlier this year, I am hesitant to proclaim that happy days are
here again, because happy days don't necessarily last many
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a small investor who hasn't invested in biotech
before, chances are if you jump in now, you'll get stung when the
air comes out of some of these stocks. It's not that the tool-kit
and genomics theories are wrong; it's just that drug discovery is a
five- to 10-year process, and over that long a period, the stock
charts of most of these firms look like mountain ranges.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're willing to do a lot of homework on a complex
industry, there's little doubt that the demographics favor this
industry. Over the long term, aging Baby Boomers will be the drug
industry's salvation.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to make a New Year's resolution, determine to bone
up on your biology, and use your common sense, and we'll have some
fun next year panning for some golden opportunities amid the
glitter of all that iron pyrLTp/;H8n
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
