<HEADLINE>
HORRY REDISCOVERS SHOOTING TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson has made it clear that, on a team with
Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and Glen Rice, there isn't much need
for a lot of scoring from the Lakers' power forwards.
</P>
<P>
   That said, he's been perplexed by Robert Horry's penchant for
passing up wide-open jumpers. ``He's a much better offensive player
than he's (shown),'' Jackson said last week. ``I think he's kind of
lost his lust for scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider that lust renewed.
</P>
<P>
   Horry turned in his best offensive game of the season Saturday,
playing a key role in the Lakers' victory over the San Antonio
Spurs. Horry converted 4 of 6 field-goal attempts and made all four
of his free throws for a season-high 12 points off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Jackson) has been really harping on me to shoot the ball when
I'm open,'' Horry said. ``They've been kind of saying it on the sly
in practice -- they've been saying, `It's OK, shoot that shot,
you're open, shoot it.' Now that I know I've got their permission,
it's a lot easier to shoot the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   A career 34 percent 3-point shooter, Horry has attempted just 14
this season, despite ample opportunities. A scorer in his early
years, Horry was averaging just 3.9 field-goal attempts and 4.0
points per game entering Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the best threesome out there scoring and we've been
winning,'' Horry said, ``so if it ain't broke, don't fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he's focused on the little things that have made him an
asset off the bench. On Saturday, he netted five rebounds, two
steals, a blocked shot and an assist in 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert had another real good game,'' Jackson said, ``and he
had points to go with it, too. I thought it was important for us.''
</P>
<P>
   If Horry continues to hit the open jumpers, it will be that much
more difficult for opposing defenses to sag off him to double-team
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it comes to me, I'm going to take it,'' he said. ``Other
than that, I'm not going to go out there and look for my shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Wild, but good: Bryant's 18-point effort Saturday had its rough
spots, particularly in a 2-for-7 first half and in several
ill-advised forays into the paint, into the arms of Tim Duncan and
David Robinson. But Jackson, who has been critical at times of
Bryant's decision-making, liked most of what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not at all disappointed, I'm almost gratified at some
times that he is as impetuous as he is at times,'' Jackson said.
``He's such a mature kid, and to show some immaturity out there on
the basketball court is I don't think unusual or out of character
for a kid his age (21).''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: To make room for Travis Knight on the roster
Saturday, the Lakers sent rookie guard John Celestand to the
injured list for the second time this season, with a case of knee
tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   Celestand played sparingly in the month he was active, playing
in 12 games, averaging 2.1 points in 10.2 minutes. But he's likely
to get another opportunity later this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing really well,'' Jackson said. ``John's improved, I
think, dramatically since training camp and has come along really
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
