<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A WHITEWASH IN ALBANY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Justice in the Diallo case?
</P>
<P>
   Don't bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know the real reason the case was yanked out of
the Bronx and shipped 150 miles north to Albany, N.Y, consider
these facts. Of the criminal defendants who go to trial in Albany
County, 90 percent are convicted. But when the criminal defendants
who go to trial are police officers, approximately 100 percent are
acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   The cops who killed Amadou Diallo could not have found a
friendlier place than Albany if they had been allowed to pick the
venue themselves. And forget the self-serving garbage from the
Appellate Division judges about their attempt to find a locale with
a ``reasonable degree of ethnic diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   The reality is this: An all-white panel of five judges, one of
whom is a crony of the lawyer for one of the accused cops, took the
case out of the Bronx (and out of the hands of a black judge) and
sent it to a place where  &UR; all  &LR; the judges and nearly all of the
potential jurors are white.
</P>
<P>
   The judges knew what they were doing and they did it well. They
went out of their way to give the accused their best chance of an
acquittal, and to deliberately exclude blacks from participation in
a case that is of profound interest to black New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Lewis B. Oliver Jr., who has practiced law in Albany
County for many years, if he could recall a single case in which a
police officer went to trial and was convicted. There was a long,
long pause. I waited. Finally, Oliver, who is white, said, ``No,
but I'm not an encyclopedic source on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last March a jury in Albany acquitted two cops who were accused
of assaulting a college student named Jermaine Henderson. According
to the indictment, the cops took Henderson into a police garage
and, while he was handcuffed, severely beat and kicked him. The
courtroom was jammed with police officers during the trial, and the
accused cops were cheered when the verdict came in.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Grace of The Albany Times Union covered the trial. She
wrote: ``All members of the jury, like the police officers, are
white. Henderson is black.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the venue into which the Diallo case has been moved.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Jack Lester, a lawyer in Manhattan who previously
practiced in Albany, how difficult he thought it would be to get a
conviction against a cop on trial in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Difficult is the wrong word,'' he said. ``The word should be
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I'm not saying the Diallo police officers should be
convicted. From what I heard, the officers at the scene who fired
the shots were very remorseful about what happened. But in Albany,
it's a guaranteed acquittal.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem here is not that the Diallo case was taken out of
the Bronx. A change of venue might well have been appropriate. And
wherever these four officers were tried, it is likely they would
not be convicted of murder. I have called the killing of Diallo
cold-blooded, reckless and wrong. But I don't believe that under
the law it rises to the level of murder.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the five Appellate Division judges who
ordered the change of venue went out of their way to shift the case
to an almost lily-white comfort zone for the officers. The judges
stomped all over the appearance of fairness when they deliberately
placed the case out of the reach of black New Yorkers, who the
judges seem to feel are by reason of their color incapable of
considering the evidence in the case and rendering a fair verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of the fact that 9 percent of the nearly
300,000 residents of Albany County are black. But that percentage
of the population is not reflected in the pool of potential jurors.
Only a tiny percentage of the men and women available to serve as
jurors are black _ and the judges of the Appellate Division know
that as well as anyone in the state.
</P>
<P>
   If they wanted to move the trial out of the Bronx, fine. But
don't tell me these cops couldn't get a fair trial in an integrated
venue in another part of the city, or in Westchester or Nassau.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Kindlon is a longtime Albany lawyer who agreed with the
appellate court's decision and believes the officers will get a
fair trial in Albany. But he sounded as if he was speaking more
from faith than experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are any black jurors, it's going to be surprising to
me,'' he said. And he acknowledged, ``In the cases here in which
officers have been accused, they've generally been acquitted.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, then added, ``Almost always been acquitted.'' (BOX)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
