<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-GROZNY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA SAYS TROOPS HAVE ADVANCED INTO GROZNY?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian forces have advanced deep into the Chechen
capital of Grozny in a major offensive to take the city and deal
separatist rebels a decisive blow, the government said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian units reportedly were close to the city center and
conducting house-to-house searches for rebel fighters in parts of
the capital. A pro-Russian Chechen commander promised to raise the
Russian flag over Grozny before the new year.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging in the balance was the fate of up to 42,000 civilians
trapped in Grozny without heat, electricity, or running water.
Russia had been encouraging them to leave via several ``safe
corridors'' the army claimed to have set up, but on Friday Moscow's
envoy to Chechnya said civilians should wait in their basement
shelters for Russian troops to liberate them.
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces announced their offensive Saturday, as special
forces troops and pro-Moscow Chechen militia entered the city on
four sides, supported by heavy artillery fire.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel fighters trying to leave the embattled city had been
stopped with ``a barrage of fire,'' according to a statement by
Russia's defense ministry reported by Russian news agencies. The
military made no mention of what was happening to civilians who try
to escape the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, talks between Russian and Chechen representatives on the
fate of civilians produced no workable plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a few days, there will be nobody to evacuate,'' Interfax
quoted a Chechen military commander, Isa Munayev.
</P>
<P>
   Capturing the city would provide a powerful moral victory for
the Russian military, which was humiliated and battered in a
1994-96 campaign against the Chechen separatists. Russian Prime
Minister Vladimir Putin hopes to parlay his leadership of the
current campaign in Chechnya into a win in the presidential
election in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   But the senior Russian commander in Chechnya played down the
scale and pace of the battle for Grozny, in an apparent attempt to
avoid comparisons with their disastrous attempt to take the city by
storm five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing terrible is happening in Grozny, it is just a
continuation of the operation for liberating the city of bandits,''
General Victor Kazantsev told Russian news agencies, using Moscow's
term for the separatists. Kazantsev added that the ``most
important'' part of the operation is ``to save lives of civilians
and soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Those remarks captured the methodical approach Kazantsev has
sought to portray throughout the three-month campaign in Chechnya.
While the Russian onslaught has often seemed heavy-handed and
indiscriminate, the tactic of pounding rebel-held areas into
submission has allowed the army to occupy much of Chechnya while
claiming to have suffered minimal casualties.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Sunday how easy the victory in Grozny will be.
The rebels say they can hold out for months in Grozny's vast
network of underground passages and Soviet-era bombshelters.
</P>
<P>
   For civilians in Grozny the situation is dire. Most appear to be
elderly people with nowhere to go, or no way to leave the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sick of this _ since the first war we have been
suffering and we are still suffering to this day,'' said one
elderly Chechen woman in footage from the city shown on Russian NTV
television.
</P>
<P>
   The footage showed devastated and nearly abandoned streets and
confident, well-armed rebel fighters who move about at night with
impunity.
</P>
<P>
   A pro-Moscow Chechen leader, Beslan Gantamirov, Sunday claimed
that his force of 800 fighters had reached a strategic square just
outside Grozny's center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are conducting a cleanup of the city, checking all homes
and basements where rebels could hide,'' Gantamirov, a convicted
embezzler who was released from prison to lead the loyalist army,
told Interfax. The agency said Gantamirov had promised to raise the
Russian flag over Grozny ``in the next few days, before the new
year.''
</P>
<P>
   But a prominent rebel commander, Shamil Basayev, dismissed
Gantamirov's force.
</P>
<P>
   ``His fighters are all criminals like him. They are not fighting
for ideals, they are only fighting for money,'' the Associated
Press quoted Basayev Sunday from one of his basement hideouts in
Grozny. ``I will fight the Russian Army or anybody sent in by the
Russians, even Chechens.''
</P>
<P>
   Basayev also brushed off the prospect of peace talks: ``With
Russians it's impossible to make a deal; only fighting works.''
</P>
<P>
   Basayev led an incursion into the Russian region of Dagestan in
August. That prompted Russia to send a 100,000-strong force into
Chechnya. The Kremlin also blames the rebels for a series of deadly
apartment bombings in September, a charge Basayev has denied.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they give up Grozny, the rebel fighters say they can
retreat to the mountain gorges in southern Chechnya, although
Russia has been bombing and mining the gorges for months.
</P>
<P>
   Large groups of refugees from mountainous villages were moving
along the Argun Gorge to the northern lowlands to escape the
bombings, the office of Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov said
Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
