<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY CAMPAIGN INFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEADQUARTERS: West Orange, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   STAFF SIZE: 150 full-time workers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN CHAIRMAN: Douglas C. Berman.
</P>
<P>
   CASH ON HAND: The campaign refuses to release an estimate.
</P>
<P>
   PROMINENT ADVISERS: Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger on
foreign policy; Paul Volcker, former chairman of the Federal
Reserve, on economics; David M. Cutler, professor of economics at
Harvard University, on health care; Robert Reich, former secretary
of labor, on social policy.
</P>
<P>
   BIGGEST COUPS SO FAR: Getting positive national attention for
the kickoff of his campaign in September; staging a well-covered
event on campaign finance reform with Sen. John McCain of Arizona,
a Republican candidate, in December.
</P>
<P>
   BIGGEST MISTAKES SO FAR: Responding slowly to Vice President Al
Gore's attacks on his health care plan.
</P>
<P>
   CHALLENGES AHEAD: Matching Gore's national organization;
translating his folksy campaign style to television.
</P>
