<DOCNO> NYT19991226.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-NY-GAS-PIPELINES-5     12-26 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-NY-GAS-PIPELINES-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRICT NEW RULES MUDDY PLANS FOR GAS PIPELINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ Freed by deregulation and the demise of
utility monopolies, pipeline companies are seeking to build two
major new lines to open the New York-New Jersey market to vast
reserves of natural gas from western Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the pipelines will enable more independent
gas-marketing companies to enter the market, encourage competition
and cost cutting, and lead to lower gas bills for homeowners,
offices and industries.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the fate of the two big proposed projects and their
impact on deregulated sales in the metropolitan region are
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   One of the proposed projects would stretch from a major
natural-gas hub in Chicago through Indiana, Ohio, Pennsylvania and
into New Jersey, cutting through 33 New Jersey towns in 10
counties.
</P>
<P>
   The other would link the Chicago hub to New York state and run
from Canada under Lake Erie and then east along New York's Southern
Tier, through Orange, Rockland and Westchester counties, ending in
Mount Vernon and Yonkers.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline companies proposing both want them built and
operating by next November to coincide with the completion of a
pipeline that will bring 1.3 billion cubic feet of gas a day from
the Canadian Rockies to the Chicago hub. Each of the proposed lines
is intended to carry about half that volume _ 700 million cubic
feet a day _ to markets in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   But completion dates of late next year seem too ambitious now.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 15, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, which
grants permits for new pipelines, imposed stiff environmental and
marketing conditions on the proposed Chicago-to-New-Jersey line.
Elated opponents of the line predicted that the new requirements
would delay construction and possibly doom the project.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed line ending in Westchester County is not as far
along in the review process. The regulatory commission is still
preparing a final environmental-impact statement on the project. It
is unclear when the agency will schedule a vote on a construction
permit for it.
</P>
<P>
   The political climate surrounding each line is sharply
different. Opposition is deep in New Jersey. An unusual bipartisan
coalition has denounced the Chicago-to-New-Jersey project, calling
it speculative and unnecessary, a risk to public safety and a
threat to preserved open spaces and sensitive wetlands that the
pipeline would cross.
</P>
<P>
   Foes include Gov. Christie Whitman; both New Jersey senators,
Frank Lautenberg and Robert Torricelli; the state's congressional
delegation; the state Legislature; and the hundreds of local
officials and residents in the 33 towns.
</P>
<P>
   New York's political and government hierarchy has been far less
strident about the proposed pipe between Lake Erie and Westchester.
Landowners and residents along its route, particularly in Orange
and Rockland counties, oppose it on safety and environmental
grounds, including the proposed line's proximity to the
earthquake-prone Ramapo fault.
</P>
<P>
   But the local complaints have not inspired any broad-based
criticism. Unlike Whitman in New Jersey, Gov. George Pataki has
been silent on the project.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The regulatory agency in each state that oversees utilities and
deregulated sales of natural gas also views the respective projects
differently. The New Jersey Board of Public Utilities says the
state does not currently need any of the new gas from the proposed
Chicago-to-New-Jersey line. Deregulation of all residential natural
gas will begin in New Jersey on Jan. 1. But a board spokesman, Eric
Hartsfeld, said that existing supplies were expected to be
sufficient for the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's gas-deregulation law requires an open and
competitive market providing users with a choice of gas merchants.
But the law does not require a cut in gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board hopes introducing competition will lower rates,''
Hartsfeld said. ``But no one can guarantee anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The board's regulatory counterpart in New York, the Public
Service Commission, says new gas pipelines are needed for growth in
demand in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   David Flanagan, a commission spokesman, said the agency had not
taken a position favoring one proposed line over the other. But in
the next decade, Flanagan said, existing pipelines will not have
enough space to carry the extra gas needed for increased demand,
for conversion of homes from oil to gas furnaces, and for several
new gas-fired electrical generating stations.
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan declined to comment on the possibility that the
Chicago-to-New-Jersey line would never be built and the effect that
could have on deregulation in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago-to-New-Jersey project is proposed by the New York
region's biggest single gas supplier, Transcontinental Gas Pipe
Line Corp., of Houston, along with ANR Pipeline Co., of Detroit,
and a subsidiary they have formed called Independence Pipeline Co.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed line across New York state, called the Millennium
Pipeline, is a joint venture of Columbia Gas Transmission Corp., of
Charleston, W.Va., and companies building the big trans-Canada
pipeline from the Canadian Rockies to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago-to-New-Jersey line ran afoul of the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission on Dec. 15 on marketing and environmental
issues. Against the backdrop of New Jersey's chorus of complaint
about the lack of a proven market, the commission criticized
Transco and ANR for not having enough customers for the line's
sections in Ohio and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the transmission space on the line was bought by a
subsidiary of the companies. The commission said it would not allow
construction until companies that are not affiliated with Transco
and ANR sign binding contracts for half the transmission space.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental restrictions the commission imposed included a $3
million bond to pay for any damage during construction and a ban on
the building of any piece of the line until all state permits are
issued for the entire project. Previously, the commission permitted
piecemeal construction once permits for different segments were
obtained.
</P>
<P>
   Foes predicted that the edict on permits would delay
construction for months. Cuba Wadlington Jr., chief operating
officer of Transco, denounced the condition as unprecedented. But
he said Transco would press ahead with the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
