u s BC-FBN-COLUMN-NYT     12-26 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTEAD (INJURED) AND STRAHAN (DOUBLE-TEAMED) FLOUNDER AGAINST
VIKES
</HEADLINE>
  (With FBN-GIANTS-VIKINGS) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J _ This week a teammate of the Giants'
Jessie Armstead watched as the Pro Bowl linebacker tried to bend
his right knee. As Armstead winced, struggling to flex it several
inches, the player said he heard a crackling noise. At first he
thought Armstead had stepped on something. Then he realized it was
Armstead's knee, which sounded like a breakfast cereal just after
the milk was poured.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't be playing,'' he told Armstead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't afford not to,'' Armstead replied.
</P>
<P>
   This is what fighters do. A champion like Armstead will play
unless he can't walk. But there is a cold reality to the National
Football League. When a team smells blood, it attacks. The
Minnesota Vikings noticed on film that against St. Louis last week,
Armstead was sluggish, able to perform at only a fraction of his
ability, because of that knee. So they decided to go after Armstead
on Sunday, and at times, he was barely able to move across the
field.
</P>
<P>
   In a game the Giants needed, Armstead played but had a modest
impact, making six tackles. Michael Strahan, one of the
hardest-working players in the game, was also not a major factor
for the Giants, with two tackles and no sacks. The lack of
production from the team's two Pro Bowl stars is the main reason
Minnesota racked up 174 yards on the ground and the Giants lost
34-17.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants may still be mathematically alive for a playoff
berth. And they may even get in. But they could easily lose to
Dallas in the final game of the regular season, too, and be knocked
out. This is a team that one week dominates Buffalo on the road,
then gets beaten easily by Minnesota at home. The Giants are hard
to figure.
</P>
<P>
   Even more difficult to understand is this: In the biggest game
of the season for the team, one in which it had to win to control
its postseason destiny, where were its two stars, Armstead and
Strahan?
</P>
<P>
   It is too simplistic to say merely that both players played
terribly. Football is much more complicated than that. Strahan is a
perfect example. The common theory among the news media is that
Strahan is not giving his usual effort. There have even been
ridiculous statements about his diet being a possible problem, as
if him eating more roughage would increase his sack total.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings' coaching staff, much more grounded in reality than
the press, noticed while watching film of the Giants that Strahan
is getting double-teamed more than ever, and so the Vikings did a
lot of that against Strahan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we singled him,'' Minnesota Coach Dennis Green said,
``but we were always sliding protection to his side.'' Meaning
there were always a number of bodies on Strahan. Maybe the tackle
would get help from another lineman or a tight end or both.
</P>
<P>
   But Strahan has always been double- and sometimes triple-teamed
the last few seasons, so why would there be such a difference now,
as Strahan has just five and a half sacks this season? There are a
number of factors at work that were not present last season. The
schemes against him, a number of injuries _ including elbow and
knee problems _ and the fact that each week, an offensive lineman
wants to make his name against Strahan, all contribute to the sack
slump.
</P>
<P>
   Against Minnesota Sunday, the two times Strahan was
single-covered, he made plays. The first was Strahan's pressure on
quarterback Jeff George that led to an interception by Jeremy
Lincoln. Later in the game, Strahan beat right tackle Korey
Stringer on a speed move and Stringer was called for holding after
he tackled the defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Armstead's situation may not be as complicated, but it is just
as difficult. The coaches know how hurt Armstead is, but what are
they supposed to do in the biggest game of the season, bench him?
The leader of the defense and maybe the team?
</P>
<P>
   This is just one of those strange seasons for the two great
players. They will most likely be back next year, in prime form.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe they can revert to last season's form for one more
game, and push the Giants into the postseason.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
