<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9410 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-     12-26 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK CLOSER AT MARCIANO'S RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Thirty years after his death in a plane crash,
Rocky Marciano remains near and dear to the hearts of many boxing
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, we ranked the top 20 fighters, pound-for-pound, of
the century. That Marciano was not on the list raised the ire of
many readers. We received dozens of phone calls, e-mails and
letters with the same sentiment: What? No Marciano? Blasphemy.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it was no misprint.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Marciano, as determined and courageous as any fighter
in history, is among the greatest of all-time. The fact he is the
only major fighter to have retired with a perfect record _ 49-0 _
is reason enough to label him great.
</P>
<P>
   That all but six of his victories came by knockout only adds to
his legend.
</P>
<P>
   However, we cannot judge Marciano solely on those facts.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant deficiency on his resume was his
opposition: He faced no exceptional fighter in the prime of that
fighter's career or in his primary weight division.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Louis was 37 and badly faded when Marciano knocked him out
in eight rounds in 1951. Jersey Joe Walcott, probably Marciano's
most credible opponent, was capable but 38 when he was stopped in
round 13 after dominating most of his first of two bouts with
Marciano.
</P>
<P>
   Ezzard Charles was a great light heavyweight but not quite at
that level as a 33-year-old heavyweight when Marciano outpointed
him in the first of two fights between them.
</P>
<P>
   And Archie Moore was 41 when Marciano stopped him in nine in
1955, Marciano's last fight.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that? A wasteland. Who today even remembers Carmine Vingo
or Roland La Starza or Rex Layne, some of Marciano's bigger-name
opponents at the time?
</P>
<P>
   Many will contend that a fighter should be judged only by his
rate of success against his contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   Yes and no, with more weight on the no. Yes because it doesn't
seem fair to punish a fighter over something he can't control. No
because a fighter's greatness can be determined only by meaningful
tests, tests that can be provided only by other great fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Take Roy Jones Jr. as a contemporary and more extreme example.
The undisputed light heavyweight champion might be as talented as
any fighter in history but will never be considered among the very
greatest for lack of decent opposition.
</P>
<P>
   It's not his fault _ but it's reality. Of course, Marciano faced
more credible opponents than Jones, but he clearly would have
benefited had he met and beaten a fighter as good as, say, Joe
Frazier or George Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   Marciano's legacy also suffers because of his brief reign as
champion. He defended only six times after he stopped Walcott to
win the title.
</P>
<P>
   He might be compared to a baseball player who's hitting .400
when he reaches the minimum number of at bats required to win a
batting championship and then decides to sit out the rest of the
season to preserve his mark.
</P>
<P>
   Do we respect his ability? Yes. Would we respect him more had he
played out the season? Of course.
</P>
<P>
   Marciano didn't retire at 32 to preserve his perfect record.
However, he (begin ital)did(end ital) quit in his prime. That
leaves us wondering what might have been and with some room to
question to Marciano's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even with his deficiencies, Marciano must be considered
among the best heavyweights of all time. We rank him No.5 since the
turn of the 20th century, which is another reason we couldn't rank
him in the top 20 pound-for-pound.
</P>
<P>
   Had we done so, five of the 20 would have been heavyweights.
That seems top-heavy when the long list of great fighters in the
lighter weight classes is taken into account, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   We don't want to reward fighters simply because they're
heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   So, in one opinion, this is where Marciano stands: Only four
heavyweights since 1900 were better and he probably would have
landed between 20 and 25 had our list of the best fighters of the
century gone on.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the thousands of fine fighters who've stepped
through the ropes, that's not exactly disrespectful.
</P>
<P>
   Top 10 heavyweights: Now that we mentioned where Marciano ranks
among the century's best heavyweights, we're compelled to provide
the rest of the list.
</P>
<P>
   Here we go again:
</P>
<P>
   1. Muhammad Ali (56-5, 37 KOs) 1960-81. Ali was lucky to have
fought in an era rich in fine heavyweights and defeated them all,
including two _ Sonny Liston and George Foreman _ who seemed
unbeatable at the time.
</P>
<P>
   2. Joe Louis (68-3, 54 KOs) 1934-51. Louis didn't have the
benefit of Ali's level of opposition but did beat six world
champions when it meant something to be heavyweight champ.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, he held the title for 11 years (three of
which he spent in the armed services) and defended (begin
ital)25(end ital) times. No other heavyweight controlled the
division as Louis did.
</P>
<P>
   3. Jack Dempsey (61-6-8, 50 KOs) 1914-27. He, too, didn't face
an abundance of imposing opponents. However, he tore through the
heavyweight division like no one before or since and became an icon
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Half his 50 knockouts came in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   4. Jack Johnson (78-13-11, 49 KOs) 1897-1938. Johnson, perhaps
the greatest defensive heavyweight ever, was champ for seven years
in an environment so hostile that officials conspired to throw him
in jail rather than allow him to remain champion.
</P>
<P>
   5. Rocky Marciano (49-0, 43 KOs) 1947-55. He did all that could
be asked of him: He beat everyone who was put in front of him. And,
with an 88-percent knockout rate, he did it with impressive
finality.
</P>
<P>
   He might not have had the boxing skills of some champions, but
no one was tougher or more driven. He arguably could be ranked as
high as No.3.
</P>
<P>
   6. Larry Holmes (67-6, 43 KOs) 1973-present. Holmes, too, fought
in an era generally void of inspiring opposition, but the length of
his reign as titleholder was remarkable: He was champ from 1978 to
1985 and won 21 title fights during that span.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes, who had perhaps the best jab in history, started his
career 48-0 before losing to Michael Spinks.
</P>
<P>
   7. Evander Holyfield (36-4-1, 25 KOs) 1984-present. Holyfield
and Ali are the only three-time world champions, a testament to
their grit and ability.
</P>
<P>
   The fact he has hovered at or near the top of the division for
15 solid years is impressive. He beat once-feared Mike Tyson twice
in title fights.
</P>
<P>
   8. Joe Frazier (32-4-1, 27 KOs) 1965-81. Frazier, who fought
like a runaway train, fell short only against Ali (two out of three
times) and Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   9. Sonny Liston (50-4, 39 KOs) 1953-70. Immensely strong,
extremely talented, Liston had the misfortune of being Ali's
contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   His left jab was as punishing as some fighters' left hook.
</P>
<P>
   10. George Foreman (76-5, 68 KOs) 1969-97: Foreman might have
been the most imposing heavyweight ever. However, like Liston, he
was unlucky to have run into Ali.
</P>
<P>
   His knockout of Michael Moorer to regain the title _ 20 years
after he first won the championship _ was one of boxing's great
moments.
</P>
<P>
   Next 10: 11.Mike Tyson; 12.Gene Tunney; 13.Jim Jefferies;
14.Jersey Joe Walcott; 15.Ezzard Charles; 16.Sam Langford;
17.Riddick Bowe; 18.Harry Wills; 19.Max Baer; 20.Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson explanation: How can Tyson be No.11?
</P>
<P>
   His thrilling run through the heavyweight division ended at the
tender age of 23 and he's been utterly ordinary since.
</P>
<P>
   He also defeated a string of forgettable opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Champions John L. Sullivan, Jim Corbett and Bob
Fitzsimmons fought primarily in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Other opinions: Marciano was ranked the No.3 heavyweight of the
century by a panel of experts put together by the Associated Press.
Ali was No.1 and Louis No.2. Tyson was not ranked.
</P>
<P>
   Marciano was (begin ital)not(end ital) ranked in the top 10
pound-for-pound. Heavyweights Ali (No.2), Louis (No.4) and Dempsey
(No.6) (begin ital)were(end ital) listed in the top 10. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
