u a BC-NY-ANIMAL-TRAVEL-2TAK     12-26 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ANIMAL-TRAVEL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKING A HOTEL ROOM IN MANHATTAN IS TOUGH IF YOUR ROOMMATE IS A
KOALA
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Fla., Ohio, Va.)  (nk) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Finding a hotel room in Manhattan during the holiday
season can be a bear. For those who travel with bears, it is even
harder.
</P>
<P>
   It is much the same for those trying to check in with an adult
kangaroo, several penguins or a cheetah. In New York, the pleasures
of a carpeted suite, skyline view and room service are mostly
restricted to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Take the struggles of Edward Clark, president of the Wildlife
Center of Virginia. Clark planned to come to New York with his bald
eagle last July for an appearance on the ``Today'' show, and began
to hunt for a room. At first he could find only frightened hotel
clerks, talk of liability and rejections all over town.
</P>
<P>
   Clark was hardly surprised. On previous visits to other cities,
he has concealed pythons in duffel bags and smuggled birds through
hotel parking garages until shocked maids blew the whistle on him.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Embery has also had doors slammed in her face. The
conservation ambassador for the Zoological Society of San Diego,
Ms. Embery and her 72-pound boa constrictor, Squeeze, took it hard
when the Hilton New York &AMP; Towers turned them down cold in 1997,
when they had come to town for ``CBS This Morning.'' The hotel, on
Avenue of the Americas at West 53rd Street, allows only dogs, and
they must be under 25 pounds, explained the front-office
coordinator, Abrahm Valdez. He added that the dog owners must leave
a $35 deposit in ase of messy cleanups.
</P>
<P>
   Even celebrity does not guarantee a room, as Jack Hanna, a
regular on ``Good Morning America'' and ``Late Show With David
Letterman,'' can tell you. Hanna, director emeritus of the Columbus
Zoo, has tried to find accommodations for everything from tigers to
camels.
</P>
<P>
   So imagine their relief that two Manhattan hotels _ the
Mayflower on Central Park West at 61st Street and Le Parker
Meridien on 57th Street off Seventh Avenue _ accommodate wild
guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only hotel that allowed me to check in with an eagle as a
roommate was the Mayflower,'' said Clark, delighted to find
``eagle-friendly'' accommodation. The hotel, built in 1925, has a
frayed old-world elegance in its 365 rooms and modern amenities
like conference rooms and a health club. Rooms start at $180 a
night, and a penthouse terrace suite is $500.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the liberal guest policy that drew Suzi Rapp,
promotions director of the Columbus Zoo. She checked in with her
adult kangaroo, which got its exercise hopping down the halls
wearing a leash and collar. ``They have been a wonderful hotel for
us,'' she said. ``Of course, we're very responsible,'' she added.
Most animal trainers cover the costs of any damage to rooms.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Ms. Embery learned of Le Parker Meridien, with its
expansive atrium lobby, glass penthouse and 494 luxurious rooms,
from $365 a night to $2,500 for a Presidential Suite; she never
looked back. She took her koala bear, booked it a room and rigged
up several trees so it could sleep. Ms. Embery stored the koala's
food, 500 pounds of eucalyptus leaves, in the room-service
refrigerator downstairs.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's slogan, ``Uptown, but not uptight,'' proved true.
``I can see no reason not to allow animals,'' said the general
manager, Steven Pipes, who has even allowed Ms. Embery's cheetah to
stroll the lobby. ``They are easier than humans, and when they
leave, the rooms are usually cleaner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mayflower was less eager to discuss its unusual guest
roster, a tradition that began more than 15 years ago, when the
staff from the Columbus Zoo began checking in. ``Animals must be
kept in cages,'' said a hotel spokeswoman, Michele De Milly. But
from time to time, she said, curious guests may stroll by the rooms
and ask, ``Oh, what do you have in there?'' Ms. De Milly added that
guest safety is paramount and that large and dangerous dogs are not
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the two penguins that stayed in a two-bathroom
suite, some baby tigers that smashed a lamp, a cheetah that
urinated on the bedroom carpet and the kangaroo hopping up and down
the halls, she said that the hotel made its decisions on a
``request-by-request basis,'' but was not eager to ``expand this
particular guest situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But those zoo professionals and wildlife experts _ who
frequently travel with industrial vacuum cleaners, drop cloths and
meals of live rats _ have nothing but praise for the Mayflower,
with a staff they described as courteous and well-trained.
</P>
<P>
   Clark appreciates how the bellhop always brings the oversize
luggage cart for his kennels. Ms. Rapp recalls that room service
delivered raw steak for her cougar when she ran out of meat. The
doormen will even keep an eye on those animals too large for rooms,
like camels and bulls, which can be parked outside in trailers.
</P>
<P>
   Ron McGill, zoo ambassador for the Miami Metro Zoo, said the
Mayflower was exceptionally generous, even after his cheetah had
that accident. ``They came right up with the carpet cleaner,'' he
said, and added, ``It's extremely rare to have a hotel like this on
Central Park West.''
</P>
<P>
   Even his penguins did not tap out the hotel's good will. He kept
the noisome birds in the bathtub, though they would occasionally
pop out, and he was concerned about the smell. ``They're fish
eaters, and I thought, `Surely, these people are going to hate
me,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But no. The staff remained upbeat and even came to the room with
air freshener. ``This is a full-service hotel like I've never seen
before,'' McGill said.
</P>
<P>
   Compare this with restrictions at other Manhattan hotels, which
limit animals mostly to dogs and other ``normal'' pets under a
certain weight limit.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pierre, which has a 15-pound per-pet weight limit, a
scrupulously polite reservations agent, Joachim von Moltke,
defended the hotel's policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really doubt that we would be able to accommodate a
kangaroo,'' he said, ``but I would have to check that with one of
our managers.''
</P>
<P>
   A python? ``Security would have to analyze how it should be
brought in and kept.''
</P>
<P>
   With a cheetah, the game wore thin. ``I would probably presume
the answer would be no,'' he said somewhat impatiently, ``given
that the animal might just tear the room apart.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Four Seasons hotel limits its animal guests to
``laptop''-size dogs under 10 pounds. As for a small leopard, ``I
don't think so'' was the answer. ``We have an obligation to make
sure that our employees are working in a safe environment,'' said
Brian Honan, director of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   So it went, from the New York Palace to the Waldorf-Astoria to
the Inter-Continental, even though the City Department of Health
does not explicitly ban wild animals in hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is hardly much better in other cities, where
hidden animals and their owners face extraordinary heat from the
guests who encounter them.
</P>
<P>
   It was bad, for example, at the Toluca Lake Motel in California,
when an adult aardvark from the Cincinnati Zoo tunneled through the
wall with its tremendous claws, and wound up protruding into the
next guest's room, said Jim Fowler, host of ``Wild Kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
   And at the Sheraton Universal Hotel in Burbank, Calif., where
Fowler sneaked in his 200-pound anaconda in a suitcase full of
cedar chips. After bathing it in the tub, Fowler, wearing only
jockey shorts, wrapped the snake around his upper body to dry and
then leaned out his door to pick up a newspaper. The door clicked
behind him, just as members of a girls' basketball tournament
rounded the corner. ``I can hear the screams to this day,'' he
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me half an hour to get a porter up there because
whenever the elevator door opened, I got this kind of reaction,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The key, Fowler said, is to make the animals ``really
comfortable,'' and nothing does that quite as well as a
full-service hotel. ``In all the years I was on Johnny Carson, no
one could ever accuse me of my animals' being stressed,'' he said,
acknowledging luxurious digs at the Burbank Sheraton.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, however, there is some stress that no top
hotel can erase. In November, staff members from the Columbus Zoo
pulled their trailer up to the Mayflower, and within minutes, a
12-year-old barn owl named Seymour was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   The owl had no street value, but was scheduled to make
appearances with Jack Hanna on the ``The Maury Povich Show,''
``Good Morning America'' and Letterman's show. Instead, Hanna had
to appear with an opossum, giving Letterman an opportunity to rib
him. ``Jack,'' he said, ``I have those in my garbage can at home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
