<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STARS WHO MADE L.A. THE PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Y'know, the (begin ital)beeee(end ital)utiful thing about making
a list of the the top 10 Los Angeles sports figures who over the
last century best personified the L.A. lifestyle... it's truly a
(begin ital)beeee(end ital)utiful thing to see.
</P>
<P>
   As it should.
</P>
<P>
   Good looks and a great hook go a long way here. Come for the
sporting life, stay for the supporting actor Oscar. It's an
ego-a-go-go.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe in other parts of the country, athletes become legends.
Here, we make 'em into icons. Or, in Shaquille O'Neal's case,
(begin ital)he(end ital) tries.
</P>
<P>
   This is a unique club all right. Beach volleyball legend Karch
Kiraly didn't make it. Howie Long, Fred Dryer, Merlin Olsen, Mark
Harmon... thanks, but don't call us, we'll call you. Not even
Cotton Warburton, the All-American USC back in '33 who won an Oscar
for editing the film ``Mary Poppins'' could cut in.
</P>
<P>
   For outstanding lifetime achievement in athletics and
aesthetics, these 10 are always ready for their close-ups:
</P>
<P>
   10. Wayne Gretzky: Managed to keep all his teeth during his
years with the Kings for post-career endorsements. And more
impressively, kept his aspiring actress wife from getting work in
Hollywood, which only would have tarnished the Great One's legend.
</P>
<P>
   9. Dodgers first basemen: The first-base bag at Dodger Stadium
is the equivalent to Schwabs Drugstore. Steve Garvey, everyone's
All-American. Eric Karros, dubbed ``Fabio'' by former teammate Mike
Piazza. And don't forget Wes Parker, still one of the city's most
eligible bachelors whose acting career didn't quite make it past a
``Brady Bunch'' cameo.
</P>
<P>
   8. Jerry Buss: Without him, there's no Jack Nicholson and all
his rowdy friends gettin' their mugs on camera at courtside during
Lakers games. The Hugh Hefner of sports owners, whose daughter once
posed for Playboy, also isn't above asking bar-pals like Dennis
Rodman to help out the club.
</P>
<P>
   7. Pat Riley: It started when he was a backup guard on the
Lakers in the mid-'70s, with the long hair and sideburns. He stuck
around as Chick Hearn's sidekick, and worked his way to the bench.
Eventually, Mr. Armani put the show into ``Showtime'' and made good
on a guarantee of back-to-back titles.
</P>
<P>
   6. Bill ``Spaceman'' Lee: He not only fit the stereotype of the
California flake when he admitted to sprinkling his pancakes with
marijuana. He expanded on it. A self-proclaimed Roman Catholic Zen
Buddhist who believes the spirit of Satchel Paige jumped into his
body, this San Fernando Valley native got into USC and survived a
decent major-league career by throwing left-handed comments past
stunned writers. The Hunter S. Thompson of baseball now has Woody
Harrelson ready to be executive producer of a film on his life,
likely named after his autobiography, ``The Wrong Stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   5. Oscar De La Hoya: ``The Golden Boy'' was named ``Hispanic of
the Year'' in '99 by an Hispanic marketing company. He's made
Forbes' Power 100 and its Celebrity 100. Soon, he'll enter the
acting and music worlds. Occasionally, he'll box.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bo Belinsky: The '60s were his party, and the Angels pitcher
was freaking out. When he wasn't swinging with babies like Mamie
Van Doren, Tina Louise or Jayne Mansfield, opposing hitters were
swinging and missing at his stuff.
</P>
<P>
   3. Chuck Connors: He had a taste of pro basketball (an original
Boston Celtic in '49) and major-league baseball (with the Brooklyn
Dodgers and Chicago Cubs), but the future star of ``The Rifleman''
shot down his future with a bold move in 1951. As a member of the
Pacific Coast League's L.A. Angels, he refused to participate in
the major-league baseball draft. He wanted to stay here so he could
be an actor.
</P>
<P>
   2. Buster Crabbe: The USC All-American struck Olympic gold at
the '32 Games in Los Angeles _ the only U.S. swimmer to do so. Then
he cashed it in. After five world records and 35 national
championships, he took Paramount up on an offer to become an actor
_ specifically Tarzan, which would be their studio's answer to
Johnny Weismuller over at MGM.
</P>
<P>
   1. Marion Morrison: A tackle on USC's football team in 1925 and
'26, he swaggered over to small movie parts and found out he liked
it more. Thus became John Wayne. Without his true grit, would
movies and TV have been as open to a legacy of local gridders?
Doubtful. He's the original. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
