<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-VATICAN-RADIOLINK-ART     12-26 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VATICAN-RADIOLINK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOICES FROM NEW YORK WILL RING AT THE VATICAN AS 2000 DAWNS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ About midnight on New Year's Eve, the voice of Daisy
Lopez _ Bronx teen-ager, Cathedral High School student and loyal
parishioner of St. Brendan's Church _ will travel through telephone
lines, across thousands of miles, and reverberate in the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Some 18 relatives and hundreds of other parishioners will be
with her at St. Brendan's, in the Norwood section of the Bronx, to
celebrate not just the advent of a new millennium, but a singular
honor for their church. St. Brendan's was the only Roman Catholic
church in America to be chosen for a 24-hour, 24-country radio link
to the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, churches from Papua New Guinea to Seoul to
Nairobi to the Bronx will broadcast prayers and greetings to Rome
through a special phone link, and Rome will broadcast to them.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lopez, 16, will be one of 13 St. Brendan's parishioners _
five young people and eight adults _ who will read prayers from a
script during the 15-minute link to the Vatican. The church's
Spanish and Filipino choirs will also sing as part of the program,
which is scheduled for the same time as a radio link between Rome
and Havana. The efforts of thousands of people around the world
should make it ``one of the most powerful prayers ever offered,''
said Monsignor. Patrick J. Boyle, who has been the pastor of St.
Brendan's for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   And so as New Year's Eve parties, concerts and cruises deflate
from surging millennial anxieties and sudden nesting urges, the
program at St. Brendan's is still a hot ticket. Boyle said that
hundreds of people were expected to attend the program and a social
gathering afterward at St. Brendan's School. Roughly 100 show up
for a typical New Year's Eve Mass. It was promoted at every Mass
Sunday, and even those who cannot be there were eagerly inquiring
whether the link could be heard on a local radio station. (As of
Sunday, no.)
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Delgado, 40, a building superintendent, was one of those
asking: he has elderly relatives and cannot be at church New Year's
Eve. Still, Delgado was pleased. ``It puts us on the map,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For Boyle, ``It is a way to call people's attention to the
spiritual value of the New Year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle said the church was selected for the ceremony because of a
connection between Jo Grafil, the chairwoman of the Vatican's Youth
Committee for the Great Jubilee Year, and the Rev. Sebastian
Bacatan, who is in residence at St. Brendan's while studying at
Fordham. The two are best friends, so when Ms. Grafil was looking
for a parish in New York, she called Bacatan, Boyle said.
</P>
<P>
   The parish, which serves about 2,000 families, celebrated its
90th anniversary this year. Its current building, a modern
structure that resembles a large brick ark, was completed in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Like many churches, St. Brendan's is in transition. At the 11
a.m. Mass Sunday, the upper level was half full with mostly elderly
parishioners, the Irish immigrants who once filled this
neighborhood. But downstairs, at the Spanish-language Mass, a new
church was being born. Every pew was packed with Hispanic
worshipers _ single young men, young parents and squirming
children.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics bear out the church's revitalization. Ten years ago,
it performed about 250 funerals and 150 baptisms a year, Boyle
estimated; now it performs about 350 baptisms and 90 funerals.
</P>
<P>
   And Hispanic parishioners are not solely responsible for the
rebirth. There are also Filipinos, many of whom work as doctors and
nurses at nearby Montefiore Medical Center, African immigrants,
African-Americans, new Irish immigrants and more. At the 1 p.m.
Mass, a mix of ages and ethnicities assembled to hear Bacatan
preach.
</P>
<P>
   In the rectory, Ms. Lopez was volunteering, as she often does.
She has attended St. Brendan's since she was about 6, and said she
wanted to participate in the link as soon as she heard about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to speak out to the people _ to let them know the
truth,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
