<HEADER>
A9419 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-DOCTORS-MISCONDUCT     12-26 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DOCTORS-MISCONDUCT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE BILL WOULD HELP INFORM PATIENTS ABOUT DOCTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As far as prospective patients know, Dr. Salvatore
Zelano will be taking new cases in March. At least that is what the
staff in his Brooklyn office tells callers, even though the doctor
lost his license and his right to admit patients to hospitals,
because state officials found he neglected to treat several
patients properly.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, he performed what the state considered a very
dangerous procedure: a biopsy on a patient who was already bleeding
heavily.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Hwu, who is listed among available doctors in
several health maintenance organizations' brochures, was recently
reprimanded by the state for incompetence and neglecting to care
properly for seven patients, including one with congestive heart
failure who died under his care. But that reprimand did not cause
New York Hospital Medical Center of Queens to dismiss him or the
HMOs to drop him from their lists.
</P>
<P>
   Hwu said in a telephone interview that he disagreed with at
least part of the findings, but that he did not want to comment
further, because he feared the state. Zelano, for his part, said he
fully expected his license to be reinstated this spring, and
disparaged the disciplinary process.
</P>
<P>
   In most instances, patients who are interested in knowing the
disciplinary history of their doctors are highly unlikely to have
access to such information. Disciplinary records against doctors
are not widely disseminated, and are often not divulged by medical
groups and hospitals who employ many of the physicians involved in
troubled cases.
</P>
<P>
   For example, HMOs do not include such information with the names
of the doctors who fill their provider lists, and doctors are
hardly inclined to volunteer the information to patients. If a
patient asks an HMO to provide the information, it is not required
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals and medical groups say some disciplinary actions are
taken because of personal animosity and some could be
misinterpreted by patients who do not understand the complexities
of modern science and medical malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   A bill now before the Legislature in Albany would give consumers
better access to doctors' disciplinary and malpractice history.
Part of a pile of health-care bills the legislators considered this
month, it is known as 1401-A but is more familiarly called ``Lisa's
Law,'' for Lisa Smart, a woman who died in 1997 during routine
gynecological surgery at Beth Israel Medical Center in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The primary surgeon in the operation on Mrs. Smart, Dr. Marc
Sklar, was on probation with the state at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would augment the information about doctors available
on the state Health Department's Web site. Under the bill, the
site, which currently lists doctors who have been disciplined by
the agency, would also include each doctor's malpractice history,
educational background, and any dismissal from a hospital staff.
Massachusetts, the model state for New York's proposed law,
provides the same information.
</P>
<P>
   More important, under the proposed law, doctors would have to
hang signs in their offices telling patients about the state Web
site and the toll-free telephone number they can call for the same
information.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, few patients even know there is a Health Department
Web site where information is available, say the bill's proponents,
which include a broad range of groups, from consumer advocates to
the Business Council, a statewide chamber of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Many patients do not have access to computers. ``The current Web
site is a buried treasure in state government,'' said Blair Horner,
the legislative director for the New York Public Interest Research
Group.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is one of several moves that state and federal
officials have considered in response to medical errors.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a congressional debate has focused on the
so-called patients' bill of rights, which seeks to hold
managed-care companies accountable for the result if they refuse to
pay for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The National Academy of Sciences recently recommended that
Congress begin a standard and rigorous system for reporting
mistakes made in hospitals, noting that tens of thousands of people
die each year as a result of medical errors. And several states
have considered legislation similar to the New York bill.
</P>
<P>
   The New York bill, which passed the Assembly last year and is
now before the Senate, will be taken up next session. The Business
Council has supported it because it sees consumer information as a
possible way to lower health care costs, because patients would
tend to avoid a doctor whose mistakes have led to further costly
procedures and care. The New York Health Plan Association, a trade
group for 33 HMOs, also offers guarded support of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always supported the effort to provide consumers with
information,'' said Leslie Moran, a spokeswoman for the
association. But she added: ``We have to remember that when someone
has a disciplinary action pending against them, we can't disregard
due process. The other question is: Whose responsibility is it to
tell the consumers?''
</P>
<P>
   The bill's detractors include the Medical Society of New York, a
professional association for doctors, which strongly opposes
posting doctors' malpractice history. The association contends that
this can be misleading, because some specialties, like obstetrics,
have a higher rate of malpractice suits, as do doctors who take on
high-risk cases. They also argue that patients may not be
sophisticated enough to understand all the reasons that a hospital
dismisses a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates argue that patients need the information,
because disciplinary records often do not keep doctors from moving
to different hospitals, or to different states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
