<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9420 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-HOMELESS-COCOONS-A     12-26 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELESS-COCOONS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTIST DESIGNS PERSONAL, COCOON-LIKE SHELTERS FOR HOMELESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One night this week, according to plan, a homeless
man will find a suitable air duct or steam grate near Pennsylvania
Station, hook up a plastic intake tube that inflates a
personal-size plastic cocoon, and crawl into it for a warm night's
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   He will be introducing to New York a two-year-old project to
help the homeless whose creator, Michael Rakowitz, acknowledges
that its centerpiece is potentially life-saving and pointedly
creepy. Working with his homeless clients, Rakowitz custom-builds
free temporary shelters that keep them from freezing, let them see
out and even have plastic pockets where they can put up pictures or
store clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The personal shelters were used by 15 homeless people in Boston
and Cambridge, Mass., in the winter of 1997-98, with assent from
building owners and no problem from the police, said Rakowitz, who
was then a graduate student at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and now lives in Long Island City, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   He made his first New York tent for a man he met outside Penn
Station. He also plans to help a group of men near the Staten
Island Ferry terminal.
</P>
<P>
   The structures, which resemble giant grubs or some sort of
device for removing hazardous materials, are just a Band-Aid for
the problems faced by street people, Rakowitz acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ugly condition, and people shouldn't like the
project,'' he said. ``The project should disappear. The project
should never have been made in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was trying to alter ``the everyday experience of
seeing homeless dwellings as bundles of clothing in doorways,
cardboard boxes,'' and getting passers-by to ``experience the sight
of the homeless once again for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   His personal shelters also work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not an urban planner, and I'm not somebody who can serve
as a social worker,'' said Rakowitz, 26, who is an adjunct lecturer
at the State University of New York at Purchase. ``I'm an artist,
and this is the only way I can act.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Open Door drop-in center on 41st Street near Ninth
Avenue, Kane, a man who said he had until recently lived on the
streets for 18 months, examined photographs of Rakowitz's shelters
and said he liked them. He praised the tents' designs and approved
of their special features. But would he use one?
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong,'' Kane said, as a friend nodded in
agreement. ``I think it's a good idea.'' But, referring to Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, he added: ``In New York, Giuliani is kind of
tough on anything, especially homeless people. You hook that up to
anything, you're going to get arrested. Giuliani don't want
homeless people on the streets in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Brosnahan, executive director of the Coalition for the
Homeless, was also not optimistic about the reception the tents
might face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they'll last more than a few hours, except in
the most hidden, remote places of our city,'' Ms. Brosnahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Walter Burnes, a police spokesman, said: ``When you
really think about it, it's a nice thing that he's doing. It's a
nice thing he's designing these tents. There's no problem with his
giving them away. But there's a legal issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnes said that using the tents on city property was illegal
camping, using them on private property without permission was
trespassing, and using them on sidewalks was impeding traffic. ``If
you want to pitch a tent in your back yard, there isn't a problem
with that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brosnahan described the issues raised by Rakowitz's shelters
as ``very complicated terrain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent the last decade advocating for decent, safe,
affordable housing, and this obviously falls short of that
threshold,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, ``This is a life and death struggle, and clearly
anything people can provide as an interim measure to enable our
homeless friends to survive through the night cannot be dismissed
out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brosnahan noted that she had just finished two weeks of
legal work fighting Giuliani's policy against allowing homeless
people to sleep on sidewalks, and that the litigation included
testimony from a Boston doctor about his autopsies of 13 people who
had frozen to death on the streets. ``Not even very cold weather,
but 32-degree weather,'' Ms. Brosnahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Rakowitz began designing the tents, which cost him about $5 each
for materials, in 1997 as a graduate project at MIT, partly in
response to a decision by Harvard University to put raised bars on
many of its building grates to keep the homeless from lying down on
them. That winter, 15 structures were in use.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of ways, they were their own designers,'' Rakowitz
said of the street people, whom he calls collaborators. They
insisted on clear plastic, not black trash bags. They were less
concerned about privacy than security; they wanted to see and be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   They also wanted a place to store their caps and gloves and
maybe put up a picture or a ``hungry'' sign, so Rakowitz put zipper
bags between the ribs of the tents. The bags are attached with
Velcro and can be taken off and carried in chains like bandoliers.
The whole tent fits into a clear plastic carrier the size of a
shopping bag.
</P>
<P>
   The tents' biggest advantage, aside from warmth, is that street
people do not have to sleep directly on hot grates, where they risk
severe burns, Rakowitz said. Occupants do not breathe air and
possibly harmful fumes from the vent or grate; instead, the warm
air circulates through the ribs of the tent, as in a radiator.
</P>
<P>
   Rakowitz titled his original project ParaSite, which he said
referred to the use of waste air from buildings and to an ancient
Greek root word: a person who received free meals in return for
amusing or entertaining conversation. The day he graduated with his
master's degree, two former users of the bags called him from their
shelter to congratulate him, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the New York project with the current uproar about
the homeless is pure coincidence, Rakowitz said. ``It's not a
protest against Giuliani at all,'' he said. ``Actually, the plan
was to do this project since last winter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that the issue is being discussed,'' he added, and
then, referring to the mayor, he said, ``He himself is agitational,
just as this project is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
