<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday, 12/26/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- NY-HOMELESS-COCOONS --
Michael Rakowitz on the roof of his studio in Long Island City,
Queens, with one of the personal shelters for the homeless he
designs. The shelters keep the homeless from freezing, let them see
out and even have plastic pockets where they can put up pictures or
store clothing. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- VATICAN-RADIOLINK -- The
Rev. Sebastian Bacatan, left, was instrumental in the selection of
St. Brendan's for a New Year's telephone link with the Vatican.
Throughout the day, churches from Papua New Guinea to Seoul to
Nairobi to the Bronx will broadcast prayers and greetings to Rome
through a special phone link, and Rome will broadcast to them.
(Chris Maynard/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- NY-ANIMAL-TRAVEL -- The
guest policy at the Mayflower Hotel on Central Park West enabled
residents of the Columbus Zoo to book accommodations. Only two
Manhattan hotels - the Mayflower and Le Parker Meridien - allow
wild guests past their front door. (Jeffery A. Salter/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- OBIT-WAINE-B&AMP;W -- Dr. Hans
Waine, who received a doctorate in history in Germany and worked as
a journalist in Berlin before moving to the United States and
becoming a prominent rheumatologist, died Dec. 5 at a nursing home
in Stamford, Conn. He was 92. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) EL TORO, Calif. -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- CALIF-BASE -- The
Pentagon's decision to close El Toro Air Station has divided Orange
county, north from south. The issue is whether to build an
international airport on El Toro's 4,738 acres, a plan supported by
the older, more ethnically mixed suburbs to the north, or to use
the land for parks, schools and other public amenities, as Irvine
and the neighboring, mostly new cities to the south are urging.
(Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 26, 1999 --
MILLENNIUM-ORGANIZER-PROFILE -- George Stevens Jr., 67, is
co-producing the New Year's Eve celebration of ``America's
Millennium'' on the Mall in Washington. Stevens, who is busy on
several other film projects, says he decided to take on the
millennium celebration ``because it is there.'' (Justin Lane/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- OBIT-SARETT-B&AMP;W -- Dr. Lewis
Hastings Sarett with a vial of synthesized cortisone in 1949.
Sarett, an organic chemist who received the National Medal of
Science for his work with cortisone and other substances as the
senior vice president for science and technology of Merck &AMP; Co.,
died Nov. 29 at his home in Viola, Idaho. He was 81. The cause was
advanced colitis, his family said. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BRIDGEWATER, N.J. -- Dec. 26, 1999 --
NEWEST-IMMIGRANTS-5 -- Local high school students Jessica Tang,
left, playing the mother, and Chelsey Tanaka, as the daughter, in a
play for second graders at the Bradley Gardens School. ``Cherish
your heritage,'' advices the mother. ``Ignore the bullies.'' No
institution has been more affected by Bridgewater's churning
population than the schools, which have the potential to become a
model United Nations - or a multicultural tinderbox. (Dith Pran/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) BRIDGEWATER, N.J. -- Dec. 26, 1999 --
NEWEST-IMMIGRANTS-4 -- Turkey and shrimp with steamed sweet rice as
prepared, from left, by Sharon Wang, Susan Lin and Sharon's mother,
Chunting Chai. In the southwestern sections of Bridgewater, the
last decade has seen farms and woods give way to 3,000 houses in
glistening subdivisions. As many as half the residents in some
neighborhoods are Asian, led by Indians, Chinese and Filipinos.
(Dith Pran/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WOODBRIDGE, N.J. -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- NEWEST-IMMIGRANTS-3
-- Yousheng Tang, center, is a reserve tight end for the
Bridgewater-Raritan sophmore team. At just under 6 feet in cleats
and a taut 150 pounds, Yousheng is one of only two Asian-Americans
on the Panthers, but it is easy predict that more will follow. Even
the quietest bedroom communities are finding their rhythms jolted
by the greatest wave of immigration since the start of the century.
(Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BRIDGEWATER, N.J. -- Dec. 26, 1999 --
NEWEST-IMMIGRANTS-2 -- A religious procession taking place near the
new, commodious Sri Venkateswara Hindu temple In Bridgewater. This
rambling township of 38,000 sets a subtle example of how even the
quietest bedroom communities are finding their rhythms jolted by
the greatest wave of immigration since the start of the century.
(Dith Pran/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BRIDGEWATER, N.J. -- Dec. 26, 1999 --
NEWEST-IMMIGRANTS-1 -- Gati Desai leads a prayer service conducted
by her family twice a day in their Bridgewater home; Saval, 5, sits
at right; Sachin Shah (right reflection), Kaushad Desai (left
reflection), Sahaj, 3, rear and Shaili Shah, 2, standing at left.
By leapfrogging to desirable suburbs, many Asians are upending
stereotypes about new immigrants being poor and tethered to ethnic
neighborhoods, desperate to wriggle out of the city. (Nicole
Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- MEDIA-TALK -- For the first
time, John Grisham will publish a semi-autobiographical literary
novel. The book, ``A Painted House,'' will be published over the
next year in serial form in The Oxford American, a bimonthly review
of Southern literature of which Grisham has been co-owner and
publisher since 1996. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) YONKERS, N.Y. -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- SPEEDING-DRIVERS --
Early last week, Mathew Hennessy, mild-mannered computer
programmer, was driving toward Manhattan at 100 mph. He is one of a
growing number of American drivers who, according to traffic
experts, are pushing highway speeds to new heights. Steering bigger
and more powerful cars and exploiting increasingly lax police
enforcement, more drivers than ever are treating speed limits as
suggestions, experts say. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- MILLENNIUM-AD-COLUMN -- Many
consumer products have appeared in humorous millennial guises. The
second millennium is ending not with a bang or a whimper but with a
sales pitch. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) STRATFORD, Conn. -- Dec. 26, 1999 --
DICTAPHONE-TURNAROUND -- John H. Duerden, Dictaphone's chief
executive, with a dictation machine from 1924, and, in his right
hand, part of a new system that uses speech recognition to convert
voice to text. ``For too long, Dictaphone thought of its core
competency as word processing,'' he says. ``It's not. It's
recording, storing and retrieving data that happens to enter the
system as voice.'' (Joseph Kugielsky/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- PATENTS -- In a highly
unusual move, Todd Dickinson, the Patents Commissioner, ordered the
re-examination of a patent. Though rare, such an action usually
results in the patent being revoked. The move was widely praised.
(The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN -- Former
Sen. Bill Bradley across the table from Sam Donaldson, Cokie
Roberts and George Will on ABC's ``This Week'' earlier this year.
Just 15 months ago, Bradley was not a candidate and Vice President
Al Gore was the party's presumptive nominee. Today, he has matched
Gore in fund-raising, built a national organization and given
himself a shot at upsetting the vice president. But the coming
weeks will provide a critical test of Bradley's staying power. (ABC
News/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) REDMOND, Wash. -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- ONLINE-NEWS --
MSNBC.com commands the largest audience of news Web sites. ``The
goal from the beginning has been to package the experience, instead
of giving people endless lists of things _ which for many other
news sites is the norm,'' says Merrill Brown, who has been editor
in chief of the site since its start in 1996. (Peter Yates/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- THISWEEK-DEMISE -- The
``This Week'' crew: George Stephanopoulos, Bill Kristol, Sam
Donaldson, Cokie Roberts, George Will. The declining fortunes of
ABC's Sunday morning political-interview program may just be a
belated reaction to its descent into celebritymongering. In recent
months the program has been blasted in the ratings by NBC's ``Meet
the Press,'' where Tim Russert often comes through with tough,
probing interviews that leave the ABC chatterers in the dust. (ABC
News/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- BRITAIN-TV-SHEEPDOG -- A
scene from ``One Man And His Dog,'' a 23-year-old sports show in
which a bunch of sheep running in the wrong direction qualifies as
high drama. ``Strangely, it's not boring,'' says Paul Latham,
spokesman for the Countryside Alliance, speaking fondly of a show
in which spectacularly taciturn shepherds compete to see whose dog
can most neatly herd some sheep into a pen. (BBC Productions/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- BAROQUE-BRAZIL -- Detail of a
statue by Aleijadinho, from ``Baroque Brazil: Between Heaven and
Earth,'' a beautifully designed exhibition at the Petit Palais
through Feb. 6. The show gives Parisians a chance to discover not
only some two dozen works by Aleijadinho, but also other treasures
from the baroque movement that shaped Brazilian art and
architecture from the early 17th century to the early 19th. (Museu
do Ouro, Sabara/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- MILENNIUM-MUSIC-PICKS --
Peter Schickele's collection of some 4,000 discs has room for
everything from Beethoven to bluegrass. Schickele, composer of
works both serious and hilarious, draws on a broad range of music
for inspiration. ``There are people who react to words and people
who react to music,'' he says. ``I'm definitely a music kind of
guy.'' (Chris Ramirez/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Dec. 26, 1999 -- RIGOLETTO-OPERA-REVIEW --
Sumi Jo as Gilda and Paolo Gavanelli in the title role of
``Rigoletto'' at the Metropolitan Opera House. Those who can
overlook his vocal idiosyncrasies and listen for style and
interpretive richness will find things to admire in Gavanelli's
work. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SAG HARBOR, N.Y. -- Dec. 26, 1999 --
SPALDING-GRAY-DOMESTICITY-2 -- Spalding Gray playing with his son,
Theo, outside their Sag Harbor home. Domesticity and life outside
the city have clearly had something of a calming effect on Gray,
who left a SoHo loft and a racier life three and a half years ago
for this home on the east end of Long Island. ``I do feel somewhat
reformed,'' he says. ``Like an AA person, I'm taking it one day at
a time.'' (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SAG HARBOR, N.Y. -- Dec. 26, 1999 --
SPALDING-GRAY-DOMESTICITY-1 -- Spalding Gray is sampling domestic
bliss these days at the Sag Harbor home he shares with Kathie
Russo; his sons, Forrest, left, and Theo; and his stepdaughter,
Marissa. ``Real life has always let me down,'' he says. ``That's
why I do the monologues. I have always said I'd rather tell a life
than live a life. But I have to live a life in order to tell one.''
(Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
