executive, with a dictation machine from 1924, and, in his right
hand, part of a new system that uses speech recognition to convert
voice to text. ``For too long, Dictaphone thought of its core
competency as word processing,'' he says. ``It's not. It's
recording, storing and retrieving data that happens to enter the
system as voice.'' (Joseph Kugielsky/The New York Times)
