work. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SAG HARBOR, N.Y. -- Dec. 26, 1999 --
SPALDING-GRAY-DOMESTICITY-2 -- Spalding Gray playing with his son,
Theo, outside their Sag Harbor home. Domesticity and life outside
the city have clearly had something of a calming effect on Gray,
who left a SoHo loft and a racier life three and a half years ago
for this home on the east end of Long Island. ``I do feel somewhat
reformed,'' he says. ``Like an AA person, I'm taking it one day at
a time.'' (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SAG HARBOR, N.Y. -- Dec. 26, 1999 --
SPALDING-GRAY-DOMESTICITY-1 -- Spalding Gray is sampling domestic
bliss these days at the Sag Harbor home he shares with Kathie
Russo; his sons, Forrest, left, and Theo; and his stepdaughter,
Marissa. ``Real life has always let me down,'' he says. ``That's
why I do the monologues. I have always said I'd rather tell a life
than live a life. But I have to live a life in order to tell one.''
(Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
