<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SMIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEO SMIT, 78, COMPOSER AND CONCERT PIANIST, DIES
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Calif., N.Y., Pa., Mass., D.C.)   (jw) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leo Smit, a composer, pianist and teacher, died on Dec. 12 in
Encinitas, Calif. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart failure, said Nils Vigeland, a friend.
</P>
<P>
   During a long and varied career that began when he was 15, Smit
worked with Stravinsky, was closely associated with Copland, wrote
an opera with the British astronomer Sir Fred Hoyle and became a
highly valued teacher.
</P>
<P>
   This year, in notes for a new recording, he remembered these and
other highlights from a rich life, including ``the golden years in
Rome with the high-spirited companionship of Alexei Haieff, Harold
Shapero and Lukas Foss''; the time Leonard Bernstein ``set a
high-jump record while conducting the climax of my Second
Symphony''; and encounters with painters, dancers and poets.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Philadelphia on Jan. 12, 1921, the son of a
violinist, Kolman Smit. At 8 he went with his mother to Moscow,
where he studied for a year with Dmitri Kabalevsky. He then
returned to Philadelphia and went from there to New York to
complete his studies with Isabella Vengerova and Jose Iturbi for
piano and with Nicolas Nabokov for composition. In 1936-37 he was
Balanchine's rehearsal pianist, and it was in that role that he met
Stravinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Smit made his Carnegie Hall debut in 1939, when he was only 18.
Disdaining the conventional recital program, he later pioneered
thematic concerts (``Liszt in Italy,'' given with his own slides;
``Mozart: A Self-Portrait,'' mixing piano and vocal music) and made
a feature of new pieces, especially by Copland and other composers
close to him. In 1952, he gave the first performance of Haieff's
Piano Concerto.
</P>
<P>
   His start as a composer was slower. Two ballets written for
Valerie Bettis, ``Yerma'' (1946) and ``Virginia Sampler'' (1947),
won him some attention, but his big break came in 1957 when the
Boston Symphony played his Symphony No. 1, honored by the New York
Music Critics' Circle as the best new orchestral work of the year.
Also in 1957, he moved to Los Angeles to teach at the University of
California. In 1962, he began teaching at the State University of
New York at Buffalo, but he returned to California each winter and
settled there last year.
</P>
<P>
   Among his later works are two more symphonies, a piano concerto
and a second collaboration with Sir Fred, ``Copernicus: Narrative
and Credo,'' which had its first performance at the National
Academy of Sciences in Washington in 1973. His last decade was
devoted to songs based on the poems of Emily Dickinson, of which he
completed nearly 100.
</P>
<P>
   No immediate family members survive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
