<DOCNO> NYT19991226.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-26 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-RANGERS-NY     12-26 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOMEZ NETS HAT TRICK FOR DEVILS, BUT RANGERS RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For 15 games, Scott Gomez scored no goals. He was
still getting assists, but the overall pace of production had
slowed for the Devils' contender for rookie of the year. Before the
New Jersey Devils visited the New York Rangers on Sunday at Madison
Square Garden, Gomez got some advice from Claude Lemieux, a veteran
teammate and also his linemate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `You know, you need a couple goals tonight,''' Lemieux
recounted. ```You're due for some goals. You've been passing a lot.
You've got to get shooting.'''
</P>
<P>
   Obeying Lemieux, Gomez put five shots on Mike Richter in the
Rangers' net. Three of them went in and the third one _ late in the
second period _ gave the Devils a two-goal lead. But the Rangers
refused to fold. They tied the score before the second intermission
and both teams settled for a point after overtime left them with a
3-3 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the standings, Gomez said, ``I'd rather have two
points than a hat trick any day.''
</P>
<P>
   But he admitted that it was most enjoyable to have his first
three-goal game in a special building while his mother and father,
visiting from Alaska, cheered from the seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something about this place,'' Gomez said, with a smile on his
face and a dazzled look in his eyes. ``Kind of magical.'' Early in
the day, in talking with his father, Carlos, Scott had said, ``Dad,
when you skate at the Garden, you've made the big time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez has just turned 20 years old and he could become the
sport's first Hispanic star. His attitude about big-league hockey
is still at a kid-on-Christmas-morning stage, and he is charming
his teammates, fans and the news media with an exciting playing
style and a guileless personality. As he spoke there was an ice bag
on his right ankle, which was sore from stopping a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's result affected several streaks. It ended the Rangers'
losing streak at two games, and it ended their losing streak
against the Devils at six, although they have not defeated the
Devils in 16 regular-season games (0-11-5). But as they left for a
three-game road trip, they conceded that this one felt better than
your average single point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' said Theo Fleury, who had a goal and two
assists. ``When you're down a couple goals, it means you battled
back.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Devils led by 2-0 after one period, Fleury scored at
six minutes 29 seconds of the second, taking advantage of a
turnover by Devils defenseman Scott Niedermayer. After Gomez gave
the Devils a 3-1 lead at 14:03 of the same period on a breakaway
out of the penalty box, Fleury helped Adam Graves score to make it
3-2 at 15:11.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury did it by baiting Devils defenseman Scott Stevens with
irritating forechecks. When Stevens concentrated on chasing Fleury,
it created more room for Graves, who carried the puck through a
poke-checking attempt by goalie Martin Brodeur. Graves didn't get
an assist on Mathieu Schneider's tying goal at 16:51, but he was
important to the play, creating traffic in front of Brodeur as
Fleury and Mike York worked the puck into scoring position for
Schneider.
</P>
<P>
   York, a Rangers rookie, had three assists. Two years ago, he and
Gomez were roommates on the U.S. team in the world junior
tournament, and they remain close friends. This did not stop them
from tussling late in the third period and getting penalized for
roughing. Gomez said he laughed when he saw whom he was wrestling
and was tempted to tease York for playing in college instead of in
a major junior league, as Gomez did. But he thought better of it.
</P>
<P>
   The goals gave Gomez eight for the season to go with 26 assists
for 34 points, most on the team and most among rookies in the
National Hockey League. (York leads all rookies in goals with 10.)
</P>
<P>
   The Devils outplayed the Rangers for most of the game,
outshooting them, 44-24, as Richter played in his 17th consecutive
game, the last 13 of them starts. ``Spotting them two goals early
certainly isn't a good beginning,'' he said. As for the long
stretch without a victory against the Devils, Richter said that
most players on the Rangers don't make much of it, because not many
were with the team when it started.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had the best chance to win in overtime when Patrik
Elias hit the goal post just 10 seconds after the opening face-off.
The Rangers' best chance, a shot by Schneider, was stopped by
Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   Graves, who wears the captain's C in place of the injured Brian
Leetch, led the comeback with aggressive forechecking, particularly
against the line of Gomez, Lemieux and Sergei Nemchinov. ``We kept
it simple and tried getting the puck in deep and forcing
turnovers,'' Graves said. ``Fortunately, we were able to get back
into it. It is not very often you come back against the Devils,
because they play so well defensively.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
