<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIANTS-VIKINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PLAYOFF STUMBLE, GIANTS FIND MEDIOCRITY LOVES COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Two graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ As the New York Giants ran from the
tunnel at the west end of Giants Stadium early Sunday afternoon,
there was a throaty roar from the grandstand _ an ovation with a
past, when the Giants regularly played meaningful games in late
December.
</P>
<P>
   For all the tumult of an uneven year, the Giants had much to
play for in Sunday's final regular-season home game, and the
cheering, if nothing else, was a gesture that recognized a turn of
good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly three hours later, the Giants left the field to the
humbling murmur of indifference.
</P>
<P>
   For all the promise the day brought, in the end, after a
discomforting 34-17 loss to the Minnesota Vikings, the Giants had
once again squandered another playoff opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' collapse was so thorough _ the defense inept, the
offense feeble and the special teams play disastrous _ the fans
were too disgusted to boo and at least one player too dejected to
find hope in what remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technically, we're alive in the playoff race,'' running back
Tiki Barber said. ``We don't deserve it. That was rotten today.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Giants (7-8) live still, by the miracle _ or folly _ of
the NFL's parity party. The Giants will sneak into the postseason
with this combination next Sunday: a Giants victory in Dallas and a
loss by Green Bay at home to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   An 8-8 record might document mediocrity, but this season in the
N FC, an 8-8 team _ either the Giants, the Packers or the Cowboys _
will be heading to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants can make the playoffs if they and the Packers each
win Sunday, but only if they pull off the wildest finish for a
wild-card berth. If the Giants and the Packers each win Sunday, but
the Giants win their game by 56 more points than the Packers win
their game, the Giants go to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were dominated by the Vikings (9-6), who scored
touchdowns with great variety _ on a reverse option pass by wide
receiver Randy Moss, on an 85-yard kickoff return and on a 70-yard
run in which Robert Smith was barely touched.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, the Giants' front four created no pressure in the
Minnesota pocket, where quarterback Jeff George placidly picked
apart their depleted secondary with the aid of the stellar
receiving duo of Moss and Cris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, facing the 30th-ranked defense in the league, the
Giants moved the football but rarely when it counted. They rushed
for 42 yards on their first possession and 34 yards the rest of the
game. Quarterback Kerry Collins was forced to throw 51 times, and
though he completed 31 passes for 297 yards, he also had a costly
interception and generally seemed as out of sync as the rest of the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   For the Giants, the high-water mark of the game was in the first
eight minutes. After forcing the Vikings into a three-and-out
series, the Giants marched down the field, with running back Joe
Montgomery carrying nine times for 37 yards. They had a first down
at the Vikings' 5-yard line, but could not advance the ball for the
touchdown and Cary Blanchard kicked a 24-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota's second drive, Leroy Hoard pushed over from 3
yards out to give Minnesota a 7-3 lead it never relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   Blanchard kicked a 43-yard field goal in the second quarter, but
a second Hoard touchdown gave Minnesota a 14-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants drove to the Vikings' 16-yard line with the opening
kickoff of the second half but again got only a field goal out of
the possession.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one play after Collins was intercepted by safety Anthony
Bass, the Vikings ran a reverse to Moss, who stopped and threw a
perfect pass to Carter in the right corner of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Blanchard added a 42-yard field goal as the third quarter ended
to cut the Vikings' lead to 21-9, but on the ensuing kickoff Moe
Williams burst through a gaping hole in the coverage for an 85-yard
touchdown return.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the worst Giants attempt to stop the Vikings from
scoring. That came several plays later in the fourth quarter. After
the Giants had cut Minnesota's lead to 28-17, Smith ran around left
end for 70 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The only Giant who got a clear shot at Smith, who rushed for 146
yards, was cornerback Jeremy Lincoln, who put both hands on Smith's
back _ like he was playing two-hand touch _ as Smith ran past him
about the 15-yard line and into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   By then, empty seats outnumbered spectators at Giants Stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
