<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS ALIVE IN A WORLD OF PARITY
</HEADLINE>
   (With FBN-GIANTS-VIKINGS) 
(rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ By late Sunday afternoon, before a Green
Bay score could be had, Jeremy Lincoln was not quite sure how the
New York Giants could still make the playoffs. He thought it might
have something to do with the square root of the number of his
team's defensive blunders divided by the sum of the Packers'
conference points allowed, on the road, in the red zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty much out of it,'' the cornerback said sadly,
before suddenly remembering that until proven otherwise, contention
in this NFL is conceptual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe not. I'm not a math genius, with all these equations.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln and the rest of the Giants were actually too depressed
to compute the possibilities, too dizzy from watching Cris Carter
zig and Randy Moss zag into and beyond their shopworn secondary. By
the time the home team marched off the Giants Stadium turf, 34-17
losers to the Minnesota Vikings, the number of fans still in the
house roughly equaled the sum of NFC playoff berths that are
unclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   This was not quite the send-off to Dallas for the regular-season
finale that Giants coach Jim Fassel envisioned during a week of pep
talks about the benefits of destiny controlled. In the season's
latest statement game, the Giants stood up and told their fans to
go get a head start on the traffic, if not on next season. The game
itself was a medley of the Giants' worst hits, particularly those
of the tackling variety. After all the noise about obstacles
overcome and corners turned, the Giants reverted to a show of
ineffectual offense, uninspired play calling, overrated defense and
dismal special teams.
</P>
<P>
   But they were, in the eyes of their coach and the ebb of their
conference, still mathematically alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't give you the percentages right now,'' Fassel said.
``Are we playoff caliber? I'm not going to dis this team right now
and tell you we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   They had been all set up to prove themselves the class of
several common man teams, and perhaps, with some luck, even secure
a first-round playoff game at home. Dallas had lost in New Orleans
on Friday. Detroit had blown a home game Saturday against Denver.
Minnesota had beaten Green Bay last week. All the Giants had to do
was control the ball on the ground, punch it into the end zone two
or three times, charge into Dallas and bust those ghosts running
around in Cowboys uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   This game plan worked perfectly until the Giants reached the
Minnesota 5-yard line, first-and-goal, on their first series. They
wound up losing 2 yards in three downs and settling for a field
goal. After the way Joe Montgomery had churned up yardage as the
Giants drove from their 28, there was something defeatist,
something deflating, about their inability to get into the end
zone.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the Vikings' Jeff George was given time to throw, the
big plays began coming in bunches. When it wasn't George to Carter
or Moss, it was Moss on the fake end-around, leading Carter into
the right side of the end zone with a better throw than we have
seen from any New York quarterback all season. Fassel, trailing by
21-6, for some reason ordered a field goal on fourth-and-3 from the
Vikings' 25. This was the last play of the third quarter. The first
play of the fourth was Moe Williams' 85-yard touchdown on a kickoff
return, an untouched speedster running through stooges.
</P>
<P>
   Nyuk, nyuk, nyuk. Cary Blanchard, the Giants' kicker, was
knocked cold on the play. Before he was even back on his feet,
thousands began an exodus from the stadium, presumably to get a
good seat in front of the television for next weekend, when this
playoff jog will be settled, once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the league right now,'' said Jessie Armstead, the
Giants' Pro Bowl linebacker. ``You've got teams going back and
forth. Eight and seven. Seven and eight. You have a team that you
expect to win and they lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Given an opportunity to pass the Giants and the Packers,
Carolina lost yesterday to Pittsburgh. The fading Packers, home
next week to Arizona, were slaughtered at Tampa Bay. None of this
bottlenecking, this parity, is anything to get upset about. Not
when a third of all major league baseball teams begin every season
with no realistic postseason aspirations at all. Unlike baseball,
the NFL at least has a playoff system in place that puts these
wild-card impostors on a longer road to glory.
</P>
<P>
   What's the harm? Let the Giants and the Packers and the rest of
the pretenders dream on, for one more week. Let them go approach
the end alive, if not kicking.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you play for, what you work for,'' said Ernie
Accorsi, the Giants' general manager. ``After all we've been
through this season, we can go into the 16th game with a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week, though, it is the Packers' turn to play the early
game. The Giants could be dead by 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, they could score 80 points and rewrite the
tiebreaker script. Keep the beer cold, and the calculator close by.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-99 2226EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
