<HEADER>
A9448 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-HEALTHCARE-NYT &LR;      12-26 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HEALTHCARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TWO VISIONS ON HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Dec. 27:
</P>
<P>
   Recent debates between Vice President Al Gore and Sen. Bill
Bradley have put health care squarely on the campaign agenda, but
no doubt confused many voters about complex cost and coverage
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley proposes an expensive plan that invites uninsured people
to buy coverage, with the help of federal subsidies for families
with incomes of up to about $50,000, from any one of hundreds of
private plans that serve federal employees.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, arguing that Bradley's plan would lead to unacceptably
high tax increases or federal spending cuts, proposes taking modest
steps that would reduce the number of uninsured people by expanding
existing federal-state programs to cover more low-income children
and their parents. He would also offer tax credits to individuals
and small businesses that acquire coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the two approaches poses the central
question that divides liberals from moderates in the Democratic
Party: Is universal access to health insurance worth its costs?
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to achieve universal coverage. The first
imposes a legal mandate. But with mandates come complexity and
intense political opposition, as President Clinton learned to his
regret in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The second _ Bradley's way _ relies on voluntary purchase. The
problem here is cost. If Bradley were to subsidize coverage only
for uninsured people, he would encourage employers to drop
coverage, use some of the savings to boost wages and invite workers
to switch to the subsidized public program. That would drive up
costs and possibly increase the number of uninsured workers.
</P>
<P>
   So Bradley is forced to offer subsidies to low-wage workers who
remain insured through their employers, eliminating any incentive
to drop their private coverage. He says his program, including a
drug benefit for the elderly, would cost up to $65 billion a year.
Gore's advisers say it could cost twice that much. In fact,
Bradley's figure is probably low.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley provides a maximum subsidy of $1,800 for a single adult.
The problem, as Gore never ceases to point out, is that in many
parts of the country there are no federal plans that offer coverage
for only $1,800. In practice Bradley's subsidy would probably have
to rise to an average of between $2,100 and $2,400. Bradley's drug
plan would also probably cost more than he estimates. It would
cover 75 percent of all drug costs for the elderly above $500 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gore's drug plan would pay 50 percent of the costs
up to an initial maximum of $2,000 a year. Bradley says the two
plans would cost about the same amount, but his more comprehensive
coverage might cost 50 percent more.
</P>
<P>
   It is when the debate shifts from costs to coverage that Bradley
has a chance to score with voters. Gore's advisers say his plan
would provide coverage to 12 million uninsured people, while
Bradley's would reach 15 million. Bradley's advisers counter that
the Bradley plan plan would cover 30 million Americans, Gore's only
7 million. Gore also accuses Bradley of eliminating Medicaid. But
Bradley says he is doing what Clinton proposed in 1994, enrolling
the poor into the same health plans that cover everyone else. He
says he provides enough money to keep their benefits from falling.
</P>
<P>
   On narrow calculation, Gore's plan gets more coverage per
dollar. It covers approximately 10 million people at a cost of
about $25 billion a year. Bradley's plan would cover between 15
million and 30 million people for $85 billion to $100 billion a
year. But Gore's strategy of incremental steps is unlikely to ever
produce universal coverage. Once he tries to extend coverage beyond
the least privileged people, he will run into Bradley's problem
that any effort to subsidize uninsured workers requires subsidizing
insured workers as well.
</P>
<P>
   A realistic look at budget options starkly outlines the question
underlying their differing approaches. In a $9 trillion economy
that is experiencing the best economic times ever, is it worth
spending $100 billion a year on universal coverage, something
other, less wealthy industrialized countries have already achieved?
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's plan would mean less money for Medicare, education and
other programs and might require higher taxes. Gore says, in
effect, that the benefits are not worth these costs. That is the
right debate for an election year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
